BUSH AND McCAIN IN AIR WAR, TO THE DELIGHT OF DEMOCRATS 
(UPDATES with McCain pulling ads in 9th graf) 
 (rk) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ Dick Harpootlian, the chairman of the South
Carolina Democratic Party, sounded as giddy as a lottery winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an electronic charnel house,'' Harpootlian said gleefully
of the attack ads with which the leading Republican presidential
candidates, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas and Sen. John McCain of
Arizona, have been bludgeoning each other on the airwaves here all
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush and McCain have not only taken the gloves off,'' he said,
``they've put the brass knuckles on. I am one happy camper.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic leader is witness to a primary election media
campaign unlike any this state has seen. After observing the
niceties in New Hampshire, Bush and McCain have for a week been
accusing each other on television and radio of hypocrisy,
untrustworthiness and being in the pocket of lobbyists and other
Washington guardians of special interests.
</P>
<P>
   One even compared the other to President Clinton, which most
Republicans would consider the foulest of all possible attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Harpootlian may be getting more of a kick out of it
than most people. ``In one Bush ad, they refer to McCain as a pawn
of the left-wing labor bosses,'' he said. ``I had such a hysterical
giggling jag I had to pull the car over.''
</P>
<P>
   Politics with a bite is not unknown in South Carolina, the state
that was home to one of the masters of negative campaigning, the
Republican strategist Lee Atwater.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say South Carolinians invented hardball politics,
but they're certainly used to them,'' said Blease Graham, a
political scientist at the University of South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   And even as McCain sought Friday to end the barrages by pulling
all his attack ads in South Carolina, and calling on Bush to do the
same, the two camps continued to trade accusations over who had
done more harm to the political process.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, both sides had new commercials on the air Thursday that
portrayed each as the victim of the other's viciousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``When John McCain compared me to Bill Clinton and said I was
not trustworthy, that's over the line,'' Bush says in his new TV
spot.
</P>
<P>
   The new McCain advertisement, called ``Courage,'' depicts the
senator as a hero taking enemy fire. ``Now they're coming after him
here in South Carolina because John McCain will take the government
away from the special interests and give it back to you,'' the
announcer says.
</P>
<P>
   As the crucial Feb. 19 primary here approaches, the shrillness
of the cycle of attack-and-response has all but drowned everything
else out. The two camps have already poured at least $5 million
into television and radio in the state, the heaviest media blanket
anyone can recall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on what we had budgeted for January and February, we
have exceeded that,'' said Debbie Johnson, sales manager for
political advertising for WIS in Columbia, one of the state's
largest television stations.
</P>
<P>
   Radio, too, has been a conduit for attack. Bush has been running
three attack-style commercials on radio, including the spot that
had Harpootlian cackling, in which the state attorney general,
Charlie Condon, says that ``big labor comes out a big winner'' in
McCain's proposals for revamping campaign finance, because the
proposals ``would give union bosses and the liberal media more
control over elections.''
</P>
<P>
   And right-to-life groups have initiated an assault on McCain. A
spot running frequently on the radio has a man and a woman
discussing the horrors that might befall the U.S. Supreme Court if
former Sen. Warren Rudman, a ``very pro-abortion'' New Hampshire
Republican who serves as McCain's campaign chairman, was to be
named attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want someone like that helping pick Supreme Court
judges,'' the woman says. ``I'm pro-life!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Then don't vote for John McCain,'' the man advises.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't. I'm voting for George Bush,'' the woman replies.
</P>
<P>
   The tenor of the confrontation may make the race rawer and more
compelling _ ``Lee Atwater had a famous statement; he called it
`taking the bark off,''' Graham said _ but it's beginning to make
Republicans nervous. As in any pitched battle, there is the worry
of collateral damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news for Democrats,'' Harpootlian observed, ``is that
when these guys get done with each other, there is not going to be
much left.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   This is what Mark Miller, executive director of the Republican
Leadership Council, says has him dismayed. The centrist group,
based in Washington, helped head off a bruising television war in
New Hampshire by putting on a series of commercials there warning
Steve Forbes not to engage in the type of negative advertising that
he had done in 1996 against Bob Dole. Dole's campaign never
recovered.
</P>
<P>
   It's deja vu in Charleston and Spartanburg and Beaufort. ``We
wish they would both stick to their positive agendas,'' Miller
said. ``We don't want a damaged nominee.''
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina may have turned nasty for the Republicans, said
Graham, because the candidates suddenly had to differentiate
themselves in a hurry. McCain, for instance, had spent months
meeting voters in more than 100 town hall meetings across New
Hampshire. ``We don't have a tradition of town meetings, and we are
three times the size of New Hampshire,'' Graham said. ``It requires
much more of a reliance on media and impersonal contacts; these
candidates were making up for lost time.''
</P>
<P>
   The bad blood may also be the result of the split in two
intensively competitive factions of South Carolina Republicanism.
Former Gov. Carroll Campbell is backing Bush, while Rep. Lindsay
Graham is a frequent presence in television and radio spots for
McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans outside South Carolina say privately that the media
strategies being employed in the state could come back to haunt the
eventual nominee. In particular, they say, they worry that the
introduction of anti-abortion groups into the fight could, for
instance, force Bush to move too far to the right and risk
alienating middle of the road and independent voters, who are
likely to be decisive in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Stevens, McCain's media consultant, said that the senator
had made his point in answering Bush's attacks. ``You couldn't not
respond,'' he declared, adding that now the campaign would move on.
``The fact is that's run its course, that's done its job,'' he said
of McCain's recent spots.
</P>
<P>
   But even if McCain's call for a truce leads to a lasting peace,
the bad taste left by the commercials may take time to dissipate.
``Since the New Hampshire primary, Bush's campaign has turned
completely negative, with a hatchet job du jour from the governor
and his attack dogs,'' Howard Opinsky, a McCain campaign spokesman
said Friday. And this was after his candidate pledged in New York
to adopt a more positive campaign posture. .
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Bush, who was said to have been stung by the accusation
that he was like the president in untrustworthiness, were not
sounding particularly conciliatory either. ``That's one of the
oldest tricks in the book,'' Ari Fleischer, a spokesman for Bush,
said of McCain's renunciation of attack ads. ``Just because it is
not up on the air doesn't mean voters have forgotten it.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever ends up on television in the next week, Harpootlian
intends to enjoy the show. He is a bit incredulous, in fact, that
he gets to watch the battering from the sidelines. ``Usually,'' he
said, ``they save it for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
