<SLUG> BC-PARK-BOND-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 HISTORIC $2.1 BILLION BOND TO BENEFIT STATE, LOCAL PARK SYSTEMS  &HT;     By GREG LUCAS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Citing 12 years of widespread neglect,
environmentalists and business groups are asking voters in March to
approve the largest park bond in state history.
</P>
<P>
   At $2.1 billion, Proposition 12 would dramatically increase
financial aid to city and county parks as well as the 268 parks
owned by the state.
</P>
<P>
   It's the first park bond on the ballot since 1994, when voters
rejected a similar $2 billion proposal. If passed, Proposition 12
would be the first new bond money for parks since the 1988 approval
of more than $770 million.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents say the cost of paying off the bond is prohibitive and
that the measure is riddled with pork barrel projects sought by
individual legislators.
</P>
<P>
   But supporters say well-maintained parks _ in urban centers or
in the wild _ are critical to the quality of life of present and
future Californians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state has grown dramatically in 12 years and we've not
invested in parks and open space and our wildlife corridors are
being hurt by that,'' said Rusty Areias, director of the state
Department of Parks and Recreation.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the best economy of our lifetime _ the most sustained
period of growth in the history of this country _ it seems logical
we would want to pass Proposition 12 and repair past
irresponsibility,'' Areias said.
</P>
<P>
   The park bond's money would be spent in four broad areas:
</P>
<P>
   -- State parks _ $545 million.
</P>
<P>
   -- City, county and park districts _ $400 million.
</P>
<P>
   -- Land, watershed and wetlands purchases _ $355 million.
</P>
<P>
   -- Playground safety, urban creeks, zoos, museums, aquariums and
soccer fields _ $427 million.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1983, the state has consistently underfunded the money
needed to maintain the 1.3 million acres of parks, 1,455 historic
buildings, 3,000 miles of trails and 18,000 campsites it operates.
</P>
<P>
   Now, some 2,600 piers, roads, trails, roofs, campgrounds, picnic
sites, sewer systems and structures dating back to the Civil War
and earlier are rotting, rusting, buckling, leaking, sagging and
crumbling.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gray Davis has already given the state park system $157
million to restore aging campsites and dilapidated structures.
</P>
<P>
   Money in the bond for state parks is mainly targeted for the
rehabilitation, restoration and improvement of existing parks. But
$50 million can be spent to purchase new state parklands.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last few years we have not been able to take advantage
of acquisitions because of our deferred maintenance,'' Areias said.
``The new money goes a long way for us, but some people say just to
upgrade and repair the parks we have now could cost $1 billion.''
</P>
<P>
   There's also $15 million to spruce up Golden Gate Park, but
finding it requires a careful search. Buried in the dense pages of
the bond is this nugget:
</P>
<P>
   ``The sum of ($15 million) to a city for rehabilitation,
restoration or enhancement to a city park that is over 1,000 acres,
that serves an urban area of over 750,000 population in northern
California and that provides recreational, cultural and scientific
resources.''
</P>
<P>
   The bond also contains $15 million to restore the Immigration
Center on Angel Island and another $10 million for the California
Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Across the Bay, $2 million is earmarked for the Delta Science
Center in Oakley and another $2 million for the Arroyo del Valle
Children's Day Camp in Alameda.
</P>
<P>
   There is also $30 million for the San Francisco Bay Area
Conservancy, which acquires lands next to the bay. Another $25
million is budgeted for the Bay Ridge Trail.
</P>
<P>
   The website supporting Proposition 12 _  &UR; www.parks2000.org  &LR; _
shows how much various cities and counties would be entitled to
under the grant programs created by the bond.
</P>
<P>
   Alameda County, for example, could receive nearly $8.9 million
while Berkeley could get $1.4 million and Oakland more than $4.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Clara County and the city of Santa Clara could each
receive more than $10 million, according to the website.
</P>
<P>
   Vallejo and Vacaville could receive over $1 million while Santa
Rosa and Sonoma County could pocket $1.7 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
