<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WATER-BOND-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 STATE BOND WOULD RAIN CASH ON WATER PROJECTS  &HT;     By GREG LUCAS 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ The largest water bond in state history _ bigger
even than the bond that financed construction of the California
Aqueduct _ awaits voters on the March ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to capitalize on voter optimism stemming from a strong
economy, backers of the initiative are seeking nearly $2 billion
for a smorgasbord of flood control, water conservation and habitat
protection projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of like the transportation issue in this state.
There's a lot of unmet water-related needs that will be satisfied
with the proceeds of this bond,'' said Tom Hannigan, director of
the state Department of Water Resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``Proposition 13 will move toward more environmental
restoration,'' Hannigan said. ``This will also help create better
facilities for water conservation, so you can save agricultural
water and then use it for urban purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   The bond is roughly $200 million larger than the $1.75 billion
measure barely approved by voters in 1960 to build the State Water
Project, the linchpin of California's water delivery system.
</P>
<P>
   That engineering feat included construction of Lake Oroville on
the Feather River and the 500-mile California Aqueduct to move
water from the Sacramento-San Joaquin River Delta to Southern
California.
</P>
<P>
   The new water bond creates nothing of that magnitude.
</P>
<P>
   Just over $1 billion of the $1.97 billion contained in
Proposition 13 is devoted to water projects, including $250 million
for improvements in the San Francisco Bay-San Joaquin Delta.
</P>
<P>
   Those include strengthening the levee system, reducing drainage
from abandoned mines and spending $120 million for fish screens to
reduce the number of migratory fish killed each year by water
diversions.
</P>
<P>
   Another $40 million is devoted to creating a salmon migration
barrier to divert fish from the  &LR; South Delta pumping plants.
</P>
<P>
   The bond also earmarks $70 million for projects around the state
to improve water quality.
</P>
<P>
   Another $232 million is slated for flood protection, including
$70 million for levee work.
</P>
<P>
   Flood control projects in Contra Costa, Marin, Napa, Santa Clara
and Sonoma counties will receive part of another $45 million.
</P>
<P>
   Habitat restoration and watershed protection account for another
$253 million.
</P>
<P>
   Among the watershed protection projects are $2 million for Clear
Lake and $1 million for the Russian River.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents object to the bond based on the cost of paying it back
over 25 years. Interest and principal on the measure over that time
will bring the total to $3.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The projects would be far cheaper, opponents contend, if the
state paid for them out of annual revenue, which in recent years
has been running surpluses averaging $4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The last water bond passed by voters was in 1996. It contained
$995 million.
</P>
<P>
   Although most of that money has been spent or set aside for
specific projects, still unspent as of June 1999 was $415 million
for Bay-Delta ecosystem preservation and other improvements.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
