r a BC-DEMOCRATS-CALIFORNIA-     02-12 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMOCRATS-CALIFORNIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE BASKS IN HIGH CALIFORNIA APPROVAL RATING, WHILE BRADLEY
TO  STRUGGLES TO GET BACK INTO THE RACE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By JOHN WILDERMUTH  
 and LYNDA GLEDHILL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Looking for a knockout blow in California, Vice
President Al Gore focused on gay rights, women's issues and the
nation's high-tech economic future as he campaigned in the state
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must continue what needs to be done to keep prosperity
coming and make sure nobody gets left behind,'' Gore told 150
workers at Covad, a San Jose Internet firm.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was in the South Bay for this weekend's state Democratic
convention in San Jose. He's slated to address the nearly 3,000
delegates Saturday morning, just after a speech by former New
Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, Gore's rival for the party's presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley spent the day campaigning in Seattle before flying into
San Jose for the convention. He continued to slam Gore for what he
sees as the vice president's half-hearted or belated support for
such issues as abortion rights, gun control and campaign finance
reform, all charges Gore denies.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has been hitting Gore hard and plans to continue to
emphasize his differences with the vice president, said Gale
Kaufman, Bradley's California advisor.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the issue of gun control and many others, there is a real
difference,'' she said. ``We have the strong programs and core
values that it takes to get elected.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's speech could provide a very visible stage for
Bradley's ongoing assault on the vice president, but he's likely to
be speaking to a crowd that heavily favors Gore. Bradley, whose
backers don't include many of the Democratic party faithful who
will be attending the convention, plans to stage a rally at a
nearby hotel to put the spotlight on his own supporters.
</P>
<P>
   With this week's Field Poll showing the vice president leading
Bradley in California by more than a 4-to-1 ratio, Gore looked to
put a lock on the state with his three-day campaign swing. At stop
after stop, he showcased the support he has among the Democratic
leadership and the various interest groups that form a strong base
of the party's backers.
</P>
<P>
   For much of his tour, he was joined by California Gov. Gray
Davis, a long-time friend and supporter who hosted a
television-friendly late-night reception and rally for Gore last
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no one in the country better qualified to be
president,'' Davis said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   When the vice president arrived in Los Angeles Thursday, he was
greeted at the airport by about a dozen black ministers,
politicians and community leaders. Later in the day, during a
speech on health care at Los Angeles County-USC Medical Center, he
specifically thanked leaders of the two giant health-care workers
unions for their support. On Thursday and again last night, he
attended receptions sponsored by women's groups.
</P>
<P>
   Friday morning in West Hollywood, he received the endorsement of
the 350,000-member Human Rights Campaign, which called him ``the
lesbian and gay community's best friend ever in the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Birch, the group's executive director, said Gore is
favored over Bradley because the vice president ``is deeply, deeply
committed to uniting our country'' and has long championed gay
rights issues, ``both in word and deed.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was a personal endorsement that provided the day's most
dramatic moment for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   At the West Hollywood stop, Judy Shepard, whose son, Matthew,
was beaten and left to die on a Wyoming fence in an apparent hate
crime, fought back tears to thank the vice president for his and
his family's kindness in the wake of her son's 1998 death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that you will use your power wisely to create a safer
world for all people, including our gay sons and daughters,''
Shepard said, her voice cracking. ``It is because of our shared
vision of an America free of descrimination and hate-motivated
violence that I offer my support to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Gay rights and opposition to hate crimes is not just an
election-year issue, Gore promised.
</P>
<P>
   ``This (Human Rights Campaign) endorsement is about more than
just votes,'' he said. ``It's about the fundamental ideas of
fairness and nondiscrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the wave of endorsements and high-level support for Gore
in California, Bradley's campaign shows no signs of quietly
slipping away.
</P>
<P>
   The contested primary has been good for the party, said Joe
Andrew, chair of the Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process has reminded people what the Democratic Party
stands for,'' he said. ``Both Gore and Bradley were 30 points
behind (Republican frontrunner George W.) Bush last fall. Now they
both are even or ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Art Torres, the state party chairman, also said he thought the
battle for the nomination was good _ but for his preferred
candidate, Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It energized his campaign and candidacy,'' Torres said. ``It
made him focus on the issues that are really important.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the disputes and intra-party bickering, party spokesman
Bob Mulholland suggested Friday that Democrats at the convention
focus on the big picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next president of the United States will be speaking to us
tomorrow,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
