<HEADER>
A4654 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-SCHULZ-MONUMENT-SFCHR     02-12 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHULZ-MONUMENT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CHARLES SCHULZ' HOMETOWN PLANS A PEANUTS MONUMENT  &HT;     By STEVE RUBENSTEIN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA ROSA, Calif. _ Charlie Brown and Snoopy, who bid a final
farewell Sunday, have got plans. They will spend the summer posing
for their very own bronze statue.
</P>
<P>
   It's the least we can do, said just about everyone in Santa
Rosa.
</P>
<P>
   The beloved Peanuts comic strip, drawn by the even more beloved
Charles Schulz, makes its last Sunday appearance with another sweet
farewell letter typed by Snoopy on his manual typewriter.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking up is hard to do and saying goodbye to Peanuts is
harder. Last month, Snoopy said goodbye to readers of the daily
strip. This time, Snoopy is saying goodbye in the glory of full
Sunday color.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, Santa Rosa has tried to figure out how to say thank
you to Schulz, the 77-year-old barber's son who lives in the hills
west of town and who has drawn every word and picture in every
Peanuts strip for 49 years until failing health forced him to cap
the ink bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Should there be a street named in Schulz's honor? Discreet
inquiries were made.
</P>
<P>
   ``No street,'' said Mayor Janet Condron. ``He didn't want a
street. He's such a private person.''
</P>
<P>
   What about a statue of Schulz in front of the courthouse or City
Hall?
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't want that, either,'' the mayor said. ``We asked. He
doesn't want a lot of recognition.''
</P>
<P>
   Polls were commissioned. Surveys were taken. Citizens clipped
coupons and mailed them in. The ideas with the most support were
some sort of fountain or a kids' playground full of climbing
equipment in the shape of Peanuts characters.
</P>
<P>
   But Schulz himself said the idea that appealed to him was a
metal sculpture _ not of himself, but of his alter ego, Charlie
Brown, and of Snoopy, the most famous beagle in history.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the City Council votes to cough up $150,000, which
almost everyone in town figures to be a slam dunk, the two
likenesses will be cast in bronze by sculptor Stan Pawlowski, a
longtime pal of the cartoonist, and installed this fall in Railroad
Park by the rusty old tracks _ a bit off the beaten track and out
of the limelight, just the sort of quiet spot that Schulz might
find comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Schulz said a series of small strokes that ensued
after abdominal surgery for colon cancer in November left him
unable to draw and impaired his vision and speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, one day, it's taken. It's gone. I can't do
it,'' he told a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't matter to Santa Rosa, which adores its most
favorite son, even if times and tastes have eclipsed Snoopy and
Company just a bit. In the Santa Rosa Plaza shopping center, there
was only one store with Peanuts memorabilia for sale _ and it was a
nostalgia store.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought the Peanuts items would be flying out of here, but
it hasn't really happened yet,'' said April Wise from behind the
counter at Nostalgic Classics.
</P>
<P>
   The big display at the entrance was not Peanuts but Pokemon.
Wise was apologetic, but business is business.
</P>
<P>
   On the streets of Santa Rosa, even people who did not look like
they were Peanuts readers turned out to be Peanuts readers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Peanuts a lot,'' said Andrew Rossini, dressed in
raggedy, jaggedy leather garments and wearing his cat, Vivian, on
his shoulder. ``There aren't any grown-ups in the strips, and
that's one of the best things about it.''
</P>
<P>
   His pal Harmony Green, who wore spiky purple hair, said she
always liked Peanuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll like it if they build a statue and I'll like it if they
don't build a statue,'' she said. ``What does a statue have to do
with it?''
</P>
<P>
   At present, the only display in town honoring the Peanuts gang
is a small glass display case inside the convention and visitors
bureau. There is a Snoopy piggy bank and a Snoopy hockey puck and a
few stuffed Peanuts characters, and that's about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physical tributes are not really Mr. Schulz's style,'' said
Laura Whiting, the director of the bureau, who has been working on
the statue project.
</P>
<P>
   Some said the statue really should have Schulz in it, standing
next to Charlie Brown, like the statue in the middle of Disneyland
that has a giant bronze Walt Disney holding hands with Mickey
Mouse. That idea was suggested to Schulz and shot down quicker than
a biplane in the sights of the Red Baron.
</P>
<P>
   Just about the only thing Schulz would ever let the city do for
him, said Mayor Condron, was to install a few speed bumps on the
street leading to his famous ice rink. Those were approved faster
than just about any speed bumps in history.
</P>
<P>
   The ice rink, built by Schulz in 1969 and commonly regarded as
the benchmark against which other ice rinks are held, sits on the
northwest edge of town, next door to Snoopy's Gift Shop, which
stocks every Peanuts item on the market and, strangely enough, not
a single Pokemon.
</P>
<P>
   On display, along with $30 pewter Peanuts toothbrush holders and
$15 silk Peanuts boxer shorts and $390 solid gold Charlie Brown
charms, is a 10-foot-high get-well card, addressed to Schulz and
crammed full of the signatures of practically every soul capable of
holding a pen.
</P>
<P>
   ``You made my childhood a little sweeter,'' said one scribbled
tribute, wedged between drawings of giant hearts.
</P>
<P>
   Passers-by, gazing at the card, said if any get-well card can
make its recipient get well, they hoped this one does.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they ought to forget about the statue and just erect the
card in the middle of the park,'' said one woman. ``It says how
everyone feels around here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
