<HEADER>
A4655 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-RAIN-LADN     02-12 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAIN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JET STREAM'S DIP EXPECTED TO BRING SERIES OF STORMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JESSE HIESTAND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  LOS ANGELES _ Packing up to two inches of rain, a powerful
eastern Pacific storm will soak the Los Angeles region today,
followed by another downpour late Sunday that could last into the
Monday morning commute, forecasters said.
</P>
<P>
   Today's soaking will signal that the rainy season finally has
arrived in Los Angeles, despite La Nina. Forecasters said the jet
stream has moved far enough south to deliver a series of storms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like it will stay on the wet side for the next two
weeks or so,'' said National Weather Service meteorologist Gary
Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   While gardeners reveled in the belated wetness, golfers might be
in for a disappointment: Today's rounds at the Los Angeles Women's
Championship in Simi Valley and the Buick Invitational in La Jolla
could be postponed if it rains too hard.
</P>
<P>
   For hillside dwellers, a flash flood watch was issued for
Glendale and Ojai, where wildfires denuded hillsides.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles city firefighters braced for flooding, passing out
sandbags to residents and preparing to deploy swift-water rescue
teams at stations around the city today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything indicates that this will be the most significant
storm we've had this season,'' said NWS meteorologist Dennis
Tussey.
</P>
<P>
   Today's storm is expected to bring one to two inches of rain
along the coast and in valleys, and up to four inches in the
foothills and mountains, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The worst of the storm was expected to arrive before daybreak
today, giving way to steady rain in the morning and scattered
showers throughout the day, Tussey said.
</P>
<P>
   After a reprieve tonight and into Sunday, a second, smaller
storm is expected to arrive with one-quarter to one-half inch of
rain, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Those on-and-off-again showers, now forecast at 30 percent
probability, could last into Monday.
</P>
<P>
   However much rain falls, it is sorely needed.
</P>
<P>
   The season-to-date total, as measured at the University of
Southern California, was just 2.24 inches, compared with 9.05 in a
normal year, Tussey said.
</P>
<P>
   With the heavy cloud cover this weekend, temperatures will vary
little from overnight lows in the low 50s to highs in the mid- to
upper 50s.
</P>
<P>
   In the local mountains, the snow level should drop to about
5,000 feet, giving the mountains and ski resorts from six to 10
inches of snow.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would help us so much,'' said Samantha Teofilo,
promotions manager for Big Bear Mountain Resort, where the 18-inch
to 36-inch snow base has mostly been machine-made.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will paint the picture of winter: snow in the trees, on the
homes, smoke coming from the chimneys,'' Teofilo said, noting that
conditions have been cold enough but too humid for the past two
weeks to make snow.
</P>
<P>
   Big Bear Mountain and other resorts expect a big weekend turnout
of skiers, even with the prospect of heavy snow today.
</P>
<P>
   In the Los Angeles Basin, the strong rains are expected to keep
public works crews busy handling flooding on streets and hillsides.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be looking closely at hillsides, any clogged catch
basins that might be reported and any known flood zones,'' said
Tonya Durrell, a spokeswoman for the Los Angeles Department of
Public Works.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters are preparing by offering residents free sandbags
at any city fire station.
</P>
<P>
   Free sand, enough to fill up to 25 sandbags, will be available
to individuals at nine city Bureau of Street Services yards today,
between 8 a.m. and 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   One group particularly looking forward to the rain is green
thumbs, from backyard tomato growers to professional landscapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all honesty it means we can now turn the water off and let
the rain take over,'' said Ben Weissbach, owner of Green Diamond
Landscaping, which primarily serves homeowners associations. ``For
property owners it lets them cut down on their water bills.''
</P>
<P>
   Deep-rooted vegetation like trees will benefit greatly from the
rain, given the drought-like conditions that have persisted in this
second consecutive La Nina year of less-than-expected rainfall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've now gone two years with a minimal amount of water,''
Weissbach said. ``Just a fraction of an inch here, a fraction
there. When the rain comes, it will be great.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
