<SLUG> BC-METHODISTS-LESBIANS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 METHODIST CLERGY AT LESBIAN `WEDDING' WON'T BE PUNISHED  &HT;     By JASON B. JOHNSON 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ In a move that is likely to reverberate through
other religious communities, Methodist officials said Friday they
will not hold church trials for 68 pastors who participated in a
same-sex wedding ceremony in Fairfield last year.
</P>
<P>
   While not explicitly endorsing the ``holy union'' ceremony
between Jeanne Barnett and Ellie Charlton, church leaders
determined that the act did not merit punishment. Pastors could
have been dismissed from the church had they been tried and
convicted in a church tribunal for defying their denomination's ban
on such ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by an investigative committee of the
California-Nevada Annual Conference of the United Methodist Church,
one of the nation's largest Christian denominations, will be
watched closely by other religious communities struggling to
resolve the issues of same-sex marriage and the ordination of gay
clergy.
</P>
<P>
   During a news conference at the conference's headquarters,
Bishop Melvin Talbert read the verdict and said the strength of the
Methodist faith is in its diversity and willingness to accept
differing viewpoints while maintaining strong beliefs in Jesus
Christ.
</P>
<P>
   But it was clear that the decision did nothing to end the
controversy that has rocked the church for the past year.
</P>
<P>
   The leader of a conservative faction within the conference
blasted the ruling and said his group will seek permission to break
away from the conference for its acceptance of ``sin.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Greg Smith, the pastor of Sacramento's Hope United
Methodist Church, said many congregations will never accept
same-sex unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a day that could lead to division, even a breaking up of
our discipline,'' said Smith. ``It's a very sad day for the
California-Nevada conference.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said his group will seek to form a separate conference
within the Methodist church, which has 8.5 million members.
</P>
<P>
   The decision brought smiles to the faces of Charlton, 64, and
Barnett, 69, and the clergy members who performed their ceremony.
At a separate press conference, they thanked the committee and
Talbert.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're extremely pleased,'' Barnett said with a smile and a pat
of Charlton's hand. ``The commission worked very hard to cover both
sides and to be fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of the clergy who participated in the ceremony said they
would be open to performing similar weddings in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy to go against what would seem logical,'' said
Carol Carter of the Wesley Methodist Church of Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just so proud. We think this is a great time for us
today,'' said Pastor Hubert Ivery of the El Cerrito Methodist
Church.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud to be a United Methodist today. Today, you're seeing
the church at its best,'' said Alan Jones, director of the San
Francisco United Methodist Mission.
</P>
<P>
   The clergy also used the event as an opportunity to speak out
against Proposition 22. The measure on the March 7 ballot seeks to
ban same-sex unions by declaring that only a union between a man
and a woman can be recognized as a marriage.
</P>
<P>
   The clergy members said they would have continued to defy their
church's ban on same-sex unions and possibly would have performed
more ceremonies even if the committee had voted to put them on
trial.
</P>
<P>
   In explaining the church's ruling, Talbert said they had to
weigh the rules in the church's Book of Discipline against their
wider duty to the faithful and the mission of the church.
</P>
<P>
   He said the issue caused divisiveness, and ``we confess that our
differences of opinion have resulted in divisions among us. Each
person is of value in the eyes of God.''
</P>
<P>
   Talbert said no further action would be pursued. He said the
dispute over same-sex marriage must now be taken up by the national
Methodist leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will not resolve the issue,'' Talbert said, adding that
he hoped that the controversy would not break up the conference.
</P>
<P>
   The conference has 93,000 members in California and Nevada.
Talbert said clergy and members of about 21 churches have met to
voice their opposition to the ceremony and say they wish to leave
the organization. There are more than 380 congregations in the
California-Nevada region.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our denomination there is room for diversity,'' said
Talbert. ``There is room for a difference of opinion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
