<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 00:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4658 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-HACKER-ATTACK-SFCHRON     02-12 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HACKER-ATTACK-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI SAYS INTERNET VANDALS USED UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA COMPUTER, 
 LEFT SLOPPY CLUES
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By JAXON VAN DERBEKEN, TODD WALLACK and STACY FINZ 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
The vandals who jammed CNN's Web site this week used a desktop
computer at the University of California at Santa Barbara in a
sloppy attack that left vital clues, FBI officials said Friday.
<P>
   That revelation came as Stanford University and UCLA confirmed
that their computers also were used in the recent attacks against
some of the nation's biggest Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   The cyberspace assaults have exposed the vulnerability of even
the most sophisticated sites and come during a time of explosive
growth in online commerce as consumers turn to the Internet for
everything from automobiles to ZZ Top concert tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, federal agents scrambled to obtain warrants in
California and Oregon to search computers that may have been used
to overload Yahoo, Amazon.com, eBay, E-Trade, CNN.com, ExciteAtHome
and others, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Experts theorize the vandals hacked their way into hundreds of
computers and installed software programmed to bombard targeted Web
sites with requests for information _ thus clogging their systems
and denying access to legimate users for hours.
</P>
<P>
   Since Wednesday _ when the San Jose-based online auction house
eBay fought off a second attack and traffic at ExciteAtHome slowed
to a crawl _ the Net has returned to normal.
</P>
<P>
   The federal investigation gained speed after it was discovered
that the UC-Santa Barbara computer was used in the CNN.com attack.
Stanford officials also announced that a computer system at an
off-campus research center near Monterey was used against Yahoo on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   And officials at UCLA reported that some campus computers were
used in assaults against unspecified sites. University officials
don't know how many computers were used in the attack but said they
are ``confident the hackers are not based on campus.'' They
declined to say when the attacks happened.
</P>
<P>
   Special Agent Charles Neal, head of the FBI's computer crime
squad in Los Angeles, said the attack on CNN.com through the UCSB
site was ``sloppy'' and left behind several traceable log files.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those might point back to (the culprit). We hope to find
that,'' Neal said. `'It's among the better clues we have to
identify him (and) where he was going.''
</P>
<P>
   Although those responsible may have left electronic
fingerprints, it remained unclear Friday how many people are
responsible for the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Agents are following leads in California and Oregon and would
not identified who is being investigated.
</P>
<P>
   Despite new clues, many high-tech experts say finding those
responsible could be extremely difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be really impossible to track a hacker, especially if
they know what they're doing,'' said one computer crime specialist.
</P>
<P>
   Still, authorities were sifting through information from the
UCSB break-in. Hackers often use university or large business
computer systems to carry out cyber-vandalism because it's easier
to hide in their large volume of telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Sugar, acting director of the Office of Information
Technology at UCSB, said there are indications the computer was
broken into through the Internet by someone off campus.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Schmidt, a network programmer at the university who first
detected the break-in, said a desktop computer in a research lab
was electronically broken into by a hacker sometime before Tuesday
night's attack on CNN.com. He said the intruder entered the
computer at least twice. After gaining entry to the system, the
hacker returned to install software designed to carry out the
attack, Schmidt said.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt noticed an abnormality in the university's computer
traffic after checking the system from home at 11:32 p.m. Tuesday.
After further investigation, Schmidt realized what was happening
and contacted CNN the next morning. CNN then notified the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't a great effort to hide their presence,'' Schmidt
said of the hackers.
</P>
<P>
   A computer system at Stanford was briefly involved in Monday's
attack on Yahoo, said Stephen Hansen, a campus security officer.
</P>
<P>
   The attackers sent a flurry of questions to Stanford, each
asking for a short response, Hansen said. But the return addresses
were all forged to make it look as if they were coming from Yahoo,
so that's where the Stanford system sent its answers.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, the attackers sent the information requests to Stanford's
router, which direct bits of data on computer networks, and asked
it to forward them to every computer, printer and other device
linked to the network, instead of a single computer. Since there
are dozens of devices on the network, each request from the
attacker generated dozens of responses, all of which were sent to
Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   The attackers also sent similar requests to hundreds of other
college or corporate computer networks linked to the Internet,
creating a tidal wave of traffic that overwhelmed Yahoo for hours
and kept real users from reaching the site. Experts said it is a
type of denial-of-service attack known as Smurfing.
</P>
<P>
   But Hansen said the Stanford research center's computer network
has a relatively slow connection to the Internet, so it could do
only limited damage. And he said administrators cut off the attack
after a few minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yahoo probably didn't even notice,'' Hansen said.
</P>
<P>
   Hansen also said he doubts investigators will be able to uncover
any clues leading to the attackers at Stanford because the
addresses were forged. He said it would have been necessary to run
a trace while the attack was in progress in order to catch those
responsible.
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle staff writers Carrie Kirby and Chuck
Squatriglia,correspondent Jerry Cornfield in Santa Barbara and the
Washington Post contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-12-00 0043EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000212.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 00:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4661 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-MCCAIN-1STLD-WRI     02-12 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MCCAIN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BUSH AND McCAIN BATTLE TO CLAIM THE HIGH GROUND  
 (Updates with McCain pulling ads in 3rd graf.) 
(previously budgeted as BUSH-REFORM)  
 (See also SC-TV-BLITZ)  
 (bl)  
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ Capping a week of ceaseless attacks in the
Republican presidential race, Gov. George W. Bush on Friday recited
a litany of what he said were contradictions between Sen. John
McCain's words and actions, while McCain pledged to end television
advertisements that belittle Bush's character.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, campaigning and raising money in New York City, said he
wanted a truce because he was so dismayed by the negative turn the
contest had taken. He challenged Bush to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will run no attack, response or any kind of negative
advertising for the rest of this campaign,'' &UR;  &LR; said McCain who later
pulled his attack ads in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   McCain released two television commercials early this week that
compared Bush's level of honesty to that of President Clinton and
that signaled an increasingly bitter air war.
</P>
<P>
   Bush implied that he would not change his strategy, saying he
had not run any truly negative commercials comparable with
McCain's. He also dismissed McCain's gesture as a political ploy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an old Washington trick, the bait-and-switch trick,''
Bush said. ``He runs an ad for 18 days defining me for something
I'm not, then all of a sudden says, `OK, let's all quit.' I'm going
to make sure people understand exactly what I believe, exactly
where I stand.''
</P>
<P>
   The day's charges and countercharges reflected the importance of
the Feb. 19 primary in South Carolina to both candidates.
</P>
<P>
   But the exchanges also demonstrated each candidate's desire to
grab hold of the news coverage of the campaign, portray himself as
the person of greater integrity and muffle his opponent's words
with an even stronger, more aggrieved voice.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's vow came as he released a commercial that highlighted
his experience as a prisoner of war in Vietnam and Bush released a
commercial that lambasted McCain's campaign tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politics is tough,'' Bush says in the advertisement, ``but
when John McCain compared me to Bill Clinton and said I was
untrustworthy, that's over the line.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's pledge also came as one new poll suggested that his
unfavorable ratings among South Carolina voters had grown since he
began likening Bush with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the past week, the two men have traded accusations,
including insinuations in a Bush commercial that McCain accepted
favors from people who wanted his help in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference on Kiawah Island on Friday morning, Bush
summarized his case and made cutting mention of a McCain
fund-raiser in Washington on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night, he passed the plate amongst the lobbyists and the
special interests that he rails against,'' Bush said. ``I can just
hear him now, `Give 'em hell and pass the hors d'oeuvres.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bush noted that several newspapers had reported McCain's
opposition to donations from political action committees, but that
McCain had accepted hundreds of thousands of dollars of such
contributions. Howard Opinsky, a spokesman for McCain, said that
those newspaper reports had mischaracterized McCain's position.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a man that stood up and said, `I'm the only one who
can stand next to Al Gore on a stage and talk about campaign
funding reform,''' Bush said on Kiawah Island. ``What I'm reminding
people of is that he isn't the only one. I'm better suited to
campaign against Al Gore on campaign funding reform because I
haven't said one thing and done another.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-12-00 0049EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
