<DOCNO> NYT20000212.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4664 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-OU-NAJERA-HNS &LR;      02-12 1303
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-OU-NAJERA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
OU's Najera fosters hoops awareness in Mexico
<TEXT>
<P>
   By TERRY BLOUNT
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   NORMAN, Okla. _ If you sit down and talk to Eduardo Najera, his
accent is barely detectable after spending one year in San Antonio
and almost five years in Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   He's pretty much your typical college senior, except taller, of
course, with his muscular 6-8 frame.
</P>
<P>
   What isn't typical about Najera is his reckless abandon as a
basketball player and his boundless determination to make the most
of the opportunity he worked so hard to earn since leaving
Chihuahua, Mexico, when he was 17.
</P>
<P>
   Najera (pronounced Na-ha-ra) is closing out his career with the
Oklahoma Sooners as one of the best power forwards in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``These have been the best years of my life, not only as a
player, but also as a student,'' Najera said of his time at OU. ``I
came here as a boy, but I'll leave here as a man.''
</P>
<P>
   Najera enters today's important Big 12 game against Oklahoma
State averaging 19.3 points and 9.6 rebounds for an OU team that
likely is headed back to the NCAA Tournament after making it to the
Sweet 16 last year.
</P>
<P>
   He is the clear inspirational leader of the team because every
OU player knows what Najera has overcome to be where he is today.
He also is an inspirational leader to the youth of his country.
</P>
<P>
   Najera is well on his way to becoming the Michael Jordan of
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eduardo is a national hero, which is amazing when you
understand how much the country is soccer-driven'' said Roberto
Gonzalez of Basketball Mexicano, a private corporation that
promotes youth basketball in Mexico. ``It's hard for me to describe
just how big he has become, but Eduardo can do for basketball in
Mexico what Fernando Valenzuela did for baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a statement would have seemed ludicrous when Najera came to
Texas for his senior year of high school, hoping to earn a
scholarship to play college basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was excited about coming,'' Najera said. ``I had a long talk
with my father and told him I wanted to get a good education and be
the best I could be in basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Najera's father, who works for the Mexican government in the
water department, got financial help from the Mexican Basketball
Federation and Basketball Mexicano to send Najera to Cornerstone
Christian Academy in San Antonio. And guess how much English Najera
spoke when he arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``None. Not a word,'' he said. ``It was really hard for me to
adjust to everything, especially the language. But I picked it up
quickly. The toughest thing was having the confidence to talk to
people. I thought they might make fun of the way I talked.''
</P>
<P>
   Najera lived with John and Sandra Schieffer in San Antonio, and
they became his second family. Their daughter, Kristen, 11, calls
Najera her ``big brother,'' and Najera said she probably helped him
learn English more than anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Schieffers were very good to me,'' Najera said. ``They are
just like my family now. They call me about once a week, and they
try to go to the games we play in Texas. They are the ones who
helped me make all the important decisions. They told me the right
thing to do, and they helped me do it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was clear from the moment Najera stepped on the court for
Cornerstone that he had the ability to play major-college
basketball, but the difficult part would be doing the things he
needed to do to qualify academically.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a college entrance exam is difficult and stressful for
most high school students, so imagine taking it in a language you
had just started to learn.
</P>
<P>
   His ACT score was not high enough to qualify the first time he
took it, but he still enrolled as a part-time student at OU, hoping
he could eventually learn enough English to earn an NCAA qualifying
score. His second and third attempts were too low, and Najera was
ready to go back home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so frustrating,'' Najera said. ``I just didn't
understand what I was reading. I had to study every day, and there
were a few times when I just wanted to quit and forget the whole
thing. But the Schieffers helped me and encouraged me. I kept
trying, and my dream came true.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, on his fourth try, Najera became an academic qualifier.
Duke recruited him, but he didn't want to go that far away from
home. Najera also felt a loyalty to OU coach Kelvin Sampson, who
stood by Najera while he was struggling to pass his entrance test.
Sampson says recruiting Najera was one of the best decisions he
ever made as a coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ed is a special player and a special person,'' Sampson said.
``He is so outgoing and vibrant that he just attracts people. And
there are not many players like him. He's a hoss, and I think he
finally has started to realize he can be a great player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ed is the player in our league who most influences his team's
outcome. I can't say who the best pro prospect is, but when the
(NBA) scouts ask me about Ed, I say, `What do you need? He can do
anything.'''
</P>
<P>
   One thing the scouts like is the fact Najera, 23, has gotten
better every year. He averaged seven points per game as a freshman,
10.5 as a sophomore and 15.5 as a junior.
</P>
<P>
   It's also impressive that Najera consistently holds his own with
some of the best power forwards in college basketball. The Big 12
is loaded at that position with players such as Gabe Muoneke of
Texas and Marcus Fizer of Iowa State.
</P>
<P>
   ``Najera is a player who is extremely hard to guard because he
can do so many things,'' said Iowa State coach Larry Eustachy. ``He
can shoot from the perimeter, and he can be very physical inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Najera is one of only five Mexican nationals who play Division I
basketball, but he is not the only one at OU. His roommate is
backup center Victor Avila, who also attended Cornerstone Christian
a year after Najera.
</P>
<P>
   But Najera is the one Mexican player in the spotlight, and he
knows it. TV Azteca, a Mexican television network, covered the
Sooners' home game against Texas on Jan. 31, and four Mexican
newspapers sent reporters to cover Najera's every move.
</P>
<P>
   It is similar to the way Hideo Nomo was covered in Japan during
his first season as a pitcher with the Los Angeles Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to set a good example so more Mexican players will
get an opportunity to come play in the U.S.,'' Najera said. ``Every
time I step on the court, I think about that. The things I do on
and off the court reflect on Mexico, and I understand that. I use
that as motivation in everything I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Najera needs only six more hours to receive his degree in
sociology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to get my degree no matter what happens with the
NBA,'' Najera said. ``I know that's important to my parents, and I
know the Schieffers want that for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's also important because of the kids in Mexico who look
up to me. I like being a role model. There's nothing wrong with
that. If kids look up to you, you have to show them and tell them
what's right.''
</P>
<P>
   Najera said he's the lucky one, but he believes there are other
quality basketball players in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some other players in Mexico that have the talent
and skills to play Division I basketball, but they don't have
enough help to get here,'' Najera said. ``If I do play pro ball, I
want to do something to help those kids. They just need an
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing pro ball appears to be a given at this point. Najera
likely will be a first-round NBA draft choice this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always dreamed about the NBA, and I made it one of my
goals,'' Najera said. ``But I knew when I came to Oklahoma I would
have to improve my game a lot every year before that would become a
possibility. I wanted to be sure and make my last year my best
year.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
