<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIR-SAFETY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRCRAFT INSPECTIONS REVEAL PROBLEMS IN TAIL PARTS
</HEADLINE>
  (UPDATES thruout) 
 (rk) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Inspections of 1,100 airliners ordered by the
Federal Aviation Administration revealed further problems Friday in
tail parts that are suspected to have had a role in the crash of an
Alaska Airlines plane last week.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska Airlines canceled 12 flights Friday so it could complete
additional inspections of the mechanism that moves the horizontal
stabilizer on Boeing MD-80 series jets.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA ordered the airline, a unit of the Alaska Air Group in
Seattle, and other airlines in this country to inspect the
mechanism on MD-80 and similar jets. Metal shavings were found on
the jackscrew of a horizontal stabilizer on an Alaska Airlines
MD-83 that crashed last week and on two other Alaska jets.
</P>
<P>
   Two other airlines said they were looking into problems with the
stabilizers on their airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   And the National Transportation Safety Board said Friday night
that it was investigating three additional airplanes, a total of
five, that had reported finding filings or shavings in or around
the horizontal stabilizer jackscrews.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest Airlines replaced a jackscrew assembly on one of its
DC-9 aircraft after inspectors found what they thought might have
been an irregularity with the part. Delta Air Lines said it was
removing two of its MD-90 aircraft from service for closer
inspection after ``residue was discovered just below the
tail-mounted horizontal stabilizer'' on the planes, said Peggy
Estes, a Delta spokeswoman.
</P>
</TEXT>
