<HEADER>
A4667 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-NIRELAND-BRITAIN-1STL     02-12 0505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-BRITAIN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRA SUBMITS DISARMAMENT PLAN AFTER NEW GOVERNMENT IS SUSPENDED 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to correct verb tense in 2nd graf.)  
(mk) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The government of Catholics and Protestants in Northern
Ireland that held out the tantalizing promise of an end to the
British province's dangerously polarized political life came to a
halt Friday after only ten weeks in operation.
</P>
<P>
   But in a promising late development, the Irish Republican Army
came up with a long-awaited plan for dismantling its arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   The Northern Ireland secretary, Peter Mandelson, cited the
conflict over paramilitary arms as the reason for suspending the
power-sharing administration in Belfast and reimposing rule from
London.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has dogged the process, it has sapped confidence in the
institutions and we really have got to resolve it once and for
all,'' he said of the weapons issue.
</P>
<P>
   But in a last-minute surprise, the head of the independent panel
on disarmament, Canadian Gen. John de Chastelain, reported to the
British and Irish governments that IRA contacts had presented him
with a broad outline that he said showed ``the real prospect of
agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   The document was far different in tone and content from the
panel's conclusions of two weeks ago that reported no signs of any
IRA cooperation in beginning to disarm and led to Britain's action
shutting down the government.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for 10 Downing Street said Friday night that the
government welcomed the disclosure as a ``development of real
significance'' and that it ``will form the basis of our continuing
discussions.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandelson was acting under legislation enabling Britain to take
back direct rule of Ulster; it was rushed through Parliament during
the week and became law Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The event represented the gravest threat to the unaccustomed
political stability that Ulster has experienced since the signing
of the April 1998 peace settlement, but officials tried to dampen
fears over the consequences for the longer term and to play up the
importance of the IRA offer.
</P>
<P>
   Martin McGuinness, Sinn Fein's chief negotiator and the
education minister in the new government, said his party would not
walk away from the pact because it believed it was still ``the only
show in town.''
</P>
<P>
   David Trimble, the first minister of the Northern Ireland
Assembly, cautioned people against judging Friday's development a
``terminal crisis. It is not that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what the difficulties we might have,'' Trimble said,
``no one should regard that as being the end of this process.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandelson said he had taken his decision with reluctance but saw
it as the only way of preserving fragile political structures in
Belfast for future revival. Suspending the government Friday, he
claimed, was the only way to spare it being threatened with total
collapse when Trimble meets with members of his party council in
Belfast on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-12-00 0108EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
