<DOCNO> NYT20000212.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 01:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4669 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     02-12 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
NBA developing into a fun-for-all
<TEXT>
<P>
   By FRAN BLINEBURY
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Fun is watching Steve Francis, with all of his
rookie innocence and abandon, come down the court making decisions
at roughly the speed of a motorcycle rider with the throttle
wide-open.
</P>
<P>
   Will he go right or left, through his legs or behind his back on
the dribble? Will he slither through the tiniest crack in the
defense for a sneaky layup? Or will he go right over the top and
throw down a slam dunk with all the subtlety of a sledgehammer?
</P>
<P>
   Fun is watching Kobe Bryant, so full of himself and yet so empty
still of any discipline to his game, race across the floor like a
panicky man trying to cross a crowded freeway and get off a shot
that defies description.
</P>
<P>
   Fun is watching Latrell Sprewell beating defenses with his
quickness and instincts as he makes us forget the ugliness of his
past.
</P>
<P>
   Fun is little Allen Iverson darting among the giants and Jason
Kidd staying always ahead of the pack and Jason Williams doing his
21st-century versions of Pistol Pete Maravich's old tricks as he
whips another no-look pass to Chris Webber as they rocket toward
the basket.
</P>
<P>
   One year after the first work stoppage in league history gave
the sport a black eye, it's not only the NBA that's back but the
fun as well.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there is a difference to the games this year that is easy
to see. They are faster, quicker, far more entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than two elephants wrestling, the NBA experience this
season has been more like dueling cheetahs.
</P>
<P>
   There will be rule changes and stricter calls by the referees
given credit for why the product has so quickly become more
entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   But the truth is much more basic _ coaching.
</P>
<P>
   The sideline generals who had been choking off the creativity
for too long, are once more letting it breathe.
</P>
<P>
   The rules committee might have done away with the
backing-it-down isolation play in the low post and the officials
might be doing their determined best to get rid of hand-checking.
</P>
<P>
   But still, it is the control freaks in the designer suits who
are making it all possible just by not trying to do it all.
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Tomjanovich, of course, was nudged along the path of
enlightenment by the early-season losses of Charles Barkley and
Hakeem Olajuwon. So he turned loose the frisky colt in Francis, and
the young herd of the Rockets has followed.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks, as they discovered on their surprising trip to the
NBA Finals, can run to glory. Sacramento sizzles. Phoenix will
phly.
</P>
<P>
   And nowhere in the league is the trend toward openness more
openly apparent than in Miami, where iron-fisted Czar Riley has
suddenly become Laid-back Pat again.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Bad Boys of Detroit who first played the beat-'em-up
style of ball on their way to back-to-back titles in 1989 and '90.
But it was Riley, who steadily took the game to new depths of
plodding ugliness when he made his jump from the Lakers to New York
and groomed his team with Patrick Ewing and Charles Oakley to be
like his moussed hair _ stiff and unbending.
</P>
<P>
   The result was the 1994 Finals between the Rockets and the
Knicks that was almost like watching basketball in slow motion, and
then when fled to Miami, he quickly turned the sheer entertainment
factor of a Heat game to lukewarm, at best.
</P>
<P>
   And sports being the copycat business that it is, so many of the
others followed until the game was virtually in danger of stopping
in its tracks.
</P>
<P>
   They called meetings. They changed rules. They handed out edicts
to the men with the whistles. But it was the coaches who had to
change and, to their begrudging credit, it appears they have.
</P>
<P>
   Check out the numbers around the league in the first half of the
season. Scoring is up because shots are up, and final scores like
126-116 and 117-112, which had once been thought to have gone the
way of the buffalo, are back roaming the prairies and the box
scores.
</P>
<P>
   Consider that a year ago, in the aborted lockout season, Riley's
Heat broke the 100-point barrier only four times in 55 games,
including playoffs. Now see that the Heat broke 100 in its first
five games this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets are playing most of the time with the pedal to the
metal and already have hit the century mark 21 times this season.
</P>
<P>
   All, of course, is not perfect. There is too much fighting and
trash-talking, not enough pros capable of hitting the open
15-footer, Dennis Rodman is returning and Larry Bird is leaving.
</P>
<P>
   But for those of us who do love the game and all it can be, at
least the suits have given us the fun back.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-12-00 0110EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
