<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER COMPUTER USED IN ATTACKS IS IDENTIFIED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.) (With BC-WEB-ATTACK. No byline) 
(ko) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Another university's computer system was identified Friday as a
conduit in the attacks that blocked several leading Web sites
earlier this week, but network officials and law enforcement
authorities reported no new intrusions.
</P>
<P>
   Network administrators at the University of California at Santa
Barbara said in interviews that they had found evidence that
software had been remotely planted in a campus desktop computer
that may have been used in an attack on Tuesday against CNN.com,
the Web site of the Cable News Network.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Tuesday night we discovered signs of anomalous network
traffic,'' said Kevin Schmidt, a campus network administrator. ``On
Wednesday morning we figured out we had at least some role in the
CNN denial-of-service attack.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, a computer security official at Stanford University
said the computer system there had also been used in blocking
access to the Web sites by overwhelming them with data.
</P>
<P>
   CNN reported that the Federal Bureau of Investigation was
focusing on undisclosed places in California and Oregon as the
source of the attack on its Web site. But FBI officials in
Washington and on the West Coast would not confirm the report.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press reported that it had obtained e-mail
messages sent by engineers at Yahoo, another target this week, to
other Internet companies indicating that the attacks had been
sophisticated and that the attackers had had some knowledge of the
internal workings of the networks.
</P>
</TEXT>
