<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-STEEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON IMPOSES TARIFFS ON STEEL IMPORTS THAT EXCEED QUOTA 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton imposed punitive tariffs Friday
on steel imports valued at $410 million, answering pleas from steel
makers and labor unions but raising tensions with South Korea,
Brazil, Germany, Japan and other major trading partners.
</P>
<P>
   The tariffs apply to wire rod, often used to make hangers and
nails, as well as steel pipe, used to transport water and gas. The
duties, which take effect immediately, will sharply raise the price
of steel imports that exceed a quota pegged at 1998 import levels.
The United States says it was flooded with steel imports in 1998
and 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton decided to impose the tariffs after the International
Trade Commission, an independent U.S. agency that monitors the
effects of trade, was split over whether to recommend the duties.
</P>
<P>
   An administration official said that the duties were mandated by
U.S. law and were consistent with World Trade Organization rules,
which in some circumstances allow a country to defend domestic
producers against a sudden rise in imports.
</P>
<P>
   The decision will strain relations with several important
trading partners at a sensitive time. The administration has been
trying to jump-start global trade talks after they collapsed in
Seattle late last year. Japan, the European Union and developing
countries have complained that while the United States preaches
fair trade, in practice it often falls back on protectionist
measures when vocal domestic industries cannot compete.
</P>
<P>
   The steel industry and steel unions had pressed the Clinton
administration to take action to protect the domestic steel
industry for two years. The decision had been delayed for months,
leading to speculation that the administration was deeply divided
about what to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very concerned about the delay,'' said James English,
an executive at the United Steelworkers of America. ``Our focus is
on helping the steel industry to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   English said the union was pleased with the administration's
remedies on steel pipe imports. But he said he was disappointed
that Clinton had not imposed higher tariffs on wire rod.
</P>
<P>
   Relatively few U.S. workers are employed making wire rod and
steel pipes. The administration estimated the numbers at 4,000 and
1,300 respectively. The companies that will benefit from the
tariffs protection are mostly small- and medium-sized producers,
the administration official said. Birmingham Steel Corp.,
Northwestern Steel and Wire Co. and Keystone Consolidated
Industries are among the companies that produce wire rod.
</P>
<P>
   Labor unions have put pressure on Clinton and Vice President Al
Gore to rein in imports of a wide variety of steel products,
especially from Japan. Gore, who is seeking the Democratic
presidential nomination, has actively courted labor's support. An
administration official denied that the decision was made for
political reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. has a right to safeguard its industries and to impose
temporary relief to address serious injury,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The action places a 10 percent duty on wire rod and a 19 percent
surcharge on line pipe, with the duties phased out over three
years. The duties will hit only those imports that exceed the 1998
baseline.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea is by far the largest producer of steel pipe
exported to the United States, followed by South Africa and Turkey.
Trinidad and Tobago, Ukraine, Germany and Brazil are among the big
exporters of wire rod.
</P>
<P>
   While the duties will effectively raise prices of these goods
for companies in the United States, they will not drastically
affect steel prices overall. The United States imported nearly $14
billion in steel last year. The goods affected by the duties are
valued at one-thirtieth of that number.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-12-00 0111EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
