<DOCNO> NYT20000212.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 01:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4674 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBO-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      02-12 1540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CINCINNATI GOES GAGA OVER GRIFFEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Some were hungry. Others desperately needed a
bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   All were shivering and chapped, as the wind whipped off the Ohio
River across the barren parking-lot plaza.
</P>
<P>
   Worth it?
</P>
<P>
   What, you kidding?
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Jr. was back in town.
</P>
<P>
   Didn't matter that the sprawling, all-day line Friday outside
the Cinergy Field ticket office was hundreds deep and barely seemed
to move, nor that Griffey already had been flown back to his
Florida home.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest thing to hit town since chili mac was for sale.
Everyone wanted a piece of Reds baseball at its most majestic.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband has said for years if Griffey ever came here, we'd
have to get divorced, because he'd be at the ballpark all the
time,'' said Kate Gearding. ``Well, here I am, buying him tickets,
enabling him.''
</P>
<P>
   She was smiling. Soaring, even. As was every baseball soul in
town. There are no other kinds here.
</P>
<P>
   Sour as was Seattle over the departure of its greatest pro
sports icon, Cincinnati was joyous times 10.
</P>
<P>
   Gearding's husband, Ray, normally a dedicated auditor for Arthur
Andersen who lately has been working steadily past 10 p.m., rushed
home by 5 o'clock Thursday all lathered to watch the wall-to-wall
TV coverage of an epochal moment for the oldest professional
franchise in American sports.
</P>
<P>
   What he experienced was a frenzy that was about one yellow
submarine short of a full Beatle:
</P>
<P>
   -- Hundreds of fans met Griffey at the airport, from where he
was driven to the stadium by Carl Lindner, the tottering
80-year-old team owner, in his Bentley.
</P>
<P>
   -- Stadium fireworks were ignited. For the start of Griffey's
indoor news conference. Believed to be a world pyrotechnic first.
</P>
<P>
   -- On one TV station, the popular show ``Friends'' was bumped
off the air. On another station, the same fate befell Ted Koppel's
``Nightline'' for a wrap-up show. Yet another station's newscast
contained a weather segment comparing the baseball season climates
of Seattle and Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   -- The Cincinnati Enquirer newspaper devoted an eight-page
special section to Griffey.
</P>
<P>
   -- Radio station WLW began a ``Grif-a-thon'' Wednesday in which
listeners were asked to pledge non-cash goods and services to help
close the gap between the Reds' contract offer and his market
value. Among the offerings: Cars from dealers; a free pony and
riding lessons for his kids; lawn-mowing and snow-shoveling for
life; 150 pounds of sausage; free legal and computer services; a
lifetime supply of fresh-baked biscuits.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati wanted Griffey the Younger more resolutely than water
wants its own level.
</P>
<P>
   After spewing what he identified as his own ``explosive,
pandering rhetoric'' that invoked the names Caesar, Patton,
MacArthur and Eisenhower, as well as the creations of the Eiffel
Tower and Golden Gate Bridge, all in a hysterical effort to
analogize about Griffey's return to Cincinnati, WLW air personality
Bill Cunningham calmed down a bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a thousand years, Cincinnati will shine as the brightest
star,'' he intoned, heavily. ``Griffey has lit a thermonuclear
fuse, fallout from which will cover the town forever and ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Yo, Bill. Please. A moment of sober reflection, fergawdsakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK. I was born and raised in Cincinnati, which is the best
baseball town in America,'' he said. ``We have gone through a
drought for some time where we haven't had the kind of
personalities of which we can be most proud.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he paused.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Oracle,'' he said, ``has returned to Delphi.''
</P>
<P>
   Argh. Hold it, Bill. Talk to the hand.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody else say something rational, before the entire Ohio
River valley hyperventilates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Griffey is,'' said Gearding, the soon-to-be-divorced ticket
buyer, ``one of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Whew. Thank you.
</P>
<P>
   Danger averted.
</P>
<P>
   Truth found.
</P>
<P>
   stars
</P>
<P>
   The thing about baseball and Cincinnati, Paul Smith said, is
that it goes long _ the Cincinnati Red Stockings began in 1869 with
a 130-game winning streak _ and deep.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's 50 degrees and not raining, the kids are out playing
ball,'' he said. ``The 5-year-olds start with T-ball, and it goes
from there. Baseball is such an important part of this community.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith has been the assistant baseball coach at Moeller High
School practically since the Big Red Machine was a humble pile of
sprockets. He and Mike Cameron, the head coach (no relation to the
new Mariners outfielder acquired for Griffey) have watched a couple
of generations of ballplayers come through the private Catholic
school with the renowned athletic reputation.
</P>
<P>
   None was more special than Junior. None more revered. Nowhere
was the week's news more celebrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was walking through the halls yeterday and saw this group of
usually listless kids,'' he said. ``They were talking about how
great it was that Kenny's coming back. They were actually
high-fiving each other, kids who never cared that they were at
Moeller or anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of them said, `Wait till I tell my grandmother I'm going
to the same school that Ken Griffey Jr. went to.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his 13 years with the Mariners organization, Griffey
always stayed knotted to his hometown. Besides the obvious
connections of his parents and grandparents, he followed the Reds
closely, as well as his old high school team. He seemed to trust
the relationships he made here more than those he made where he was
known only as a ballplayer, or at least as an adult.
</P>
<P>
   The adult part has not been nearly as fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always tickled to see the kid come out in him,'' Smith
said. ``When he was here, you knew he was different than all the
rest, but he always enjoyed being a kid. If he ever loses that ...
''
</P>
<P>
   About a year ago, Griffey, as he is wont to do with friends,
called Smith out of the blue with an offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wanna play golf?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, said Smith.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, plane tickets arrived in the mail _ for
Arizona, where he joined Griffey for spring training and some hacks
in the desert.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a great time,'' he said. ``He didn't have to do that,
but it was his way of saying thanks for the times he had here.''
</P>
<P>
   stars
</P>
<P>
   Back at the ballpark, there is a second queue. This one is for
season tickets. It is shorter, and more sheltered, under the top
deck of the parking structure.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Stoff, an executive assistant for a downtown
corporation, spent two hours trying to get through on the phone to
order tickets for herself. She gave up, only to get to work to
discover her bosses desperate to get tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me there's nothing more important I could do,'' she
said. ``Stay here all day if I had to.''
</P>
<P>
   A guard managed the line, letting one buyer at a time in the
door to a waiting room in the Reds offices. Inside, the room
resembled an airport gate for an overbooked flight, although
everyone was much more agreeable. Men and women, old and young,
suits and overalls, are sprawled over couches and chairs. Some sit
on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   All would have been elsewhere, but for Thursday's splendid news.
</P>
<P>
   ``I held my 2-year-old daughter to the TV screen and pointed out
Griffey,'' said Julie Hagenmeier of nearby Fairfield. ``She smiled.
I think she understood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that sounds silly, but I remember growing up here with
Johnny Bench, Joe Morgan, Pete Rose and Ken's dad. It was a
wonderful time, and I want my daughter to have that same kind of
experience. With Junior here, I think we will. I see no reason why
we won't be in the championships.''
</P>
<P>
   Hagenmeier was among those who called WLW's ``Grif-a-thon.'' She
runs a personal-services business that helps busy families with
grocery shopping, pet care, errand running, etc. Even though she
was well aware that Griffey can afford to pay for chores, she
volunteered her staff's services.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just the way Cincinnati is,'' she said. ``We're known
for looking after our own.''
</P>
<P>
   stars
</P>
<P>
   At this raw moment, it may be asking a lot for the legion of
Griffey fans in the Northwest to step out of their moss-caked
skins. But if it is possible to set aside the rancor of the last
few months, as well as the suspicions and cynicism created by
Griffey's own prevarications and selfish behavior, the return home
of a favored son from a popular family is about as sincere an
expression of joy as one is allowed to have in the increasingly
unhappy world of pro sports.
</P>
<P>
   He came back to Cincinnati. He didn't run away to New York or
Los Angeles. Unfortunately for Seattle, neither did he help to make
the Mariners whole.
</P>
<P>
   But he brought a fresh round of exuberance to some who enjoyed
him long before he ever hit the first of his 398 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   In a downtown restaurant, Thad, the waiter serving lunch, heard
the visitor telling stories from Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure people in Seattle are sad,'' he said, ``but I think
they must understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is home.''
</P>
<P>
   Has sports become too complicated for an answer that simple?
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
