<HEADLINE>
DALLAS STARS' REIGN OVER LA KINGS ENDS AT 22
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Roman Empire, the Cowboys' reign, singer Ricky
Martin's 15 minutes of fame... Yes, all things eventually come to
an end. Some just last longer than others. The end for the Stars'
unbeaten streak against the Los Angeles Kings came last night in a
3-2 loss that snaps a 22-game string of dominance which began long
before Martin began living La Vida Loca. The Kings' previous
victory against the Stars was April 6, 1995. In the 22 games since,
the Kings did just about everything except beat the Stars. In No.
23, they did just enough to beat them, snapping a four-game Stars
winning streak in the process. Last night's game had that usual
Kings-Stars feel. LA emerged breathing fire, holding a 2-0 lead
through 20 minutes. By the middle of the second period, the lead
was 2-1, and the Stars, as usually happens, looked to have survived
the onslaught and were slowly inching toward a victory. Stars-Kings
games have a tendency to follow form from that point. Something
happens to keep the Kings from winning. Only last night, that
``something'' was the reason they won. LA scored with four-tenths
of a second remaining in the second period. ``That third goal gave
them the break they needed,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``The
difference in the game was their physical players. This is really
typical of how all the games have gone. This time, they were on the
right side of the one-goal game.'' Kings winger Luc Robitaille
scored the goal. and was able to do so easily because Kings
defenseman Rob Blake was laying on top of Stars goalie Ed Belfour
when the pass went across the crease from center Jozef Stumpel to
Robitaille. The play was reviewed, but referees ruled that Blake
had been pushed into Belfour. And while Stars defenseman Richard
Matvichuk scored at 6:18 of the third period on a pass from Aaron
Gavey, the Robitaille goal did to the Stars what they usually do to
the Kings. ``We ran out of time,'' Gavey said. ``We had battled
back. It's unfortunate they scored a goal with .4 seconds, but we
had an entire period to come back and take it to them.'' Until the
Kings' goal, the second period had been one of the Stars' best in a
while. Gavey's goal at the 5:55 mark was one of their 15 shots that
period. The Stars took the play to the Kings, a polar opposite of
the first period when the Kings did all of the initiating. The
difference was the Kings had two goals to show for it. The Stars'
problems began while they had a two-man advantage for 76 seconds of
the first period but generated only two shots. The Kings had one in
one second out of the penalty box, and they scored on it. The play
began with a turnover at mid-ice. Kings winger Ziggy Palffy then
worked the give-and-go with Stumpel, who ended up with the puck
just shy of the crease. He deked Belfour down and then went high,
giving LA a 1-0 lead at 7:12 of the first period. On the second
goal, Kings defenseman Garry Galley skated right into it. He picked
up a loose puck near the blue line, skated in until he got between
the circles and blasted a shot that snuck in under the crossbar,
stick side. The Kings suddenly led 2-0, less than 15 minutes into
the game. ``We had our chances,'' Stars winger Mike Keane said.
``We were swarming at the end of the second and early in the third.
We battled back. I don't know if it was as lopsided as some people
say.'' If the streak had taught the Kings anything, though, it was
that they could always find a way to lose. Streaks have a way of
making teams think. The Stars said they didn't think about it. The
Kings said they couldn't help thinking about it. It was with this
in mind that Kings coach Andy Murray brought LA comedian Harris
Peete to yesterday's pregame skate. He played the role of Belfour,
complete with jersey. A little chubbier, a lot less agile than the
actual Belfour, the idea was to get them thinking they could beat
Belfour and, in the process, the Stars.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
