<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIES SHOOTS EYE-OPENING ROUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  SIMI VALLEY _ Turns out, Laura Davies couldn't see her way to
an LPGA title last year.
</P>
<P>
   Not clearly, anyway. So on Thursday morning the unconventional
Davies rose early, drove more than an hour to Brea and had laser
surgery to correct her vision.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four hours later, she shot 5-under par to take the
opening-day lead of the Los Angeles Women's Championship on Friday
at the Wood Ranch Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   All those fuzzy edges around the cup, ball and club, were
suddenly gone. Dimples on a ball, what a thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to just hit the ball and ask the caddie, `Where did
that one go?' '' Davies said.
</P>
<P>
   Under dark skies that threatened but never did erupt in rain,
Davies shot a 67 to take a one-stroke lead over three others _
Janice Moodie, Laura Philo and Moira Dunn.
</P>
<P>
   A downpour is forecast for today's second round, but tournament
organizers said play will continue in the rain unless the course
simply becomes unplayable.
</P>
<P>
   At least Davies will be able to look up and clearly see drops
falling. For Davies, it's a whole new world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friends would wave at me from across the green and I wouldn't
wave back,'' she said. ``They thought I was rude. I'd wave and
didn't know who the hell I was waving at.''
</P>
<P>
   Davies is the 36-year-old from England who has 17 career
victories but failed to win an LPGA tournament last year for the
first time in seven years. She came in second in three tournaments.
Of course, that was the Davies who now says she was ``seeing in a
haze.''
</P>
<P>
   So when Davies was playing in Wednesday's pro-am event, she
mentioned to a partner who'd had the surgery and was a member at
Wood Ranch, she also wanted the surgery. He put her in contact with
the club's general manager, David Foster.
</P>
<P>
   Foster had the surgery himself and set up the procedure for
several other club members at the Lazer Eye Center in Brea. A
couple of phone calls later, and Davies _ who loves to gamble _ had
surgery scheduled on the eve of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took a chance and it paid off,'' she said. ``They told me
people walk out with 95 percent of their vision. I figured 95
percent was better than the rubbish I was used to.''
</P>
<P>
   Davies said she had the surgery at 3 p.m. and was back in Simi
Valley and asleep five hours later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pulled the patches off when I woke up and I could see
everything I couldn't see before,'' Davies said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best I've putted and chipped in some time. I can
see the break on the green. Before, it was a bit of a guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Davies birdied five holes and played the 72-par course without a
bogey.
</P>
<P>
   Still wet from Thursday's rain, the fairways played better for
the long-ball hitters like Davies on the windless day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rain helped the greens, but the fairways were pretty wet and
we didn't get any roll,'' Dunn said.
</P>
<P>
   None of those a stroke back _ Dunn, Moodie or Philo _ have won
an LPGA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Six others are backed up two strokes back _ Sherri Steinhauer,
Brandie Burton, Tina Barrett, Suzanne Strudwick, Mi Hyun Kim and
Jen Hanna. Burton is making a comeback after missing all of last
season following a pair of arthroscopic shoulder surgeries.
</P>
<P>
   Highly regarded rookie Grace Park was 3 under after just four
holes but ended up one of six who finished 2 under. Defending
champion Catrin Nilsmark is one of nine who are four strokes back
of Davies.
</P>
<P>
   Se Ri Pak, who's won eight tournaments in the past two seasons,
is grouped with Nilsmark. Pak would have finished 21 over in the
tour's opening tournament last month in West Palm Beach but failed
to sign her final card and was disqualified.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Pak complained her game was bothered by new clubs, a
new swing _ and recent lazer surgery. Friday afternoon, TLC Lazer
Eye Centers announced Pak had been signed as a spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   LPGA spokeswoman Connie Wilson said despite the weather,
organizers hope to complete the tour as scheduled Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will do everything we can to get it completed by Sunday,''
Wilson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
