<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPP-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAVES SET STAGE FOR SHOWDOWN WITH GONZAGA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU, Calif. _ On the eve of the big test, Pepperdine settled
in for some last-minute studying Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   The concern was that the Waves would have to pull an
all-nighter. Instead, they glanced at the textbook for a few
minutes, then slammed it shut and proclaimed themselves ready.
</P>
<P>
   After rolling over study partner Portland 80-60 before 1,611 at
Firestone Fieldhouse, they just might be.
</P>
<P>
   The final is today, of course. That's when Gonzaga strolls onto
campus for a critical West Coast Conference battle.
</P>
<P>
   The first-place Bulldogs have a one-game lead over Pepperdine
(18-6, 8-1) with five games remaining. A win for the Waves would
pull them even and clear a path to a share of the WCC
regular-season crown, perhaps even the outright title.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, a berth in the NCAA Tournament becomes a
distinct possibility provided Pepperdine doesn't collapse at the
WCC Tournament in March.
</P>
<P>
   A loss severely hurts the Waves' title hopes and makes it almost
imperative that they win the WCC Tournament to reach the big dance.
The tournament champion gets an automatic bid, everyone else's fate
is property of the NCAA selection committee.
</P>
<P>
   Other then that, it's just another game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're ready,'' said Tezale Archie, who had 15 points
to lead the Waves. ``We're coming off a big win; now hopefully
we're ready to go and handle Gonzaga.''
</P>
<P>
   Tommie Prince and Kelvin Gibbs added 13 points each for the
Waves, who shot 50.9 percent from the floor (28 of 59), forced 21
turnovers and blocked seven shots.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Dejworek had 16 points for the Pilots (8-14, 2-7), who
shot just 38.3 from the field but stayed somewhat close by shooting
18 of 19 from the free-throw line.
</P>
<P>
   All the Gonzaga implications were on the Waves' minds Friday,
although they did their best to stay focused on the task at hand.
After all, the Gonzaga game was meaningless without a win over the
Pilots first.
</P>
<P>
   On paper it looked like a walkover. Portland was winless in nine
road games, and only hapless Loyola Marymount and St. Mary's are
worse in the WCC. But recent history suggested otherwise. Last
week, Pepperdine struggled at Portland in a 75-68 win. A year ago
the Pilots beat Pepperdine in Malibu.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't look past Portland at all,''Archie said ``We knew
they were a tough team and that they played us tough up there. We
just concentrated on them tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take the Waves long to put to rest any thoughts of a
major stumble. They jumped out to a 16-2 lead early in the first
half, holding Portland without a field goal for the first 8:38.
</P>
<P>
   There was one minor scare _ Portland closed to within 36-33 late
in the first _ but it turned out to be nothing. The Waves quickly
restored order in the opening minutes of the second, outscoring the
Pilots 10-2 to stretch the lead to 51-35. It was a peaceful cruise
from that point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we closed out the first half with a little momentum
and then we brought our energy in the second half,'' Pepperdine
coach Jan van Breda Kolff said. ``As I tell our team, when we play
with a high energy level, we're a very good basketball team.''
</P>
<P>
   The comfortable cushion allowed van Breda Kolff to substitute
freely with about 10 minutes left. With Gonzaga playing Loyola
Marymount on Friday, van Breda Kolff was hoping to conserve some
energy.
</P>
<P>
   Now the attention shifts back to Gonzaga, which came back from a
15-point second-half deficit last week to beat Pepperdine 62-57 in
Spokane.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like we have some momentum and we're playing the way
we're capable of playing,'' van Breda Kolff said. ``It's going to
be a game against an excellent basketball team who is going to be
ready for us, and we'll be ready for them. That's where you're at
at this point in the season.''
</P>
</TEXT>
