<SLUG> BC-RUN-VANCRASH-REAX-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Prairie View A&AMP;M track team vows to carry on, honor those who died
<TEXT>
<P>
   By NEAL FARMER
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   PRAIRIE VIEW _ In good times and bad, one of the constants of
excellence at Prairie View A&AMP;M University has been the track and
field team.
</P>
<P>
   In this worst of times _ the deaths of four members killed
Thursday night in a northeast Texas van accident that injured five
athletes and coach Hoover Wright _ athletes and students gathered
Friday at the college campus about 40 miles northwest of Houston to
mourn and to consider the twists of fate that kept some of them
from making the fatal trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is in total shock and denial, really,'' said Anthony
Coe of Austin, a trainer for the Prairie View baseball team who
formerly worked with the track squad. ``Nobody wants to accept it.
They know it happened, but it is just like no one can believe it.
Everybody is still in shock. From what we understand, the ones in
the hospital are doing well. So hopefully we will have them back
home next week some time.''
</P>
<P>
   When word of the accident first came about 11 p.m. Thursday,
students gathered at the school's fountain to console one another.
A memorial service was held Friday morning, and the student
government provided purple and gold ribbons to be worn by students
or posted around campus.
</P>
<P>
   Team member Jacques Hudson said as many as eight team members
had a chance to accompany their teammates on the long drive to Pine
Bluff, Ark., where they were scheduled to compete at an
invitational meet. Some chose not to make the trip or elected to
compete at another meet set for this weekend at the University of
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody told me just to stay put,'' Hudson said. ``God must
have sent an angel from heaven, because I could have been on that
van. It just goes to show that God has a purpose for me in life.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprinter Andre Edwards was scheduled to make the trip to
Arkansas as well but didn't get the message from Wright in time.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came home about 1:30 (p.m.), I had a message on my
answering machine that coach said, `You are going to Arkansas at 1
(p.m.),''' he said. ``And I said, `Oh, well.'''
</P>
<P>
   Hudson said team members will compete the rest of the year to
honor the memory of their late classmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should (continue to run) because they wouldn't want us to
stop,'' Hudson said. ``They would want us to go on and run for
them. We'll dedicate this season to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Added javelin thrower Demarco King: ``I think every time I step
onto the track, I'm going to have them in my heart. I'll have them
looking over me and helping win my event. I'll try to just keep
them in my heart and dedicate my season to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Track team member Lewis Turner, whose brother, Jerome Jackson
was killed in the accident, said Jerome ``would want me to keep
moving on, keep continuing what I am doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner said he hopes another message emerges from the accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``People need to start putting on their seat belts,'' he said.
``I think if they had their seat belts on, it wouldn't have been as
bad as it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Prairie View was a powerhouse in track and field in the late
1940s and early 1950s, then had a revival of sorts in recent years.
The team won the 1998 Southwestern Athletic Conference indoor title
and in 1999 ended a 29-year drought by winning the outdoor
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Jamie O'Neal, who worked with the track team for three
years, said the team members ``would want us to go on. We won the
SWAC last year, and we were on the verge of winning it again this
year. We still can. We've just got to stay strong.''
</P>
<P>
   But for the survivors of the accident, returning to competition
might take some time. Tirhas Kedane of Dallas said her boyfriend,
Trent Harris, survived the accident but was shaken by what he saw,
particularly the death of teammate Houston Watson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trent is in the hospital (in Marshall) and said he was doing
OK physically,'' Kedane said. ``He told me it's just the fact that
he saw his teammate (Watson) there lying dead. He was one of his
best friends, and Houston had been driving.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in another world right now. He won't be back here for a
while. He is from Texarkana, and he is going to stay there until he
gets his thoughts together.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people supporting him, but at the same time
there are a lot of rumors about the accident going around. I think
he wants everybody just to back off for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Kedane said she had been concerned about Harris making the trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had told him not to go because he had a test (on Friday),''
Kedane said. ``And I was against him going to the track meet. But
he wanted to compete and there was really nothing I could do.''
</P>
<P>
   Reginald Johnson, a Smiley High School graduate, didn't know any
of the team members but said everyone on the Prairie View A&AMP;M
campus shares in the losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in the North Forest area, where everybody knew
everybody else, and I get that same feeling at Prairie View,''
Johnson said. ``Something like this really hurts a small campus,
because this campus is one of the few around that is still small.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't know any of the track people who died in this
incident, you knew someone who knew them, or you have seen them
around at some point here. It's such a tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
