<HEADLINE>
ROOKIES GET TASTE OF REAL LIFE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIMI VALLEY, Calif. _ The Ladies Professional Golf Association
has the right idea. Make the rookies pay their dues.
</P>
<P>
   Ever wish the million-dollar brats who populate the locker rooms
of the major sports had been shaken by their silken lapels and
reminded how the other half lives before their egos went completely
out of control?
</P>
<P>
   Can you picture Ryan Leaf being required, as a term of his
employment, to phone Chargers fans and hawk season tickets? Or
Latrell Sprewell, in his first year in the NBA, having to iron the
head coach's sweat suit? Or a young John Rocker sweeping up trash
in the stands behind the Shea Stadium visitors' dugout?
</P>
<P>
   The LPGA can.
</P>
<P>
   The LPGA, which is making its L.A.-area stop this week for the
Los Angeles Women's Championship at Wood Ranch Golf Club, requires
its rookies to put in 16 hours during the year doing the work of
tournament volunteers and organizers.
</P>
<P>
   That might mean handing out tickets at the will-call window,
setting up gallery ropes, posting numbers on the scoreboard,
fetching buckets of range balls for veteran players or answering
phones in _ cringe _ the press room.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd (callers) say, `How'd did this player do?' '' said
Moira Dunn, recalling her 1995 rookie experience, after shooting a
4- under-par 68 in Friday's first round to join Janice Moodie and
Laura Philo in a second-place tie a stroke behind leader Laura
Davies. ``I'd say, `Didn't you call five minutes ago? They haven't
finished the next hole yet!' ''
</P>
<P>
   The program was begun in 1992. It was prompted by no particular
crisis. LPGA players weren't routinely cursing the volunteers or
anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was just a way, as we (the tour) became bigger and
stronger, to make sure they still understood where we came from,''
said Connie Wilson, the LPGA's public-relations manager. ``To try
to make sure they're well-rounded human beings.''
</P>
<P>
   Everybody thinks it contributes to the generally friendly
atmosphere you'll find on the LPGA, where players call out ``Good
shot!'' to each other and seem to treat the little people with
respect.
</P>
<P>
   The ``rookie hours,'' as the players call them, might sound a
little like rookie hazing. And there is an element of the old
rookies-carry-the-veterans'-suitcases going on here.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-one-year-old Jane Egan was in the locker room, getting
ready for a long day of setting ropes and working the 18th-hole
leaderboard, when a veteran player said, ``Hey, go get me a Dr.
Pepper,'' Egan obeyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually fell for that,'' she said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever camaraderie the program engenders _ we're assuming Egan
took that Dr. Pepper thing as a joke _ is a bonus. The idea is
simply to teach the young golfers a little appreciation for the
hundreds of volunteers it takes to put on a tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these volunteers take the week off to do this,''
Moodie, a 1998 rookie, said with apparent surprise. ``I don't think
!ital!I'd do that.''
</P>
<P>
   One tournament spectator Thursday thought the LPGA program
sounds like a sharp idea: Fred Claire, the former Dodgers general
manager who teaches a USC class neatly titled ``Sports, Business
and Media in Today's Society.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports needs mentoring, and golf seems to do that, with
players giving and getting help from each other,'' Claire said.
``It's a lot more important than it's ever been, when you look at
the vast amounts of money that players receive at the outset.''
</P>
<P>
   Claire isn't talking about women golfers when he refers to vast
salaries, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Still, sauntering into the rookie program this season is the
most confident, credentialed class of LPGA freshmen since Nancy
Lopez teed off alone. Among the 28 tour rookies _ 12 of whom are
playing at Wood Ranch _ are players like Grace Park, who won five
of 10 events on the 1999 Futures Tour, Jenny Rosales, the 1998 NCAA
champion from USC, and Jen Hanna, tied for fourth after a
first-round 69.
</P>
<P>
   Park likes the idea. ``I'm a rookie. All I know is between the
ropes,'' she said. ``I want to know more about the tour.''
</P>
<P>
   All I know is it sounds like an idea whose time has come. I
picture Lamar Odom answering phones in the press room.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
