A4713 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN-(SLANG     02-12 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS SHOOT DOWN STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Nearly five years of frustration was resting on
the stick of Jozef Stumpel as he skated in on Dallas' Eddie Belfour
Friday night at the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   It was only the first period, only a moment in the 23 games
since the Los Angeles Kings had beaten the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   But when Stumpel scored, it became clear this would be the night
the streak would end.
</P>
<P>
   Not only had the Stanley Cup champion Stars beaten the Kings
four times this year, they had never trailed. When Stumpel scored
the first goal in a 3-2 victory. the sellout crowd of 18,118 sensed
the end of some pretty messy history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Jason Blake was born the last time we beat this
team,'' said a smiling Kings coach Andy Murray, referring to his
25-year-old rookie. ``I've been here only one year, but you could
tell by the fans that this game was something special.''
</P>
<P>
   The streak that began after a 3-2 Kings victory April 6, 1995
was the longest between the two clubs, one more than Dallas'
ancestors, the Minnesota North Stars, laid on the Kings in the
early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kings now have four wins in their last five games,
including victories over the elite of the Western Conference
</P>
<P>
   Detroit, Phoenix and now Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Luc Robitaille's 26th goal with one second left in the second
period stood as the game-winner. Garry Galley also had a goal in
the first period.
</P>
<P>
   But the sequence that changed everything belonged to Stumpel.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings had just killed off a two-minute, 5-on-3 disadvantage
with IanLaperriere and Bryan Smolinski in the penalty box. Their
defense stiffened and goalkeeker Jamie Storr stopped a certain goal
on a shot by Blake Sloan from the slot.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was so big,'' said Robitaille, who now has 543 career
goals, one short of Maurice (The Rocket) Richard for 18th place all
time. ``When we killed those penalties it was a tremendous lift.
But we have been playing hard and playing well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars, who lead the Pacific Division, didn't make it easy,
cutting the lead to one goal early in the third period on a goal by
Richard Matvichuk after a misplay by Storr behind his own net.
</P>
<P>
   It was Matvichuk, who broke the Kings hearts Nov. 24 with an
overtime goal that gave the Stars a 3-2 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The puck cameto me and I waived at it,'' Storr said. ``I
thought (teammate) Sean O'Donnell was going to hit me over the head
with his stick after the goal. But that play wasn't going to stop
us tonight. We just played very well.''
</P>
<P>
   The same was true the last time the two teams met Jan. 26 when
the Kings outplayed Dallas, but were stopped by Belfour in a 3-1
loss.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour was solid as usual, but two things were missing this
time. He was not playing with the lead and didn't have Brett Hull,
who got a broken nose in the Stars last game. In the last meeting
between the teams, Hull scored an empty net goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars also played without former captain Derian Hatcher,
last year's playoff MVP Joe Nieuwendyk and Jere Lehtinen.
</P>
<P>
   At the 7:12 mark of the opening period, Ziggy Palffy, who had
10points in his previous four games, spotted Stumpel breaking past
the Dallas defense. Palffy put the puck on Stumpel's stick and he
did the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Stumpel, who has missed most of the season with knee and
abdominal injuries, now has goals in each of his last five games.
</P>
<P>
   Galley made it 2-0 with less than seven minutes to play in the
first. In the first two meetings between the clubs this year,
Dallas took two-goal leads in the first period.
</P>
<P>
   Galley moved into the slot virtually untouched by the Dallas
defense. It was his seventh goal of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two weeks ago we went on the road and thought we could have
gotten six points,'' Galley said. ``We got two and were
disappointed. We've been playing hard and now the rewards are
coming. We are beating very good teams.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-12-00 0204EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
