<DOCNO> NYT20000212.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4716 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-KOBE-LADN-(SLANG)     02-12 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KOBE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOBE'S STAR IS SHINING BRIGHTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ Kobe Bryant has been here before, under the glare of
these lights, surrounded by this mob of media, propped up, promoted
and sold by these NBA marketing mavens.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant, a star the moment he entered the league in June
1996, is back in the NBA's ultimate hype vehicle, All-Star weekend.
He's been here before, as a starter in the 1998 All-Star Game in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   But this is not the same Kobe who at age 19 was forced onto the
national stage and into a prepackaged head-to-head battle with
Michael Jordan. That Kobe, not yet a starter on his own Lakers
team, was an All-Star in popularity but an unpolished phenom in
professional basketball.
</P>
<P>
   His charisma and style earned him a free pass, and resentment
over his accelerated ascent. There was the Bryant Backlash, a
feeling he was more hype than substance. There was his second-half
tailspin, when his game took a nosedive.
</P>
<P>
   So here's Bryant again, an All-Star starter once more, and his
game has caught up to his stardom. Substance has grabbed the lead
in the race with Kobe's immense hype.
</P>
<P>
   Even Bryant, now 21, admits, that this All-Star Game carries a
certain legitimacy his first election lacked.
</P>
<P>
   ``A little bit,'' he said. ``I was proud when I made the All-
Star team my (second) year, but to prove to myself that it wasn't a
fluke, to be able to come back. . . . It was such a huge challenge,
because I missed so many games. I didn't know if I was going to be
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Adoring fans left little doubt that would happen, even after
Bryant missed the first month of this season with a broken hand. He
has rewarded their faith.
</P>
<P>
   Through the first 48 games of the season, Bryant has averaged
22.6 points, 6.2 rebounds and 4.3 assists. He and Shaquille O'Neal
have been the league's most lethal one-two punch, leading the
Lakers to a 37-11 record, second best in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Few doubt anymore that Bryant belongs here. That he belongs with
the group of next-generation superstars _ Kevin Garnett, Allen
Iverson, Tim Duncan, Vince Carter _ poised to take over the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just getting started,'' Bryant said. ``I haven't
accomplished anything yet.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the problem two years ago, when the backlash began.
</P>
<P>
   He's always had the look of a star, from the moment he stepped
onto a stage in the Lower Merion High School gym in Philadelphia
and declared, with sunglasses perched on his forehead, ``I've
decided to take my talents to the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   He had the good looks and flashy moves of a young Michael
Jordan, and through no fault of his own, by his sophomore season,
the ``Heir Jordan'' label was affixed. Then came All-Star weekend
'98 _ Bryant vs. Jordan, screamed volumes of NBA print and TV ads.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the game and Bryant exacerbated matters by waving off
a screen from Utah's Karl Malone so he could go one-on-one with
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the weekend was over, Bryant was worn out. And he
was tarnished, as Malone angrily criticized Bryant's choice of
showmanship over team play. Then Lakers coach Del Harris poured
fuel on the fire, criticizing the league for elevating Bryant too
quickly, before he had done a thing on the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Del viewed it that way, which made it even harder,''
Bryant said. ``I think if he just would have viewed it as, this is
the opportunity I had here and it's a good opportunity . . .
instead of viewing it as a negative matter. I think once you view
things negatively, it has an impact on your mind. I think his views
made it even harder.''
</P>
<P>
   It certainly weighed on Bryant, who began to wilt under the
scrutiny. After scoring 17.9 points per game before the All-Star
crush, Bryant's average plummeted to 12.7 points in the second half
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the league really put a lot of pressure on him to go
out and be such a super duper-star, when you need him to just play
the game. . . . It was just ridiculous for him to go through all
that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bryant said other factors were at work then, specifically
his coach and some teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made it hard the second half of the season, because
(Harris') perception of me trickled down to my teammates,'' who
also seemed to think Bryant had gotten too big for his own good, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has a lot to do with emotions. Once the emotions kind of
get dented a little bit, it's kind of hard to play,'' Bryant said.
``I mean, I went out and played hard, but it was their perception
of me that affected my game, which made it even harder. I was
frying my brain _ `What the hell is going on?' But as years went
on, a couple years down the road, I was able to kind of look back
and analyze things, break things down.''
</P>
<P>
   The main thing he learned?
</P>
<P>
   ``Just enjoy yourself regardless of what people are saying.''
</P>
<P>
   But the experience certainly changed him. Witness his decision
not to compete in the slam-dunk contest or the 2ball competition,
both events the league desperately wanted him in. Instead, he'll
unveil his rap debut _ ``K-O-B-E'' with Tyra Banks _ this morning,
and spend time with a cousin who lives in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all the experience of what I learned about perceptions,''
he said. ``I'm very picky about my time and keeping it to myself.''
</P>
<P>
   His growth on the court is even more pronounced.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant, oft-criticized as selfish, leads his team in assists and
came within a rebound of his first career triple-double this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We keep coming together and talking about it, and I'm
remaining very positive that he's learning game by game and
experience by experience,'' coach Phil Jackson said. ``I'm never
displeased with his effort.''
</P>
<P>
   And Jackson, no stranger to the effects of hype after mentoring
Michael Jordan with the Bulls, said Bryant has ultimately benefited
from his experiences in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``The aspect of having that happen to him really matured him
quickly in that kind of a setting, and subsequently what happened
after the game,'' he said. ``His play has left him to say, `Well,
I'm not going to go to the dunk contest, the 2ball contest or
whatever else.' And he's just taking the event for himself, and I
think that's important now, that he can narrow his scope a little
bit and say, `I'll stay focused on what I'm doing.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
