<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 02:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4717 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     02-12 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOBE IN STORE FOR LESSON FROM BEATTY BOOK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant had more on his plate than Gilbert Brown. When
you're a prime cut of NBA beef, there are going to be days like
this when you're drowning in gravy.
</P>
<P>
   A one-on-one session with a reporter preceded a two-hour Lakers
practice that came before a video shoot for a cable-music TV
channel that bled into a photo session for a TV magazine, which
bumped up against a taping across town with a late-night TV
talk-show host.
</P>
<P>
   It has been that way all week for Bryant, who will participate
in his second All-Star game Sunday. Over the past few days, only
computer hackers have been busier than Bryant, 22, who admitted,
``It's been kind of crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   He had just swallowed the last bite of a nutritional bar that
passed for lunch and was slipping into his sneakers even as he
started striding toward his next obligation. Unless it's on a cue
card, Bryant probably hasn't read it, but, what the heck. ``Uh,
Kobe,'' you say, quickening your step to keep up with him, ``have
you finished the book, ``The White Boy Shuffle,'' that coach Phil
Jackson gave you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Haven't even cracked it open,'' Bryant said, so crunched for
time he was blowing off personal pronouns.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, what Jackson knows and what Bryant has yet to learn
is this: Because Bryant doesn't have time to read is exactly why he
needs to sit down and acquaint himself with Gunnar Kaufman and the
other characters in L.A. native Paul Beatty's first novel, which
was published in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman, the story's narrator, is a basketball player, but
that's almost beside the point. He is an African-American kid who
goes from living as a curiosity in Santa Monica _ ``the whitest
Negro in captivity,'' in his words _ to being a cultural misfit
when his mother uproots Kaufman and his sister and moves them to an
impoverished multiracial West L.A. neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   In this new world Kaufman might look to outsiders like he fits
right in, but in fact he is himself an outsider. He has to find his
way and earn his station and it doesn't happen overnight. As
Kaufman puts it, ``Dues had to be paid or you wasn't joining the
union.''
</P>
<P>
   He was talking about the neighborhood the locals called
Hillside, but Kaufman could have been speaking of the NBA, where a
crisp crossover dribble, a harefooted first step to the basket or
balletic dunks can buy you fame and a corporate following but not
the love of the guy in the locker stall next to yours.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman talks about all the rules from the old neighborhood no
longer applying. The eye contact he was taught to maintain when
speaking to someone in the name of common courtesy, for example, is
considered an affront that necessitates immediate physical
retaliation on the hardscrabble streets of Hillside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned the hard way that social norms in Santa Monica were
unforgivable breaches of proper Hillside etiquette,'' Kaufman says.
</P>
<P>
   Think the sporting norms at Lower Merion High in Philadelphia,
where Bryant starred before coming to the Lakers aren't egregious
transgressions in the NBA? Think of Karl Malone's reaction to
Bryant waving him off when the Utah star forward endeavored to set
a pick for Bryant at the at the All-Star game in New York two years
ago and think again.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Jackson, when asked what prompted him to pick this
particular book for Bryant, went straight to the theme of having to
adapt to one's environment in order to survive and thrive. ``I like
that,'' Jackson said with a crooked smile, his shrewd eyes
sparkling.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the same day, Jackson would launch into a discussion of
how Bryant is in some ways behind for having made the leap from
high school to the NBA insofar as college forces even the most
cloistered or coddled teens to ``step out of their environment into
an environment they don't have any control over and . . .
reorganize their lives accordingly.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman starts playing basketball and in doing so gains the
acceptance of his peers, though it is as a poet that he ultimately
commands the respect _ indeed, the reverence _ of his community.
</P>
<P>
   Beatty, the author whose own life is reflected in Kaufman's
story of race confusion, isolation and self-hatred, was surprised
when he heard his book had been hand-picked for Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   Reached at his New York City home earlier this week, Beatty
said, ``I have no idea why he would give him my book.''
</P>
<P>
   Beatty's best guess was that Jackson maybe sees shades of Bryant
in Kaufman's friend, Nicholas Scoby, a basketball phenom who lived
uneasily (until his self-inflicted death) with his reputation for
never missing a shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watching his hands shake,'' Kaufman says of Scoby, ``I
realized that sometimes the worst thing a (black man) can do is
perform well. Because then there's no turning back.''
</P>
<P>
   Beatty, an accomplished poet who just completed his second
novel, said, ``You see it all the time, how much pressure is put on
young athletes. A lot of people are like [Scoby]. They are
paralyzed by the pressure they feel to be perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant poured in 18 points and had six rebounds and two steals
in 22 minutes at the 1998 All-Star game and his life hasn't been
quite the same since. We wondered, has he felt at all nonplussed by
all the expectations heaped on him the past two years?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nah,'' Bryant said. ``After [the 1998 All-Star game], I kind
of had to raise the bar a little bit on my own expectations so I
wouldn't feel the pressure from everybody else. It forced me to
elevate my game.''
</P>
<P>
   The first line of ``The White Boy Shuffle'' reads: ``On one hand
this messiah gig is a (bear).''
</P>
<P>
   Can Bryant relate to that?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yep,'' he said, smiling and shaking his head. ``That's the
first line? Man, I've got to crack this book open.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-12-00 0210EST &QL; 
