<SLUG> BC-ACADECA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EL CAMINO HIGH SCHOOL REPEATS ACADEMIC DECATHLON VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JASON KANDEL  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  LOS ANGELES _ El Camino Real High School in Woodland Hills
captured its fifth consecutive city championship title Friday in
the Los Angeles Unified School District Academic Decathlon.
</P>
<P>
   At an awards banquet at the Westin Bonaventure Hotel in downtown
Los Angeles, amid applause and shouts, El Camino students jumped
and howled the second it was announced that their team had won the
championship and would advance to the statewide contest.
</P>
<P>
   El Camino beat 58 other teams _ with nine students each _ in the
competition that was held Jan. 29 and Feb. 5. The win marked the
school's seventh city title in 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   El Camino will now gear up for the state Academic Decathlon,
which the team has won four times. Local winners will compete March
17-19 at the LAX Marriott Hotel, Westchester High School and Loyola
Marymount University in Westchester.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the state competition will go to the U.S. Academic
Decathlon April 14-16 in San Antonio, Texas. El Camino has one
trophy from the national event.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday's celebration was a time for the winners to rest on
their laurels.
</P>
<P>
   Team members Jennifer Beatty, Shamiq Hussain, Jeana Jorgensen,
Dmitry Miroshnichenko, Burton Newman, Sean Rosami, Ernest Rasyidi,
Kyle Wilding, and Qi ``Janet'' Zhou and coaches Melinda Owen and
Christian Cerone screamed and cheered the moment that their team
was announced the winners.
</P>
<P>
   Competition was tight at this year's event. Many of El Camino's
earlier champs have graduated, leaving it up to freshmen to carry
the torch.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles High School was a close second, while Palisades
Charter High School took third place.
</P>
<P>
   El Camino accumulated 49,097 points in the two-day competition,
capturing first place in the art, math, and speech categories. L.A.
High followed closely, earning 49,020 points, while Palisades
earned 45,090 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Most Improved Team award went to Sherman Oaks Center for
Enriched Studies, which jumped 31 spots from its final position
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Based on all 10 events, In Yong Song of Palisades scored the
highest individually with 8,931 out of 10,000 points. She led all
Honor Division opponents, followed by El Camino's Rasyidi (8,627)
and L.A.'s Tae Hong (8,547).
</P>
<P>
   Top scorers in the Scholastic Division were L.A.'s Igor
Sapozhnikov (8,706), Roosevelt's Rodrigo Luna (8,025), and L.A.'s
Vladimir Kogan (7,967).
</P>
<P>
   In the Varsity Division, El Camino's Sean Rostami took first
(8,419), followed by teammate Wilding (8,173), and then
Birmingham's Erik Himmel (7,894).
</P>
<P>
   The first-, second- and third-place individual scoring winners
in each division received $1,000, $750, and $500 scholarships,
respectively, donated by the Milken Family Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The winner was selected based on total points in 10 events,
counting the scores of the top two students from among the three
team members in each grade-point average category
</P>
<P>
   Varsity (2.99 GPA and below), Scholastic (3.0-3.74 GPA), and
Honor (3.75-4.0 GPA).
</P>
<P>
   Individual events included multiple-choice tests in art, math,
music, social science, economics, language and literature. Each
student also gave two speeches, wrote an essay and was interviewed
by a judging panel.
</P>
<P>
   The 10th event _ the Super Quiz _ was the only event scored as a
team event. L.A. High took first in that competition, followed by
El Camino.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-12-00 0218EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
