<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 02:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4722 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BKC-CRAWFORD-SPI &LR;      02-12 1568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CRAWFORD-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCUMENTS SHINE NEW LIGHT ON FOUNDATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANGELO BRUSCAS and TED MILLER  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ As newly discovered documents detailed the scope of
his relationship with Michigan basketball player Jamal Crawford,
Seattle businessman Barry Henthorn on Friday emphatically denied he
had set up a scholarship foundation solely to benefit the former
Rainier Beach High School star.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, Henthorn also explained how he met Crawford
and supplied a personal reference in response to the documents
uncovered by the Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
<P>
   The documents, obtained by the P-I from attorneys and school
officials, include:
</P>
<P>
   -- A signed agreement in which Henthorn promised to repay
several loans that his former administrative assistant entered into
on behalf of Crawford.
</P>
<P>
   -- Loan agreements with a bank, a jewelry company and a
commercial lending company to purchase items for Crawford.
</P>
<P>
   -- A letter questioning Henthorn's relationship with Crawford
dating to 1998, when Crawford was the Washington state player of
the year at Rainier Beach.
</P>
<P>
   -- An unsigned ``Scholarship Acceptance Agreement'' between
Crawford and Hen-thorn's Academic Assistance Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Henthorn, 33, president of Innovative Communications
Technologies, maintained he never intended to eventually profit
from his relationship with Crawford or from the money, cars,
jewelry and living arrangements he provided for the Michigan
freshman. Henthorn also insisted the Academic Assistance Foundation
is only in the planning stages and has yet to offer any benefits to
athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jamal never received anything from the foundation. Anything
given to Jamal was given by me,'' Henthorn said. ``The foundation
exists, but so far we haven't been able to enact it.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time Friday, Henthorn disclosed that he met
Crawford through a third party, Tim McGee, director of the Joshua
Generation Teen Center in Seattle. McGee brought Crawford and four
or five other young basketball players to Henthorn's former Edmonds
residence, which contained an indoor court.
</P>
<P>
   McGee could not recall the date of the meeting, saying it was up
to three years ago. Also, he said he knew Crawford and Hen-thorn
had spoken previously at a basketball game but had not been
formally introduced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know about this friendship. It is a genuine friendship,''
McGee said. ``There is nothing that Jamal can give Barry.''
</P>
<P>
   However, documents obtained Friday detail the extent of the
gifts Henthorn provided Crawford over the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   The documents show Henthorn had his administrative assistant
co-sign on a loan of $3,763 for a 1985 Chevy Blazer and another
personal loan of $4,088, and open an account at Gordon's Jewelers
(current balance $2,813) for jewelry that allegedly went to
Crawford.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford is listed as co-signer with the administrative
assistant, Darcienne LeRoue, on the Blazer purchased in December
1998 from Bayside Auto Sales with a $2,954 loan from First Security
Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The documents also show that Henthorn drafted a scholarship
acceptance agreement with his foundation ``for the purpose of
establishing a relationship where Jamal Crawford may receive
assistance in his pursuit of academic excellence and the
development of his persona.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, which does not specify how much assistance
Crawford would receive, states that the foundation would ``from
time to time'' ask Crawford to appear on its behalf to ``promote it
or its contributors.''
</P>
<P>
   It also states that Crawford agrees ``to disclose and consult
with the foundation on any and all business decisions or
opportunities so as to allow for accurate advice.'' The
foundation's main requirement is that Crawford maintain a B average
or better.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation, listed under non-profit corporations with the
Secretary of State's Office, has the same phone number as
Henthorn's telecommunications business.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about this scholarship acceptance agreement,
Hen-thorn said: ``I cannot speak to that.''
</P>
<P>
   The document specifically contains several clauses that would
have bound Crawford to the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree to allow the foundation or its representatives to
inquire and negotiate any and all other scholarships or assistance
programs that they feel may benefit me,'' it states.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA last week suspended Crawford, Michigan's leading
scorer, for five games on top of the one handed down by the
university for violating a bylaw concerning amateurism. The NCAA
also ordered Crawford to repay $15,000 to Hen-thorn.
</P>
<P>
   Henthorn, a 1985 graduate of Issaquah High School who attended
the University of Puget Sound, Seattle University and Bellevue
Community College, has no direct connection to Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   He did, however, meet with Wolverines coach Brian Ellerbe during
the recruitment of Crawford.
</P>
<P>
   Since new allegations about Henthorn's financial and personal
relationship with Crawford were published by the P-I this week, the
NCAA and the University of Michigan have sent officials to Seattle
and reopened their investigations.
</P>
<P>
   In a wide-ranging interview, Henthorn at first declined to
discuss the specifics of the LeRoue-Crawford loans because they are
now the subject of a lawsuit filed by LeRoue in King County
Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   LeRoue, who filed suit against Henthorn and Innovative
Communications on Nov. 10, 1999, seeks repayment of the loans and
damages for loss of wages and benefits, emotional distress and pain
and suffering from having to leave her job last year.
</P>
<P>
   One document, dated July 27, 1999, is a signed agreement between
Henthorn and LeRoue, in which Henthorn agrees to repay the loans.
The agreement notes that Henthorn had made some of the payments on
the jewelry account, but that payments were late and some checks
did not clear.
</P>
<P>
   However, the agreement states Henthorn did pay off the loan on
the Blazer and the personal loan at Norwest Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Henthorn said LeRoue refused to settle the suit when he offered
to repay any outstanding debts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a flat-out extortion attempt,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazer was one of three cars Henthorn apparently provided to
Crawford dating back to his days at Rainier Beach and continuing to
the most recent car, a 1988 Mercedes valued at $12,000, that
Crawford recently tried to register on campus at Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   When the university learned of the vehicle, it suspended
Crawford for one game and launched its own investigation into the
basketball player's relationship with Henthorn.
</P>
<P>
   Also while in high school, Crawford allegedly was given a 1993
Jeep Grand Cherokee from Henthorn that became a subject of
controversy when Crawford started driving it to Rainier Beach in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   In a Sept. 18, 1998, letter from Rainier Beach athletic director
Dan Jurdy to the Washington Interscholastic Activities Association,
Jurdy disclosed that Henthorn and the Academic Assistance
Foundation had reportedly supplied the car to Crawford.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barry told Jamal that he had been selected as the student the
foundation would help,'' Jurdy said in a letter to the WIAA. ``He
gave Jamal a pamphlet about the program and said that it was a new
program that targets one young person each year, and provides them
with academic and personal assistance. On the pamphlet are the
names of various reputable businesses and individuals which make
the foundation appear very legitimate.''
</P>
<P>
   Jurdy's letter states he called Henthorn and ``asked him what he
was doing giving a high school kid a car?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I informed him that this was against WIAA rules and that he
was putting Jamal in jeopardy,'' Jurdy said in the letter. ``He
(Henthorn) said that his lawyers had informed him that it was not
against WIAA rules and that I should mind my own business.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jurdy then told Crawford that the foundation was ``set up
against the rules of the school and the WIAA,'' according to the
letter to the agency. ``Jamal has assured me that he will have no
further contact with these people.''
</P>
<P>
   Henthorn on Friday first said he couldn't recall ever speaking
to Jurdy. Then he said that he had requested a meeting with Jurdy
but was denied.
</P>
<P>
   In a story in Thursday's P-I, businesses and individuals listed
on the foundation's brochure _ which Henthorn has since claimed was
merely a ``mock-up'' _ either didn't exist or denied having any
connection to the AAF.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, more questions about the foundation surfaced. An
apparent pay stub from the foundation obtained by the P-I listed
$21,666 in salary payments ($1,666 a week) to Gerald Piper of Des
Moines.
</P>
<P>
   However, when contacted about his employment with AAF, Piper
said he never worked for AAF or for Henthorn. He said his only
connection to Henthorn was that he bought a house from him in July
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Piper said he was a high school security guard and wanted to
know how he came to be listed on a pay stub.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea what you are talking about,'' Piper said.
</P>
<P>
   Henthorn also said he had no idea what the pay stub was or how
Piper's name and Social Security number surfaced in connection with
the foundation.
</P>
<P>
