<HEADLINE>
ALL-STAR GAME BRINGS SONICS' PAYTON BACK HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ It started way back when the Jherri curl was a
cool hairstyle and just about any basketball shoe made of leather
heightened streetball fashion.
</P>
<P>
   On one of those countless occasions when kids frolicked under
eight-foot rims outside Jefferson Elementary School, there was Gary
Payton _ a mischievous third-grader with an athletic gift _
exercising his basketball prowess and a mouth that, even then, ran
with more RPMs than a race car.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA, fancy cars, big houses and long money awaited him,
Payton would often say between peewee pickup games in his the East
Oakland neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we would tell him `Yeah, right''' said Milton Jackson,
Payton's best friend of nearly 30 years. ``He was always lying.''
</P>
<P>
   There was something Payton did a lot more of than embellish.
He'd perpetually play basketball _ in the morning, at recess, after
school, until dusk, in the driveway, in the bedroom and definitely
in his dreams.
</P>
<P>
   In Payton, the playground truthfully had a rising star and one
of its most audacious characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing's changed,'' Jackson said, sounding proud. ``He's
still black and loud like he was then.''
</P>
<P>
   And he's still got game.
</P>
<P>
   Payton has since exchanged the dripping curl for a bald 'do. And
those Dr. J. sneakers that made Payton the envy of his peers have
been replaced by a pair of self-named Nikes.
</P>
<P>
   But the locals _ as well as a national television audience _
will see the same mannerisms Payton first exhibited just 10 miles
from the Arena at Oakland, when the NBA All-Star Game tips off here
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   It will mark Payton's sixth All-Star appearance, but the first
in his hometown since he entered the NBA nearly 10 years ago. The
Sonics' point guard will be joined by fellow Oaktown native Jason
Kidd (Phoenix) as All-Star hosts.
</P>
<P>
   However, the allure of Payton is as unparalleled now as it was
then.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he won't start for the Western Conference (Kidd and
the Lakers' Kobe Bryant won the fans' balloting), Payton has
developed into one of the top three players in the NBA. Payton also
is recognized as the absolute best player this little melting-pot
community across the bay from San Francisco ever produced.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who knew Payton as a child says the same thing. His
jumper was crooked and he wasn't extremely quick. But Payton ``was
so much more advanced than anyone else. He'd do whatever it took to
win games,'' longtime friend James Dailey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all he wanted to do,'' Dailey said. ``We'd take a break
every now and then to go swimming or do something else. Gary was
always on the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I always knew Gary had more of a future playing
basketball than anyone else around. Not that he was always the
best, but you just had a feeling with his determination, and as
much as he played basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   `PAYTON'S PLACE'
</P>
<P>
   The walk to Jefferson Elementary was short. Just 2{ blocks from
the house on 41st Street where Payton lived. Payton's family lived
in the West Oakland projects when he was born July 23, 1968. He is
the youngest of five children born to his mother, Annie, and
father, Al. The Paytons moved into the same one-story,
three-bedroom home Payton's father still occupies.
</P>
<P>
   Fittingly, a sign hanging above the porch reads ``Payton's
Place.''
</P>
<P>
   For a good while, Payton excelled in this section of East
Oakland. His father made sure of it, as Payton's first coach and
constant motivator.
</P>
<P>
   Al didn't want his son playing on the low rims. Instead, Payton
made an early impression with kids twice his size.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father used to tell me I had to go play with them,'' Payton
said. ``I didn't have a choice. But that's what made me better. The
games were always hard-core.''
</P>
<P>
   And so was the little, trash-talking Payton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was as tough as they come back then, because he
would talk so much and the things he'd say made people afraid,''
Dailey said. ``I learned his bark was a little bigger than his
bite. But not a lot of people knew that. He wasn't a punk, but he
definitely handles himself by the way he talks.''
</P>
<P>
   A saucy mouthpiece is what was needed in the Flats, a somewhat
precarious part of town. The Hills, where Kidd grew up, was a nicer
area with better schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the broke brothers lived in the Flat lands,'' Payton said.
</P>
<P>
   As legend has it, you had to have attitude to be successful in
the Flats, or at least be able to protect yourself. It was common
for shady characters to try to take over a game, disregarding those
waiting on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   It was be rough or be run over. Payton's toughness stood out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to be,'' Payton said. ``I mean, I wasn't as big as some
of those guys. But I had to act like I was. It was just the way it
was.''
</P>
<P>
   SERIOUS GAME
</P>
<P>
   Payton carried that no-fear attitude from the playground to
organized basketball. When Payton finished his seasons at Jefferson
Elementary, he'd immediately start playing for the Jefferson
Cobras, a recreational league team coached by his father, a.k.a.
``Pops.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd travel to places like San Francisco and Phoenix,'' said
Dailey, who along with Jackson were Payton's teammates. ```Pops'
always had us in tournaments. And he treated us all like his sons.
Gary got the ball when the game was on the line. But that was OK,
because he was usually our best player.''
</P>
<P>
   Payton called himself the ``Iceman'' because he idolized George
Gervin. ``Iceman'' posters covered nearly every inch of wall space
in his bedroom, and Payton was adamant about the nickname making
the back of his rec-league jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   Payton's reputation as a solid player grew across town at
Claremount Junior High later, Skyline High School and eventually
Oregon State.
</P>
<P>
   Entering Skyline, in the Hills 12 miles from his house, Payton
was a little-known player because he made his name in the Flats.
Playing in the Hills turned out to be a tough adjustment for
Payton. He struggled as a student/athlete his freshman and
sophomore seasons, seeing little playing time as his grades
declined.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until Payton was declared ineligible that he got
himself together. A couple of run-ins with his father played a
part, too.
</P>
<P>
   There was the time when Payton was supposed to be washing his
dad's car on the street. When he was done, Payton jumped in the
driver's seat and drove away. That short joy ride ended with Payton
slamming the car in reverse against a curb.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was taking the long way to the driveway. And wrecked that
car,'' Jackson said, laughing. ``He knocked the concrete off the
curb, and `Pops' was highly upset.''
</P>
<P>
   Pops, who would lay into Payton, shook up the 15-year-old for
good when he burst into a classroom at Skyline and admonished him
in the hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went back in there crying, in front of all my friends,''
Payton said. ``I straightened up. You know, you don't want him to
come back again.''
</P>
<P>
   Payton became the most celebrated player to leave Skyline's
dingy, 600-seat gymnasium. He has donated so much to the school,
and is such an example for current players, that the school
district is proposing the gym be renamed after Payton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows what he'd be doing if he wasn't playing
basketball,'' Jackson said. ``Gary always wanted to play. And
`Pops' didn't play.''
</P>
<P>
   Payton's father, also known as Mr. Mean in the neighborhood, was
always firm. Payton's friends, though, remember the deep affection
`Pops' had for his youngest son.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary always had new gym shoes, and he always had money in his
pocket due to his father,'' Dailey said. ``I remember when we'd
hang out after school and go get some Chinese food. It would cost
99 cents, $1.08 with tax. And Gary would have a $20 bill in his
pocket but say, `Give me a dollar so I don't have to break my $20.'
Me and Milton would have a couple of bucks at the most.''
</P>
<P>
   Payton divided his time at the homes of Dailey and Jackson. As
teenagers, the trio eventually graduated to the Malibu, now a
vacant lot, but once a place to play video games and ride go-karts.
</P>
<P>
   Just one of the many pit stops on Payton's way to becoming a
local legend.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a special guy,'' Jackson said. ``That's all you can say
about him. He's one of a kind.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
