<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-GALLOWAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS EXPECTED TO OBTAIN GALLOWAY DESPITE SNAG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
By Ray Buck Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Cowboys appeared to have had a seven-year,
$42 million deal in place, or nearly in place, with Seattle's
unhappy big-play receiver Joey Galloway last night when Galloway
suddenly fired his agents.
</P>
<P>
   As of late last night, the Cowboys were still working on trying
to sign Galloway, who is now represented by Leigh Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   A contract is imperative before a trade _ which still appears
imminent _ can be consummated between the Seahawks and Cowboys, who
are willing to give up their first-round draft pick (19th overall)
in the April 15-16 draft and other possible considerations.
</P>
<P>
   Galloway, who is one of the NFL's premier big-play men, missed
eight games last season over a bitter contract dispute in which he
turned down a seven-year, $35 million offer from the Seahawks.
Galloway was demanding a $10 million signing bonus on a five-year
deal instead.
</P>
<P>
   Last night, Galloway fired his agents, Eric Metz and Ethan Lock
of Phoenix, and hired Steinberg to resume negotiations with the
Cowboys, Steinberg told the Seattle ``Post-Intelligencer''.
</P>
<P>
   According to a source, a deal between Steinberg and the Cowboys
is expected to be reached today.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg, who has had a close working relationship with Cowboys
owner Jerry Jones over the years, represents five Cowboys,
including quarterback Troy Aikman.
</P>
<P>
   The bizarre twist to this story is that Stephen Jones, Cowboys
vice president/director of player personnel, was negotiating
positively with Metz when suddenly all bets were off, as Galloway
changed agents.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Holmgren, Seattle coach and general manager, made it clear
that he was eager to trade Galloway _ and sooner rather than later.
Holmgren received what he considered to be serious inquiries from
six NFL teams, including the Cowboys, over the past two days.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Seahawks made Galloway their ``exclusive
franchise player,'' which meant they would receive two first-round
picks if he left via unrestricted free agency. This set up the
trade scenario.
</P>
<P>
   The Joey Galloway Sweepstakes took a specific direction toward
Valley Ranch when Holmgren decided late yesterday afternoon that
the Cowboys would receive an exclusive first crack at trying to
sign Galloway.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren's reasoning was based on the Cowboys having what he
felt was what it would take to meet the needs of both Galloway,
contractually, and the Seahawks in a trade.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren explained that he saw the potential for time-wasting
gamesmanship among owners and general managers of these six teams
if given the chance to bid against each other. Dallas, Washington,
Philadelphia, Baltimore and Cleveland are known to be among the six
teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has gone on long enough for my tastes,'' said Holmgren,
deciding not to turn show-and-sell into something that could drag
out for weeks, or even months.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the Seahawks had gone through a messy three-month
holdout last season with Galloway, who sat out the first eight
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said the same thing to every \Rinterested\S team: `Talk to
me and tell me what we can do.' I'm not going to go back and forth
between teams,'' said Holmgren. ``To me, \Rthe Cowboys\S present
the best scenario.''
</P>
<P>
   That's now up to Galloway and his new agent, Steinberg, to
determine.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins, with three first-round selections (second, 12th
and 24th) reportedly offered the lowest of these picks and wide
receiver Albert Connell to the Seahawks. But Holmgren preferred
19th overall to 24th overall, and therefore gave the Cowboys first
dibs.
</P>
<P>
   Galloway, 28, caught 29 of his career 37 touchdown passes over
the 1996, 1997 and 1998 seasons. In his first four years in the
league, he averaged 65 receptions, 1,030 yards and nine touchdowns
before his 22-catch, 335-yard, holdout-marred half-season in 1999.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
