<SLUG> BC-AWARDS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TROPHIES' EN HANCE CITY IM AGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY RICCARDO A. DAVIS  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Another week, another award for Phoenix. But how does the trophy
case of No. 1 rankings help the area? Or could it hurt?
</P>
<P>
   In a just over a year, Phoenix has been cited among the top
places, if not the No. 1 spot, to start, expand or move a business
by at least a dozen national publications. Last week, the Phoenix
area
</P>
<P>
   was named the hottest area in the United States for an
expansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all read those publications as site-selection consultants,
as well as the corporate CEOs we are working with,'' said Peter
O'Neill, senior vice president of Corporate Real Estate Advisors,
based in Irvine, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Phoenix isn't under consideration, we will go back and give
it another look.''
</P>
<P>
   Area economic-development professionals said the national notice
pushes Phoenix to the top of the list of potential sites for
companies looking at the Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   Recognition ``is a major plus for Phoenix and because of it we
will probably make the short list,'' said William Stephenson,
certified economic developer for Arizona Public Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you can't make the short list if you don't get on the long
list,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   David Roderique, Scottsdale economic-development director, said
the recognition could go a long way in sinking the business world's
perception that the Phoenix area is only a great place to golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (CEOs) now see the Valley as a serious business center,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix area has won several high-profile projects in the
last few months: the USAA operations center; a $2 billion chip
plant that boosts Intel Corp.'s presence in the Phoenix area; and a
new credit-card processing center for retailer Target Corp.
Honeywell International now has headquarters for its $10.5 billion
aerospace business in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix area's booming business climate and the resulting
migration of people to the metropolitan area can have a downside. A
disproportionately large number of start-ups in Arizona translates
into a higher number of small-business failures.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Department of Commerce Director Jackie Vieh isn't
concerned with the number of the failures. Unsuccessful businesses,
she said, are a mark of the entrepreneurial spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the nature of business in the New Economy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   All the executives and workers who come because of the Phoenix
area's reputation further strain the area's infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   Although a December poll showed residents loved Arizona, almost
half said they would leave the area tomorrow if they could. Among
the reasons cited: air pollution, traffic and encroaching
development.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Weddle, president of the Greater Phoenix Economic Council,
said a balance between a high quality of life and a healthy economy
would almost ensure the Phoenix area's future competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Being more selective in the types of businesses GPEC seeks to
lure to the Phoenix area, Weddle says, also will help preserve some
of the quality of life while sustaining a vibrant economy.
</P>
<P>
   Weddle says his work is not done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our image race is not over we have to push it to an even
higher level,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-12-00 0304EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
