<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SCORSESE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE NIGHTS THAT WILL SATISFY SCORSESE FANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
A PERSONAL JOURNEY WITH MARTIN SCORSESE THROUGH AMERICAN MOVIES 
Written and directed by: Martin Scorsese and Michael Henry Wilson. 
Produced by: Florence Dauman and edited by Thelma Schoonmaker.
When: Monday through Wednesday night at 8 p.m. and 12 a.m. 
On: Turner Classic Movies. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Taking a trip through the history of American movies with Martin
Scorsese is a film lover's dream. It would be like a house tour for
architects led by Frank Lloyd Wright or sitting next to Isaac Stern
for a concert series or talking baseball with Ted Williams or the
history of hoops with Bill Russell.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next three nights on Turner Classic Movies, Scorsese
weaves his idiosyncratic way through genres, directors, stars,
studios, and writers in ``A Personal Journey with Martin Scorsese
through American Movies.'' The documentary airs from 8-9:30 p.m.
and repeats from midnight-1:30 a.m. each night.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Scorsese spoke in a conference call to a handful of
writers throughout the country, explaining his passion for movies
and why this journey is so personal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really a film critic,'' he says from his office in
Manhattan. ``I love movies too much to be a critic.''
</P>
<P>
   What Scorsese means is that he can isolate a particular sequence
or a specific shot or the artful use of a color and appreciate that
portion of a movie. He can forgive innumerable sins for one
brilliant moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at this documentary as not really a history but what
affected me,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   As an asthmatic child growing up in the Little Italy section of
New York City, he virtually lived at the movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't play sports,'' he says. ``I spent my time inside
movie theaters.''
</P>
<P>
   That early exposure transformed the youngster into a virtual
encyclopedia of film knowledge. Sometimes, while shooting his own
films, he'll request his office to ship him clips from other movies
that might help him resolve a particular problem.
</P>
<P>
   What makes Scorsese's cinematic journey so memorable is his
intelligence, affection, and humility.
</P>
<P>
   For those who know Scorsese only through his films, the
documentary is an opportunity to be both entertained and educated
through his vast knowledge of other directors' work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just ran the new print of `Rear Window,' '' he says of the
Alfred Hitchcock classic. ``You might as well give up. He's the
best.''
</P>
<P>
   Scorsese wants the viewer he calls the ``younger film
enthusiast'' to appreciate more obscure directors. Instead of
concentrating on filmmakers whose work is already well-documented
and respected _ such as John Ford and Hitchcock _ Scorsese lauds
more obscure talents such as Andre de Toth and Anthony Mann.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want them to build up an appreciation for the little
movie,'' he says. ``These films are art. Sometimes good, bad, or
indifferent but they were art. It's like spending time with a piece
of music or a painting that moves.''
</P>
<P>
   Scorsese, whose own film resume includes ``Mean Streets,''
``Taxi Driver,'' ``Good Fellas,'' ``Raging Bull,'' and ``Bringing
in the Dead,'' speaks of ``Detour,'' Edgar G. Ulmer's low-budget
1945 film noir with a no-name cast, with the same enthusiasm
usually reserved for Orson Welles's ``Citizen Kane'' (1941). ``Its
crudity made it special,'' he says. ``It created a nightmarish
atmosphere . . . a hyper-reality. He had no time to shoot it . . .
he had to use his imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   And imagination is still what fuels Scorsese and, he hopes,
future generations of filmmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each generation is trying to re-invent what cinema is,'' he
says, in response to a question about the new digital technology.
``But we're all doing the same thing. We're trying to do something
that will emotionally affect people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
