professor of political science at Michigan State University. ``Ten
years ago, they would have called on the telephone in search of a
campaign headquarters. Now they can go on the Net and find a Web
site and in a few moments make a contribution or volunteer.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 100,000 people have volunteered to help McCain's campaign
through his Web site, 37,000 of them since the first primary.
``What's really interesting about this is an enormous amount of
activity is simultaneously being initiated by thousands of people
around the country,'' Rohde said. ``The people are initiating the
contact. Usually, it is the other way around.''
</P>
<P>
   This success is due largely to McCain himself. Aides say he
recognized the Internet's potential in 1998 and, early on, he hired
some twenty-something Webmasters to design a ``user-friendly'' Web
site geared primarily toward attracting money and volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   The ease with which McCain has raised his money is not lost on
Republican fund-raisers.One of them, Ted Welch, said somewhat
wistfully last week: ``It's an amazing thing. You don't have to go
get the money. The money comes to you.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas enlisted 200
``Pioneers'' to each raise $100,000, and they did it the
old-fashioned way: calling friends, writing letters and gathering
checks with a lot of zeroes. It still works, of course; Bush has
raised a record-shattering $70 million thus far.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of people began flocking to McCain's Web site
(www.mccain2000.com) at 7 p.m. on Feb. 1, the night of the New
Hampshire primary, just after the networks announced his crushing
victory over Governor Bush. The cash, given by credit card,
cascaded in at a rate of $20,000-an-hour..
</P>
<P>
   ``We always looked at this as a David and Goliath thing,'' said
Max Fose, the Internet manager for the McCain campaign. ``John
McCain is David, the Internet is our sling shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, it was former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey who
built the foundation for McCain's success. In March 1998, Bradley's
campaign asked the Federal Election Commission for permission to
count credit card contributions to the campaign's Web site toward
presidential matching funds. ``At a time of concern over citizen
disengagement from the political process, the commission has the
opportunity to encourage citizen participation, reduce the
influence of large contributions and restore confidence in
democracy,'' Bradley's lawyers wrote the commission.
</P>
<P>
   The commission allowed credit card contributions to be matched
by the federal government, which means that McCain's $2.7 million
will earn him an additional $1.4 million. Bradley's argument
appears to be correct. Thirty-nine percent of those who have
contributed to McCain over the Internet had never given to a
candidate before, and 70 percent had only contributed once. Nearly
half of his e-supporters are under 40.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts warn that candidates attempting to copy
McCain's success will have to do more than build a snazzy Web site
or host chat sessions. After all, McCain is perceived by many of
his supporters as an honest maverick, which nicely matches the way
many Web users regard themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how much we can generalize about Internet fund
raising in the future from this single experience,'' Rohde said.
``I think the Internet phenomenon is mixed up with the McCain
phenomenon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
