<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Sunday, Feb. 13. The N.Y. Times News Service supervisor is
Lynn Hoogenboom; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
lyhoog(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-IRS (Undated) _ Warning that continuing cuts at the
Internal Revenue Service threaten the nation's tax system, the
Clinton administration is proposing more money to find cheaters and
make them pay up. And the agency's top official has begun
emphasizing that getting tough with cheaters is as important as
helping honest taxpayers. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 1 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Top center story: with 3-column photo
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-SPRAWL (Santa Clarita, Calif.) _ This is the future home
of Newhall Ranch, the largest housing development ever approved by
Los Angeles County, with 21,600 units for 70,000 people to be built
over the next 20 years. To its critics, Newhall Ranch is a symbol
of all that is wrong with California's decades of
catch-as-catch-can development. But big as it may be, Newhall Ranch
is nothing compared with the projected need for new housing in Los
Angeles County: about 25,000 units a year, according to the
Southern California Association of Governments. By 2025, the
state's population of 34 million is projected to grow by 18 million
more (a whole New York state) and that of the Los Angeles region by
6 million (or two Chicagos). By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   With photos and map.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 1 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   HOME-CARE (Washington) _ Following up on a Supreme Court
decision, the Clinton administration has told states to evaluate
hundreds of thousands of people in nursing homes, mental hospitals
and state institutions to see whether they could be receiving care
in their own homes or elsewhere in their communities. By Robert
Pear.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 2 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   2-graf refer:
</P>
<P>
   WEB-SECURITY (Undated) _ The consternation over the assaults
that hobbled popular Web sites underscored how heavily both
businesses and consumers had come to rely on the Internet for
everything from paying bills to planning vacations. But as Internet
executives beef up security and public attention turns to the FBI
pursuit of the culprits, some network experts _ and at least a few
lay Internet users _ contend that last week's electronic attacks
should sound an alarm. As Internet entrepreneurs and investors
entice people to put more of their personal, political, financial
and even medical lives online, those who counsel caution see need
for a more gradual pace. By Amy Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 2 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   CHILE-DECLASSIFIED (Undated) _ About 25 years ago, as the forces
of Gen. Augusto Pinochet overthrew the Socialist government of
Salvador Allende, two American supporters of President Allende were
killed in Chile under circumstances that stirred suspicions of CIA
involvement. U.S. officials categorically denied any role in the
young men's deaths, which were dramatized in the 1982 movie
``Missing.'' Now, spurred by the arrest of Pinochet in 1998,
President Clinton has ordered the declassification of ``all
documents that shed light on human rights abuses, terrorism and
other acts of political violence during and prior to the Pinochet
era in Chile,'' and there are answers to many longstanding
questions. By Diana Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 2:30 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FAKE-FISH-TROPHIES (Millstone, N.J.) _ The centuries-old art of
skinning, stuffing and varnishing a fish so it can be stuck on the
wall and bragged about is still alive. But taxidermists are
increasingly making trophies out of resin and plastic. They simply
go to a shelf and pull down a blank _ an 18-inch brook trout, say,
or a 21-inch largemouth bass _ paint it, stick on synthetic fins,
and voila. By Andrew C. Revkin.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 1 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
