<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 11:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4753 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-CORPORATE-MISSIONS-RE     02-12 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORPORATE-MISSIONS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSION STATEMENTS: WORDS THAT CAN'T BE SET TO MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mission statements _ those distilled essences of corporate goals
_ will never be confused with works of Donne or Shakespeare. Yet
they have caught on like Britney Spears' latest hit, becoming
poetry to executives' ears, sonnets to shareholder value, so much
so that 86 percent of U.S. corporations have their own carefully
worded, neatly printed, widely disseminated statements.
</P>
<P>
   While this mass embrace of codified corporate goals seems part
hula hoop fad, part keeping up with the Joneses, many business
executives say they serve as a vital compass. Also called credos or
vision statements, they range from florid language to business
school argot, from snappy staccato to
I-need-No-Doz-to-finish-reading-this-thing.
</P>
<P>
   In its credo, Johnson &AMP; Johnson, the pharmaceutical giant, says,
``Our first responsibility is to the doctors, nurses and patients,
to the mothers and all others who use our products.'' BankAmerica
boasts of its dedication to ``unselfish banking,'' while Celestial
Seasonings pledges to sell ``the best-tasting, 100 percent natural
hot and iced teas, packaged with Celestial art and philosophy,
creating the most valued tea experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Many executives hail their statements as magic potions that help
inspire corporate turnarounds. But others acknowledge that such
documents fall flat and end up forgotten just months after
corporate leaders trumpeted the statements, which were often
developed during lengthy retreats with high-priced consultants.
</P>
<P>
   When Christopher K. Bart, a business school professor at
McMaster University in Hamilton, Ontario, surveyed 88 corporations
about their statements, he came up with surprising results. For
some companies, the documents are the ``sex drive'' or ``libido''
of organizational life and inspire high performance and passion
toward the organization. But at other companies, they were an
assemblage of trite phrases that impress neither senior managers
nor low-level employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overall conclusion is that, in any sample of mission
statements, the vast majority are not worth the paper that they are
written on and should not be taken with any degree of
seriousness,'' Bart said.
</P>
<P>
   This description could have been borrowed from a game, called
Mission Statement Generator, at the www.dilbertzone.com Website,
inspired by the I-don't-buy-the-company-line comic strip. This
Mission Statement Generator offers 17 interchangeable adverbs, 26
interchangeable verbs and 39 interchangeable adverbs that produce
bureaucratic gems like, ``It's our responsibility to
synergistically supply virtual leadership skills as well as to
continually build prospective paradigms for 100 percent customer
satisfaction.''
</P>
<P>
   The statements are no laughing matter to supporters. ``It's the
glue that holds this corporation together,'' said Michael J. Carey,
Johnson &AMP; Johnson's vice president for organizational planning and
development. ``The message is the ability to produce business
results, not at any cost, but within our value system.'' Johnson &AMP;
Johnson's credo, which dates from 1943, calls for maintaining
reasonable prices, paying employees adequately, being good citizens
and even bearing ``our fair share of taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   But Michael Moore, the bane of Corporate America and author of
``Downsize This!'' (Crown, 1996), mocked credos that call employees
``team members'' as attempts at brainwashing. In an era when
corporations lay off thousands of workers at a time, he faulted
these statements for making believe that management's and labor's
interests were one and the same.
</P>
<P>
   Mission statements, which were far less prevalent in the 1970s,
became ubiquitous management tools after President Jimmy Carter
urged companies to adopt tougher ethical standards and after the
1982 best seller, ``In Pursuit of Excellence'' advised companies to
articulate clear goals.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say Johnson &AMP; Johnson's credo guided them through one
of its worst crises: the 1982 incident in which cyanide placed in a
bottle of Tylenol killed a consumer. The company recalled every
bottle at the cost of $75 million. After seeing the cookie-cutter
approach of many companies, Harvey Mackay, chairman of Mackay
Envelope Corp. in Minneapolis, adopted a statement that has raised
a lot of eyebrows: ``To be in business forever.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I look at a lot of these mission statements,'' he said,
``they are a total, unequivocal blur.''
</P>
<P>
   The emphasis on staying in business forever tells employees to
focus on the long term, MacKay said, and not to push too hard a
bargain with customers or suppliers because customers might go to
other companies and suppliers might give the best new technologies
to competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that some short statements, like the Marines' ``Semper
Fi,'' work splendidly, Mackay settled for brevity. ``I like to
shock people,'' he said. ``And this one just clicked.''
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; VISION THING, EXCERPTED &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first responsibility is to the doctors, nurses and
patients, to the mothers and all others who use our products.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Johnson &AMP; Johnson
</P>
<P>
   ``Boundaryless . . . Speed . . . Stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   _ General Electric &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We will stay in the business we know best and where we are
leaders _ air transportation and related services. We believe air
transportation will grow worldwide, and we will focus our time,
attention and investment in building on our leadership position. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Delta Air Lines
</P>
<P>
   ``Our mission is to grow and dominate the U.S. specialty tea
market by exceeding consumer expectations with: the best-tasting,
100 percent natural hot and iced teas, packaged with Celestial art
and philosophy . . . '' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Celestial Seasonings
</P>
<P>
   ``To boldly go where no man has gone before.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Star Trek &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
