<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000212.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 12:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4761 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-WEST-POLITICS-ART-NYT     02-12 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEST-POLITICS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMID CAMPAIGN HOOPLA, ONE REGION FEELS LEFT OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Colo., Idaho, Mont., Nev., N.M., Utah, Wyo.)   (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Ethanol plays so large a role in the agricultural
economy of Iowa that candidates campaigning before the January
caucuses there, the first test of presidential aspirations, ignored
the issue at their peril.
</P>
<P>
   Yet huge regional issues here in what is loosely defined as the
Interior West _ eight states that account for nearly a quarter of
the country's land mass but only 40 of its 538 electoral votes _
have been all but ignored this year because of the marginal role
these states play in the nomination process. Virtually nothing is
heard from the stump about land management, water rights, nuclear
waste cleanup or endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the polls close on Super Tuesday, March 7, more than
two dozen states and U.S. territories will have held primaries or
caucuses that could well determine the major parties' presidential
nominations. But among the Interior eight _ Arizona, Colorado,
Idaho, Montana, Nevada, New Mexico, Utah and Wyoming _ Arizona
alone will have voted by then (in a primary for Republicans only).
</P>
<P>
   In a further reflection of the region's scant influence, for the
fifth straight election cycle not one of the presidential or vice
presidential debates is to be held in any of the eight states.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the rarity of such debates anywhere in the West
prompted the Western Governors' Association to ask the Commission
on Presidential Debates last week to add a fourth presidential
debate or a second vice presidential debate, to be held in a
Western state. In a letter to the commission, the governors
expressed concern that it ``has again overlooked the
fastest-growing region in the country,'' with issues different from
those in states to the east.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just insane,'' Gov. Michael O. Leavitt, R-Utah, said of
what many here regard as the Interior West's status as an
afterthought, a result in part of the tendency of big states like
California and New York to gain greater influence in the nomination
process by moving up the dates of their primaries. ``Everybody
races to the front, and the more it's front-loaded, lots of areas
in the United States get completely left out of the process.''
</P>
<P>
   No region so vast has been more frequently overlooked than the
Interior West, whose eight states rank from forth to 12th in land
mass but from 24th to 50th in population. And as if the low
population alone was not enough to make them hardly worth fighting
over, most of the eight are so heavily Republican that the party's
nominee can virtually take them for granted. Only in Colorado and
Nevada have Democrats achieved nearly equal strength.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of attention has been especially noted by environmental
organizations that focus much of their efforts on the West and rely
on public awareness to get their issues before Congress and the
administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gays in the military _ that is an important issue, but it
affects a very small portion of the populace,'' said Kieran
Suckling, executive director of the Center for Biological Diversity
in Tucson, Ariz. ``Clean air and clean water affect every single
American.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Marshall, coordinator of the disarmament program for the
Rocky Mountain Peace and Justice Center in Boulder, Colo., said the
cleanup of nuclear waste from Cold War weapons programs, an
enormous problem in the West, ``is an issue that rarely shows up,
if at all, in presidential campaigns.''
</P>
<P>
   The same can be said for many other Western issues. ``Any kind
of public debate would focus on policies of the West,'' said Gov.
Jim Geringer, R-Wyo. ``Like protection of national forest lands.
Who wouldn't be for that? But if you don't talk about areas for
grazing and areas for logging, then you've not taken everybody into
consideration. And without debates, that part of it gets lost.''
</P>
<P>
   To increase the influence of the Interior West and shine a
spotlight on Western issues, Leavitt led an effort two years ago to
create a Western presidential primary in early March that would
have enabled voters in all eight states to cast votes on the same
day. But the effort failed for a variety of reasons, and a chance
for the region to broaden its influence was lost.
</P>
<P>
   Nor has the West as a whole had much success attracting
presidential debates. In recent years, only Los Angeles, in 1988,
and San Diego, in 1996, have been host to any held in the region.
</P>
<P>
   James M. Souby, executive director of the Western Governors'
Association, said many universities, civic groups and other likely
hosts of a presidential debate ``are not aware of the process'' of
applying. But the debate commission's executive director, Janet
Brown, said that was not necessarily so.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Brown said, the commission received dozens of
inquiries but, finally, just 12 formal bids, only three from
prospective hosts in the West: the University of California at Los
Angeles, the University of Southern California and the University
of Portland. No bid, she said, came from the Interior West, and the
Pacific Coast bids were eliminated when the commission selected St.
Louis, Boston and Winston-Salem, N.C., for the presidential debates
and Danville, Ky., for the vice presidential debate.
</P>
<P>
   That prompted the Western governors to ask for the additional
debate and for a response from the commission by the end of the
month.
</P>
<P>
   A commission co-chairman, Frank J. Fahrenkopf Jr., a Nevadan who
is a former chairman of the Republican National Committee, said
that he sympathized with the Western states but that at this late
date in the presidential election season, he could not hold out
much hope for the request.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
