<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 12:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4766 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-FAKE-FISH-TROPHIES-AR     02-12 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAKE-FISH-TROPHIES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO CATCH A TROPHY FISH WITHOUT GOING NEAR THE WATER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Fla., Wyo. N.J.)  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By ANDREW C. REVKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILLSTONE, N.J. _ Mark Hayward has caught dozens of smallmouth
bass in the Delaware River over the years, so it is not surprising
that he decided one day to have a taxidermist put one on a plaque.
What is remarkable is how the taxidermist, Robert Kennedy, did it.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, who recently completed the order in his basement
workshop in this central New Jersey town, never handled one of
Hayward's fish. He never even saw one. Nor was he given a photo of
a fish, or its measurements.
</P>
<P>
   That is because Hayward has released almost every bass he has
ever hooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't really have a particular one in mind,'' Hayward said.
``So I ordered one about in the middle of the range he offers, not
overly large. The middle of the range seemed like the way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Such is the state of taxidermy in this increasingly virtual
world: trophy fish can now be ordered like a pair of L.L. Bean
boots. The centuries-old art of skinning, stuffing and varnishing a
fish so it can be stuck on the wall and bragged about is still
alive and well. But taxidermists now make trophies out of resin and
plastic, too. They can simply go to a shelf and pull down a blank _
an 18-inch brook trout, say, or a 21-inch largemouth bass _ paint
it, stick on synthetic fins, and voila.
</P>
<P>
   The shift toward fake-fish trophies, which has accelerated over
the last few years, has to do with their durability, as well as
with a new environmental sensitivity that enables anglers to claim,
the way movie credits sometimes do, that no animals were harmed in
the making of this trophy.
</P>
<P>
   A few saltwater species, like sailfish, have long been
reproduced synthetically because their oily skin deteriorates
quickly. But taxidermists now make replicas of everything from
arctic char to piranha to spoonbill catfish.
</P>
<P>
   Hayward found what he wanted on the Internet. His order was for
one ``SMB 16.5 RT'' (smallmouth bass, 16.5 inches, with a
right-hand turn to the body). The price was $180, about what a
traditional mount costs.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Many anglers recoil at mock trophies, Kennedy and other
taxidermists acknowledge. But many others embrace the
nonbiodegradable souvenirs. Conservation groups, naturally, are
delighted.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have the satisfaction of having that replica there to
remind you of your great experience,'' said Kathy Buchner, a member
of Trout Unlimited in Jackson Hole, Wyo., and the owner of a
replica Snake River cutthroat trout, ``but you have the
satisfaction of knowing you could catch that same fish again.''
</P>
<P>
   Virtual ``wall hangers'' have also been a boon to restaurants
and bars. In Stuart, Fla., Mike Kirkhart, whose specialty is
replicating giant ocean fish, recently made a 5-foot head of a
black marlin for a restaurant in Cape Hatteras, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   The trend has also helped anglers carry on a tradition usually
reserved for barroom or dockside conversations _ embellishing the
truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had people come in to do a 30-inch fish,'' Kirkhart said,
``and end up leaving with a 40- or 50-inch fish.''
</P>
<P>
   Some taxidermists, including Kennedy, make synthetic trophies
not only for individual customers, but also for fellow
taxidermists. He uses rubber molds of prize specimens to turn out
white blanks that he sells wholesale.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, 39, also molds just the heads of fish _ oily species
like Atlantic salmon, which tend to rot if mounted in the old way.
He sells these to other taxidermists, who meld the heads with foam
bodies on which real fish skin is glued.
</P>
<P>
   His business, Great American FishHead Co., has grown so much
that he employs four high school students to help him make 100
heads a week, which he ships across North America and as far afield
as New Zealand. It has taken over his basement, where dozens of
full-body fish replicas hang from the ceiling, and freshly molded
heads jut from wall hooks. Shelves hold amber molds made using
prime specimens brought in for traditional mounting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fish are like people,'' Kennedy said. ``Some are better
looking than others. Some have better lines.''
</P>
<P>
   In a corner of his workshop recently, he poured white resin into
a mold, set a timer for 13 minutes and started up a big blue
machine that slowly spun the mold to spread the liquid as it
hardened.
</P>
<P>
   He then returned to another project, a smallmouth bass. With
scissors, he cut out fins from a sheet of plastic and stuck them
into slots on a white body. Then he sat at a bench and _ with a
rhythmic hiss, hiss, hiss _ airbrushed the bass' stripes.
</P>
<P>
   As he painted, he acknowledged the oddness of his craft. ``A
beautiful fish swimming in a stream ends up with a product
number,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When the timer chimed, he walked back to the blue machine,
peeled open the mold and pulled out a 23-inch rainbow trout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perfect,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
