<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 12:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4769 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-STAMINA-HNS &LR;      02-12 1636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-STAMINA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUESTIONS DOG BUSH ON WILLINGNESS TO ENDURE GRUELING RIGORS OF
CAMPAIGNING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When former Republican presidential candidate Gary Bauer was
waiting to be the first speaker at a Lincoln Day Dinner in New
Hampshire, an aide to George W. Bush approached him and said: ``Can
Governor Bush speak first? He's tired.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer refused to yield. ``I'm tired, too,'' he recalled saying.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, 53, sets aside two hours a day to exercise. But in the
wake of his upset loss to John McCain in New Hampshire there is a
nagging question about whether Bush has the necessary fire in the
belly to run for president.
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, the fire-in-the-belly question involves his desire to
run, his willingness to endure the grueling rigors of campaigning _
including ceaseless attention from the global press corps _ and
whether he has the personal fortitude to turn things around in the
face of his first political trouble in 21 years.
</P>
<P>
   In the days before his New Hampshire loss, Bush repeatedly
complained about being tired and homesick. He admitted he even
carried his pillow from home to guarantee a good night's sleep.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend after New Hampshire, Bush went home to rest in
Austin, Texas, rather than attend the California Republican
convention _ where McCain gave a well-received luncheon speech _
leaving many there believing that Bush took the state for granted.
</P>
<P>
   Bush won the next primary, in Delaware on Tuesday, but McCain
got a quarter of the vote without campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   Bush attributed McCain's New Hampshire win in part to the number
of days he spent campaigning there.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with South Carolina's primary approaching Saturday, Bush is
resting Sunday, Feb. 13, in Austin. McCain, who is 10 years Bush's
senior, is holding a Seneca, S.C., picnic before traveling to
Atlanta to promote his war-hero autobiography.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of South Carolina will understand that someone
wants to go home to go to their own church and to be with their
teen-age daughters for one day, on Sunday,'' said Bush spokeswoman
Karen Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a completely full schedule,'' Hughes said. ``We're
doing as much as possible to interact with individual voters, to
talk with them one on one, answer their questions, talk about the
issues, to do all kinds of South Carolina media, to continue to be
as accessible to the national media as we have been.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said anyone who believes Bush is taking the race for
granted has ``underestimated his desire.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has found himself reassuring supporters about these
questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go to a meeting this morning, I walk in and could look in
their eyes and they were wondering if the man has it,'' Bush told a
Grand Rapids, Mich., Republican gathering. ``I looked right back at
them in a private meeting and said, `Don't worry about me. I've
dusted the snow off of my suit. I'm ready to fight.'''
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, ``I miss my family, miss our girls, miss
the cats _ they don't miss me,'' a homesick Bush lamented to an
Iowa State University audience last month. ``I miss the dog. She
does miss me.''
</P>
<P>
   After a series of verbal misspeaks, Bush said it was fine for
the media to poke fun at his verbal gaffes _ ``just put in there
he's real tired.''
</P>
<P>
   University of Virginia political scientist Larry Sabato said
Bush's fatigue and apparent lack of enthusiasm has not sunk in with
the general voting population. But Sabato said Bush is sending a
bad signal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's homesick, maybe he shouldn't be president,'' Sabato
said. ``Presidents are gone almost every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Sabato said there is little doubt that Bush could perform as
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it does create the question of whether there is fire in
the belly,'' Sabato said. ``Between Bush and McCain, McCain's fire
is hot enough to melt steel. I'm not sure Bush's is hot enough to
melt butter.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the candidate's struggle with fatigue, Bush's campaign
has tried to portray him as a man of vigor.
</P>
<P>
   Photographers often have been allowed shots of him in his daily
workout or run. In New Hampshire, he held photo opportunities while
snowmobiling or sledding. Last year, his doctor released a physical
report that said Bush's fitness was in the top 1 percent of his age
group.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's New Hampshire chairman, Sen. Judd Gregg, was featured in
a television commercial telling voters that Bush ``reflects
Reagan's optimism and Teddy Roosevelt's energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Roosevelt _ declaring that anyone who is ``sober, washed and
free of bodily advertising'' should get to shake the president's
hand _ on New Year's Day 1907 pressed 8,150 palms at the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   The handshake has been an integral part of Bush's campaign for
president. Bush remains after almost every speaking event to shake
hands with voters, sometimes for almost two hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the way, it takes a lot of effort to shake every hand. I'm
tired,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   For whatever good may have come from Bush's hand-shaking, it was
McCain's open, ask-any-question town hall meetings that captured
voters' imaginations.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign at first said that voters asked the governor
questions while he shook their hands. But in the wake of New
Hampshire, Bush's staff started a daily count of how many people
mentioned issues to Bush while shaking his hand.
</P>
<P>
   Bush quickly dropped that, and on returning to South Carolina
last week Bush had adopted the McCain-style town hall meeting
format, called ``One on One with Governor Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   But McCain still maintained a more vigorous public schedule than
Bush. On Saturday, McCain had scheduled door-to-door campaigning
and three town hall meetings. Bust had set two morning town hall
meetings before flying to Austin in the early afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Bush's challenge is to overcome the image that his
campaign created when they positioned him as the front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had a groundswell of support from the GOP establishment
nationwide and raised a record amount of money, $68 million. He had
an aura of invincibility, an aura that vanished with McCain's upset
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Former Reagan administration official Bill Bennett made an
inescapable comparison between Bush and the late-blooming prince of
Shakespeare's Henry IV, who gave up a life of good times to assume
his father's throne and ``pay the debt I never promised.'' The
prince ultimately has to fight for the throne, fending off a
challenge from a lord, who like McCain, had been a war hero.
</P>
<P>
   After New Hampshire, Bennett said that Bush, like Shakespeare's
prince, now needs to prove he is willing to fight and not take his
nomination for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still a lot of support for him, but now the question
is asked and the issue now is can he rise to the challenge,'' said
Bennett, who has campaigned with McCain. ``Now, we will see what is
in him, what is truly in him.''
</P>
<P>
   Revealing ``what is truly in him'' is not only Bush's job, but
the self-assigned role of the national and international media, who
have trailed Bush endlessly since he began officially campaigning
last June.
</P>
<P>
   Bush seems weary of the media attention as well.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush has a ``media availability'' every day, his access to
the press is tightly controlled. By contrast, McCain will speak to
reporters at length every day, answering whatever questions are
pitched to him.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's attitude toward the media was captured last year when a
C-Span reporter asked him if he was treated unkindly by the Texas
news media. ``I'm treated with respect,'' the governor said.
</P>
<P>
   But recently when Sam Donaldson and Cokie Roberts asked Bush the
same question three times during an interview, Bush grew visibly
angry and his spokesman later said that the journalists had been
``disrespectful'' in their efforts to pin down the governor.
</P>
<P>
   Because of his father's presidential campaigns, Bush and his
aides were wary of the national news media. Shortly after the
former president left office, he declared that he didn't miss
Washington or politics: ``I damn sure don't miss the press.''
</P>
<P>
   Longtime Bush friend and adviser Clay Johnson said he asked the
governor last June how the Texas press corps differed from the
national press corps.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `There's no humor,''' in the national press corps,
Johnson said. They were ``real serious, real grim. Their jaws were
tight. It's not very friendly, very adversarial.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of Bush's different approach to the media has been the his
campaign's effort to keep the front-runner on message, mistake
free. As the underdog, McCain was at liberty to swing away with
little to lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you run against George Bush, he is going to have one
message,'' former Gov. Ann Richards said last year. ``He is going
to say that message until the world gags and everybody else is
going to be able to say it back.''
</P>
<P>
   A rare crack in the Bush campaign's facade occurred last month
as reporters badgered press aide Mindy Tucker about when would they
get their next news availability with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to have one big, fat news conference on our
schedule where everyone can come and ask about what you think the
news is. It's not in our best interest. We have a message of the
day, and we want to stick with it,'' Tucker said.
</P>
<P>
   For Bush now, the question is does the man have what it takes to
keep going at this pace through the mid-summer conventions on into
November?
</P>
<P>
   ``It can't be just adrenaline 'cause you can't keep adrenaline
going,'' said McCain, still perky as he headed into his 12th hour
of campaigning aboard the ``Straight Talk'' express last week in
South Carolina. ``It's a sense of excitement. It's a sense that
you're in something miraculous.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
