<HEADER>
A4792 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-DATELINE-INDIA0213-CO     02-12 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DATELINE-INDIA0213-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Filmmaker's creative license revoked
 &HT;    By Moni Basu
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALCUTTA, India _ These days, Indian Prime Minister Atal Behari
Vajpayee has more to worry about than plane hijackings, arch-foe
Pakistan and nuclear proliferation.
</P>
<P>
   Even as his government announced a much-awaited visit to India
by President Clinton to discuss security issues _ the first visit
by a U.S. president since Jimmy Carter _ Vajpayee was busy
reviewing, well, a script for a film.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian filmmaker Deepa Mehta's latest project, ``Water,'' has
turned into a deluge of controversy in the country of her birth.
The film, the last of a trilogy, depicts an outcast Hindu widow's
attempt to rejoin conservative society in 1930s India. But even
before a single scene was shot, Mehta and her film were in hot
water.
</P>
<P>
   Hindu radicals claim Mehta is grossly distorting traditions, and
after weeks of protests, angry mobs ransacked the sets the day
shooting was to begin. Mehta was even called a prostitute and
burned in effigy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very disturbing. Very absurd,'' said director Gautam
Ghose, who faced similar opposition when he made ``Antarjali
Jatra,'' a film that explored the practice of sati, in which widows
burn themselves to death in their husband's funeral pyre. ``As a
filmmaker, you have to be tactful. There are plenty of sensitive
issues here _ it's a very complex country.''
</P>
<P>
   But tact has not gotten Mehta very far.
</P>
<P>
   Following the attack on the sets of ``Water,'' the government of
Uttar Pradesh state, ruled by Vajpayee's Hindu nationalist
Bharatiya Janata Party, withdrew permission to make the film in
Varanasi. The city along the banks of the Ganges, about 400 miles
southeast of New Delhi, is one of India's oldest and holiest. In
the period in which ``Water'' is set, many Hindu widows sought
refuge in ashrams or homes in Varanasi after being turned out by
their families because of superstition that staying with widows
brings bad luck. Widows were often made to shave their heads, wear
only white, eat one meal a day and be confined to their homes.
</P>
<P>
   With production stopped at a loss of $50,000 a day, a desperate
Mehta flew to New Delhi to make a personal appeal to the prime
minister to save her project. That's when Vajpayee stepped in,
giving his approval after Mehta agreed to an altered script. Five
``offensive'' lines were removed from the script including one that
read: ``There is no difference between widows and prostitutes. Both
are soiled goods.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope this puts an end to the controversy,'' said Mehta, who
was finally able to start filming last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   It did not.
</P>
<P>
   Production halted again the next day when a Hindu radical
belonging to the Shiv Sena nationalist organization weighted
himself down with rocks and plunged into the Ganges in an attempted
suicide to protest the film. On Monday, a group of Shiv Sainiks
threatened self-immolation if Mehta's crew did not leave Varanasi
immediately. The district magistrate then ordered a 15-day
postponement of production and asked the film crew to leave town.
</P>
<P>
   We can't shoot anymore. We have to pack up and go. This is very
disappointing,'' said Mehta, who accused the Hindu radical of being
a professional in attempted suicides. She said the man had tried to
kill himself three times before in the name of religion.
</P>
<P>
   Several fundamentalist groups such as the Shiv Sena and Vishwa
Hindu Parishad have publicly vowed to put an end to Mehta's film.
They say a few altered lines are not good enough: The very theme of
the film tarnishes the image of Indian women.
</P>
<P>
   Controversy is new neither to Indian cinema nor to Deepa Mehta.
Her film, ``Fire,'' enraged Indian audiences for showing a lesbian
relationship that develops between two women bound by tradition and
trapped in bad marriages. But if Mehta thought she could put out
``Fire'' with ``Water,'' she was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   And now a disconcerted artists' community in India a serious
threat to freedom of expression.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is plain hooliganism and illiteracy in the garb of Hindu
militancy,'' said Indranil Chakravarti, Indian coordinator for the
European Union-India Media Meeting Point, a EU-financed forum for
cross-cultural film and television production. ``It seems like we
are moving towards an official declaration of India as a Hindu
state just as Pakistan is Islamic. That is what I find offensive.
The brouhaha is a total negation of the idea of India.''
</P>
<P>
   Though India is the world's largest democracy, the federal
government maintains tight control over the film industry, which
churns out more films each year than Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign filmmakers are required to obtain clearance from the
Information and Broadcast Ministry before beginning production.
Steven Spielberg, for example, was denied permission to shoot
``Indiana Jones and the Temple of Doom'' here because the script
was considered to show India in a poor light.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to check the script to see if there is anything
detrimental to India,'' a ministry official told The Statesman, an
English-language newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Even if a film is given initial clearance _ as was ``Water'' _
it could still run into trouble later. Director Louis Malle was
allowed to shoot ``Phantom India'' here, but the film has yet to be
screened in the country. And ``City Of Joy'' encountered all sorts
of production problems after the state government decided the
cinematic version of Dominique Lapierre's story was not a
flattering portrayal of Calcutta.
</P>
<P>
   ```City of Joy' was not my cup of tea. But it doesn't matter.
The film should be allowed to be made,'' said Calcutta filmmaker
Mrinal Sen. ``If the film is bad, the heavens are not going to fall
on the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Moni Basu, an assistant international editor of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, is currently on assignment in Calcutta, her
hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-12-00 1329EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
