<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4793 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SLAYINGS-OAKLEY12-COX     02-12 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLAYINGS-OAKLEY12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Murder suspect in Atlanta slayings talked of rich pals
 &HT;    By Joshua B. Good
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ At the Garfield's Phase II Beauty Salon, Reginald
``A.J.'' Oakley was known to brag about the celebrities he knew.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was buddies with Ravens linebacker Ray Lewis, movie
star Denzel Washington and members of the R&AMP;B group Dru Hill.
</P>
<P>
   The barbers who worked for Oakley figured it was all talk. They
used to tease him by asking why he didn't bring any of his
superstar buddies to the shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said the neighborhood was too bad to bring celebrities
to,'' said Kevin Parker, 32, a barber who used to work for Oakley.
</P>
<P>
   But now that Oakley, whom Atlanta police described as ``armed
and dangerous,'' has been charged along with Lewis with murder,
Parker said he guesses Oakley must have been telling a little truth
about knowing Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Just how he knew the football star is a mystery in the Pimlico
neighborhood of northwest Baltimore where Oakley operated a
barbershop for more than three years. Police say the neighborhood
is known for street drug sales.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, a boy who looked to be 13 offered ``weed'' to
people walking the streets. Restaurants barricade their workers
behind thick plexiglass and pass customers' food to them through a
drawer similar to what all-night gas stations use.
</P>
<P>
   Oakley's barbershop is padlocked. He stopped paying rent in
August. Even when the business was open, Oakley wasn't too good
about paying his rent on time, said Taylor Lee, owner of the
building where Oakley rented his shop for $425 a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once in a while a check would bounce. I'd have to come and
collect cash,'' Lee said Friday. ``He'd say he had a problem with
his wife.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Wife? He didn't have a wife,'' Parker chimed in.
</P>
<P>
   Parker worked for Oakley for two years. It was a tough two
years, Parker said. Most of the other barbers quit rather than work
for Oakley, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was he like? He was a low-down, dirty shame,'' Parker
said. ``He would even get into brawls with people over their
business. He could never keep barbers in there, never.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Parker's customers, Tony Downs, said Oakley once gave him
trouble because he stopped by to say hello to Parker.
</P>
<P>
   ``We exchanged words. We almost got into a fight,'' Downs said.
``But I left. I didn't want to go to jail for hurting that boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker said Oakley would talk about having spent time in prison
for a drug conviction.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina Department of Corrections records show Oakley _
who was born in Granville County, N.C., and once lived in Charlotte
_ has been in prison. In 1991, he was convicted of assaulting a
police officer, resisting arrest and speeding.
</P>
<P>
   Parker said that for a time Oakley drove a Toyota Celica, but
talked about becoming a big-time record and movie producer. Then he
started driving a new BMW.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got money,'' Parker said. ``He can get out of town and
hide out with someone for a while, easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
