<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4794 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-CALIF-SPRAWL-ART-2TAK     02-12 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-SPRAWL-ART-2TAKES-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES' RELENTLESS SPRAWL BUMPS BUCOLIC NEIGHBOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos, graphic and a map are being sent to NYT
photo/graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase
by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARITA, Calif. _ This is the last frontier, the place
where the suburban sprawl of Los Angeles meets a peaceful patch of
live oaks, rolling hills and quiet back roads along the Santa Clara
River, one of a tiny handful of wild waterways left in Southern
California. It is also a battle zone, the future home of Newhall
Ranch, the largest housing development ever approved by Los Angeles
County, with 21,600 units for 70,000 people to be built over the
next 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   To its critics, including neighboring Ventura County, which has
filed a lawsuit seeking to block it, Newhall Ranch is a symbol of
all that is wrong with California's decades of catch-as-catch-can
development, in which suburbs sprang up in ever-widening,
ill-considered rings.
</P>
<P>
   To its backers, Newhall Ranch is a sensitively planned
community, the vision of a responsible developer with a long track
record of building affordable slices of the American dream.
</P>
<P>
   But as big and controversial as it may be, Newhall Ranch is
nothing compared with the projected need for new housing in Los
Angeles County: about 25,000 units a year, according to the
Southern California Association of Governments.
</P>
<P>
   By 2025, the state's population of 34 million is projected to
grow by 18 million more (a whole New York state), and that of the
Los Angeles region by 6 million (or two Chicagos).
</P>
<P>
   That pace would exceed the boom years of the 1950s, '60s and
'70s combined in absolute numbers, though not in percentage. New
Californians are being born or moving into the state at the rate of
1,700 a day, or roughly one every 50 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``L.A.'s so big that you can take the biggest project anybody's
ever conceived of, and it is, in regional terms, only a drop in the
bucket,'' said William Fulton, an urban planner, ``which shows you
how hard it is to meet the need with traditional suburban
development.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you going to do?'' asked Fulton, the author of ``The
Reluctant Metropolis: The Politics of Urban Growth in Los
Angeles.'' ``Build 200 Newhall Ranches? The truth is, with 6
million people, growth has got to be both up and out.''
</P>
<P>
   That is easier said than done in a place where even residents of
modest means have long viewed a patch of yard and sky, a lemon tree
and maybe even a swimming pool as all but a birthright, and the
fight over Newhall Ranch is proof positive of how hard it will be
to change the paradigm. Planners and politicians may talk of
``urban infill'' and ``downtown redevelopment,'' but Los Angeles
has been steadily sprawling for more than 80 years.
</P>
<P>
   Since at least the mid-'70s, residents of established
neighborhoods have consistently opposed construction of
higher-density apartment complexes, leaving developers little
choice but to build in fringe areas like those near Santa Clarita,
a collection of old farming towns northwest of Los Angeles that
have been consolidated into the fourth-largest city in the county,
with nearly 150,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Los Angeles, it's part of our culture to aspire to live in
open spaces in single-family homes,'' said Supervisor Zev
Yaroslavsky of Los Angeles County. Yaroslavsky, a Democrat,
acknowledged that it pained him to vote for a project as big as
Newhall last year but felt he had little choice, given his own
constituents' opposition to living any closer together.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't want to live in skyscrapers like New York,'' he
said. ``People fled New York to come here, and once you've lived in
a single-family house with your own back yard, you're basically not
interested in moving back to what amounts to a Holiday Inn-like
existence.''
</P>
<P>
   The population of Riverside and San Bernardino Counties, which
make up the ``Inland Empire'' east of Los Angeles, has roughly
doubled since 1980, making the area the fastest-growing part of the
region, and the population there is expect to double again in the
next 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Such explosive growth has ignited widespread anxiety, and a
recent statewide survey by the Public Policy Institute of
California found that four in 10 residents said they believed the
state would be a worse place to live in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   The fight over Newhall Ranch, to be built in an unincorporated
area of Los Angeles County, has put the debate over urban sprawl
into particularly sharp relief because the project abuts the border
of Ventura County, an agricultural enclave that is Southern
California's least populated. For years, Ventura has looked askance
at growth and recently adopted some of the most stringent
anti-growth measures in the nation, which generally require voter
approval to rezone farmland or open space for development, or to
expand cities beyond their existing boundaries. Fulton, the
planner, calls this conflict the region's Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Newhall Land &AMP; Farming Co., the 117-year-old real estate and
ranching concern that is developing the project, says it is merely
keeping pace with realities and demand by building Newhall Ranch,
which is to be divided roughly between single-family houses with
prices up to $1 million and town houses and rental apartments.
Newhall began developing some of the 36,000 acres it owns in the
area more than 30 years ago after county tax assessors, watching
the northward growth from the San Fernando Valley, raised
assessments on what had long been agricultural land.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The result was the planned town of Valencia, a still-growing
leafy haven that boasts two office parks, two industrial parks and
a pedestrian-friendly Town Center mall that is the shopping and
entertainment hub for the Santa Clarita Valley.
</P>
<P>
   This suburb, first settled by workers in the aerospace industry
who were attracted by the short commute to places like the Lockheed
plant in Burbank, is now home to many support workers and
technicians in the entertainment industry, and to high-tech types
who work in the office parks of the San Fernando and Santa Clarita
Valleys.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite all that you would hear, and the outcries about
development,'' a house ``is still the American dream,'' said Thomas
L. Lee, chairman and chief executive of Newhall, which expects that
about half the buyers for Newhall Ranch houses will come from the
Santa Clarita Valley itself. ``We're providing homes to people who
just want a piece of the American dream like everybody else. The
large majority of people want to live that way.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Lee added: ``The people are going to be here, whether the
housing is here or not. They already have a serious problem in Los
Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   But critics of Newhall's plans point out that much of the demand
for housing in the region is among the growing Hispanic and
immigrant populations of urban Los Angeles, where families are
doubled up in apartments and cannot yet afford suburban houses.
(Hispanic residents were the only group in the recent Public Policy
Institute survey that said the state would be a better place to
live in 20 years). At the same time, Newhall's opponents note that
some 40,000 additional housing units have already been approved but
not built in Santa Clarita, and they would like to see these
developed before builders encroach on pristine land.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're just vaporizing your open space and watershed and
indiscriminately paving it over for something that I can't see as a
genuine need,'' said Lynne Plambeck, first vice president of the
Santa Clarita Organization for Planning and Environment. The
organization is part of a coalition of several environmental
groups, Ventura County and the state attorney general's office that
challenged Newhall's environmental review as inadequate, especially
in its analysis of water supplies for the new development. A trial
in the case is set for next month in a state court.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of opposition, Newhall scaled back the project from
the originally planned 25,000 units, and it has set aside about 10
percent of the units as lower-income housing and promised to
preserve about nine square miles of the 19-square-mile project as
open space.
</P>
<P>
   But the critics have dismissed the concessions and contend that
Newhall Ranch would damage the delicate ecosystem of the Santa
Clara River and threaten birds and other wildlife, as well as the
flood plain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sort of feel like sometimes it's a situation where if you
don't build it, they won't come,'' Plambeck said, reversing the
``Field of Dreams'' formulation.
</P>
<P>
   The reality is not quite so simple, and the growing population's
demands on state roads, schools, bridges and public transportation
are already a concern. Newhall itself expects to pay tens of
millions of dollars in the coming years for highway improvements.
But statewide investment in public facilities has lagged since the
tax revolt of the late '70s, which was itself fostered in part by
local opposition to apartment construction. That caused housing
shortages that led real estate prices _ and, eventually, property
tax assessments _ to rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you build fences around communities in areas that are
adjacent to the high job-growth areas of the state, you're not
going to meet your housing needs, period,'' said Tim Coyle, the
California Building Industry Association's chief lobbyist. ``The
politics of antigrowth initiatives not only limit housing, but
ultimately they're hostile to the economic and social interests of
the citizenry.''
</P>
<P>
   Some politicians, like Philip Angelides, the state treasurer,
have proposed investments aimed at rebuilding neighborhoods. As a
member of state public employee pension boards, for example,
Angelides has voted to invest $1 billion in pension funds in urban
real estate development, and he has restructured tax credits to
make $450 million a year available for construction and
rehabilitation of affordable rental housing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't take the view that even the most robust of public
policies is really powerful enough to shape growth patterns,''
Angelides said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But clearly, their absence will result in a situation in which
we're the victims of unplanned growth. As long as we remain
productive and attractive, we will have that growth demographic.
Our challenge is how do we maintain the livability and quality of
life that brought residents and economic vitality in the first
place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
