<DOCNO> NYT20000212.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4799 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BUSH-STRETCH13-COX     02-12 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-STRETCH13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush in critical phase of campaign
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush, his big-budget and
big-buddies presidential campaign hanging in the balance, is
entering nine days that could go a long way toward determining
whether he will become a president or a poster boy for political
underachievers.
</P>
<P>
   In what could be the most important stretch of his political
career, Bush is battling toward crucial showdowns with Sen. John
McCain in South Carolina, Michigan and Arizona, his foe's home
state.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will tell us whether the race will be over quickly or
whether this is going to be a divisive battle with both candidates
winning some states all the way through,'' University of Virginia
political scientist Larry Sabato said of the coming contests.
</P>
<P>
   At a South Carolina campaign stop Friday, Bush worded it a
little differently:
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, during times of adversity, you get to find out who
your real friends are,'' he said, confident that things are going
his way because ``the crowds are big and enthusiastic. ... I'm less
windy on the speeches, more windy on the answers.''
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, a prohibitive front-runner for the nomination until
people started voting, the goal is simple: Prevent the ``bump in
the road'' caused by McCain's big win in New Hampshire from turning
into a full-blown detour to two more years in the Governor's
Mansion.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina Republicans _ and independents and Democrats, who
are not barred from participating in the GOP primary _ go to the
primary polls Saturday. The outcome there could have major impact
in Michigan and Arizona, where voting is set for Feb. 22.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Steve Forbes' exit from the race, the upcoming
contests are largely one-on-one battles, though Alan Keyes is still
a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Though each state primary is a separate contest, all evidence
indicates that a win in one state can spark momentum in the next.
McCain trailed Bush by about 20 points in most South Carolina polls
until he whipped Bush in New Hampshire. Now the polls show a tight
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's suppose that McCain wins South Carolina,'' said Sabato,
``he would then almost certainly win Michigan and Arizona. Virginia
then becomes Bush's next big chance to stop McCain and I don't know
whether he can or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Republicans vote Feb. 29, the last major test before
the March 7 ``Super Tuesday'' contests in 12 states, including
California and New York, and the March 14 contests in Texas,
Florida and four other states.
</P>
<P>
   ``If McCain wins most everything, obviously it's over for Bush
and I assume he would withdraw shortly after March 14,'' Sabato
said. ``If on the other hand McCain is turned back, he would run
out of money and he would have to withdraw by the 14th.''
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, three losses in the next nine days might start a
domino tumble that would be hard to halt.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, although it's not quite panic time, it is time
to fish or cut bait before you lose another primary and get a real
black eye,'' University of Texas government Professor Bruce
Buchanan said of Bush, the man with the money and endorsements.
``It would certainly not be a flattering story told of him if he
managed to blow this lead with these advantages.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a time, pre-New Hampshire, when Bush victories in
South Carolina and Michigan, combined with a tight race in Arizona,
might have been enough to knock McCain out and effectively hand the
nomination to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, buoyed by the New Hampshire win, McCain seems
poised to ride it out unless Bush wins big in the upcoming
contests, something no polls indicate.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and McCain are sparing no energy or expense in South
Carolina. Both plan to be there all week, highlighted by a Tuesday
night debate that has the potential for full-contact politics from
two men who spent much of the previous debates telling people how
much they like and respect each other.
</P>
<P>
   The South Carolina battle has the Bush campaign in a
hunkered-down mode that differs from the less-intense attitude that
prevailed in New Hampshire. Bush, adopting a tone he declined to
use against former Gov. Ann Richards in his 1994 race and didn't
need in his 1998 re-election contest against Garry Mauro, is
attacking McCain personally, as an underachieving senator guilty of
some of the campaign finance abuses he curses.
</P>
<P>
   The upcoming battles also will test the prognostication
abilities of Bush political strategist Karl Rove, who said last
month there was no way McCain could win the nomination. Rove's
confidence was based on the campaign ``firewall'' theory that said
any of several states _ including South Carolina and Michigan _
were solidly for Bush and would stem any McCain wildfire ignited
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The race also will hit another major milestone sometime in
coming weeks. For now, it's a battle for momentum. The goal is to
drive foes out of the race by piling up victories.
</P>
<P>
   But if no pattern develops and each candidate picks up some
wins, it becomes a numbers game as the contenders work toward
piling up the 1,034 delegates it takes to win the nomination at the
Republican National Convention in Philadelphia this summer.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of this month, only 307 delegates will have been
awarded. But by March 14, 1,301 will have been doled out.
</P>
<P>
   If, somehow, McCain and Bush both keep piling up delegates, the
GOP faces the unpleasant prospect (''nightmarte scenario,'' says
Sabato) of a national convention at which the nomination might
still be in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
