<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4801 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-REBEL-FLAG13-COX     02-12 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REBEL-FLAG13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NAACP urges Texas officials to remove Confederate flag from
buildings, plaque
 &HT;    By Dave Harmon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ John Evans Jr. isn't about to get sucked into
the controversy over the Confederate battle flag. For the
67-year-old Austinite, it is a symbol without any power in his
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``From an old man born in 1932 who went through all that Jim
Crow stuff, the flag's not important,'' said Evans, who is
African-American. ``I know the controversy. People are bitter, but
what's happened has d. People need to get their minds and
hearts together.''
</P>
<P>
   But 135 years after the Civil War ended, the Confederate battle
flag still resonates deeply with many people, either as a symbol of
heritage and those who fought for the Confederacy or as a reminder
of slavery and a symbol of hate.
</P>
<P>
   Its presence on a plaque in the Texas Supreme Court building and
its use as a mascot at several high schools have brought the flag
under attack in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People,
which has urged Americans to boycott South Carolina for flying the
Confederate battle flag over its Capitol, wants Texas leaders to
remove the plaque at the Supreme Court building, which was built in
the 1950s with money from the Confederate Pension Fund. The group
also wants the flag banned from schools and other public buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The battle flag) symbolizes slavery, racism, and division,
and also disloyalty,'' said Gary Bledsoe, president of the NAACP's
Texas chapter.
</P>
<P>
   For 24-year-old University of Texas student Sabrina Everett, who
also African-American, the flag represents ``all the oppression
that the white South still wants us to be under.''
</P>
<P>
   That kind of view saddens Ralph Green, the former commander in
chief of the Sons of Confederate Veterans, an international group
dedicated to confederate heritage whose members have family ties to
confederate veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Green said the flag symbolizes heritage, but has been misused by
hate groups like the Ku Klux Klan.
</P>
<P>
   ``With me, it's simply a symbol of my heritage, my history,''
said Green, who lives in Fairview, north of Dallas. ``It's not a
white flag, it's not a black flag, it's the flag of a nation, and I
hate to see it used to divide people.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the national Confederate flag, a red, white, and blue
flag with three stripes and seven stars in a circle, is featured
across the state in displays of the six flags that have flown over
Texas, Bledsoe said the NAACP is focusing on the battle flag. With
its distinctive ``southern cross,'' Bledsoe said the flag ``has
been utilized by hate groups that preach that (minorities) should
be eliminated from the face of America for no other reason than for
being what they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe said he isn't planning to file a lawsuit, ``but I hope
people will do the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the state leaders who have responded to the NAACP's
request don't seem convinced a flag ban is the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush has faced numerous questions about his stand
on Confederate symbols during his presidential campaign. Bush has
said South Carolina's citizens should decide whether to continue
flying the Confederate battle flag in their state.
</P>
<P>
   When the NAACP asked for his support in removing the Supreme
Court building plaque, Clay Johnson, Bush's executive assistant,
sent the group a letter saying the governor supports posting an
explanation for why the plaque, and a second plaque bearing the
seal of the Confederacy, are displayed. Johnson wrote that the
reason for the plaques should be better explained.
</P>
<P>
   The NAACP has not targeted the second plaque.
</P>
<P>
   The state General Services Commission is working on the
explanatory plaques.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gov. Rick Perry said last month he won't enter the divisive
debate, adding, ``like it or not, the Confederacy is part of our
history.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe said the Texas Education Agency and state board of
education have an obligation to make sure the Confederate battle
flag isn't displayed at public schools.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Education Agency does not have the power to order
schools to stop using the battle flag, said TEA spokesman Debbie
Ratcliffe.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, the education agency ordered Robert E. Lee High
School in Tyler to stop using the Confederate battle flag, but the
agency lost its power to control school mascots when the
Legislature re-wrote the public education laws in 1995, Ratcliffe
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The choice of school mascots and symbols are completely local
decisions,'' she said. ``If people want a mascot ... changed, the
school board is really where they need to start. Short of
legislation, I don't think there's a blanket way to effect this
change.''
</P>
<P>
   Statues, monuments, and other tributes to the Confederacy are
everywhere in Texas. A monument on the Capitol grounds stands as a
memorial to the Confederate dead. At the University of Texas,
statues of Confederate President Jefferson Davis and rebel
commander Robert E. Lee have been the target of protests in years
past.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe said the NAACP isn't targeting statues or other
monuments.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
