<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4810 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-WEB-SECURITY-2TAKES-N     02-12 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-SECURITY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECURE OR NOT, THE INTERNET HAS BECOME A PART OF LIFE'S ROUTINE 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Calif., Colo., R.I., Wash.)  (nk) 
 By AMY HARMON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Jon Tara first heard that unknown vandals with unclear
motives had managed to sabotage several of the Internet's most
prominent businesses last week, the San Diego software engineer
posted a probing message to an online investing forum that he
frequents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this the end of Internet innocence? Is the house of cards
about to crumble?'' Tara, 45, wondered. ``Can we move to an
Internet-based economy while the potential exists for a group of
hackers to bring it to its knees at any time?''
</P>
<P>
   Yet by Friday, Tara had settled back into his normal Internet
routine, which includes trading stocks, exchanging e-mail with
clients all day, and checking traffic conditions before he drives
home from work. ``I could see discontinuing trading online if the
instances of this were accelerated, but it would be a very
difficult decision.'' Tara said. ``We're going to be dependent on
the Internet, and I don't think you can stop that.''
</P>
<P>
   While the assaults hobbled popular Web sites like Yahoo, Amazon
and eBay for only a few hours, the ensuing consternation
underscored how heavily both businesses and consumers have come to
rely on the Internet for everything from paying bills to planning
vacations.
</P>
<P>
   But as Internet executives beef up security and public attention
turns to the FBI pursuit of the culprits, some network experts _
and at least a few lay Internet users _ contend that last week's
electronic attacks should sound an alarm. As people are enticed to
put their personal, political, financial and even medical lives
online, those who counsel caution see a need for a more gradual
pace.
</P>
<P>
   They say that the kind of mischief that today might merely cause
delays and frustrations could eventually have more serious and
far-reaching consequences. Being blocked from an eBay auction for
four hours may be only a nuisance. But being shut out from ETrade,
the online brokerage firm that was also hit last week, had a more
direct financial impact on those affected. And what would happen
if, as many planners hope, all of a person's medical history was
someday stored on a Web site? A Netscape error message may provide
little solace to the next of kin.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should give us pause,'' said Lauren Weinstein, co-founder
of a group called People for Internet Responsibility. ``With all
the dot-com hype that's been going on, not enough attention has
been given to the fact that the Internet is not like the older
technologies on which we have built our commerce over the last
century. It has vulnerabilities that need to be factored into
decisions about all these important applications.''
</P>
<P>
   Yu Sun, a computer science student in Seattle, had another
suggestion for the Internet industry. ``Maybe they should stop
wasting huge amounts of money on Super Bowl advertising and spend
more on improving their security,'' said Sun, who was unable to
compare homework with a fellow student by e-mail last week while
Yahoo, their e-mail provider, was recovering from the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Spoilsport views are, of course, not popular among e-commerce
executives, who have sought to cast the vandalism as an unfortunate
cost of doing business online. Nor are many frequent Internet users
or technology investors receptive to the notion of downsizing
digitization.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic at the compromised sites returned to normal almost
immediately after the attacks. Online Valentine's Day shoppers also
seemed unfazed, with reports showing traffic spikes at sites like
1800Flowers.com and VictoriasSecret.com last week.
</P>
<P>
   As for investor confidence, while the share price of some of the
affected companies dipped this week, all of them had recovered by
the close of trading Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be problems with the Internet here and
there,'' said Donna Pelletier, 45, of Harrisville, R.I., echoing
the sentiments of many others on the eBay Cafe discussion group.
``This only lasted for a couple of hours, so I don't think it's
that big a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps not, or at least not now. Only a tiny fraction of
consumer sales _ 1.2 percent _ currently take place over the
Internet, according to the Boston Consulting Group.
</P>
<P>
   But several million military personnel will cast their
presidential ballots via Internet this year. Online banks and bank
services are proliferating. And online transactions, while still
small, more than doubled last year.
</P>
<P>
   The security of such transactions has already proved shaky. Last
month, for instance, an extortionist disclosed some of the 300,000
customer credit cards he said he had stolen from CD Universe, an
online music retailer. Days later, a new online bank, X.com, a
division of the La Jara, Colo., community bank First Western
National Bank, discovered that for almost a month, its customers
had been able to transfer funds from any other account in the
nation's banking system to accounts at the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, as businesses transfer more of their internal
operations online, the potential toll rises. ``The biggest risk is
not what we've seen so far, it's if hackers start to attack
business-to-business sites,'' said David Pecaut, head of Boston
Consulting's e-commerce practice.
</P>
<P>
   That's partly why consultants urge their Internet clients to go
the ``clicks and mortar'' route, operating through multiple
channels. Charles Schwab, the brokerage firm, which has call
centers and physical branches as well as a Web service, is often
held up as a model.
</P>
<P>
   Whether confidence in the Internet as an economic engine
declines at all after last week's brazen attacks may depend on
whether law enforcement authorities are able to apprehend whoever
orchestrated the electronic incursions. Yet even if the rule of law
prevails in this instance, Internet executives acknowledge that
there is little they can do to prevent similar assaults in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way today to stop the attack from occurring if it
gets launched,'' said Greg Hawkins, chief executive of Buy.com, one
of the sites disabled by a deluge of data on Tuesday, the day it
went public. ``All we believe we can really do is to ensure that we
can deal with it as rapidly and efficiently as possible.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The form of assault on the sites last week, known as denial of
service, is particularly difficult to defend against. Essentially,
intruders use third-party machines to overwhelm the victim's
servers, preventing customers from gaining access to the site.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, lax security on any of the millions of computers
connected to the Internet leaves every other one exposed.
</P>
<P>
   E-commerce executives prefer to compare their security risks to
those of real-world retailers. On the Internet, they note, stores
are open all day, they do not worry about shoplifting, and they can
operate much more efficiently. Occasional interruptions of service
are unfortunate, but hardly cataclysmic.
</P>
<P>
   But Web retailers offer vandals a single target to attack
instead of a series of separate stores. Critics argue that such
attacks are likely to increase both because of the network's
inherent security flaws and because vandals will discover they are
able to achieve a dramatic effect with comparatively little effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``The French farmers blockading the McDonald's were not that
effective,'' said Tom Eisenmann, who teaches e-commerce at the
Harvard Business School. `What's different here is the scale.`
</P>
<P>
   The Internet's scale _ and its sheer ubiquity _ are why even
disgruntled Internet users are hanging tough. After being shut out
of Yahoo last week, Sun and his friend briefly contemplated faxing
their homework. But instead, they signed up for free e-mail
accounts at another Web site. ``E-mail,'' Sun said, ``is so much
easier.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
