<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, Feb. 13, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wintry precipitation will fall from the north central
Mississippi Valley across the lower Great Lakes to the interior
Northeast. A large, developing storm in Missouri will draw very
mild, moist air northward from the Gulf of Mexico. As the humid air
rises over a dome of very chilly air covering the northern states,
a mixture of snow, sleet and freezing rain will form. A swath of
moderate snow will coat the region from eastern Wisconsin across
central Michigan and southwest Ontario. Lighter snow will commence
in upstate New York and advance into western New England.
</P>
<P>
   Sleet and freezing rain will glaze surfaces from northern
Pennsylvania to southern Michigan. A cold drizzle will envelope the
northern Middle Atlantic region as ocean air glides over a wedge of
chilly air. An ice storm is possible tonight from the Mohawk Valley
of New York to central Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Repetitive showers, with embedded thunderstorms, will drench a
section of the Ohio and lower Mississippi Valleys. More than 2
inches of rain may fall over the same area that was soaked on
Friday night. This will lead to a rapid rise in creeks and streams,
perhaps above flood stage in parts of Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Cold, moist air will circulate into the western high Plains and
along the east slopes of the northern Rockies. Rain and snow
showers will diminish along the west slopes of the central and
southern Rockies. Clouds should break in parts of the interior
Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   A large disturbance off the Pacific Coast will send a front of
warmer, moist air inland. Rain will return to California and snow
levels will rise in the Sierra.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Thunder and Sleet
</P>
<P>
   On Friday evening, thunder and lightning was noted in the lower
Ohio Valley. Weather stations in this region also reported sleet. A
thunderstorm is the only production mechanism for hail, the balls
of ice that form in the rapid, turbulent motions in a cumulonimbus
cloud. Sleet occurs when a cold rain falls through a layer of
sub-freezing air near the ground and freezes into tiny pellets of
ice. Sleet forms in winter storms when cold air is trapped below an
advancing, rising warm air mass. Sometimes, this warmer air can be
buoyant enough to form thunderclouds above the wintry air below.
</P>
</TEXT>
