<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 14:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4835 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-FCC-2TAKES-NYT     02-12 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-FCC-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN'S ROLE IN RADIO LICENSING DISPUTE DISCLOSES BREAK WITH
PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: N.C., La., Pa.)  (nk) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER and DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Buried in the 2-foot stack of more than 500 letters
from Sen. John McCain to federal agencies released by his office
several weeks ago is a strongly worded appeal to the Federal
Communications Commission written in McCain's very first week as
chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The letter, dated Jan. 9, 1997, all but demanded that the
commission take no action on 200 contested radio licenses pending
before the panel. McCain told the agency that he planned to
introduce legislation to resolve the backlog and to rewrite the
60-year-old law under which radio licenses were then granted.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes, the potent lobbying firm of Patton Boggs was
quietly working toward the same end on behalf of a half-dozen
clients whose applications for broadcast licenses were among the
200 that had been frozen for four years. Handling the matter for
Patton Boggs was the son-in-law of McCain's Republican colleague
from Arizona, Sen. Jon Kyl.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting McCain legislation _ added as a rider to the
comprehensive Balanced Budget Act of 1997 and virtually unnoticed
at the time _ appeared to have the effect of wrenching broadcast
licenses from a number of owners of small-town radio stations and
benefiting a handful of rich clients of Patton Boggs.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's behavior as Commerce Committee chairman has been under
scrutiny because of his intervention, which came to light last
month, on behalf of a political donor, Lowell Paxson. The senator
wrote the communications commission last year, urging action on
Paxson's application for a television license in Pittsburgh.
Although McCain did not suggest how the commissioners should vote,
Paxson's application was approved.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, the radio license issue looks like an example of
hypocrisy, which McCain's critics, especially supporters of George
W. Bush, say he exhibits when it comes to moneyed special
interests: He rails against them, but does favors for them, as
chairman of the commerce panel.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Crispin Miller, director of the Project on Media Ownership
at New York University, says the case casts McCain's maverick
reputation into doubt. ``This case demonstrates that his sympathies
do seem to be squarely on the side of large corporations,'' Miller
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the real story of the disputed radio licenses is more
complex, far from a simple tale of a Senate chairman catering to
big business interests or connected Washington lobbyists. It also
provides a revealing glimpse of how McCain operates as Commerce
Committee chairman.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, a federal court invalidated the lottery system method
the communications commission had used since 1934 to grant radio
licenses. It ordered the commission to come up with a new system;
about 200 pending license applications were frozen.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the new commission chairman, Reed Hundt, a
Democrat from North Carolina and a close political ally of Vice
President Al Gore, was undertaking an effort to replace the lottery
system with public auctions of a variety of radio, television,
telephone and satellite airwaves. Auctions were a fairer system,
Hundt argued, and one that could bring big money to the government.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was one of only a handful of Republicans who supported
Hundt's push for auctioning radio licenses. The auction system was
vehemently opposed by the National Association of Broadcasters,
representing the owners of hundreds of television and radio
stations, who preferred the old system of free, eight-year licenses
awarded by lottery. It was the old system, in fact, that favored
those who already had licenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain said no more lotteries,'' said Blair Levin, Hundt's
former chief of staff. ``He was philosophically very consistent on
that.'' He earned the enmity of the broadcasters, perhaps the
biggest lobbying force with interests before his panel.
</P>
<P>
   A half-dozen applicants hired Patton Boggs' well-connected
armada of telecommunications lobbyists to push for a legislative
resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Applicants for licenses also contacted their home-state senators
and representatives to push for a solution. Among the most vocal
was the Lee family of Asheville, N.C. The family, which had
operated a small-wattage AM station in Asheville since 1938, wanted
to expand to FM.
</P>
<P>
   The radio license brouhaha was one of the first issues to
confront McCain when he assumed the chairmanship of the Commerce
Committee in January 1997. His staff urged him to propose
legislation to unclog the licensing pipeline, and he vowed to do
so. He told the FCC in a letter that he would soon introduce a bill
to authorize the commission to auction the disputed licenses.
</P>
<P>
   And while McCain never introduced a separate bill on the issue,
he did secure passage of an amendment to the 1997 budget bill that
gave the commission the authority to auction licenses. The
amendment was attached at a closed meeting of a Senate and House
conference committee on the budget bill and was never debated
publicly.
</P>
<P>
   Allowing the FCC to auction radio licenses was a potential
disaster for the Lee family, which feared (correctly as it turned
out) that its opponents could easily outbid it for the Asheville FM
frequency.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Lee, son of the AM station's founder, Zebulon Lee, and now
the 6,000-watt FM station's general manager, saw a conspiracy at
work. He believed McCain's proposal was covertly supported by big
radio groups and their Washington lobbyists, and he now says he
partly blames McCain for allowing big radio conglomerates to
flourish by outbidding locally owned radio stations for licenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a hypocrite,'' Lee said. ``The hypocrisy is he talked
about how awful the Telecom Act was, but he has basically created
the means to allow all the corporate giants to get their hands on
all the new stations. How does it influence the public's best
interest when the group with the most money wins?''
</P>
<P>
   Such a belief was fed by Patton Boggs, which boasted on its Web
site that it had ``successfully lobbied Congress'' to resolve the
radio matter to the benefit of its clients.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Patton Boggs' claim turned out to be exaggerated. Its expert on
the issue was Stephen Gavin, Kyl's son-in-law. His contribution to
the process was a narrow proposal, ultimately included in McCain's
amendment, to allow a 180-day window during which the competitors
for the disputed frequencies could reach private settlements.
</P>
<P>
   McCain aides insist that Gavin and others from Patton Boggs had
nothing to do with the drafting of the larger legislation. Patton
Boggs officials back them up, confining their contribution to the
relatively minor settlement provision.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one from Patton Boggs ever met with Senator McCain on this,
nor did anyone from Patton Boggs meet with me,'' said Mark Buse,
chief of staff of the Commerce Committee. ``It was I who brought
this issue to the senator's attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Many station owners avoided auctions and legal delays by
settling with their license competitors, sometimes for millions of
dollars. But the Lee family spent hundreds of thousands of dollars
on legal challenges and, after the sale of the AM station, gained
possession of the FM license, though it is still in dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's brother, Brian, a disc jockey and program manager at the
FM station, traveled to Washington to meet with McCain's senior
aides in September 1997. But Lee failed to change McCain's mind,
even with the backing of Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Buse stressed that the Lees should not be surprised that McCain
stuck to his position on the license issue. Neither the Lees nor
Patton Boggs affected his views, Buse said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Billy Tauzin, R-La., agrees. He opposed McCain on the
auction provision and is supporting Bush's candidacy. But he does
not question McCain's actions or his motives.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain had taken this position early on,'' Tauzin said. ``I
don't think it was designed specifically to help someone or hurt
someone. Every time you change policy you make some people happy,
some unhappy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
