<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4839 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-JAPAN-KAMEI-650&AMP;ADD-N     02-12 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-KAMEI-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICIAN SEES FUTURE OF JAPAN IN ITS PAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ By midday the visitors were spilling out of the waiting
room and into the corridor outside the office of Shizuka Kamei, the
longtime machine politician who has suddenly become one of this
country's most powerful and solicited figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very critical moment in Japan's history, that will
decide whether we have a good 21st century or not,'' said Kamei,
who is the policy chief in the governing Liberal Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   What many of Kamei's critics question, though _ and they abound
not only in the opposition and in business circles but also in his
own party _ is whether this staunchly conservative former policeman
is in fact trying to steer Japan into the present century or back
into the last.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, Kamei's scornful views on efficiency and
competition. ``The competitive market principle, which made the
United States affluent and made its people happy, cannot
necessarily be applied to Japan,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Kamei is an old-time politician, and he is trying very
hard to keep old-time Japan going, its industries, its society,''
said Taro Kono, a 37-year-old member of parliament from the Liberal
Democratic Party frustrated by Kamei's powerful influence. ``We lag
behind the U.S. because too many people like him are trying to keep
Japan the way it is, rather than adapt to our new circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, with each tentative step that Japan takes toward
economic recovery, after a decade of slow growth, Kamei has emerged
increasingly resolute _ and usually successful _ in his opposition
to the liberalizing reforms that many say are badly needed to
ensure future prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   His influence was most recently on display over the New Year
holidays, when, in the midst of the traditional news lull, he
prevailed upon the government to scuttle quietly an important
component of its longstanding plans to reform the banking sector.
</P>
<P>
   The move _ decried by Japan's leading business association, the
Keidanren, editorial writers and many economists _ was seen as a
costly sop to the country's thrift institutions and other small
banks, many of which would fail without protection.
</P>
<P>
   As the leader of a loose band of Liberal Democratic Party
figures and parliament members who unabashedly call themselves the
``anti-deregulation committee,'' Kamei is the unapologetic champion
of troubled businesses, and of a Japan whose past glories are now
fast fading.
</P>
<P>
   His is the land of high trade barriers protecting deeply
inefficient businesses, from steel and textile manufacturers to the
small retail sector, while relentlessly promoting Japan's sleeker
exports.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, while the government of Keizo Obuchi, the prime minister
who appointed him, often preaches the gospel of competitiveness,
the importance of the Internet and internationalization, for Kamei
globalization stands out as a real menace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Japan has a long history, just like America,'' Kamei said in
his large office, which is filled with expensive orchids and every
manner of the animal that is his namesake, the turtle. ``Our
society is based on villages and towns which have been in existence
for hundreds of years. During that time, a certain lifestyle has
formed, and we should attach some importance to these traditional
ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Many, however, see Kamei's championing of the little man and of
depressed industries as driven not so much by principle as by
political and financial calculations.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberal Democratic Party, which has governed Japan for all
but two years since the end of World War II, is above all a
vote-getting machine whose wheels are greased through patronage and
endless fund raising.
</P>
<P>
   Kamei has excelled in this world, and charges of numerous
financial irregularities have dogged him throughout his political
life, including involvement with the Japanese mobs that operate the
country's ubiquitous pachinko game parlors.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Kaoru Ogawa, a well-known corporate gadfly, who has himself
often been accused of associating with gangsters, recently called
Kamei the ``dirtiest in Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   Kamei gave an impassioned but nuanced defense of his reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a former police officer and have never touched dirty
money,'' he said. ``My fund raising comes from small and
medium-size businesses, and I have done nothing which could be
reproached me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a politician, however,'' he added. ``And I am sometimes
asked to take care of certain people. Some of them have sometimes
been convicted of crimes, but I have nothing to be ashamed of.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
