<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CAMPS _ NESTEROVSKOE, Russia _ At first glance, scenery
along the well-paved country road running across the Russian
republic of Ingushetia resembles many American back roads. But the
resemblance ends at the driveways, where instead of mail boxes or
house numbers stand hand-painted signs with the words ``Refugees
Live Here.'' An estimated 200,000 people, or a third of Chechnya's
population, have fled fighting between the Russian army and rebels
and moved to neighboring Ingushetia, nearly doubling this
republic's population. (Coker, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Thursday, Feb. 10.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-VOTEBUYING _ MEXICO CITY _ Somebody obviously didn't like
the idea of a special commission to prevent vote buying during the
campaign to select Mexico's next president on July 2. Elodia
Gutierrez, the commission president, received threatening anonymous
letters and phone calls that only stopped after she went public in
January. Buying or coercing votes by using public social programs
for the poor as bait is considered one of the biggest obstacles to
holding truly clean elections in Mexico. Despite claims they've
changed their ways, the country's ruling Revolutionary
Institutional Party, the PRI, takes ``the grand prize'' when it
comes to this illegal practice, according to groups monitoring
elections. (Ferriss, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTO (of Elodia
Gutierrez).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Thurs., Feb. 10.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS _ JERUSALEM _ The deadline for the framework
agreement toward a final pact on peace between Israel and
Palestinians is expected to come and go. That's a lot less
pessimistic outlook for the oft-turbulent Middle East peace process
than when Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak took over. What now?
(Kaplow, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Thursday in (i) International and (k) Commentary
categories.
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRIA-EU _ VIENNA, Austria _ Austria's new government took
office this week amid cries of outrage from around the world and
threats of isolation from its European neighbors and the United
States. Each night, thousands of raucous demonstrators marched down
this staid and elegant city's boulevards. The cause of it all is
the government's inclusion of the Freedom Party, which is described
as somewhere between neo-Nazi and American Republican. So far, the
greatest affect of the domestic and international indignation is to
greatly enhance Joerg Haider's popularity in Austria and perhaps to
encourage other right wing parties seeking power across Europe.
(Roughton, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Thursday in (i) International (k) Commentary
categories.
