<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 14:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4842 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CHINA-TRADE-DEBATE-NY     02-12 1274
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-DEBATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXECUTIVES MAKE TRADE WITH CHINA A MORAL ISSUE
</HEADLINE>
  (DUPLICATION WARNING: Also being filed in `i' category.) 
(nk) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ When a group of Florida businessmen paid a
visit one recent afternoon to Corrine Brown, their congresswoman,
they put her on notice that they consider trading with China a
moral crusade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way we're going to undermine that regime is to
infiltrate it,'' Frank Pearce, a business consultant and local
Chamber of Commerce leader, told Brown in a meeting. ``You can't
moralize across the ocean.''
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Nash, who runs his own import-export company, said
missionaries and businessmen will work together to change China,
unless Congress interferes. ``The missionaries are over there doing
the dangerous stuff,'' he told Brown, ``but trade is what opens the
doors.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration and corporate America have a great
deal riding on whether such pitches persuade Brown, a four-term
Democrat who considers herself a leader in human rights causes, to
vote in favor of extending new, permanent trading rights to China.
She is among 70-odd wavering members of Congress whom both sides
see as crucial.
</P>
<P>
   Congress must decide, as early as spring, whether to give up its
annual review of China's trading rights. In a landmark agreement
last year paving the way for China to join the World Trade
Organization, the Clinton administration promised that China would
be guaranteed the same low-tariff access to the U.S. market that
most countries have. But Congress has the final say.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton argues that the choice is clear. The often
tense relationship with China and America's global leadership in
trade would get a significant boost with a yes vote. Rejecting the
agreement would deal a serious blow on both fronts.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the decision is being hotly contested, and the outcome is
uncertain. Trade, in the final year of the Clinton presidency, has
become a tough sell. The failure of global trade talks in Seattle
late last year emboldened a coalition of labor, environmental and
consumer groups that now want to derail or at least delay trade
liberalization with China.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be the toughest fight we face this year on
Capitol Hill,'' White House chief of staff John Podesta told a
friendly group of farm lobbyists this week. ``There are people who
have strong views who don't agree with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Congressional leaders say they will not schedule a vote until
Europe closes its own deal with China, and the timing of that
remains uncertain. Yet nearly everyone agrees that the vote must
take place by June, before the election year pressures become any
more intense.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has not rallied to the cause. Republican leaders back
China trade. But, facing some ideological opposition in their
party, they say that they will not push the measure through unless
they get support from 90 or so Democrats, roughly half that party's
number in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Already, 53 members of the Democrats' left-leaning Congressional
Progressive Caucus have announced that they will vote no. Pro-trade
Democrats worry that the United Auto Workers and the Teamsters, two
unions determined to defeat the China accord, could make this an
excruciating choice for liberals facing re-election.
</P>
<P>
   To turn the tide, the administration and big business, which
strongly supports a China trade deal, have launched what they are
billing as the largest lobbying effort on a foreign-policy vote
since the North American Free Trade Agreement in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   America Online leads a coalition of computer and Internet
companies trying to give the China vote a high-tech spin, arguing
that free trade opens China's promising telecommunications and
Internet industries. Michael Eisner of Walt Disney Co., Sumner
Redstone of Viacom and Rupert Murdoch of News Corp. are pushing the
accord because it would increase the number of films they can
market in China.
</P>
<P>
   The two biggest business lobbying groups, the U.S. Chamber of
Commerce and the Business Roundtable, have vowed to try to whip up
support for the China trade agreement in several dozen swing
congressional districts with a $12 million campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville, the northern Florida port city, is viewed as a
test of whether business can stoke pro-trade enthusiasm at the
local level. Spurred by the national Chamber of Commerce, local
business leaders hold regular meetings with Jacksonville's port
authorities and the city's economic development board to plot ways
of persuading the city's representatives in the House, Brown and
Tillie K. Fowler, a Republican, to vote for China trade. Both have
opposed extending normal trade privileges to China in the past.
</P>
<P>
   The pro-trade forces are emphasizing the city's vested interest
in expanding economic ties. Its port employs 35,000. With sparkling
Toyotas and Hyundais parked bumper to bumper on acres of asphalt,
the port is also thriving on Asian cargo. It recently struck an
alliance with Hong Kong-based Hutchinson-Whampoa, a cargo handler
that specializes in China trade, to serve as a way station for
goods that pass through Hutchinson's new deep-water container port
in the Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish the downtown were just a bit farther upriver so people
could see all the traffic going through here,'' said Kenneth R.
Krauter, president of the port, which is about 15 miles from the
city center.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said she was ready to listen. She joined 800 local
executives for a Chamber of Commerce lunch late last month. After
the Pledge of Allegiance, a video tribute to Jacksonville's NFL
Jaguars and a pro-trade speech by a prominent local leader,
businessmen tried to pin Brown down on her views on China.
</P>
<P>
   They mixed testimonials about how important trade had been to
their own businesses with appeals to her human rights concerns.
They spoke of their passion for spreading democracy and
Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you change a totalitarian system?'' Pearce asked her,
stressing each syllable in a slow Southern rhythm. He answered his
own question. ``You get it exposed.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown gave them scant comfort. ``China has always been a
struggle for me,'' she said, describing how she had changed her
mind about whether expanding trade with China was a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have tried to have discussions with those people for seven
or eight years,'' she said. ``What have they tangibly done in terms
of human rights?''
</P>
<P>
   Some local business executives said they thought they had more
success converting Fowler. Over lunch, six executives of
Jacksonville companies described how their own business depended on
imports and exports. Hy W. Kliman, president of Global Sourcing &AMP;
Trading, described how he had built a thriving multinational
business on the strength of a single bowling shoe contract he
reached with a Chinese company in 1973, five years before the two
countries had formal diplomatic relations.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the business executives said that Fowler called the
session an ``education'' and told them after the lunch that she
would support the China accord. But her chief of staff said Fowler
had yet to decide how to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Schweitzer, an official of the national Chamber of
Commerce who led the Jacksonville organization drive, said there is
clearly a deep reservoir of pro-trade sentiment to be tapped. But
she acknowledged that the process demands patience.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has to be sustained long-term every place we try it to be
effective,'' Schweitzer said. ``The problem is that the most
important policy issue we face _ China _ is here right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-12-00 1425EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
