<HEADER>
A4844 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-NUCLEAR-GUIDELINES-61     02-12 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUCLEAR-GUIDELINES-610&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL FAULTS ENERGY UNIT ON PLAN FOR NUCLEAR AGENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Calif., S.C., Nev., Kan., Va.)  (lb) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A special House panel, unusually united across
party lines, criticized the Energy Department on Friday, saying it
did not follow congressional guidance in creating an agency to
oversee nuclear weapons programs.
</P>
<P>
   Energy Secretary Bill Richardson has long opposed creation of
the agency within the Energy Department, saying it would undercut
his authority. Congress mandated a revamping of the department last
year in response to accusations that China stole some of the United
States' most sensitive nuclear secrets because of lax security at
weapons laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Richardson dropped his public opposition to the
overhaul in the face of veto-proof majorities in the House and
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But critics in Congress suggested on Friday that Richardson was
continuing his fight behind the scenes, drafting a plan to restrict
the semiautonomy that lawmakers had carved out for the new agency.
</P>
<P>
   A panel of the House Armed Services Committee that is charged
with monitoring the Clinton administration's compliance with the
law said Richardson's draft plan assigned department officials to
similar jobs inside and outside the new agency, the National
Nuclear Security Administration. This overlap would undermine the
agency's autonomy, the panel said.
</P>
<P>
   The department still retains too much control over the new
agency's budgeting and management, and overemphasizes its authority
over the agency, the lawmakers said. The panel also chastised the
department for failing to consult with department experts and
outside contractors before preparing its plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The panel remains very concerned that senior DOE leadership
remains opposed to the provisions of Title 32, and lacks a strong
commitment to full compliance with the law,'' the lawmakers said in
a report, referring to a section of a larger Pentagon budget bill
that deals with the agency.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Mac Thornberry, R-Texas, who heads the panel of five
Republicans and three Democrats, said in an interview that the
lawmakers ``wanted to avoid bashing the administration and instead
guide them down the path'' before the agency formally begins
operations on March 1.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's ranking Democrat, Rep. Ellen Tauscher of California,
said in an interview that she recognized the difficulties of
revamping a federal bureaucracy late in an administration's tenure.
But she added that the department so far had ``failed to provide a
detailed road map'' for the agency.
</P>
<P>
   Seven of the panel's eight members endorsed its findings. The
only dissenter, Rep. John Spratt, D-S.C., said that the
administration's plan fell short of the law's requirements but that
Congress needed to review flaws in the statute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not think that we should criticize the department and
what it has done without also making a critical review of what
Congress has enacted,'' Spratt said in a written dissent.
</P>
<P>
   Energy Department officials defended their plan, noting, as did
the House panel, that a search committee had identified several
promising candidates to be the agency's administrator. Officials
hope to submit a nominee to the White House early next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We reject the criticism of our implementation plan,''
Richardson said in a statement. ``We are trying to make sense of
poorly drafted legislation.'' He added that he expected the agency
to be ``up and running on March 1, as required by law.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the law, the agency's administrator, an undersecretary of
energy, would have broad authority over policy, budgeting and
counterintelligence for nuclear programs. The administrator would
report directly to the secretary of energy.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The agency's creation marked the most far-reaching legislative
response to two scathing studies last year _ one by a House panel
and another by a presidential review board _ that looked into the
allegations of China espionage.
</P>
<P>
   Establishing the new agency to improve the security of defense
information also begins to reverse a trend at the Energy Department
since the end of the Cold War to emphasize nonproliferation
programs over defense programs and nuclear deterrence.
</P>
<P>
   The other panel members are Duncan Hunter of California, Lindsey
Graham of South Carolina, Jim Gibbons of Nevada and Jim Ryun of
Kansas, all Republicans; and Norman Sisisky, D-Va.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-12-00 1428EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
