<HEADER>
A4852 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TEXAS-SEA-TURTLES-600     02-12 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-SEA-TURTLES-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURTLE'S FRIENDS SPLIT OVER SHRIMPING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH PADRE ISLAND, Texas _ Despite stepped-up efforts to
protect them, sea turtles keep washing up on Texas beaches, and
environmentalists are calling for new limits on the state's $600
million-a-year shrimping industry that they believe will solve the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, 450 dead and injured turtles washed up on the Texas
coast, a 14 percent increase over 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Of particular concern is the Kemp's ridley turtle, a
wide-ranging turtle that nests mainly in one place in the world: a
90-mile stretch of beach in northern Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, Texas biologists have taken elaborate steps to
develop a second nesting area along the South Texas coast. Their
efforts have included transplanting eggs from Mexico and raising
silver-dollar-size hatchlings in laboratory buckets for about a
year. And their work seems to be paying off. In 1999 they found 16
nests in South Texas, up from six in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Kemp's ridley turtle is endangered. Scientists believe that
many are killed or injured when they are inadvertently caught in
shrimp nets, even though federal law requires shrimpers to use
devices that let turtles escape from the nets.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as shrimp season opens, the turtles start washing up
dead,'' said Teri Shore, a spokeswoman for the Sea Turtle
Restoration Project, an advocacy group for the turtles. ``This we
know, year after year.''
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, state officials began boarding shrimp boats to make
sure they were complying with laws protecting the turtles.
</P>
<P>
   But some advocates for the turtles say it is time the turtle's
second home became an outright sanctuary: a marine reserve closed
year-round to shrimpers.
</P>
<P>
   In early February a coalition of advocacy groups donned turtle
costumes and took the issue to the doorstep of Gov. George W. Bush.
They said state enforcement had failed, and they demanded that
shrimping be banned off the beaches favored by the Kemp's ridley.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a critical nesting area and a critical migrating area,
both for turtles that nest in Texas and those that nest in
Mexico,'' Shore said.
</P>
<P>
   But the issue of a marine reserve divides even friends of the
Kemp's ridley.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the fishing and seafood industry, which does
not support a Texas marine reserve, has invested in protecting the
Kemp's ridley's primary nesting place at Rancho Nuevo, in the
Mexican state of Tamaulipas. Last year the industry bought land and
materials for an additional turtle camp there.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. supervisor of the binational effort at Rancho Nuevo,
Patrick Burchfield, said the industry's support was an important
factor in the 12 percent to 14 percent annual increase in turtle
nests there.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with the 924 nests and 48,000 hatchlings counted in
1978, the project's first year, biologists protected 3,648 nests
and returned 228,000 hatchlings to the Gulf of Mexico in 1999.
Burchfield said he did not want to risk the delicate coalition and
alienate shrimpers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could very quickly get back to where we were five years
ago: people in opposing camps and spending all their money in court
instead of trying to preserve the turtle,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Les Hodgson, past president of the National Fisheries Institute,
a seafood industry group, said that additional restrictions on
shrimping were ``not out of the question,'' but that the focus
should be on proven efforts at Rancho Nuevo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at a way to solve the turtle problem that
doesn't put a lot of people out of business and shut down an
industry,'' said Hodgson, who has been honored by the Commerce
Department for his turtle conservation work at Rancho Nuevo.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Scientists disagree on the underlying reasons for high turtle
mortality in Texas. With nests multiplying in Mexico, some suggest
it is inevitable that more turtles will be harmed as they migrate
through Texas waters.
</P>
<P>
   But Donna Shaver, a federal government biologist at Padre Island
National Seashore in Texas, said Mexico's turtle sanctuary had many
more nests and far fewer deaths than Texas. It is also closed to
shrimping in the nesting season.
</P>
<P>
   Texas officials say they will probably propose new shrimping
restrictions in the spring.
</P>
</TEXT>
