u s BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     02-12 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: PAYTON RETURNS HOME WITH ALL-STAR STUDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Jason Kidd and Gary Payton sat across the room
from each other Friday afternoon as the news media swarmed into a
huge ballroom for the ritual of All-Star media day. Kidd and Payton
were separated by only a few feet, though the journey they have
traveled, from childhood to adulthood, from Oakland to the NBA to
this lofty All-Star perch has been a phenomenal mixture of
coincidence and hard work.
</P>
<P>
   Who would have thought two decades ago that two kids, one living
high, one living low, would wind up in the same place, the same
prestigious league, back home and on top of their profession?
</P>
<P>
   ``To be selected as an All-Star is a big honor,'' Kidd said
``But to have it happening back home is even a bigger honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the room, Payton, who at 31 is five years older than
Kidd, echoed the sentiment. ``This is All-Star Weekend,'' he said.
``For me to be here in my hometown and play in front of my home
folks, it's going to be great for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's game is the latest step of their parallel evolution.
For much of their lives, the gregarious, tough-as-nails Payton was
the teacher. The milder, younger Kidd was the student, watching in
awe as Payton went from high school to Oregon State to the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Payton remembers Kidd as a 12-year-old coming around to play
pickup games. When Payton was an NBA rookie with Seattle and Kidd
was a hot-shot high school senior, Payton sent him down to earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He let me take the ball out first,'' Kidd recalled, ``and
really tried to show me that my offense skills weren't up to par.''
</P>
<P>
   Kidd tried a patented crossover move and Payton stole the ball.
Kidd drove; Payton suffocated him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was something that really blew me away,'' Kidd said,
``because I thought I could get a shot off against anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew he was a good defensive player, and I thought he would,
you know, let up at some point. But he didn't. For me it was an ego
check.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the student has surpassed the teacher. At least in the view
of fans. Kidd received 1,061,031 votes, the most among guards in
the West. Payton was selected as a reserve by coaches after
receiving the third-most votes. Payton, who started the last two
All-Star Games, will come off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, when someone asked Kidd who was the best, he
demurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``At talking? Definitely Gary,'' Kidd said. At the game? ``I'd
have to go with Gary. You never disrespect your elders. I think
he's having an MVP season.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Kidd, Payton said, ``Jason's been destined for the NBA since
he could walk.''
</P>
<P>
   Kidd and Payton underline distinctions within similarities. They
are Californians, born in Oakland. But their lives began on
separate planes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary is from the Flatlands,'' Kidd said Friday. ``A little bit
rougher than where I'm from. I'm more in the Hills, a little bit
more laid back. But when it came to basketball, it didn't matter
where we played, it was always going to be a battle.''
</P>
<P>
   For Payton, the road began in the rough-and-tumble life on 41st
Street in the West Oakland projects on July 23, 1968, the youngest
of five children. From there, his family moved into a one-story,
three-bedroom home in East Oakland that his father still occupies.
Payton attended Jefferson Elementary, played for the Jefferson
Cobras, a team in a recreational league coached by his father. Then
Claremont Junior High.
</P>
<P>
   Payton finally climbed to Kidd's Hills when he attended Skyline
High School there, 12 miles from his house. He struggled
academically and was forced off the team.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, after a nose-to-nose confrontation with his father and
a commitment to buckle down, Payton achieved a balance between
academics and athletics. He went on to Oregon State and an
All-American career.
</P>
<P>
   Kidd was a phenom as a sophomore at St. Joseph's High School in
Alameda. There was an All-American career at California-Berkeley.
He was drafted by the Dallas Mavericks in 1994, then traded to the
Phoenix Suns in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The challenges for Kidd would come later in life. Learning to
work hard, get tougher, achieve a level of responsibility
commensurate with his talent. As a pro, there was a late-night car
accident from which he fled, then a paternity suit and another
lawsuit charging that Kidd hit a woman at his 21st birthday party.
He settled both cases. As a pro basketball player, Kidd was on
cruise control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earlier in my career, practice was something where I just went
through the motions,'' he said. ``I thought I was saving myself for
the game. As I found out later, if you practice just as hard as you
play, the game will be a lot easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, Kidd's father, Steve, died of a sudden heart
attack. His father's death was a jolt and a wake-up call and a
message. The message will resonate when Kidd takes the floor
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts that my dad won't be there to see me in person,''
Kidd said, ``but he'll be there in spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   This All-Star Game illustrates mentorship at its best. Kidd is
no longer coasting. Payton never did.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
