<HEADLINE>
AM-NYT-BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
 Repeating for all needing.  (lh) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, Feb. 13:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN-GOVTS-LOBBY (Washington) _ Some countries, such as
Israel, Greece and Taiwan, have always had a strong presence in the
parlors of policy-making in the capital. But the depth and breadth
of lobbying by individual countries has grown in recent years, and
foreign governments are now paying out tens of thousands of dollars
a month. By Raymond Bonner.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-MILITARY (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ Perhaps the most
telling insult to Indonesia's armed forces, people here say, is
that mothers no longer encourage their daughters to marry a
military man. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   MISSILE-SHIELD-ANXIETY (Washington) _ European allies have
expressed increasing concerns about the Clinton administration's
plans to negotiate with Russia to allow deployment of a missile
shield, and about how much the Europeans are being consulted in the
matter. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   CONGO-U.N. (United Nations) _ African governments, unable to
bring about a cease-fire in the widening war in eastern Congo, want
the United Nations to take on the job of disarming combatants,
diplomats from the region say. They also want a peacekeeping force
much larger than the 5,537-member mission now being proposed in an
American-sponsored Security Council resolution. By Barbara
Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   CONGO-ETHNIC-WAR (Bunia, Congo) _ Another ethnic war is erupting
in central Africa, this time a tribal conflict in Congo fought
mostly with machetes and barbed arrows that nurses in a hospital
near here collect in a little white box. Some of the barbs are
still covered with blood and flesh. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-KAMEI (Tokyo) _ By midday, the visitors were spilling out
of the waiting room and into the corridor outside the office of
Shizuka Kamei, the longtime machine politician who has suddenly
become one of this country's most powerful and solicited figures.
By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND (Belfast, Northern Ireland) _ A frantic week of talks
and ultimatums and deadlines that fed the grim conviction that
Northern Ireland was discarding a promising chance to escape its
rancorous past ended Saturday on a surprisingly benign and
forward-looking note. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-SPRAWL (Santa Clarita, Calif.) _ This is the future home
of Newhall Ranch, the largest housing development ever approved by
Los Angeles County, with 21,600 units for 70,000 people to be built
over the next 20 years. To its critics, Newhall Ranch is a symbol
of all that is wrong with California's decades of
catch-as-catch-can development. But big as it may be, Newhall Ranch
is nothing compared with the projected need for new housing in Los
Angeles County: about 25,000 units a year, according to the
Southern California Association of Governments. By 2025, the
state's population of 34 million is projected to grow by 18 million
more (a whole New York state) and that of the Los Angeles region by
6 million (or two Chicagos). By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-IRS (Undated) _ Warning that continuing cuts at the
Internal Revenue Service threaten the nation's tax system, the
Clinton administration is proposing more money to find cheaters and
make them pay up. And the agency's top official has begun
emphasizing that getting tough with cheaters is as important as
helping honest taxpayers. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   WEB-SECURITY (Undated) _ The consternation over the assaults
that hobbled popular Web sites underscored how heavily both
businesses and consumers had come to rely on the Internet for
everything from paying bills to planning vacations. But as Internet
executives beef up security and public attention turns to the FBI
pursuit of the culprits, some network experts _ and at least a few
lay Internet users _ contend that last week's electronic attacks
should sound an alarm. As Internet entrepreneurs and investors
entice people to put more of their personal, political, financial
and even medical lives online, those who counsel caution see need
for a more gradual pace. By Amy Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   ALASKA-AIRLINES-REPAIRS (Oakland, Calif.) _ Whatever brought
down Alaska Airlines Flight 261 is only half of the airline's
problem. The other half is in the files of the airline's
maintenance hangar here, where workers and supervisors sign their
initials to thousands of work orders. In at least a few cases,
according to the Federal Aviation Administration, they may have
signed papers approving work that was not completed. By Matthew L.
Wald.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE-DEBATE (Jacksonville, Fla.) _ The Clinton
administration and corporate America have a great deal riding on
whether Congress decides to give up its annual review of China's
trading rights. In a landmark agreement last year paving the way
for China to join the World Trade Organization, the Clinton
administration promised that China would be guaranteed the same
low-tariff access to the U.S. market that most countries have. But
Congress has the final say. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-SEA-TURTLES (South Padre Island, Texas) _ Despite
stepped-up efforts to protect them, sea turtles keep washing up on
Texas beaches, and environmentalists are calling for new limits on
the state's $600 million-a-year shrimping industry that they
believe will solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   WEST-POLITICS (Denver) _ Huge regional issues in what is loosely
defined as the Interior West _ eight states that account for nearly
a quarter of the country's land mass but only 40 of its 538
electoral votes _ have been all but ignored this year because of
the marginal role these states play in the nomination process.
Virtually nothing is heard from the stump about land management,
water rights, nuclear waste cleanup or endangered species. By
Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-FCC (Washington) _ Buried in the two-foot stack of more
than 500 letters from Sen. John McCain to federal agencies released
by his office several weeks ago is a strongly worded appeal to the
Federal Communications Commission written in McCain's very first
week as chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee. The letter,
dated Jan. 9, 1997, all but demanded that the commission take no
action on 200 contested radio licenses pending before the panel. By
John M. Broder and Don Van Natta Jr.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Keyes hangs on; Brouhaha over Bush
visit; In-fighting in GOP. By B. Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NUCLEAR-GUIDELINES (Washington) _ A special House panel,
unusually united across party lines, criticized the Energy
Department on Friday, saying it did not follow congressional
guidance in creating an agency to oversee nuclear weapons programs.
By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ King of the hoods. By Maureen Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   KRUGMAN-COLUMN (Cambridge, Mass) _ John McCain's bad idea. By
Paul Krugman.
</P>
