<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4895 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      02-12 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A BESIEGED AND BELOVED GURU'S WORTHWHILE LESSONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ore., Minn.)  DUPLICATION WARNING: Also filed in category ``s''; filed in
category ``a'' since this column contains information that may be
of interest to those covering the upcoming trial of Sara Jane
Olson, a St. Paul, Minn., housewife who was a former member of the
Symbionese Liberation Army and fugitive until arrested last June as
Kathleen Ann Soliah.) 
(rk) 
 By ROBERT LIPSYTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``If they think I'm bad,'' Jack Scott liked to say, ``they ought
to see what's going to come after me. The next reformers may be
anarchists and much more vicious than I am.''
</P>
<P>
   The next reformers were much more vicious than Scott, but they
were capitalists. While Scott, who loved games and the people who
played them, gave voice to the overcontrolled athlete, it was the
lawyers, agents and shoe sellers who adjusted the balance of power.
</P>
<P>
   They advanced Scott's athletic revolution by making the
performer who can deliver the audience more important than any
designated moral authority. They replaced the temple with the
marketplace, which was not exactly what Scott had in mind. But it
was progress. In Scott's time, an Olympic champion could be thrown
off the team for quietly raising his fist during the medal
ceremony. In this time, a basketball player who choked his coach
eventually got a better job.
</P>
<P>
   The first time I saw Scott, he was standing at the front of a
University of California classroom wearing red running shoes, a
baseball cap and gym shorts, which, in 1970, even in Berkeley, was
not considered appropriate academic garb. He brought several
hundred undergraduates to startled order by blowing a whistle. He
did that, he later explained, because ``300 yards from here, men
who are also supposed to be teachers act and dress like this all
the time, curse their students and impose arbitrary rules about
hair, clothes, social life, and no one thinks twice about it.''
</P>
<P>
   He was talking, of course, about coaches, a subject in his
course, ``Intercollegiate Sports and Education: A
Socio-Psychological Evaluation,'' because he wanted ``people to
think twice, then do something to make the university approach to
athletics more holistic instead of a fetish for performance
statistics, and stop those coaches who are distorting one of the
most creative and exciting activities of college life.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott was dubbed ``the guru of jock liberation,'' scornfully, by
the likes of the later disgraced vice president, Spiro Agnew, but
it was an accurate moniker. Scott wanted to teach athletes to take
control of their bodies and their games. He believed in discipline,
hard work, fair play, civil rights, equal athletic opportunities
for women. While he could despise the racism and hypocrisy of an
Avery Brundage, he could admire the idealism of the Olympic
movement.
</P>
<P>
   Scott was no ivory-tower theoretician. He had been a
hard-hitting high school football player and a college track
athlete. Although his avowed goal was to do well by doing good, he
was a jock, he wanted to win, to be celebrated, to kiss the cup.
This may have undone him; it certainly led him into the Patty
Hearst caper. He had only about five years as besieged and beloved
guru.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote the seminal ``Athletics for Athletes'' and ``The
Athletic Revolution.'' In two years at Oberlin, before he was
bounced with the progressive president who had hired him, he
created a prototypical Title IX program and hired Tommie Smith as
track coach. He worked with Bill Walton during the center's early
years with the Portland Trail Blazers, and he helped linebacker
Dave Meggysey with his excellent ``Out of Their League.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott was no shadow figure. He reveled in attention and
publicity. He loved being included on rosters of social activists.
In a bit of all-star name-dropping, he once told me he had been
turned on to margaritas by Fidel Castro. The chance to become
famous as the savior of Patty Hearst, to walk her back up from
underground, to sink the basket at the buzzer, must have been
irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   Scott, 57, died last Sunday in Eugene, Ore., at the home of
Micki McGee, his early partner in the athletic revolution and
mother of his three children. They had reunited in his decline and
married, for the first time, on Jan. 21. He had fought his throat
cancer in that focused way that jocks drive to the goal. In recent
years, Jack, a physiotherapist who had helped many world-class
athletes and had served as Olympic team physician for third world
countries, searched for treatments outside the mainstream. But the
opponent was too strong.
</P>
<P>
   Scott's life and legacy are important and valuable. He certainly
informed my thinking. But he also left me with a question and a
tantalizing doubt.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last October with the FBI, Scott claimed that
while he was helping Hearst elude the police in 1974, she told him
that she had arranged her own kidnapping. She wanted to break off
her engagement with Steven Weed, with whom she was living in
Berkeley, but she didn't want to give her parents the satisfaction
of having been right about Mr. Wrong. So she asked her local dope
dealer to make a connection with the radical Symbionese Liberation
Army, who could snatch her and make Weed look unworthy in the
process.
</P>
<P>
   According to Scott's story, as told to FBI agents and described
on their interview form, Patty fell in love with an SLA member,
Willie Wolfe, and became Tania the terrorist princess. After Wolfe
and other SLA members died in a confrontation with the police in
Los Angeles, Scott, with hero-hood and a book contract in mind,
went off to save the survivors. Eventually, with his parents, Scott
drove Hearst cross-country and hid her in New York and
Pennsylvania. Two of his close friends, the Olympian Phil Shinnick
and the writer Jay Weiner, also guided fugitive SLA members. But
Shinnick and Weiner eventually went to jail and Scott, the guru,
did not. I have always wondered what kind of deal Scott might have
cut for himself.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he has left us the answer. In those days, he often told
me how close he was to the Hearst family. Could he have been close
enough to that powerful media barony to have it put a lid on his
own prosecution in return for not revealing that Patty had lied
about her abduction? The prison time she served for her adventures
was nothing like the time she would have served had the judge and
jury believed she was not the victim of the kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
   The approaching trial in Los Angeles of Sara Jane Olson, a St.
Paul housewife who was a fugitive until arrested last June as
Kathleen Ann Soliah, once an SLA member, may bring some answers.
Olson is charged with conspiring to murder by planting pipe bombs
under two police cars, which never exploded, in 1975. Her defense
lawyer had petitioned the court to videotape Scott's testimony
about Hearst before he died, but the petition was denied. Hearst is
thought to be an important, if reluctant, prosecution witness.
Scott's revisionism could blow up the Olson trial as a wasteful
circus.
</P>
<P>
   The guru of jock liberation was always at his best pricking the
establishment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
