<HEADER>
A4898 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-NBAEAST0213-COX     02-12 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBAEAST0213-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jordan on Woods
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Tiger Woods won his sixth consecutive tournament
last weekend, rallying from seven down with seven holes to play, no
one was more excited than Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got goose bumps,'' Jordan said. ``Can you believe that? I'll
tell you what else _ I'm ticked off that I missed it. I'm ticked
off because I was supposed to be there, front and center, watching
it firsthand, right there by his side when he was doing it. But I
knew if I was there (as Woods' amateur partner), you guys would
have killed me in the paper for not being on my new job.''
</P>
<P>
   On their relationship: ``He calls me once or twice every 10
days, and we have great conversations,'' Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   NOT-SO-MELLOW RILEY
</P>
<P>
   Miami's practice of 6 hours, 40 minutes on Tuesday was Pat
Riley's revenge for a Sunday loss to the Knicks. Three hours of
film, the rest on the court and only two days after Riley portrayed
himself as a more gentle man who did not like the angry guy he had
become recently.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Mr. Nice Guy went over the New York game play by play on
video and ridiculed his players for their mistakes. At one point,
forward Mark Strickland allegedly was reduced to tears.
</P>
<P>
   FORTSON NO LONGER IN GREEN
</P>
<P>
   After raving about forward Danny Fortson, Rick Pitino gave up on
him after 23 games, for Toronto guard Alvin Williams. Fortson is
making $1.68 million this season and will be a free agent this
summer. The Celtics thought they couldn't afford to re-sign him.
Williams is getting $1.925 million this season and is slated to
make $2.1 million next season _ the last of his contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's throw the money issue out, which is there,'' the coach
said. ``We could not please him with playing time.
</P>
<P>
   VAN GUNDY, EWING DIFFER
</P>
<P>
   Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy admits that he and Patrick Ewing
disagree on playing time. Asked if Ewing realizes that he has lost
much of his effectiveness on a consistent basis, Van Gundy said,
``No, I don't think any player with pride can allow himself to say,
`I didn't have it tonight,' or `I should only play 15 minutes.'
Once you give in to that notion, you're on your way down. (Hakeem)
Olajuwon is coming off the bench in Houston, and he likes it.
(Utah's John) Stockton has no problem playing 28 minutes. But I
don't think Patrick can allow himself to think that way.''
</P>
<P>
   AMAECHI WHO?
</P>
<P>
   Orlando's John Amaechi had 25 points with seven rebounds Monday
after scoring 19 against Indiana on Saturday night, while Michael
Doleac, his partner in the pivot, scored 23 on Monday. ``We're
different kind of players,'' Amaechi said. ``And people don't know
who I am. They just think, `Oh, it's Amaechi. We've never heard of
him. He (stinks).'''
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN STILL A WIZARD
</P>
<P>
   The Wizards hope the Pistons agree to do a deal for Ike Austin,
but they are skeptical. As the trade deadline nears, it is becoming
apparent that teams don't want Austin because he has an option on
his three-year, $15 million deal that will pay him close to $6
million for a fourth year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
