<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBAWEST0213-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    As the Worm turns
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dennis Rodman barricaded himself in a side room for
nearly one hour Wednesday night after his first game with Dallas
and lifted weights.
</P>
<P>
   After ending an 11-month layoff, Rodman even broached the idea
that if it works out, he would like to return to Dallas next season
for one, final run. Of course, this magical, mystery Worm Tour
began with a 117-106 loss to Seattle at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me put it like this,'' Rodman said, who excited the
sellout crowd with 13 rebounds in 32 minutes. ``Tonight is a
perfect illustration so people know I can still play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can go out and get 13 to 14 rebounds any night I take the
court. Tonight, I would have gotten at least 16 or 17 if I had not
been in foul trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodman, by the way, is wearing No. 70 because the NBA denied his
requests for 69 and 007.
</P>
<P>
   JAVIE IN RARE FORM
</P>
<P>
   In Denver's bitter home loss to Minnesota last Saturday, referee
Steve Javie cursed Nick Van Exel, who did not play in the game.
Partner Tommy Nunez tried to call a technical on Van Exel with
eight seconds left in overtime because he believed the player said
something, and mild-mannered assistant coach Louie Dampier went
after Nunez in the corridor. Javie also challenged coach Dan Issel
to a physical confrontation. Issel was restrained by a team
executive, Dennis McGowan. Van Exel and Issel were fined $7,500
each.
</P>
<P>
   SHAQ ON A ROLL
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal scored 37, grabbed 16 rebounds and made 15 of
20 free throws against Minnesota in a 114-81 rout. He scored 18
consecutive Laker points in the second quarter. ``Once Shaq starts
getting 40, 50, you're going to start comparing him to the greats
like Wilt (Chamberlain) and Kareem (Abdul-Jabbar),'' Wolves forward
Kevin Garnett said. ``When he starts making his free throws, it's
going to be hands down who's the best player in the league, if it's
not already.''... More give-and-take between Lakers coach Phil
Jackson and shooting guard Kobe Bryant: In a three-game span,
Bryant's assist totals were 8-9-11, a total of 28, against eight
turnovers.... Being Bryant, impetuosness dies hard. He hit three
consecutive 3-pointers in a comeback against Denver, then put up a
fourth from about 30 feet. Jackson had a sub at the scorer's bench
before it clattered off. ``You know, I vacillate between wanting to
spank him and wanting to pat him on the back,'' Jackson said. ``And
sometimes it ends up about the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   KLEINE: GOOD REASON TO STAY
</P>
<P>
   Joe Kleine on why he's traveling the country with Portland
instead of enjoying retirement:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty simple. I was sitting at home at the end of
August, and somebody called me up and said, `Who wants to be a
millionaire?' I said, `I do,' and they said, `Is that your final
answer?' I said, `Let me call my lifeline.' So I called (wife)
Dana, and she said, `If you don't take it, I'll kill you.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really going to retire, but Mr. Visa and Mr. American
Express told me I better stick around another year.
</P>
<P>
   LONG DISCOURAGED
</P>
<P>
   Grant Long on life in Vancouver: ``I knew things would be bad
before they got good. But did I expect what's happening now? No, I
didn't. I thought we'd be better at this point of the season. I
wish I could put my finger on it. I just thought at this juncture
of the season we would be better. I thought we would be playing
with the cohesiveness you need to play with, and we're not.''
</P>
<P>
   HAWKINS RIPS CLIPPERS
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's Hersey Hawkins ripped the Clippers after the Bulls
came from 16 down to beat them. ``They are extremely talented but
it just seemed to me that they aren't playing as hard as they
could. One of the things I sensed when I got into the game in the
second quarter was that they were playing but they were not playing
to win. I told our guys to pick up the intensity and I think they
will sort of buckle.''
</P>
<P>
   ELLIOTT OUT AS BROADCASTER
</P>
<P>
   Sean Elliott is finished as a broadcaster because Spurs coach
Gregg Popovich told him he needed to spend more time around the
team. ``You can quickly become an outsider when you're not in the
locker room,'' Elliott said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
