<SLUG> BC-NY-ARCHBISHOP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE WEIGHS CHOICE OF SUCCESSOR TO CARDINAL O'CONNOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As Pope John Paul II surveys the Vatican's secret
list of candidates to succeed Cardinal John O'Connor as archbishop
of New York, he may wish that the walls of a little-known gallery
at St. Joseph's Seminary could talk.
</P>
<P>
   There hang the portraits of men other popes have chosen to lead
the Roman Catholic Church in New York, from Richard Luke Concanen,
so reluctant to take on the job that he died in the two years he
waited to come here, to John Dubois, the only non-Irish bishop to
lead the church of New York, shunned despite adopting a shamrock
for his coat of arms, to John Hughes, a scrappy leader who
subjugated a defiant laity and laid the cornerstones for St.
Patrick's Cathedral, Fordham University and St. Joseph's Seminary
in Yonkers.
</P>
<P>
   Through the challenges that these leaders tackled, and through
the city's historic rise as a cultural and financial metropolis,
the Archdiocese of New York has come to overshadow older
archdioceses, like Baltimore, and larger ones, like Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent letter to New York bishops, O'Connor said he
expected his successor to be named by March. The cardinal just
returned from a farewell visit in Rome with Pope John Paul II, who
is weighing candidates for a post he once described as ``archbishop
of the most powerful country in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Controversies debated to this day, like public financing of
parochial schools and reconciling Catholic and American values,
bubbled first in New York, and organizations like Catholic
Charities originated here.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't become archbishop of New York because you're
important,'' said Monsignor Florence D. Cohalan, 91, author of ``A
Popular History of the Archdiocese of New York'' (United States
Catholic Historical Society, 1983), in an interview. ``You become
important because you're archbishop.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the questions arising now, given the changing demographics
of the archdiocese, is whether New York Catholics will see their
first archbishop with no claim to Irish ancestry. Dubois, of
France, came so long ago that New York was not even an archdiocese
then.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor, chosen by the pope to lead the archdiocese in 1984, is
frequently described as the Vatican's spokesman to the United
States. He has strenuously advocated church teachings in an era
when many American Catholics do not agree with the church's
positions on abortion, divorce or women in the clergy.
</P>
<P>
   Cohalan ventured that O'Connor, who is expected to retire soon,
will be remembered as a ``very good caretaker.'' Asked whether he
meant of souls or of the church itself, Cohalan said the two went
together. ``An archbishop who does his duty frequently has to speak
up on issues that irritate people, like divorce, abortion,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-12-00 1513EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
