<SLUG> BC-QUIZSHOW-GENDER-THEORY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: IT'S HUNTERS, NOT GATHERERS, WHO COLLECT PELTS ON ABC 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Please note that the word AT within parentheses has been
used in the final graf instead of the symbol, which is
non-transmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
(mk) 
 By JOHN TIERNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Thursday evening, a few minutes after much of America watched
her try to win $250,000 by identifying a pseudonym used by
disgruntled movie directors (Alan Smithee, which she didn't guess),
Judy Tigay addressed a more interesting question: Why do so few
women play ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire''?
</P>
<P>
   The program's selection process, administered by a computer and
open to anyone, has provided students of gender differences with a
rigorously blind experiment involving millions of people. (On a
typical evening a quarter-million people phone to take the first
qualifying quiz.) So far 103 men have reached the hot seat facing
Regis Philbin. Tigay is only the 12th woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women are just as smart, but men are more tenacious,'' said
Tigay, who was back home in West Bloomfield, Mich., when the taped
program was broadcast. ``The men competing with me in New York said
they'd called night after night trying to get on _ nine times a
night if the line was busy. If I hadn't been lucky enough to make
it on the first phone call, I might not have kept trying.''
</P>
<P>
   During rehearsals at the ABC studio on West 67th Street, Tigay
noticed that the men remembered all the questions they'd had on
their qualifying tests. She and another woman contestant did not.
</P>
<P>
   ``This stuff is important to the men, especially young men,''
said Tigay, who at 54 is one of the oldest players. ``It's the cave
man mentality _ they have to go out and conuer the world, and the
young single guys have free time to concentrate on it. Women have
other things to worry about, like taking care of their homes and
families.''
</P>
<P>
   That theory jibed with my own experience as a game show
contestant. I was single, 24 and happy to spend dozens of evenings
training for ``The $20,000 Pyramid'' under the tutelage of another
young single guy, who had triumphed on the show.
</P>
<P>
   Using a stopwatch, he conducted drills in speed-talking and
trained the class to memorize clues to any word that would come up.
Over and over, we practiced blurting out a primary clue
(``Old-fashioned ladies' underwear'') followed immediately by a
secondary clue (``Blank Junction'').
</P>
<P>
   My skill got me on the show, through the first game, but not
quite to the top of the pyramid in the bonus round. Then I lost the
second game when my celebrity partner, Michael McKean, a wonderful
actor tragically unfamiliar with ``Petticoat Junction,'' replied to
my memorized clues by saying ``Tuxedo.'' I went home with a rug
shampooer and a case of Rice-A-Roni.
</P>
<P>
   It was not unlike the obsessive, testosterone-poisoned behavior
observed in an experiment with chicken. Researchers sprinkled two
colors of grain, red and yellow, and noticed that the
high-testosterone chickens single-mindedly went after a single
color.
</P>
<P>
   Once a high-testosterone male settled on red, he would ignore a
convenient yellow grain nearby and go off hunting for a distant
red. Meanwhile, the yellow grains were probably gobbled up by more
sensible females who gazed at the males in the way that my
girlfriend regarded me and my Rice-A-Roni.
</P>
<P>
   Men are presumed to be doing most of the pecking at telephones
to reach the ``Millionaire'' computer, and it's been theorized that
their experience with videogames makes them faster at punching the
right answers. But the speed record during the ``fast-finger''
round of the game was set by a woman _ four answers in 0.87 seconds
_ so that theory seems unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Another theory is that men tend to have an edge on quick trivia
questions. They grow up trying to one-up each other with baseball
statistics, and as adults they're more likely than women to
converse about topics in the news _ anything to avoid messy
emotional topics that might actually be personally important.
</P>
<P>
   To redress the balance, Regis Philbin issued a plea on the show
last week for women to pick up the phone and try out. But Tigay
wonders how many women will respond.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very competitive, but I'm an exception,'' she said.
``Women are geared to be nurturing and that doesn't suit the style
of this game. It's very difficult to be competitive when you feel
that you must make everyone happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps what's needed is a game attuned to women's subtle
talents at forging coalitions, one that rewards sophisticated
networkers instead of brutes trying to beat everyone at a simple
task. Suggestions are welcome here (jtier(AT)nytimes.com) for an
improved ``Millionaire,'' or for a whole new kind of game show.
Regis might like to hear them, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-12-00 1517EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000212.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4907 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-COLUMBIA-KILLING-NYT &LR;      02-12 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMBIA-KILLING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEHIND A MURDER SUSPECT'S COOL FACADE, EMOTIONAL TURMOIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   All week long, a small, close-knit group of students at Columbia
University has puzzled over the paradox of Thomas G. Nelford Jr.
What inner torment could have possessed a bright young man they
knew as a pacifist, artist and all-around mellow California dude to
suddenly slash the throat of a woman he had just taken home for
Christmas?
</P>
<P>
   If Nelford had not subsequently threw himself in front of a
subway train, dying instantly, his friends said, they would have
found it impossible to even imagine that he had killed Kathleen A.
Roskot, a 19-year-old sophomore and star lacrosse player at
Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to understand, but we don't,'' the Rev. George
Sullivan told nearly 800 friends and relatives Friday at Nelford's
funeral Mass in Oxnard, Calif. ``Our souls cry out: Why?''
</P>
<P>
   Deepening the mystery is the fact that the day before their
deaths last weekend, there were no outward signs of strain between
the two, some friends said. They shared sandwiches Friday
afternoon, did stomach crunches together and discussed going to see
the movie ``Angela's Ashes.'' Upon returning to her dormitory after
midnight, Roskot mentioned to friends that the couple planned to
stay in for the rest of the night. They were holding hands.
</P>
<P>
   After she failed to show up for lacrosse practice last Saturday,
her room was checked and her nude body was discovered. Nelford, 23,
killed himself soon after.
</P>
<P>
   While the police continue to investigate, some of Roskot's
friends have suggested that she was trying to end the relationship.
Such a rejection would have been devastating, Nelford's father, a
lawyer, said in a series of emotional interviews this week from
Reno, Nev.
</P>
<P>
   Thom Nelford said his son's seemingly unflappable cool hid an
emotional fragility, the result of endless discord between his
parents that, the father said, made his son unstable.
</P>
<P>
   Divorced in 1985, the Nelfords have grown so estranged that when
Carolyn Nelford, Tom Jr.'s mother, called last week to let her
ex-husband know about their son's death, he hung up on her before
she could tell him the news, he acknowledged. She called back and
left word of their son's death with his girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Nelford, a paralegal in Oxnard, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   There are signs that Tom Nelford had managed to overcome his
parents' messy divorce. He thrived in school, becoming one of the
best high school wrestlers in Southern California. At Rio Mesa High
School in Ventura County, he had a 3.5 grade point average, his own
rock band and plenty of friends.
</P>
<P>
   He entered Columbia in 1995. His major was visual arts, and his
freshman year seemed to go well enough. The Columbia sports media
guide called him ``one of the top'' freshmen wrestlers in the Ivy
League, and he finished the season with a respectable 17 wins and
13 losses. He earned the nickname Rugged Tom. With little money for
winter clothes, he could be seen trudging through snow in sandals,
jeans and a T-shirt as if he were strolling through warm California
beach sand.
</P>
<P>
   Nelford's sophomore wrestling season was up and down, and he did
not wrestle during his junior year, but he did find modest success
in art and music. He formed a band called Couchcase and recorded a
few songs featuring his frenetic guitar playing and scruffy voice.
He also had several cartoons published in the student newspaper,
The Columbia Spectator.
</P>
<P>
   Nelford spent more and more time on his art at the expense of
academics. He dropped out of college in the spring of 1998 and
returned to California.
</P>
<P>
   His mother sent him to counseling, but he expressed ambivalence
about re-enrolling at Columbia. He told friends that he wanted to
wander the country like Jack Kerouac, one of his literary heroes.
</P>
<P>
   He turned up one day at his father's door in Reno, their first
meeting in years. Nelford described his son at that time as
``emotionally crippled'' yet yearning for a connection. They talked
and cried together at a coffee shop. ``The father-son relationship
was so destroyed,'' Nelford said. ``We wanted to get it back
together.''
</P>
<P>
   In early 1999, Tom Nelford, then 22, returned to New York City
with no specific plan. Back in California, his mother was worried
sick. She would go weeks without hearing from him. ``She prayed for
that child every minute of every hour of every day,'' said her
friend Nancy Reddish of Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   Back on the fringes of Columbia, Nelford floated along. He fell
in with a small group of students, and spent his summer days
in-line skating, writing songs, smoking marijuana and playing his
guitar on the roof of the Beta Theta Pi fraternity house, where he
often slept in an oversized storage closet.
</P>
<P>
   He wore his hair long and scraggly, and gave little thought to
his ratty clothes. ``He was one of those guys it was hard not to
want to take care of,'' said Elizabeth Buckey, 21, another friend.
``He was so down on his luck.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Nelford affected an outward calm. His primary response to
everyday setbacks was a beatific ``Dude, it's cool.'' His outlook
seemed neatly summarized in one of his songs: ``Things could be
better, but I feel content. Because what I'm after, I represent.''
</P>
<P>
   In the fall, Nelford underwent an abrupt transformation as he
began to date Kathleen Roskot, the first serious girlfriend his
Columbia friends had ever seen him with. He cleaned himself up, got
a crew cut and took a job selling jeans.
</P>
<P>
   Roskot was full of drive and discipline, the two-time captain of
her high school lacrosse team on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Nelford's more bohemian friends did not understand the
attraction. She seemed preppy, standoffish. Once, when Nelford
introduced her to a friend whose bedroom walls were plastered with
photographs of marijuana buds, it was clear that she wanted to get
out of the room fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was, `Go school, go life, go career,''' Buckey said. ``She
would want to be changing him.''
</P>
<P>
   But the two had things in common _ athletics, contemplative
natures and a passion for the music and literature of the 1960s.
Roskot decorated her room with posters of Jimi Hendrix and Janis
Joplin and stuck up favorite Kerouac quotes.
</P>
<P>
   According to Romeo Petretich, who was dating one of Roskot's
suite mates, Roskot took Nelford to her home on Long Island for
Thanksgiving. During the Christmas break, the two drove out West to
visit his parents. His mother was thrilled. ``My prayers have been
answered,'' she told Reddish.
</P>
<P>
   The two then traveled to Reno to spend New Year's Eve with
Nelford's father. Thom Nelford said his son seemed happy, in love,
at peace. Weeks later, he received notes of thanks from both of
them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
