<SLUG> BC-LEVITT-WARNING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP REGULATOR TELLS INVESTORS IT'S TIME TO BE MORE PRUDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The nation's top securities regulator warned Saturday that some
of the most popular stock market strategies, including buying
stocks with borrowed money and rushing into hot new issues, may be
hazardous to investors.
</P>
<P>
   It was not the first time that Arthur Levitt, the chairman of
the Securities and Exchange Commission, had advised investors to
manage their holdings with caution and prudence. But his tone was
somewhat sharper Saturday and appeared to be an attempt to shake
investors out of a reverie created by many years of abnormally high
stock market returns.
</P>
<P>
   In prepared remarks to be delivered at an investment conference
in Los Angeles sponsored by The Los Angeles Times and attended by
individual investors, Levitt said: ``Successful investors, through
good times and bad, focus a vigilant eye on managing risk. Periods
of promise and prosperity are not an excuse to let your guard down.
In fact, it's times like these when you need to raise it even
higher.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview two days before the speech, Levitt said: ``My
sense is that many investors have become more emotional than
intellectual about their investment decisions, and this is the time
to point out to them the importance of analyzing carefully rather
than impulsively.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Levitt's chief concerns is that investors are borrowing
too heavily from their brokerage firms to buy stocks, a technique
known as buying on margin, without understanding the risk. While
borrowing to buy stocks can increase profits when stocks are
rising, when shares fall, indebted investors can have steep losses,
Levitt pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Alan Greenspan, the chairman of the Federal Reserve
Board, asked the SEC to investigate a troubling rise in the amount
of debt incurred by investors in recent months. Levitt is
highlighting the risks of buying stocks with borrowed money as a
result of the Fed chairman's request.
</P>
<P>
   The frenzy to own shares in hot initial public offerings is
another area of concern. ``With billions of dollars pouring into
fledgling start-ups with no discernible track record, naturally
investors are looking for big returns,'' Levitt said. ``But
sometimes this race to an IPO comes at the expense of laying the
foundation for a viable, long-term company.''
</P>
<P>
   Levitt warned his audience about the hazards of relying on
Internet chat rooms for investment information. ``The Internet,
with its low cost, relative anonymity and unprecedented number of
innocent investors, makes it ripe for out-and-out fraud,'' he said.
Fraudulent messages posted on investor Web sites have been the
subject of SEC enforcement cases in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC chairman also advised investors to focus on a company's
fundamentals rather than simply its future potential. Today,
figuring out what a company is worth may be the hardest analysis of
all, he said. ``But any way you look at it, many of today's
valuations seem to defy traditional explanation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not saying that the sky is falling down,'' Levitt said in
the interview. ``But it is fair to say that the biggest threat to
future prosperity is when people lose perspective.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
