u p BC-NY-SENATE-RACE-NYT &LR;      02-12 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-RACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP LEADERS WANT MAYOR'S ATTENTION UPSTATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alarmed that Hillary Rodham Clinton may be making inroads among
voters in upstate New York, Republican Party leaders have begun
expressing frustration and anger that Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has
spent so little time campaigning in a region that is essential to
winning the race for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody needs to light a fire under his backside,'' said one
Republican county chairman, who like others interviewed asked for
anonymity because they did not want to be identified as criticizing
Giuliani. ``You can't take upstate for granted, and we're getting a
little concerned about it. If he doesn't pay attention up here,
people aren't going to vote for a New York City mayor.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other Republican county leaders made similar remarks in
interviews on Friday. All three are crucial to building campaign
organizations in upstate areas where Giuliani is not as well known
as in New York City, and all three said that their motive was to
try to goad Giuliani into action. They also said that they still
considered him their best chance to defeat Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just feel as if the upstate campaign has been
nonexistent,'' one of the leaders said. ``He was around quite a bit
in the early fall, and we haven't heard from him since. I have
called a couple of times because we were interested in doing a
fund-raiser, and I never get a call back.''
</P>
<P>
   Another said that Clinton's splashy announcement last Sunday in
Westchester County and her media-saturated road trip across upstate
New York had made Republicans nervous. ``The anxiety's there,
because Hillary's off and running,'' the county leader said. ``So
it's, `Come on, mayor, let's go.'''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Giuliani has remained insistent that the best way for
him to campaign for Senate is to be a good mayor. ``People
understand that I have a full-time job,'' he said at a news
conference during a 14-hour trip to Buffalo last week, one of the
handful of times that he has been upstate in the last two months.
``And that the full-time job that I have is a very responsible one
and is one that has to be my primary concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Drawing a distinction with Clinton, who has never held elective
office, Giuliani added that people ``can look at my record as mayor
of New York City, and what they can say is that I would do the same
thing as senator as I did as mayor.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, Giuliani said on a television news program that he
had not wanted the race for the November election to begin this
early. In part because it has _ with daily dueling news conferences
and charges and countercharges between the two candidates that make
it seem like it is October, not February _ Giuliani has run a
series of expensive campaign commercials upstate, where opinion
polls show that he is still ahead of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, those polls also show that Giuliani does not have
the breadth of support upstate that Republicans traditionally do,
in part because many voters there inherently distrust mayors of New
York City. Pollsters also say that Giuliani's advertising campaign,
which began in October, has produced no evidence of success.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not enough to run 30-second campaign ads,'' said one of
the county leaders. Another said that while the commercials were
very good because they highlighted Giuliani's record in New York
City, ``you're not going to put together the campaign strictly
through broadcast media.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Jack Kemp, the former Republican congressman from Buffalo,
said Giuliani needed to venture outside New York City. ``It would
help if he were on the ground in upstate more,'' he said last week.
``I guess he hasn't started his campaign yet.'' Two weeks ago on
the Fox News Channel, Kemp said, ``I think Giuliani has got to get
cracking, particularly in upstate.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani dismissed Kemp's remarks when he was asked about them
on Friday after a speech at the Westchester County Republican
headquarters in White Plains. ``Oh, come on, that's just the latest
silliness of the day,'' he said. ``Next question. We're running,
we're running very effectively, we're doing much better than
anybody thought, and the newspapers need something negative to
write for tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani did take numerous trips upstate during the fall for
fund-raisers, speeches and endorsements of Republicans in local
races. ``He's right on it,'' William D. Powers, the chairman of the
state Republican Party, said approvingly in November.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last two months, Giuliani has been distracted by the
daily obligations and crises common to the mayor of the largest
city in the country. In December, he faced down a strike threat by
transit workers, engineered the ouster of his second schools
chancellor and played host, to glowing reviews and extensive
television coverage, of the city's New Year's Eve celebration.
</P>
<P>
   In January he delivered his State of the City speech and
released his 2001 budget _ both events so full of the good news of
financial surpluses and lowered crime rates that even Democrats
begrudgingly said they made for good campaign material.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Giuliani's campaign advisers have long been frustrated by
his dislike of traveling outside the city. He is reluctant to
leave, in large part because he loves being mayor and can never
predict what disaster might occur in his absence. Last week was a
case in point. Giuliani was in Buffalo when a bomb exploded at 4:41
a.m. Friday on Wall Street, but he could not return to the city
until later in the morning because of fog. He was finally able to
get down to Wall Street for a noon news conference, but then had to
leave immediately for an afternoon speech in Westchester County.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's advisers say that he would prefer to be mayor for
life, were it not for term limits. In his State of the City speech,
Giuliani concluded wistfully by saying: ``I'm never going to have a
better job. I've loved it tremendously.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-12-00 1531EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
