<DOCNO> NYT20000212.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4913 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TOY-FAIR-ART-NYT     02-12 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOY-FAIR-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEREFORE ART THOU POKEMON? AND OTHER ACTORS' TALES FROM THE TOY
FAIR 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By GLENN COLLINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Philip Buch, actor, clutched his script and did the
spiel one more time. ``So, Super-Ninja Action Man senses the evil
of Dr. X,'' he enthused, ``and is now ready to turn Dr. X into
sushi!''
</P>
<P>
   He paused, then turned to the director. ``Should I be touching
Dr. X here?'' he asked with concern. ``Should I pick Dr. X up and
start talking about his claw?'' He poked Dr. X.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, that's great,'' said Susan Wall, calmly. ``Try to be a
little loose with it. Try it without your script, whenever you're
ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus was the art of theater celebrated last week as hundreds of
frenzied actors and actresses rehearsed for the opening of New
York's biggest non-Broadway show. Ready or not, the curtain goes up
Sunday on the American International Toy Fair, the toy industry's
most prestigious annual trade show.
</P>
<P>
   Some 700 New York actors and actresses have been hired as toy
presenters during the weeklong extravaganza, which is by far their
greatest seasonal employment opportunity outside the city's
theater, film and television industries. The 30-year-old Buch
considered himself ``quite fortunate'' to have landed the role of
toy demonstrator for Action Man, a new line of 12-inch toys from
Hasbro Inc., the world's second-largest toymaker.
</P>
<P>
   Such performers personify the hot new offerings of the $23.5
billion toy industry during its annual stage production in
Manhattan, where nearly 2,000 toy companies from 26 countries place
multimillion-dollar bets to catch the eye of 40,000 visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers, buyers, securities analysts and a squall of print
journalists and video crews will deluge the Jacob K. Javits
Convention Center and the dozens of showrooms in Manhattan's
six-block toy district.
</P>
<P>
   Although Toy Fair (nobody says ``the'') is not open to the
public, it enriches the public coffers by $180 million, according
to the city's convention and visitors' center.
</P>
<P>
   The largest toymakers don't reveal their Toy Fair expenditures,
but this year all the companies are spending more than $30 million
on their elaborate productions, according to David A. Miller,
president of the Toy Manufacturers of America, the industry's trade
group and sponsor of the show.
</P>
<P>
   Competitors estimate that Hasbro and its archrival Mattel, the
world's largest toymaker, have each spent $10 million on their
presentations and showrooms this year.
</P>
<P>
   A pre-fair visit to Hasbro revealed room after room full of
actresses and actors talking to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not from a mental ward, we're just rehearsing our
lines,'' said Christopher Wilkes, the demonstrator for the toys
inspired by ``Titan A.E.,'' a Fox children's movie scheduled for
release June 16.
</P>
<P>
   This year Hasbro _ the maker of Pokemon and Furby toys and
Parker Brothers games _ has, along with its subsidiary Tiger
Electronics, hired 90 demonstrators. Their presentations are ``very
similar to a real play, with a set, costumes and a director,'' said
Wilkes, who is making his fourth Toy Fair appearance.
</P>
<P>
   In the Toy District as in the Theater District, performers must
survive the traditional casting rituals, then endure run-throughs,
technical rehearsals, dress rehearsals and costume-fitting
sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Revisions cease only when the curtain goes up. ``We cut and
change the script till the last minute,'' said Jennifer Donahoe,
Wilkes' director, who is an associate marketing manager for toys
for boys.
</P>
<P>
   The performers even suffer from stage fright, facing judges even
harsher than New York reviewers. ``The industry is the ultimate
critic here,'' Buch said, ``and it all comes down to whether
customers buy the toys.''
</P>
<P>
   And more is at stake than on the Great White Way. If actors and
actresses can affect the destiny of a $10 million Broadway musical,
the performers at Toy Fair can help determine the fate of product
lines worth hundreds of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the room with Action Man, Buch said he was ``having
trouble with the introduction.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I think it's fine to add your personality here,'' said
Wall, Buch's director, who has the offstage title of marketing
manager for Action Man and Pokemon. She turned to an interviewer:
``We want Philip to personify Action Man.''
</P>
<P>
   Did he ever: With his chisel-jawed good looks and 6-foot-4
frame, Buch was a ringer for the full-sized Action Man mannequin in
the exhibit. But Buch isn't just another pretty face. He has taken
roles on ``Law and Order: Special Victims Unit'' and in the
forthcoming Ben Affleck film ``Boiler Room.''
</P>
<P>
   So why do they do Toy Fair? ``Give me any opportunity to get
paid for playing with toys all day, and I'm there,'' Buch said.
</P>
<P>
   No but, seriously, why? ``I'm so vain, it's scary,'' he said,
laughing. ``I want people to see ME all day long.''
</P>
<P>
   Jewel Turner, a demonstrator in the Pokemon suite, said that
``every actor in New York City wants to do this job,'' adding:
``It's great _ 14 days of work on a job that hones your talent. And
for a lot of actors, it means they won't be waiting tables for two
weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasbro works with a half-dozen casting agents. In January, 100
performers auditioned. About 75 were called back and 50 were hired.
</P>
<P>
   The lucky winners, who generally make $200 to $400 a day,
depending on their Toy Fair experience and the toymakers' largesse,
perform from 7:30 a.m. to 6 p.m for 14 straight days, including
rehearsals.
</P>
<P>
   The pace is grueling, and the audience tough. The toy buyers at
the show _ jet-lagged, partied-out, poker-faced _ do not always
happily follow Hasbro's arrows to toyland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine that the buyer just came in from the airport, and it's
raining out, and his feet are wet and he's hating life,'' said
Michael Schaefer, 40, a performer of Hasbro Game Theater. ``But you
try to find a way to bring this buyer into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Since it can take a year to manufacture fully tested production
versions of new toys, most floor samples are hand-built prototypes
_ some costing $10,000. Prototype tragedies are not unheard of.
Terri Hidenfelter, a senior manager at Hasbro, said that last year,
in one National Football League toy line, ``Wayne Chrebet's head
kept falling off.''
</P>
<P>
   Although 97-year-old Toy Fair kicks off with that
another-opening-another-toy spirit, the curtain must fall. This is
not necessarily a time for tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the last afternoon, I'm going to gather everyone in the
cafeteria,'' Hidenfelter said, ``and say, thank you.'' She added:
``I'll tell them not to forget me when they become rich and famous.
I knew them when.''
</P>
<P>
   And then the actors have their grandest finale. ``That,'' she
said, ``is when I pass out the paychecks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
