<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 15:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4914 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-ASSISTED-LIVING-AR     02-12 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ASSISTED-LIVING-ART-2TAKES(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COSTLY NEW RESIDENCES FOR ELDERLY OPEN, BUT MANY ROOMS ARE EMPTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By TERRY PRISTIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Along the Henry Hudson Parkway in Riverdale is an
elegant new 15-story building with a marble-tiled entrance, a fancy
private dining room that can be reserved for entertaining, a
24-hour snack bar and a staff pianist who performs popular
standards. Operated by Atria, a company in Louisville, Ky., the
building is intended for well-off elderly residents who have no
medical need for a nursing home but may require some help taking
care of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Highly popular in suburbs all across the country, homes like
these were rare in New York City until two years ago, when
developers began trumpeting the city as an ideal new market.
</P>
<P>
   But in the five months since the home, Atria Retirement and
Assisted Living, opened in the northwest Bronx, only about 27 of
its 238 apartments have been rented. Elsewhere in the city, homes
with similar amenities are half full.
</P>
<P>
   And now many people are having second thoughts about the market
for such assisted-living buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Disappointing occupancy rates are raising questions about
whether developers overestimated the market for such costly living
arrangements, where monthly fees start at $3,000 for a small studio
apartment and climb steeply from there.
</P>
<P>
   Yet people who provide services to the elderly say there is a
strong demand in the city for assisted living, if it can be offered
at lower rates. ``The desire for assisted living is just
enormous,'' said Jean Murphy, the executive director of Friends and
Relatives of the Institutionalized Aged, a New York consumer
advocacy organization. ``The problem is the prices are very high.''
(The fees usually cover an apartment with a kitchen, two or three
meals a day, linen services, housecleaning and social activities.
Personal and medical care are extra.)
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Assisted living holds considerable appeal for people like
Margaret Lloyd, 83, who lives alone on the Upper East Side and,
like many elderly New Yorkers, has a rich cultural life. But she is
concerned about the day when it may not be so easy to get around.
``If I stay in my apartment, which is very tempting, and I get
incapacitated, it will be like being entombed,'' she said. ``If I
need care, I'm not going to get it, and I won't have a community of
people to talk with or see.''
</P>
<P>
   As they expanded rapidly on Long Island and in New Jersey, the
publicly traded assisted living companies bypassed the city itself
as an undesirable location because of high real estate costs,
complex licensing regulations and difficult zoning restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   But about three years ago, the companies began scrambling to
build homes. About a dozen had either opened or were being planned,
and well-known operators like Marriott were scouring the city for
more locations.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Developers said they were drawn to the city because of its
relatively large population of affluent older people and its heavy
concentration of the principal marketing target for assisted
living: middle-aged professionals seeking comfortable and
convenient surroundings for their frail parents.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, however, several companies have pulled back
from the New York market. Marriott, which had hoped to operate
homes on Staten Island and in Manhattan, says it has curtailed the
pace of new development and is no longer looking for sites in New
York. CareMatrix, a company in Needham, Mass., says problems
finding financing affected its decision to scrap plans to build two
homes in Manhattan and two in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   After trying for several years to convert the vacant Towers
Nursing Home, on Central Park West at 106th Street, into an
assisted-living home, the developers, Savanna Partners, have put
the building up for sale. At two other homes that Atria operates,
on 86th Street near Riverside Drive in Manhattan and in Kew
Gardens, Queens, only half the apartments are occupied.
</P>
<P>
   To some degree, what is happening in New York reflects a
national trend. The assisted-living industry has grown rapidly in
recent years, accounting for three-quarters of new housing for the
elderly in 1998. As the market nationwide began to appear
oversaturated, the earnings of some companies declined. Wall
Street's enthusiasm dampened, and capital for new construction
dried up.
</P>
<P>
   Susan B. Brecht, a Philadelphia consultant to the housing
industry that serves older residents, said that many operators had
been forced to scale back their expectations in many parts of the
country. ``They projected `fill' rates that were overly
ambitious,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The industry's problems seem to be compounded in New York, where
elderly people can be an especially tough sell. Even those who can
afford to move often prefer to remain in their apartments _
especially if they benefit from rent stabilization laws _ and hire
people to help them cope, according to many experts in services for
the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   While they may admire the concept of assisted living, many older
people shudder at the fees that for-profit companies are seeking.
``My parents were raised in the Depression,'' said Dorothy E.
Siegel, an education researcher at New York University who is
trying to bring her octogenarian parents up from Florida. ``They
have always had a very penurious attitude.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Older New Yorkers are often skeptical consumers. The assisted
living industry has a good reputation, but most of the new homes
are unlicensed, a status that is permitted under New York state law
as long as health care is arranged through licensed agencies. With
vivid memories of the nursing home scandals of the 1970s, many
people are wary of what Katherine Bachenheimer, an 89-year-old
Manhattan resident, describes as ``real estate ventures with
expensive rent.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, too, many potential customers are terrified of being
transferred to a nursing home _ which would be covered by Medicaid
_ if they could no longer afford the high fees. After a close
friend who is 74 became partly disabled, Jane Greengold Stevens
tried to move her into Prospect Park Residence, which is not far
from her own home in Brooklyn. ``We looked at Prospect Park, which
seemed perfect,'' Stevens said, ``except for the fatal flaw that
they wouldn't take Medicaid when the money ran out.''
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, some people said they would prefer a nonprofit
environment like the one proposed for a site on 95th Street and
Second Avenue by an organization called Health Advocates for Older
People. The fees would exceed $3,000 a month, but Friedhilde
Milburn, the president of the organization, said she had created a
special fund through private donations that could be used to
prevent anyone from being evicted.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these concerns, for-profit operators say they expect to
do well in New York over time. ``It takes a year to get a
reputation built in the community,'' said Pat Mulloy, the president
of Atria, which is offering incentives to prospective residents,
like a $1,000 decorating stipend. (The Atria home is facing
competition from a 17-story home, the Classic Residence by Hyatt,
that is going up just across the city line in Yonkers. The
apartments earmarked for assisted living or people with Alzheimer's
_ 111 of the 310 in the building _ will be licensed by the state.)
</P>
<P>
   In Sheepshead Bay, Brooklyn, nearly a third of the apartments
are already rented in a 102-unit home that Sunrise Assisted Living,
of Fairfax, Va., is opening, said Kevin Hunter, vice president for
operations in the New York region.
</P>
<P>
   Brookdale Living Communities, of Chicago, says it has accepted
41 deposits for a 218-unit retirement home under construction in
Battery Park City, Manhattan, where monthly fees range from $3,400
for a studio to $8,500 for a two-bedroom penthouse.
</P>
<P>
   Audrey and Jay Calhoun of Portland, Ore., who are in their 70s,
recently put down a refundable deposit for a two-bedroom apartment
at Brookdale so they could be near their son and his family, who
live near Washington Square. ``There are a lot of advantages to
being near family when something comes up,'' said Mrs. Calhoun, a
retired college counselor. ``The costs are more than we encounter
in Oregon, but comparing what an apartment costs in New York, I
don't think it's out of line.''
</P>
<P>
   Among local developers, Forest City Ratner, a partner in the
Hyatt project in Yonkers, is planning to build a licensed
assisted-living home in Forest Hills, Queens. Castle Senior Living
of Teaneck, N.J., is about to open a 93-unit home in Manhattan
mainly for people with Alzheimer's. Stanley Diamond, the chairman
of Castle, said his Prospect Park Residence in Brooklyn was 90
percent full.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing that his apartments are beyond the reach of most New
York residents, Diamond recently teamed with the Metropolitan
Council on Jewish Poverty to seek ways to build more affordable
housing. The state has a small Medicaid-financed assisted-living
program for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Middle-income nonprofit assisted living is indeed coming to New
York, but only in a trickle. This spring, the Hebrew Home for the
Aged will open a home with 60 apartments about three miles from its
nursing home in Riverdale. Village Care, a Manhattan organization
that runs a nursing home and other services for the elderly, is
building 84 units at 46th Street and 10th Avenue. Residents will be
chosen by lottery.
</P>
<P>
   To many people, this pace seems agonizingly slow. Helen Acker,
81, of Manhattan, perceived the need for assisted living when she
was saddled with the responsibility of caring for her own mother,
who lived to be 96. ``Our government agencies are behind the times
in not realizing the need for this kind of thing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But government's ability to bring about more assisted living is
very limited, said Herbert W. Stupp, New York City's commissioner
for the aging. ``It's very expensive,'' he said. ``To come in with
affordable rents requires huge subsidies. I'm not sure how much
government can do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
