<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mom checks best
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Toronto's acquisition of Darcy Tucker from Tampa Bay
fills the Maple Leafs' need for, well, a pest.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker has been one of the league's great antagonizers,
something the Leafs have needed desperately to go with all of that
skill. Toronto attempted to land Tucker before the trading deadline
last season.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker, who relishes his reputation, says he got his toughness
from his mother, Florence. When Tucker was 12, he was flattened by
his mother in the family's backyard rink in Alberta. ``It was the
defining moment of my career,'' Tucker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother, Dwight, who is four years younger than me, was out
there with me. I was putting the puck through his legs and
laughing.'' Florence then asked Darcy to try the same move against
her. ``When I went to put it through her legs, she gave me a
forearm shiver,'' Tucker said. ``She dropped me on my butt. Then
she told me, `Sometimes you have to pick your spots when to keep
your mouth shut.'''
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING HASEK
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo general manager Darcy Regier initially denied that he
held trade talks with Los Angeles involving goalie Dominik Hasek.
Regier recanted his denial after Kings GM Dave Taylor confirmed the
talks. But Regier said he did not initiate them and reiterated that
the goalie, in effect, is not for sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told the Kings we're not entertaining offers for Hasek,''
Regier said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Buffalo News, Hasek has a no-trade clause that
mandates the following: 1) the Sabres purchase his $189,000 home in
Amherst, N.Y.; 2) the team pay him a relocation fee of $500,000; 3)
the Sabres also pay the Buffalo Variety Club, a charitable
organization, $25,000 for a series of reachable statistical
plateaus.
</P>
<P>
   'BIG THINGS' BREWING
</P>
<P>
   The good news in Carolina is that center Rod Brind'Amour won 57
percent of his faceoffs in his first seven games with the
Hurricanes after being acquired from Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is that he had no goals and two assists, despite
playing with Sami Kapanen and Andrei Kovalenko. ``I'm doing enough
of the little things,'' Brind'Amour said. ``Now I need to start
doing the big things.'' . . .
</P>
<P>
   Carolina coach Paul Maurice on the push by some for four-on-four
hockey: ``That would be a crime. If the league thinks it needs
four-on-four skating to attract new fans, then we're marketing our
product improperly.'' Historians, take note: Hockey used a
six-on-six format until doing away with the ``rover'' position in
1911.
</P>
<P>
   DEVILS FEEL TRADE HEAT
</P>
<P>
   An Anaheim scout and the agent for New Jersey's Brendan
Morrison, who has been requesting a trade, were seen at a recent
Devils game. Naturally, everybody is making assumptions _ such as,
Morrison will be packaged with other players and sent to the Ducks
for Teemu Selanne. Devils players think that GM Lou Lamoriello is
getting ready to swing a major trade.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
