<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLFEA0213-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NHL head blamed for failing clubs
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In addition to his blur of accomplishments on the ice,
Wayne Gretzky's greatest off-ice attribute might be his Bruce
Springsteen-like flair for identifying with the common man.
</P>
<P>
   The trait was evident at the All-Star Game in Toronto last week.
Gretkzy was asked if he is surprised that the Canadian government,
under pressure from angry citizens, rejected financial aid to its
ailing NHL franchises.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty simple,'' Gretzky said. ``I mean, the whole
country is based on hard-working, 9-to-5 parents who do the best
they can to provide their families. A small percentage of the
country is people who are making over a million dollars a year. The
average person can't understand why people who are making $5- and
$6 million a year need tax benefits. So, it's pretty simple why
they rallied against it, and how can you blame them? It's too hard
for people to comprehend. If you are making $30,000 or $35,000 a
year and working your rear end off, the last thing that I would
vote for is giving a guy making $5 million tax benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it usually goes that way in professional sports.
Owners say they can't compete on the field of play without new
arenas and revenue streams, hold up local governments for tax
breaks and contributions and, failing that, move the team to a
market willing to meet their demands.
</P>
<P>
   That is why Canada figures to lose three or four of its
franchises to U.S. markets; Original Six members Toronto and
Montreal are the likely exceptions. What doesn't make sense is that
commissioner Gary Bettman is taking the heat for it.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Bettman was skewered by the sometimes
emotionally warped Canadian media in Toronto, where the All-Star
Game and affiliated events were held last weekend. Newspaper
columnists blame Bettman for not doing more for financially wrecked
franchises in Ottawa, Calgary, Edmonton and Vancouver. He also was
criticized when he announced that the NHL's Canadian Assistance
Plan, which provides aid based on need, was being extended only on
a year-by-year basis _ as opposed to a five-year extension, as some
originally thought.
</P>
<P>
   While Bettman would prefer not to lose any of the Canadian
franchises, it's not the responsibility of any sports league to
keep individual businesses afloat.
</P>
<P>
   It's not Bettman's fault the Canadian dollar has been devalued.
It's not his fault that the United States has more viable markets
than the northern provinces. It's not his fault somebody in Denver
will pay higher taxes than somebody in Quebec. That the NHL is
offering any assistance is probably more than the league should do.
</P>
<P>
   The strength of any sports league is its ownership and its
markets. But if the NHL were to flow millions of dollars into every
failing franchise, the league would suffer in other areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our priority, as a league, remains maintaining our Canadian
presence with six teams _ six competitive, viable successful
teams,'' Bettman said last week.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the NHL's responsibility to keep the Flames in Atlanta
or the Seals in Oakland or the Scouts in Kansas City. Nobody in
those U.S. towns said it was the commissioner's fault when they
bolted.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-12-00 1549EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000212.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4920 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HKN-NHLITEMS0213-COX     02-12 0480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLITEMS0213-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Faceoff with Wayne Gretzky
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   _ Player: Wayne Gretzky
</P>
<P>
   _ Position: Retired legend.
</P>
<P>
   _ On today's young players: ``We seemed to have lost the
creativity, the imagination. That creativity basically came from
the fact kids would go to the ponds and skate for six, seven, eight
hours a day, choose up sides, have two nets and no goalies and away
you go. If you take 10 kids now and rent the ice and say, `We're
going to play a scrimmage,' the first thing every kid would say is,
`What position do you want me to play?' We need to get back to just
the basics of having fun. I think that would go a long way to
getting the imagination back into our game.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On whether he has been offered a general manager's job and/or
ownership stake by any franchise: ``I've talked to a few teams. We
never got to the point where it was serious because at this point
in time it's not the right thing for me to do. I need to take a
step back from the game and get away from it for a while, and ... I
don't have the time to do it right now. It's a full-time
commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On Jaromir Jagr's backing of four-on-four hockey: ``Obviously,
it's more exciting. But one of the great things about our game is
the tradition. Five-on-five hockey, to me, is the way it should be
played. Obviously, we go in cycles. A few years from now, the
people will be saying, `We're scoring too many goals. We need to
clamp down a little bit.' So it's an evolution. I hope we don't go
to four-on-four.... Maybe we should go to four-on-four with kids,
in certain leagues and certain ages. It would be a way to get back
to some creativity with some kids who are 9, 10 and 11. There's too
much trapping instituted in Pee Wee and Bantam hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   THE SOUTH(L)EAST
</P>
<P>
   The seven-worst plus-minus players entering the weekend play for
Tampa Bay or Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
