<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLWEST0213-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Latest Mess(ier) involves possible trade
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Mark Messier caused a stir in Canada during the
All-Star break when he acknowledged the possibility of being
trading by Vancouver. Such a move would require his approval. But
Messier implied that he would not get in the way of a trade. ``I
just don't want this to turn into a sideshow,'' he said. ``This is
not about me or all my years in hockey. This is about doing the
right thing for the future of this franchise.'' At least four teams
are interested in Messier: Dallas, Toronto, St. Louis and New
Jersey. The Stars' interest is curious. They seemingly have little
in the way of prospects to give Vancouver in return, and they might
balk at the $3 million to $6 million it would take to keep around a
39-year-old whose offense is limited. Messier probably would be
playing as a third-line center, behind Mike Modano and Joe
Nieuwendyk. Then again, GM Bob Gainey and coach Ken Hitchcock have
an affinity for old guys.
</P>
<P>
   THE KIDD TO RETURN
</P>
<P>
   Florida goalie Trevor Kidd hopes to make his comeback from a
shoulder separation on Saturday against Pittsburgh. But Kidd
probably will be sent to the minors for conditioning for at least
three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the position we're in, where points are very
important, I don't want Kidd to come in and play cold,'' coach
Terry Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming that Kidd proves to be ready, the Panthers probably
will send Mikhail Shtalenkov to the minors rather than trade him,
to give the team a veteran goalie to expose in the expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   DEAN ON THE MOVE
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Dean proved in Atlanta that he could not be one of a
team's first four defensemen. In Dallas, he wasn't solid enough
even in a lesser role, which prompted the Stars to move him as part
of a package for Sylvain Cote and Dave Manson. Cote gives the Stars
another solid puck-moving defensemen who can play the power play,
which should take some pressure off Sergei Zubov.
</P>
<P>
   NOT AN ALL-STAR EFFORT
</P>
<P>
   The NHL's best plus-minus player, Detroit defenseman Chris
Chelios, was an atypical minus-five in North America's 9-4 loss to
the World in last week's All-Star Game. His postgame reaction:
``Yeah, I'm tired. I'm tired of fishing the puck out of my own
net.'' ... St. Louis goalie Roman Turek said he doesn't think that
league officials have cracked down on goaltender interference, as
promised, not after Detroit's Pat Verbeek crashed the crease the
other night. ``Goalie interference? I don't know what that means,''
Turek said. ``The NHL made some new rules, and every referee calls
a different thing.'' ... St. Louis' Tyson Nash, mocking a punch
thrown at him by Detroit's Steve Yzerman: ``I thought he threw a
pillow at me. I wasn't sure what he threw at me. He must have hit
me with a soft glove. Was it a bare hand? The ref must have had his
arm.'' ... In Los Angeles' past three wins, the forward line of
Ziggy Palffy, Luc Robitaille and Jozef Stumpel accounted for 14 of
the teams' 16 goals.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
