u p BC-MRSCLINTON-SENATE-ART     02-12 0447
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-SENATE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON GREETS PARTY'S FAITHFUL IN CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 BY JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On her first campaign swing through New York City
since becoming an official candidate for the U.S. Senate, Hillary
Rodham Clinton spent a full day rallying the Democratic faithful on
Saturday, speaking of her interest in issues related to children
and the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   It was a day that was to take her to four of the city's five
boroughs. And Clinton repeated many of the themes from her official
announcement on Feb. 6. But at every turn, the gatherings of
Democratic officials and foot soldiers responded as though they
were hearing her remarks for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   At a senior citizens center in the Flushing section of Queens,
Clinton discussed an initiative to help families pay for long-term
care for ill or disabled relatives, proposing a $3,000 tax credit.
Clinton said her proposal would provide financial support to 2
million people, about 1.2 million of them elderly.
</P>
<P>
   ``This long-term tax credit would be used to help thousands and
thousands of families,'' Clinton said. ``It will also support the
diverse needs that people have in long-term care. This tax credit
could cover up to 60 percent of the costs that families now bear.
Many of you know how exhausting it can be to care for a loved one
who has difficulties. I promise you that I will work my heart out
to support our seniors.''
</P>
<P>
   As she did in her announcement speech, Clinton told a group of
elderly listeners of her interest in extending Medicare coverage to
include prescription drugs. ``There are too many seniors who cannot
afford the drugs that are being prescribed,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady began her day basking in wild applause and chants
from about 200 elected officials and Democratic Party campaign
workers at a rally at York College, in the Jamaica section of
Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton sounded the themes that she would repeat through the
day: the need to improve the quality of the state's public schools,
the need for legislation to lower the cost of prescription drugs
and the need to bolster youth programs.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bronx, Clinton came to the headquarters of the Democratic
Party organizations, where more than 300 people waited in two rooms
to hear her. She was met by nearly every Democratic official in the
borough, as she was in Queens. Afterward, she was to meet with
other party officials and campaign workers in the Washington
Heights section of Manhattan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-12-00 1601EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000212.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4935 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-S.C.-STRATEGY-2T     02-12 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-S.C.-STRATEGY-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH TREATING SOUTH CAROLINA AS A MUST WIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Mich.)   (EDS: This story is an added starter for page 1.)  
(mk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ Gov. George W. Bush's campaign has scrapped
trips to California and Arizona, bought the leftover advertising
time once held by Steve Forbes and started contacting 135,000
independents and Democrats in an all-out bid to stop Sen. John
McCain from winning the South Carolina primary on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   To Bush and his aides, the stakes are enormous. With McCain
riding a wave of national attention after his stunning 19-point
victory in New Hampshire, the Bush camp feels that a loss here for
Bush would put his prospects for winning the Republican
presidential nomination in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign seems to be leaving little to chance. When Forbes
dropped out of the race on Wednesday, Bush aides grabbed the
remaining $45,000 worth of air time, expanding Bush's television
and radio expenses here to $3 million, nearly $500,000 more than
McCain's. In all, the Bush campaign will have pumped as much
advertising money into South Carolina as it did in New Hampshire
over a longer stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has also decided to devote virtually his entire schedule to
South Carolina. Considering that Arizona and Michigan hold
primaries only three days after South Carolina's, some Bush
supporters in those states warned that it was risky to bypass them.
But Bush's advisers concluded that the best way to assure success
in other states was to emerge triumphant here.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we'd have won New Hampshire,'' said Warren Tompkins, Bush's
chief strategist in this state, ``McCain would have been gone, so
there wouldn't have been a heck of a lot going on down here.''
</P>
<P>
   The most unusual new move is a telephone and mail appeal to
independents and Democrats, which Bush aides said had not been
planned until McCain jolted their campaign in New Hampshire on Feb.
1.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advisers said that their biggest fear, and the biggest
unknown, is that those voters _ who in this state can cross party
lines and participate in the Republican primary _ will flock to
McCain. The objective of the program, which comes on top of an
outreach to the homes of 300,000 reliable Republican voters, is to
persuade the independents and Democrats to back Bush or, at the
very least, discourage them from turning out for McCain. The total
outreach, to about 400,000 homes, is massive; in the Republican
primary in this state in 1996, the turnout was about 275,000.
</P>
<P>
   One Bush adviser said the campaign would be happy to pick off 30
percent of independents and Democrats who vote in the primary; in
New Hampshire, Bush drew only 19 percent of those voters, and
McCain won three times as many.
</P>
<P>
   In the telephone calls, Bush workers urge prospective voters to
back Bush, and raise questions about McCain. On Friday, expected
voters were reminded of Bush's ``strong victory'' in Delaware and
told, ``Don't be misled by McCain's negative campaign tactics.''
</P>
<P>
   While such calls are often effective, the efforts to criticize
an opponent can also backfire. One respondent chastised a Bush
caller, telling her: ``I saw an ad yesterday that Bush had on. I
didn't like him saying something back about McCain. To do one
negative against another. To me they both look bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Another respondent told a Bush caller, ``I like Bush, but I
don't like running people down like that.'' In recent days the
McCain campaign has accused Bush and his aides of spreading
negative information about McCain through calls intended to
resemble public opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   But a call may have had the desired effect on another
respondent, who said: ``I was for McCain wholeheartedly at first.
Now I'm on the fence.''
</P>
<P>
   In another move intended to win over more moderates, the Bush
campaign this weekend sent a letter from Elizabeth Dole to tens of
thousands of women in the state, concerning education and taxes on
charities. And earlier this week, the campaign sent a letter to
100,000 elderly voters intended to rebut claims by McCain that
Bush's proposals would threaten Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a huge mathematical puzzle,'' Karl Rove, Bush's chief
strategist, said in an interview Saturday. ``Our objective is to
maximize our vote among independents in South Carolina. We're going
out of our way with phone calls and postcards to invite these
people to our events.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond its overtures to moderates, the Bush campaign is pressing
its cause with conservatives. Beginning on Monday, a recorded
message from Rep. Henry J. Hyde, R-Ill., chairman of the House
Judiciary Committee and a revered figure among anti-abortion
groups, will be telephoned to the homes of 100,000 conservative
voters.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Several Bush advisers said they were uneasy about their
prospects, yet buoyed by surveys late last week suggesting that
McCain's momentum was waning.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain campaign, of course, is also pumping its more limited
resources into this state; McCain's aides said they were spending
close to $2.5 million on advertising.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the overt changes, like Bush's new emphasis on
depicting himself as the genuine reformer, and his more energetic
style on the stump, McCain's emergence as a threat has forced the
Bush operation to tear up its earlier, behind-the-scenes game plans
for winning the nomination. In the same way that former Sen. Bob
Dole mistakenly focused on the challenge from Sen. Phil Gramm,
R-Texas, four years ago, Bush advisers were preoccupied for more
than a year with Forbes and his hefty war chest, and never seemed
worried about McCain.
</P>
<P>
   One senior Bush official said the campaign may have been slow to
react to McCain because ``when the budgeting was done, the doomsday
scenario was Steve Forbes unleashing a huge negative attack that we
had to respond to.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Several Bush advisers said they were intent on running a tighter
campaign here than in New Hampshire. They said it was a mistake for
Bush to have appeared here with former Vice President Dan Quayle
after that defeat because it undermined the governor's message that
he, not McCain, was the anti-Washington outsider.
</P>
<P>
   Mistake or not, Bush is increasingly campaigning with public
figures from South Carolina. And his aides have spurned requests
from several of Bush's supporters in Congress to campaign in this
state. ``There's some trepidation about bringing in too many people
from the outside,'' Tompkins said. ``We're trying to use as many
home-grown surrogates as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Bush's most prominent supporters here, like Tompkins
and former Govs. Carroll Campbell and David Beasley, are keeping
some distance at public events.
</P>
<P>
   The drive to stop McCain and help Bush is not limited to South
Carolina. Late this week, Joe Allbaugh, Bush's campaign manager,
held a conference call with many Bush backers in Washington _
including people close to former President Bush _ to explain how
the governor would win South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Other Bush lieutenants in Washington, including Haley Barbour,
the lobbyist who headed the Republican Party, and Rep. Rob Portman,
R-Ohio, have reassured the governor's supporters on Capitol Hill
about the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just encourage them to take a deep breath and look at the
results in Delaware,'' Portman said of Bush's triumph this week in
the primary there.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., a Bush supporter, said that he,
for one, was worried that Bush ``took for granted that he was going
to win this thing.'' He said of McCain: ``There is some
appreciation that this guy is a war hero and has a clean record.
There are people that are concerned, and logically so, that this is
a big election in South Carolina. If McCain wins, it's going to be
a marathon to the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the Bush strategy is to tamp down any perception in the
press and among political professionals that Bush's eventual
emergence as the inevitable nominee is in doubt. As part of that,
the campaign is portraying the governor's win in the low-profile
Delaware primary as a monumental triumph.
</P>
<P>
   Rove went as far as to cite Bush's victory in the caucuses in
Alaska on Jan. 24, which campaign officials had barely mentioned in
the past. ``Bush has won three and lost one,'' he said. ``You
should be asking the McCain campaign if it could sustain a fourth
loss out of five.''
</P>
<P>
   Another senior Bush official said that while the governor could
endure a defeat here next Saturday, it would be a crippling setback
with the potential to lead major supporters to defect to McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to be nervous,'' the official said. ``There's not a
soul in this sort of high-pressure contest who doesn't think of all
the scenarios that are possible. The good ones make you feel warm
and fuzzy. The bad ones make you nervous.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In seeking to undercut McCain, the Bush campaign has had some
help from independent groups that are running commercials attacking
McCain: the National Right to Life Committee and the National
Smokers Alliance. While Tompkins insisted that the campaign did not
work in tandem with the outside groups, which would be illegal, he
said their advertisements were useful for the cause.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
