<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIULIANI-SENATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI PUSHES PRESIDENT ON OIL HEAT COSTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With NY-SENATE-RACE) 
(nk) 
 By THOMAS J. LEUCK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a move clearly meant to attract the attention of upstate
voters in his bid for the Senate, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said
Saturday that he had urged President Clinton to tap the nation's
Strategic Petroleum Reserve to bring down the soaring price of home
heating oil.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter sent to the president on Friday, copies of which
were released at a City Hall news conference Saturday, the mayor
estimated that the average New York state resident would pay $350
more for oil heat this winter unless federal officials intervened
by opening the spigot to the Strategic Petroleum Reserve, almost
600 million barrels of oil stored in salt domes in Texas and
Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't believe the impact this is having on Waterville,
N.Y., and other parts of the state where, obviously, it is even
colder than New York City,'' the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   In a news release, the mayor's staff said Saturday that home
heating oil prices had tripled in the city since Jan. 1, from 72
cents a gallon to more than $2.50 a gallon. The rising prices are
the result of reduced output by the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries and a cold winter.
</P>
<P>
   But Giuliani emphasized Saturday that he was appealing to the
White House on behalf of residents across New York state.
``Apparently, the president doesn't feel our pain,'' the mayor
said, adding that his letter was meant to ``politicize this
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe politicizing this will get the attention of the
president,'' he said. If the White House does not agree to release
part of the Strategic Petroleum Reserve, he said, ``this is
something we are going to bring up every day until they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., and other members of Congress have
been making the same argument for months. But Energy Secretary Bill
Richardson has resisted, contending that the reserve is intended
only for severe supply disruptions, not to control market prices.
</P>
<P>
   While not pumping more oil on the market, the White House has
released $175 million in emergency assistance over the last two
weeks to subsidize oil purchases by low-income people across the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Saturday, Richardson said $37 million of those
subsidies had been designated for New York residents. ``Our
immediate objective is to help consumers who are being hurt,'' he
said, adding that the federal government would continue to provide
cash subsidies instead of oil from the strategic reserve.
</P>
</TEXT>
