<HEADER>
A4940 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-SKEET-SHOOTING0213-CO     02-12 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKEET-SHOOTING0213-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wife shares husband's passion for skeet shooting
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Heat shouldn't bother a person who grew up in
Savannah. But Chris Patton wouldn't be going to her husband's skeet
tournaments if he had not gotten her a ``mobile air conditioner.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Gordon Patton, 51, an All-America shooter, began competing
in skeet two years after their marriage 12 years ago. Until he
presented Chris with a 40-foot Winnebago Ultimate Freedom
recreational vehicle, the podiatrist was missing in action most
weekends, spring through fall.
</P>
<P>
   The Winnebago worked so well that Chris is taking up skeet
herself. She can relax, read, take a nap and watch her husband
shoot _ while she's in cool comfort.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Patton reached the world-class level of skeet a lot
quicker than most. He won the world .410-gauge title at the World
Skeet Shoot in San Antonio last year and was named to the National
Skeet Shooting Association's 2000 All-America Open Honorable
Mention team.
</P>
<P>
   Getting to that level requires lots of traveling, because the
NSSA requires a number of out-of-state shoots. Patton also needs to
compete against the best to maintain his sharpness.
</P>
<P>
   The sport requires long hours at the range and a level of
discomfort only the dedicated would endure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It says something about our smarts, but the game is so
addicting we'll put up with just about anything,'' Patton says.
</P>
<P>
   Because the sport is noisy, shooting ranges are isolated and
some are built over landfills.
</P>
<P>
   And ranges are for shooters, not spectators. Since the major
part of skeet season takes place during the summer, it's hot and
humid outside and the only place to get relief is the clubhouse,
which usually isn't built for comfort. Those ranges built on
landfills add a new element to the heat _ occasional eruptions of
foul-smelling methane.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take Chris Patton, 44, many 12-hour days at the range
to decide that she would rather be at home, alone but at least
comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said if I got her a portable air conditioner she'd go with
me,'' Patton said. He found just what she was looking for through
another All-America shooter, Carl Hudson of Albany, who traveled to
shoots in an RV.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `You really need to think about this,''' Patton said.
``We spent some time visiting in his camper, got one in April of
1998, and my shooting took off.''
</P>
<P>
   It was love at first trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``After their first trip in the motor home, on the way back, she
asked Gordon, `When is the next shoot?''' says Mark Tuggle of
Bleakly Campers, who sold the Pattons their camper.
</P>
<P>
   ``It changed her whole take on the game,'' Gordon said. ``She
likes to read. She gets the air conditioner going and goes out when
she wants to.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a place to go,'' Chris said. ``You can rest, take a
shower during the day. We've got our own things with us. We're able
to bring the foods we like and to cook.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got our own bed and that's great,'' she said. ``When
he's shooting, we're sleeping in the RV more than at home.''
</P>
<P>
   It also helped to move Patton from one of the lesser categories
of All-American the past five years into the coveted Open class.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Childersburg, Ala., last August, the ambient temperature
was 117. I'm sure I won that shoot because I had a cool place to
go, take a nap, keep my cool,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And Chris found another plus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the people we meet, whether on the shooting circuit or
at campgrounds. The people are just
</P>
<P>
   terrific,'' she said. ``It's like a traveling family. One couple
we travel with, we call them our weekend neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, for a married couple, RVs keep you close to each other.
At home, you might be in separate rooms, watching different TVs,
but in the RV, you talk more, share the same TV.''
</P>
<P>
   And now, after watching Gordon shoot for 10 years, Chris has
gotten started in skeet, thanks to the RV. Last year, she even won
an event, the novice competition in the Ladies Charity Tournament
in Palatka, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Pattons went on a cruise to the Caribbean. He was
sick with the flu the whole time, and the experience seemed to
confirm what he had thought all along.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd rather be off in the motor home than anywhere,'' Patton
said. ``If we can't get there on six wheels, I don't want it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
