<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4943 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NJ-HURRICANE-CARTER-N     02-12 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-HURRICANE-CARTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOWNS COLUMN: MANY COMPLEX TRUTHS IN HURRICANE CARTER CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MATTHEW PURDY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PATERSON, N.J. _ The bar where the triple murder in the Rubin
``Hurricane'' Carter case took place 34 years ago is now called
Len's Place. The neighborhood has gone from white to black and
Hispanic, as have the bar's patrons. But you can still get the
local buzz along with your drink. As for the famous case, now the
subject of a hit film, the woman behind the counter one night last
week said, ``I don't think people even mention it.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as the scene of the crime has changed, the meaning of the
case keeps evolving with the politics of the times. Amid the urban
unrest of the 1960s, prosecutors cast the crime as two blacks
avenging a shooting by a white man in a black bar. In the Watergate
era, celebrities rallied around the famous boxer as yet another
casualty of government misconduct. Now comes ``The Hurricane,''
depicting Carter as a black man battling abusive white authority,
as racial profiling and the Diallo case have put racism and
policing on the national agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Carter was freed from prison after a federal judge ruled in 1985
that prosecutors withheld evidence, constructed a questionable
racial theory of the case and violated his constitutional rights.
The movie presents his innocence as unambiguous. But for those
touched most by the case, time has only magnified the real-life
ambiguities, as news conferences and Web sites by Carter's
detractors and defenders revive the bout for the title of victim.
</P>
<P>
   Hazel Tanis was a 56-year-old waitress, just months from
becoming a grandmother, when she was gunned down at the bar, then
called Lafayette Bar &AMP; Grill. Her daughter, Barbara Burns, stayed
with her for 28 days as she struggled to survive, her midsection
shredded by bullets. It is an article of faith for Burns that
Carter and his co-defendant, John Artis, are the murderers. They
were convicted twice. Besides, her mother said so.
</P>
<P>
   In her split-level home in Flanders, 35 miles west of Paterson,
Burns re-enacted her mother's begging for mercy on the bar floor:
```Why are you doing this? I'm a mother. These are innocent
people.' John Artis hesitated, and Carter said: `Finish her. Finish
her.''' With fresh fury, she recalled her mother's words: ```You
don't look a man in the eyes and plead for your life and forget
what he looks like.'''
</P>
<P>
   Burns' brother, Rick Burns, says just hearing ``Strangers in the
Night,'' a favorite of his mother's, brings back the pain, as does
Carter's renewed hero status. ``Poor Rubin Carter,'' he says with
sarcasm. ``How about poor Hazel Tanis?''
</P>
<P>
   Another song, Bob Dylan's 1975 ``Hurricane,'' was the first
piece of popular culture to celebrate Carter's struggle against
``criminals in their coats and ties.'' Rudy Langlais had a similar
view of Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in a Newark housing project, Langlais would watch
Friday night boxing matches on the family black-and-white
television with his father. He watched Carter then, and later
covered parts of the case as a reporter. Now, as a movie producer,
he helped make ``The Hurricane.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rubin Carter case is part of the myth, part of the sacred
history of New Jersey,'' Langlais said. He has told the story
unabashedly from Carter's point of view, portraying him as a
victim, even in his youth, when he stabbed a man.
</P>
<P>
   In making a movie, Langlais said, ``you have to decide on a
truth.'' He says the Carter story is one of ``grace and
redemption'' _ a man crushed by hatred, freed through the love of
his supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the truth is in any historical event,''
Langlais said. ``To the families of the victims, Rubin Carter and
John Artis committed the murders. The truth to Rubin Carter and
John Artis is that they were unfairly convicted, and there's
evidence to support that.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no rhetorical arguments at Len's Place. The big news
is a pregnant woman in Paterson who recently accused police
officers of slamming her head through a car window. She had about
100 stitches.
</P>
<P>
   Councilwoman Vera Ames, an advocate for the woman, said she knew
few details of the Carter case. But because of cases like the
woman's, which she said was under investigation, Ames understands
why people believe the truth according to Hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't need no movie to remind me what's going on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
