<DOCNO> NYT20000212.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4944 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CAMPUS-WARNINGS-ART-N     02-12 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPUS-WARNINGS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPUSES STEP UP WARNINGS ABOUT VIOLENCE IN RELATIONSHIPS
</HEADLINE>
  (With COLUMBIA-KILLING) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By TINA KELLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the week since a young woman was slain at Columbia University
and her boyfriend committed suicide shortly afterward, the
university and its students have grappled with an issue of
increasing concern on campuses around the country: violent
relationships among students.
</P>
<P>
   Virgil Renzulli, a spokesman for Columbia University, said
students there had turned to counseling sessions and support
groups, and that they were able to receive peer counseling over the
telephone. The university has a Rape Crisis/Anti-Violence Support
Center, and students can consult a health adviser on the Internet,
known as Go Ask Alice (www.goaskalice.columbia.edu), which offers
advice on subjects like relationships, emotional health and
sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   The murder of the student, Kathleen Roskot, a sophomore, and two
other recent attacks at other area campuses have underscored the
problem of abusive relationships. The statistics are particularly
chilling: one in five college students has reported at least one
incident of abuse when dating, from slaps to more serious violence,
according to the Corporate Alliance to End Partner Violence, an
advocacy group in Bloomington, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Other studies show that about 28 percent of high school and
college students experience dating violence.
</P>
<P>
   In about three-quarters of violent dating relationships,
problems surface after the couple is seriously involved, according
to the alliance, and drinking or drug use contribute to about 60
percent of violent incidents among young couples.
</P>
<P>
   Warning signals that a relationship may turn violent include
possessiveness, controlling behavior, unpredictable mood swings,
and rushing the relationship, said Kim Wells, executive director of
the group.
</P>
<P>
   A partner who threatens to hurt himself or others, makes many
groundless accusations of infidelity, or isolates his girlfriend
from friends and relatives could also be headed toward violence.
(Of reported domestic crimes, 95 percent of the victims were
female, she said, citing FBI statistics.)
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   At Westchester Community College in Valhalla, N.Y., on Monday,
Olonzo Davis, 19, shot his ex-girlfriend, Joy Thomas, 18, in the
head, leaving her critically wounded. He then shot himself to death
in a nearby grove of trees. He had previously smashed the windows
of her car and home, and she had sought an order of protection
against him.
</P>
<P>
   A freshman at Montclair State University in New Jersey, Chimere
McCrae, 18, was killed on Jan. 21 in Newark. Her boyfriend, Price
Hollace, 21, was charged with murder and weapons charges. He told
the police the shooting was accidental, though McCrae's family said
there had been tensions in the couple's relationship over her
spending time with friends at college.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Women in their teens and 20s are more likely to be victims of
domestic violence than older women, said Sally Goldfarb, an
associate professor at Rutgers Law School who specializes in
domestic violence and family law, and violence is more prevalent in
dating than in marriages.
</P>
<P>
   College students may be more likely to accept traditional sex
roles, in which the man dominates the woman, she said, and they
tend to go to peers for help, rather than to more informed older
people. They are susceptible to peer pressure to stay in a
relationship, which they often see as preferable to being alone,
and they may be so inexperienced in relationships that they accept
a violent one as normal.
</P>
<P>
   Dating relationships are not always covered by state domestic
violence laws, which makes obtaining an order of protection
difficult, especially for minors.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Best, a former coordinator of sexual assault prevention
programs at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign,
remembers working with 60 to 70 victims of dating violence in group
sessions in her four years there, and many more individually.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been astounded at the lengths to which young college
abusers will go to keep control over their victims,'' she said.
Often, victims ended up leaving school for protection.
</P>
<P>
   In October, the Justice Department announced $8.1 million in
grants to 21 colleges to address violence against women on campus.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the University of Connecticut will be training male
peer educators to fight violence, the Rochester Institute of
Technology is offering a mandatory violence prevention program for
incoming students, and Michigan State University is creating a
phone line for hearing-impaired students who need help from Safe
Place, the campus domestic violence shelter, established in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The grants have to include community groups outside the school.
``Campuses often don't want students who are victimized to report
to local police,'' said Bonnie Campbell, director of the Violence
Against Women Office at the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for victims have been surprised by how poorly students
understand dating violence. They may not identify with the
traditional portrayal of abuser or victim.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Columbia Men Against Violence, a group with 15
active members, attracted about 200 people to the university's
``Take Back the Night'' march, which protested violence against
women.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Warshawer, 21, the group's treasurer, said the group
tried to fight ``pluralistic ignorance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people are good guys, but think they would be yelled at
or laughed at if they speak up,'' he said. ``People remain unaware
that they are in the majority of men who might want to work on
feminist issues.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Justin Carver, 23 and a law student at St. Louis University,
remembers seeing a housemate of his at Illinois Wesleyan University
chasing an ex-girlfriend and grabbing her. It was enough for him to
pull his friend aside and tell him that such behavior was
inappropriate, unsafe and unhealthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him that as long as he felt he could engage in this
behavior, that I didn't feel I could associate with him,'' Carver
said. ``When he did come to realize he had a problem, I credited
him for this, he was willing to take some steps. He did end up
going to counseling.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-12-00 1621EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
