<SLUG> BC-BOAT-AMERICAS-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESSURE AT HOME COULD HURT NEW ZEALAND CREW 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By HERB McCORMICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ The opportunity was just too tempting to
pass up.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday, on their respective ways home at the close of a
long day of training on opposite sides of the Hauraki Gulf, Team
New Zealand and Italy's Prada Challenge engaged in a brief,
inaugural, highly unofficial scrimmage in advance of their much
anticipated duel for the America's Cup. The five-of-nine-race
finals begin here next Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the encounter took place between the syndicates'
second-team boats and crews, or that the sails under which they
jousted were tired and perhaps not optimally trimmed, or that
nothing of substance was learned or given away.
</P>
<P>
   The important point was that they lined up at all, a violation
of the cup protocol, which states that, in prematch mode, the
defender and challenger must give one another at least a
200-meter-wide berth. This is, in theory, a weighty rule to prevent
spying. In actuality, it's a buffer against that old cup malady
known as creeping paranoia.
</P>
<P>
   So one must not take too much from the fact that Dean Barker,
the young Kiwi backup helmsman, was able to nose away from the
Italians in the five-minute drag race. What will really matter is
how much the veteran New Zealand driver, Russell Coutts, is able to
discern about his opposing skipper, Francesco de Angelis, in the
first five minutes of next weekend's opening windward leg.
</P>
<P>
   Still, symbolically, the small tussle spoke volumes. Clearly and
unequivocally, these two crews are aching to mix it up.
</P>
<P>
   The America's Cup match, like any regatta, will be decided not
only by how well each crew sails, but by two critical items known
as speed and smarts. As every racing sailor knows, a surplus of the
former can make up for a deficit in the latter. So, as the date for
the first race draws near, here's a highly subjective breakdown of
how the two teams match up and what to expect on the water.
</P>
<P>
   BOAT SPEED
</P>
<P>
   Who's faster? The answer to that simple question will play a
major factor in determining whether the cup remains under the
auspices of the Royal New Zealand Yacht Squadron or takes up new
residence at Yacht Club Punta Ala in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain: Prada is a rocket ship in 10-to-15 knot
breezes, the conditions it enjoyed in the last two clinching races
in the challenger's finals against Paul Cayard's America One.
Cayard now admits that Prada was the faster boat in those deciding
contests. ``That's their sweet spot,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   No one, however, knows for certain what the Kiwis have up their
sleeve in this all-important category. Only one challenger, Japan's
Nippon Challenge, decided to break ranks and unofficially race
against Team New Zealand. But Nippon skipper Peter Gilmour said
last week that he came away very confident of his ability to tangle
with the New Zealanders and, by extension, felt that Prada owned
the faster vessel. Of course, Team New Zealand may well have
reworked its boat in the intervening weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The conventional wisdom says the Kiwis should hold the edge in
fresher winds, the Italians in the light stuff. It's high summer in
New Zealand, and if the winds will ever be consistently moderate,
now's the time.
</P>
<P>
   Advantage: Prada.
</P>
<P>
   CREW WORK
</P>
<P>
   In the last decade, as yacht racing's Grand Prix ranks turned
more open and professional, the Kiwis proved that, nation for
nation, they produce the world's top competitive sailors. The cream
of that crop has formed the nucleus of Team New Zealand since 1992,
not to mention countless Whitbread crews and other international
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   And they are led by Coutts, a 1984 Olympic gold medalist who was
at the helm of New Zealand's cup winner in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The Italian afterguard of de Angelis and the tactician, Torben
Grael, though prodigiously talented, had no match-racing experience
before joining Prada just over two years ago. But while the Kiwis
have been competing against in-house competition over the last four
months, Prada has been battle-hardened by a grueling series of
elimination trials.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the New Zealanders have been racing on the tricky, fluky
Hauraki Gulf all their lives, and their figurative home-court
advantage, coupled with their vast experience, is formidable.
</P>
<P>
   Advantage: Team New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   INTANGIBLES
</P>
<P>
   The pressure on the Kiwi team is huge. Tiny New Zealand has
invested millions of dollars, as well as hearts and souls, on its
hometown boys, and in return the populace expects nothing less than
a successful first defense.
</P>
<P>
   If Team New Zealand loses a quick race or two, the heat will
intensify. When the New Zealand rugby team, the beloved All Blacks,
lost to France in the last World Cup, the news media outcry was
swift and merciless. Should matters turn bleak, expect history to
repeat itself.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, Prada's yacht designer, Doug Peterson, has
produced the last two cup-winning boats and still appears to be on
top of his game. Furthermore, after their victorious performance in
the trials, the Italians are loose and confident.
</P>
<P>
   Advantage: Prada.
</P>
<P>
   PREDICTION
</P>
<P>
   In its 149-year history, the America's Cup has never been
successfully defended by any country outside of the United States.
That string will remain unbroken. In a tight, emotional series that
will go eight or nine races, Prada will win the America's Cup.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
