<HEADLINE>
CALL BY GRIFFEY'S AGENT HAD PROPITIOUS TIMING
</HEADLINE>
   (Originally skedded as BBO-SPRING-TRAINING) 
(With BBO-PITCHING) 
(rk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Hypothetically,'' said Sandy Alderson, who doesn't like to
deal in hypotheticals, ``it's conceivable that under some
circumstances a trade could be nullified as a result of prior
conduct of the parties.'' But, the commissioner's executive vice
president for baseball operations said, the trade for Ken Griffey
Jr. does not appear to fit those hypothetical circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on my understanding of the facts in this case,''
Alderson said, ``I don't think that would be the result.'' He
declined to say what the facts are, but it is indisputably known
that the Seattle Mariners gave Griffey's agent permission to talk
to the Cincinnati Reds when they didn't have the right to grant
that permission. It also has become known that the Mariners took
the step they weren't supposed to take at a most propitious time.
</P>
<P>
   As Chuck Armstrong, the Mariners' president, was telling Brian
Goldberg last Tuesday that he was free to find out first-hand from
the team in Griffey's hometown the chances of something happening,
Reds officials were contemplating how they should tell the world
that a tradQKT)r Griffey wasn't going to happen and furthermore
that the Reds needed to get on with their business; so would
everyone quit focusing on a player who wasn't theirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed our business to go back to normal and to let our
players know there's no deal, you can come to spring training
now,'' Rob Butcher, the team's media relations director, said. ``It
was getting to the point where the Griffey thing was slowing down
our entire business operation. Every other phone call we were
getting dealt with a player who wasn't even on our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong was aware of what the Reds might do. ``He mentioned
the Reds were probably about two hours away from issuing a
statement saying they pulled out of trying to make a trade for
Junior,'' Goldberg related. ``He gave me permission to call the
Reds to see if there was anything I could say or they could say so
that Junior would know it was a dead issue. I wanted Kenny to be
convinced that there wouldn't be a trade with Cincinnati.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg called John Allen, the Reds' chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't call to negotiate,'' the agent said. ``No money terms
of a contract were discussed. No players were talked about. It was
more like, are you guys going to issue a statement and, before you
do, is there anything we can do? I just wanted to find out if they
were really interested because that was the only place Junior would
like to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``John said our approach all along has been if a trade could be
made that didn't break the farm system or the current roster, we'd
love to have Kenny here long term as long as he understood the
parameters of how we could work it. If we could work out the
players and if you guys are reasonable, we'd like to do a trade.''
</P>
<P>
   What was reasonable?
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `John, I'm not going to discuss any specific dollars
or terms,''' Goldberg related. ```You tell me what you're looking
for, I'll tell you about Junior's long-term goals.' He said, `We
don't want him for a year; we want him to finish his career in
Cincinnati.' I said I think that's what he wants; maybe he'll
accept less money.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reds issued no statement that day. Instead, Allen called
Armstrong, and suddenly the names flowed through the phone line
more easily. By 9 p.m. Wednesday, the teams had agreed on players.
Armstrong called Goldberg and told him that he and the Reds had 72
hours ``to try to work out something on a long-term contract
because it was the Reds' desire to trade for Junior only if they
could do a long-term contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg and Allen met twice Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started out saying, let's try to get it done quickly; Kenny
doesn't have to be the highest-paid player,'' Goldberg recounted.
The Reds made an offer; Goldberg countered it. The Reds came up in
their offer; Goldberg lowered his proposal. They had a deal, a deal
that would stun baseball officials, executives of other clubs,
other players and agents.
</P>
<P>
   The raw number itself, $116.5 million for nine years, was low
enough considering the escalation of contracts for the best players
in the game and the Mariners' offer of $138 million for eight years
last year. But with $57.5 million deferred without interest, the
present-day value is reduced to about 75 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to mislead people that this is some charity
case,'' Goldberg said. ``The Reds are paying Kenny an awful lot of
money over the next nine years. But he did his part to show that
money wasn't the most important thing.''  &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
