<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IRS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PROPOSES INCREASING IRS BUDGET TO FIND CHEATERS 
</HEADLINE>
 Reapeating for all needing  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Warning that continuing cuts at the Internal Revenue Service
threaten the nation's tax system, the Clinton administration is
proposing more money to find cheaters and make them pay up. And the
agency's top official has begun emphasizing that catching cheaters
is as important as helping honest taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   The administration is seeking a 9 percent increase in the
agency's budget, the largest increase, adjusted for inflation, in
13 years. That would allow the IRS, whose auditing staff is down
one-fourth since 1995, to raise the number of auditors for the
first time in six years.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in Congress who have criticized the IRS said they
were open to the idea that more money might be needed.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the request for an increased budget is taken up by
Congress, IRS Commissioner Charles O. Rossotti is moving to ensure
that the agency does a better job of collecting taxes owed by
companies and individuals, he said in an interview last week. For
example, he has summoned all 665 managers in the collections
department to a three-day meeting in Chicago next month to insist
that they act when taxpayers do not pay.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first such meeting of collection managers in the
agency's history, said Jody Patterson, an IRS spokeswoman. At the
meeting, Rossotti will drive home the message that collection
managers cannot allow delinquent taxpayers, especially those who
flout the law, to get away without paying.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to stanch the decline in collection activity,''
Rossotti said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton's budget request is approved, part of it would pay
for 633 more auditors, a 5 percent increase. They would hunt for
cheating by people with incomes over $100,000, especially business
owners, professionals and investors in partnerships. In the last
three years, audit rates among such taxpayers have fallen by
two-thirds, to about one in 131 returns.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS said it would also focus on illegitimate business tax
shelters that make profits invisible to the IRS. These shelters are
growing so fast, IRS officials say, that despite soaring profits
the taxes paid by large companies have actually begun to decline.
These officials say that less than 70 cents of each dollar of
profit reported to shareholders in 1998 was reported by companies
as taxable, down from 91 cents in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The administration also wants to hire more people to answer
telephone calls to the agency, allowing about 300 auditors detailed
to this kind of customer service work to resume examining
questionable returns.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers said that ``we need to begin
increasing capacity'' to enforce the tax laws ``to maintain
people's confidence that this is a tax system that works.''
</P>
<P>
   He said enforcement must go hand in hand with improving service
to cooperative taxpayers. ``Better customer service and greater
collection volumes go together,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Congress and the president have kept such a tight rein on
spending that the IRS has hired only 20 new auditors even as more
than 2,000 have quit or retired since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   One result is that this year fewer than one in 300 personal
returns is expected to be audited, down from one in 63 two decades
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The decline in enforcement has become so significant that
Rossotti now warns that it threatens to ``undermine our entire
system of voluntary tax compliance.''
</P>
<P>
   Rossotti and others worry that understaffing and a growing
timidity by front-line auditors and tax collectors have allowed
more Americans and businesses to get away with not paying what they
owe.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS also has fallen down at the job of collecting from those
who fail to turn over taxes due, mostly small businesses and the
self-employed. Since hitting a record $38 billion in 1996, taxes
collected through enforcement actions like audits and levies on
bank accounts have fallen by 13 percent, or $5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS came under fire in Congress two years ago, in hearings
at which taxpayers said they had been bullied and harassed.
Congress answered with, and Clinton signed, legislation intended to
give taxpayers more protection against overzealous tax agents.
</P>
<P>
   After the law was passed, Rossotti, a wealthy businessman
brought in to fix the agency, made improving service to customers _
as he calls taxpayers _ his theme.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the mission statement _ ``to collect the proper
amount of tax due'' _ was replaced by ``provide America's taxpayers
top quality service by helping them understand and meet their tax
responsibilities and by applying the tax law with integrity and
fairness for all.''
</P>
<P>
   But recently Rossotti has begun to emphasize the catching of
cheaters as much as helping taxpayers. Earlier this month, for
example, he told the Senate Finance Committee, ``Customer
satisfaction is not achieved by failing to collect taxes that are
properly due.''
</P>
<P>
   And he has spoken out about the agency's weaknesses in enforcing
the law.
</P>
<P>
   He talks about shrinking resources, for one thing. This year,
full-time IRS payroll has fallen nearly 16,000, to 81,834
employees, a 16 percent decline since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the last five years the number of income tax returns has
grown 11 percent and the number of complex returns filed by people
making $1 million or more is doubling every three years. About
250,000 households will report an income of $1 million or more for
1999.
</P>
<P>
   And this at a time when the agency has had to comply with more
than 1,200 changes imposed by Congress that essentially make its
job more demanding. Some of those changes make it easier for
taxpayers to get answers from the IRS, such as having people
available around the clock to answer telephone inquiries. Others
require the agency to take many more steps in the audit and
collection process to make sure that taxpayers are not abused.
</P>
<P>
   The equivalent of 3,000 more workers have been assigned to
comply with the changes.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But beyond the shrinking size of the work force has been its
attitude toward pursuing tax cheats. Many IRS employees are now
operating extremely cautiously for fear that under the new rules
they can be fired for the way they once did their jobs. In
interviews with The New York Times in the last year, collection
officers across the country, all of whom insisted on anonymity,
said that even in cases where they had followed the rules
faithfully their managers were unwilling to approve seizures and
levies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real problem,'' Rossotti said, ``is that there is a lot of
confusion, and sometimes managers are backing off to the point
where they are not managing.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, tax revenues have been soaring in recent years as the
economy has boomed and profits have jumped. But IRS officials say
many forms of cheating have proliferated and tax revenues should be
even higher. Their concern is that if people think they can cheat
without being caught, many more people will do it and honest
taxpayers will sour on the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our entire tax system depends on the vast majority of
taxpayers who attempt to pay their taxes that are due having
confidence that they are being treated fairly and that their
competitors and neighbors are also paying what is due,'' Rossotti
told the Senate Finance Committee earlier this month. ``If the
public concludes over a period of time that the IRS cannot meet
these basic expectations, the risk to the tax system will become
very high and the effects very difficult and extraordinarily
expensive to reverse.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in his new budget proposal earlier this month, has
asked for $8.84 billion for the IRS in 2001, up 9 percent from the
$8.11 billion Congress approved for this year. The $729 million
increase includes $174 million this year and next to hire 1,633
more people, including 633 more auditors and 33 more tax
collectors.
</P>
<P>
   The extra money would allow the IRS to replace about one-sixth
of the auditors, collectors and related personnel it has lost since
Clinton took office. It would also allow the hiring of more people
to answer telephone inquiries from taxpayers, a job that diverted 3
percent of auditors and collectors from their primary work last
year.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the Republicans who control the House
Appropriations Committee said that adding a total of 2,800
full-time employees, as proposed in the budget, is a rather large
request, one that will be discussed in hearings next month.
Republicans have long held a suspicious view of the IRS and have
criticized the agency for what they call its plodding pace and its
emphasis on catching tax cheats.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to look very closely at this request,''
said Elizabeth Mora, the spokeswoman, adding that Congress has had
a different set of priorities for the IRS in the past. ``We have
been concerned and remain concerned about modernization. We are
also very concerned about a balance between law enforcement and
customer service. We need to make sure there is a correct balance
between the two.''
</P>
<P>
   Two architects of the recent laws overhauling the IRS said they
were open to the idea that more money may be needed for
enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, who chairs the House Ways and Means
Committee, said he ``will do what's necessary so the IRS can serve
the taxpayer.''
</P>
<P>
   And Sen. William Roth, R-Del., who chairs the Senate Finance
Committee, said, ``It's important that the IRS have sufficient
funding to ensure successful execution of the current
reorganization plan in order to make tax collection more efficient,
and provide better service to taxpayers.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The IRS has also backed away from an interpretation of the new
tax act that required collectors to demand full payment of taxes
past due _ or nothing at all.
</P>
<P>
   Under that new approach, tax delinquents who did not pay in full
were having their cases put aside. Tax experts said that many
people who owed money would bet that the statute of limitations
would expire before the IRS pursued them, and that therefore people
who could have paid something would no longer do so.
</P>
<P>
   The new policy directs agents to collect as much as possible
from such taxpayers, just as was done previously.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
