<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4959 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-LEWIS-DEFENSE-ART     02-12 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LEWIS-DEFENSE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYER SAYS LEWIS ACTED ONLY AS A PEACEKEEPER
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JON NORDHEIMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Lawyers representing the All-Pro linebacker Ray Lewis
on Saturday detailed the step-by-step movements of the football
star from the time he left a post-Super Bowl party at an Atlanta
nightclub and minutes later became entangled in a street brawl that
left two local men stabbed to death.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a kaleidoscope of confusion,'' said Ed Garland, the
lead criminal lawyer defending Lewis, 24, who was indicted Friday
by a grand jury on two counts of murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all took place within a minute or so, and there were a
bunch of people moving, running and struggling in a dimly lighted
spot, with maybe 100 witnesses seeing different parts of what was
going on,'' Garland said of the confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   It began sometime before 4 a.m. on Jan. 31, Garland said, when
Lewis, dressed in a full-length black mink coat and black cowboy
hat, and 10 male and female acquaintances, left the Cobalt Lounge
in the fashionable Buckhead section of Atlanta and walked a block
and a half to his 35-foot-long leased limousine.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were guys on the street who start `jawboning' _
harassing them _ and one of the men with Lewis breaks back and
starts a loud argument with them,'' Garland continued. The lawyer
identified this man as Reginald Oakley.
</P>
<P>
   Oakley, 31, of Baltimore and Joseph Sweeting, 35, of Miami were
also indicted by the grand jury on murder charges. Both men are
being sought by the FBI and police agencies in Maryland and
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Garland provided this description of what happened next based on
information provided by Lewis and other witnesses:
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray goes back and snatches Oakley up and drags him back to the
limo. At that point, Ray and all the men and women in his party get
into the limo except Sweeting. About four or five guys, and one
short guy with the biggest mouth, come up to the door of the limo,
yelling and taunting. All the while, people leaving the clubs are
passing by on the sidewalk or across the street.''
</P>
<P>
   Garland said Oakley jumped out of the vehicle and was hit on the
head with a Champagne bottle by one of the men on the sidewalk.
``Then everybody piled out of the limo, including the driver,''
Garland said.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis pushed his date, a woman identified only as ``J,'' back
into the limousine as two groups of brawlers fought on the sidewalk
and the street, Garland recounted. ``It's clear others from the
limo engaged in a fight with some people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe Ray Lewis acted only as a peacekeeper, trying to
pull people away. The great danger in our case is because of the
confusing scenery. It is dark, and who can be sure who you're
seeing?
</P>
<P>
   ``But you can't attribute criminal liability to him, much less
murder, because there was a sudden, spontaneous event and he's
there trying to break it up.''
</P>
<P>
   After the fighters separated, Garland said, everyone got back
into the limousine and it pulled away with all the original
passengers. Then, the lawyer continued, someone on the sidewalk
fired five .45-caliber slugs into the back of the departing vehicle
``and everyone inside hit the floor in a jumble.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the back tires was flattened by a slug, and the limo
stopped at a hotel more than a mile away. Lewis and his date took a
cab from the hotel to his suite at the Georgian Terrace Hotel,
close to downtown Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Garland said Lewis was unaware of the stabbing deaths of Richard
Lollar, 24, and Jacinth Baker, 21, both of suburban Decatur, and
learned of them only later in the day.
</P>
<P>
   That morning, Lewis, this time accompanied by his pregnant
fiancee, Tatayna McCall, who had been staying with the couple's two
children at the Atlanta home of her aunt, left for the Atlanta
airport to catch a plane for Hawaii, where Lewis was scheduled to
play in the Pro Bowl representing the Baltimore Ravens the
following Sunday, Garland said. He said they missed the plane,
however, and went to her aunt's house, where he soon was notified
that the Atlanta police wanted to question him about the Buckhead
killings.
</P>
<P>
   After questioning by a homicide detective _ a session in which
the authorities described Lewis as uncooperative and misleading the
police on the identities of those who had been with him in the
limousine _ Lewis was arrested later that night.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, he has been held in isolation at the Atlanta jail. A
bond hearing will be held Monday, and his lawyers will argue that
he should be allowed to post bail because he is not a significant
risk to flee the court's jurisdiction and does not pose a risk to
the community. His lawyers plan to present several witnesses and
letters at the hearing testifying to Lewis' good character and
charitable works. Among the letter writers is Warren Sapp, All-Pro
defensive lineman for the Tampa Bay Buccaneers and Lewis' former
teammate at the University of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities charged that Lewis was a combatant in the melee,
saying he ``punched, encouraged and assisted others in the
attack.''
</P>
<P>
   Those close to the investigation have indicated that Duane
Fassett, the 51-year-old limousine driver who took Lewis to Atlanta
from Baltimore several days before the Super Bowl, and who
chauffeured him on the night of the killings, told investigators he
saw Lewis punch someone.
</P>
<P>
   Garland, however, said his staff of four full-time investigators
learned that the driver would corroborate the defense's claim that
Lewis became involved only to break the fight up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
