<DOCNO> NYT20000212.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4960 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NY-GRAND-CENTRAL-REAL     02-12 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GRAND-CENTRAL-REAL-1045(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BUILDINGS RISE AROUND NEW YORK'S GRAND CENTRAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In 1994, when it still had eight years remaining on
its lease at 245 Park Ave., smack in the middle of the tony Grand
Central area between 46th and 47th streets, the investment banking
firm of Bear Stearns &AMP; Co. began looking for a new home, and soon
its name was linked to sites from Times Square to the financial
district.
</P>
<P>
   Today it is well along on its planned 45-story headquarters,
sections of its steel structure already thrusting above much of
Manhattan's East Side skyline. Once the new site, the entire block
bounded by 46th and 47th streets and Madison and Vanderbilt
avenues, became available, said James E. Cayne, the chief executive
of Bear Stearns, ``it was our first choice, our second choice, our
third and our fourth.''
</P>
<P>
   While the renaissance of Times Square has been more dramatic,
largely because of the depths to which the area had plummeted in
the 1970s and '80s, the area around Grand Central Terminal is
undergoing a significant transformation of its own.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Bear Stearns skyscraper, another new office
building is rising in the district and several others are in
various stages of planning. Construction has also begun on a
54-story residential tower, while two boutique hotels are scheduled
to open in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   The 200-foot walkways under the Helmsley Building at 230 Park
Ave. leading to Grand Central Terminal are to undergo extensive
renovation later this year, while the 34-story building itself _
bought by Max Capital Management last year for $225 million _
undergoes extensive refurbishing. And any number of buildings have
recently completed multimillion-dollar makeovers or modernizations,
or are in the process of doing so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Times Square has been the focus of development,'' said Tara I.
Stacom, executive director of Cushman &AMP; Wakefield, the real-estate
services group, ``but in a few years Grand Central will be the main
focus.''
</P>
<P>
   The main reason for the flurry of face-lifts and upgrades is
economic, to command higher rents, or, at the very least, to
dissuade tenants from bailing out when their leases expire. But
there is also the matter of pride _ of many landlords wanting to
keep up with the neighboring Joneses, who in turn were inspired to
dress up their properties because of the example set by the
acclaimed makeover of Grand Central Terminal.
</P>
<P>
   That makeover not only improved the experience for the
half-million commuters who pass through it on an average day, but
``it amounted to a vote of confidence in the area's potential,''
said Robert L. Billingsley, vice president of Colliers ABR, the
leasing agent for many properties in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Even the success of Times Square, which until recently had been
a model only of urban decay, served as an example for what's going
on in Grand Central. ``The ripple effect of Times Square
development and energy can be felt all the way to Third Avenue,''
said Mary Ann Tighe, vice chairman of Insignia/ESG, the real estate
services group.
</P>
<P>
   Because the new Bear Stearns building was intended to
accommodate the business of the firm, not to attract tenants
(although it will have retail tenants along Madison Avenue, as
required by zoning regulations), its raison d'etre from the
beginning was decidedly pragmatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had your druthers and could afford it, this is what you
would do,'' Cayne said. ``It was the only major site available on
the East Side of Manhattan, and its location and design convey
convenience, stature and commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   Between December 2001 and the expiration of its current lease in
2002, Bear Stearns plans to move most of its 4,500 employees in New
York into the new site, which is owned by CS First Boston and the
al-Babtain family of Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   Until it was leveled to build the Bear Stearns building, the
12-story Knapp Building stood on the site, at 383 Madison Ave.,
although it remained unoccupied for a dozen years. At one time it
was the headquarters of the Manhattan Savings Bank and the Webb &AMP;
Knapp real estate domain of William Zeckendorf Sr., whose circular
penthouse office was designed by I.M. Pei.
</P>
<P>
   Bear Stearns signed a 99-year lease for the land beneath its new
building in 1996. But some employees will remain at its current
headquarters, 245 Park Ave. at 46th Street, where its lease on the
almost 600,000 square feet of space it has been occupying includes
options for the 25 years beyond its 2002 expiration.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the space we will have for internal growth,'' Cayne
said, referring to 245 Park Ave., ``so we will end up using all or
most of the space available to us under the agreement with
Brookfield.'' Brookfield Properties Corp. owns the building.
</P>
<P>
   Both Cayne and Samuel L. Molinaro, the firm's chief financial
officer, said that a major factor in their decision had been the
restoration of Grand Central Terminal, which they said greatly
enhanced the aesthetics and quality of life throughout the broader
Grand Central area.
</P>
<P>
   They were equally lavish in their praise both of the
administration of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and of Metro North, whose
train tracks run beneath the new Bear Stearns building, as well as
beneath those of most buildings between Lexington and Madison
avenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was only one of the problems we confronted,'' said David
M. Childs, a senior partner at Skidmore, Owings &AMP; Merrill, the
architectural firm that designed the Bear Stearns building.
</P>
<P>
   Other challenges included the design, which calls for the base
of the building to rise nine floors (seven of them trading floors
with 2,000 trading positions) before two setbacks between the 10th
and 17th floors. From there the building becomes an octagon until
it reaches the crown, 777 feet above ground, where it is sheathed
in a patterned, rolled, laminated glass _ or, in the architects'
phrase, ``crinkled glass.''
</P>
<P>
   T.J. Gottesdiener, the architectural firm's managing partner on
the project, added that the building would be unusual in New York
because ``it's a square full-block site, and there are so few of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So we took advantage of this geometry,'' he said, ``by
designing a skyscraper that starts square at the base and
culminates in a crystal octagon in the skyline.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Within the Bear Stearns building will be a pedestrian arcade _ a
block-long passageway that will connect with Grand Central Terminal
through a new north end passageway that can be accessed at either
Madison Avenue at 47th or Vanderbilt Avenue between 46th and 47th
streets.
</P>
<P>
   All this costs a great deal of money, of course _ almost $280
million for construction alone. But Cayne, a world-class bridge
player and a self-described ``pretty good'' poker player, does not
regard that investment as a risk. ``It's the closest thing to a
sure thing I've ever seen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   How so? ``Because opportunities like this don't come along
often,'' he said. ``You couldn't duplicate it because New York real
estate has since gone through the roof.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Axel Stawski had the foresight to buy his properties almost
20 years ago at 360 Madison Ave. and just around the corner at 17
East 45th St. Now his Kipp-Stawski company is knocking down the
building on 45th Street and keeping only the steel frame, columns,
beams and slabs of the Madison Avenue building and combining the
new and the old structures into a single 24-story office building
at the 360 Madison address _ a mere chip shot from the new Bear
Stearns tower.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grand Central has always been special,'' Stawski said, ``and
it's extra-special since the terminal was restored.''
</P>
<P>
   Lots of heavy-duty restoration is taking place in and around the
terminal, the very heart of Grand Central. The 200-foot-long
Helmsley arcades, which connect Grand Central Terminal with Park
Avenue through the Helmsley Building at 230 Park Ave., will be shut
down one at a time for 18 months starting later this year while
they are spruced up.
</P>
<P>
   The makeover will include 30-foot-high ceilings (double the
existing height), a 15-foot by 40-foot center skylight that will
fill the passage with natural light, new double-height retail
spaces facing 14-foot-high video screens along the walls, a glass
floor beneath the center skylight revealing trains below street
level _ and, not least, direct access to Grand Central Terminal.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Helmsley Building itself _ originally the New
York Central Building, but whose most recent name will remain on
the facade of the building, as part of the sales contract, under
the new ownership _ will be extensively gussied up.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Hochfelder, the president of Max Capital, said that the
limestone and granite of its four-story base would be restored, its
glazed terra cotta roadway tiles would be cleaned, and that he is
considering restoring the building's copper mansard roof and its
gilded golden cupola (which previously had been restored in July
1998).
</P>
<P>
   In the lobby the installation of the original brass fixtures,
marble trim, travertine walls and floors is nearly completed, while
the public corridors are being redone with custom screened wall
coverings and Persian carpets.
</P>
<P>
   By late summer people who visit the 24-story building at 350
Madison Ave. _ formerly the Conde Nast Building, until that
publishing company moved into its skyscraper in Times Square _ will
have an unusual urban experience awaiting them. As they enter the
building they will cross a glass bridge that can be illuminated
from underneath, and once inside they they will find themselves in
a 22-foot-wide lobby that is also made of glass, thus affording a
rare unobstructed view of the sky.
</P>
<P>
   ``By breathing new life into these older buildings in Manhattan,
where there's almost no space to put up new buildings, you preserve
the archaeology of New York,'' said Roger Duffy, a design partner
at Skidmore, Owings and Merrill, the architectural firm that
designed the bridge and glass lobby. Duffy also designed the
Helmsley Building arcades.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the two new buildings now under way on opposite
sides of Madison Avenue, several other new office buildings are in
advanced planning stages.
</P>
<P>
   Tishman Speyer Properties, part owner of Rockefeller Center and
the Chrysler Building, is planning to build a 365,000-square-foot
speculative office building at 222 East 41st St., near Third
Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   And at the northeast corner of 42nd Street and Fifth Avenue
Mitchell B. Rutter, the president of Essex Capital Partners,
intends to put up a 30-story office building that will include
retail stores on the street level. That building is also expected
to be put up as a speculative building.
</P>
<P>
   Brookfield Properties has announced plans to buy a site at the
equally conspicuous corner of 42nd Street and Madison Avenue to
build a million-square-foot building, which is likely to be
occupied by the Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce, Canada's
biggest bank.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the activity in and around Grand Central involves office
buildings. The office vacancy rate in the area _ 38th to 47th
streets, Fifth Avenue to the East River, was 7.1 percent last
month, according to Barbara Byrne of Colliers ABR, compared with
6.7 percent in midtown Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   But a sprinkling of residential properties are also under
construction.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest of these is RFR Davis' 54-story limestone and brick
residential tower at 425 Fifth Ave., at 38th Street, on which
construction started three months ago. Eighteen floors are intended
for extended-stay residents, while the remainder will house
apartments. The building, designed by Robert A.M. Stern and H.
Thomas O'Hara Architects, will also have space for commercial
tenants.
</P>
<P>
   At 52 East 41st St., between Madison and Park avenues, in the
former Chemists Club building, the 108-room Dylan hotel and the
separately owned Restaurant R are scheduled to open in April. The
Dylan's owner, Morris Moinian, said that more than $1 million of
the overall $30 million renovation is devoted to architectural
details, including a marble staircase that spirals up three floors.
(The architect is Jeffrey Beers of Manhattan.)
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, at the northeast corner of Madison Avenue and 41st
Street, a former 12-story office building is expected to open at
the end of April as the refurbished 16-story, 60-room Library
Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Under the husband-and-wife design team of Stephen B. Jacobs and
Andi Pepper, each floor will be keyed to the Dewey decimal system
used to catalog books. Not only will floors will be named after
various subject headings (Social Sciences, Economics, etc.) but
rooms on each floor will contain books on the appropriate topic.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Library Hotel's developer, Henry Kallan, said he was
undertaking the $10 million restoration largely because Grand
Central is about to become a mecca for tourists as well as visitors
on business. ``The whole area,'' he said, ``from Grand Central
Terminal to Bryant Park'' _ at 42nd Street and Avenue of the
Americas, behind the New York Public Library _ ``is already dynamic
and will become more so.''
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to find an important building in the area that is not
being upgraded, or has not been upgraded recently. The $100 million
refurbishment continues on the Chrysler Center, the name recently
bestowed on the 76-story Chrysler Building at 405 Lexington and the
32-story East Building (formerly the Kent Building) at 666 Third
Ave.
</P>
<P>
   The work on the landmark Chrysler Building, which is nearing
completion, includes refurbishing the entire facade as well as the
signature stainless steel and nickel top. It also includes
modernizing the system that controls and operates the 20 elevators
and employing artisans to renovate the landmark elevator cabs. The
building will have new heating, ventilation and air-conditioning
systems, and a new generator will provide emergency backup for both
Chrysler Center buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, work on the East Building is expected to last at least
a couple more months, according to Valerie Peltier, senior director
of Tishman Speyer Properties. That ranges from changing its
white-brick exterior to aluminum and glass, enlarging the lobby,
modernizing offices, improving the heating and ventilating systems,
replacing the elevator cabs and much more. By adding space on each
floor, the East Building will have an additional 150,000 square
feet.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, two small buildings and three floors of a
five-story in the middle of the Chrysler Center have been torn down
and will soon be replaced by three glass trylons (one 75 feet high)
designed by Philip Johnson that will house a restaurant accessible
from 42nd Street. (The East Building's main entrance will remain at
666 Third Ave.)
</P>
<P>
   For the better part of two years S.L. Green Realty, which has
extensive holdings in the Grand Central area as well as elsewhere,
has been busy rewiring and otherwise upgrading all its buildings,
most of them Class B.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to our tenants to have speedy access to the
Internet,'' said Jerry Nocera, Green's executive vice president of
leasing, ``so we're putting in fiber-optics that will take us into
the next decade.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, Green is carrying out an extensive renovation of
the Graybar Building attached to Grand Central Terminal. This
includes a new bronze and glass entrance, a renovated lobby, a
steam-cleaned facade, and new floors, ceilings and bathrooms.
</P>
<P>
   At the landmark former Bowery Savings Bank at 110 East 42nd St.,
where the Cipriani family leased the ground floor and basement for
its catering service _ and where the taped voice of Enrico Caruso
resonates from the marble mosaic floor as well as the 65-foot-high
ceiling _ S.L. Green was able to redo the lobby and install new
elevator cabs without running afoul of the landmark preservation
strictures.
</P>
<P>
   The former bank has been host to bar mitzvahs reunions, weddings
and similar happy occasions _ and according to Charles Kasper, the
doorman at the property, ``we've even had some divorce parties.'
</P>
<P>
   A block west, the Lincoln Building, owned by East 60 East 42nd
St. Associates, of which Peter Malkin is the general partner, is in
the midst of a $28 million refurbishment. The original ceiling has
already been restored by a New York firm that specializes in
historic restorations. A new concierge desk was added recently, and
a new corridor, new windows, a new conference center, new public
bathrooms on each floor and a covered lobby entranceway are either
already completed or will be soon.
</P>
<P>
   Lest art and history buffs rise up in arms, they can rest
assured that Daniel Chester French's sculpture of the ``Seated
Lincoln,'' the model used for the creation of the Lincoln Memorial
in Washington, still reposes in the building's lobby.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
