<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ONEAL-ALLSTAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'NEAL HAS HIS HEALTH AND A HEALTHY ATTITUDE
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ He occupied the farthest corner of the hotel
ballroom, away from the madness encompassing Kevin Garnett and
Vince Carter. You can't keep a low profile at 7 feet 1 inch and 320
pounds. But Shaquille O'Neal tried on Friday afternoon, attracting
less attention from the news media than some of his more acrobatic
peers did.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was surprised about not being asked to participate
in Sunday's dunk contest, he laughed and said, ``They didn't want
me to win it.''
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, it is the same old Shaq. Cornball humor. Life of
the party. A man who is said to be renting an entire hotel this
weekend for a grand total of $700,000. But beyond O'Neal's
extravagances and carefree attitude off the floor, he is a
different kind of player this season.
</P>
<P>
   He moves his feet better on defense, helping out and playing
with passion on both ends. And he keeps extending the range on that
pretty little jump hook, enough so that you wonder why he just
doesn't start shooting his free throws that way.
</P>
<P>
   He is averaging more than three blocked shots a game, double his
output last season. In 12 games this season, he has scored more
than 30 points and grabbed 15 rebounds. Second in scoring, first in
field-goal percentage, he is playing on a Lakers team that has
dabbled with the league's best record.
</P>
<P>
   If this keeps up and he overcomes his team's recent string of
being swept out of the playoffs, a most valuable player award may
be in the offing. Only Tim Duncan, Kevin Garnett, Grant Hill,
Alonzo Mourning or Jason Kidd can compete.
</P>
<P>
   You can credit Coach Phil Jackson, O'Neal's injury-free status
or the lack of many bona fide centers to contain such an awesome
force. But maybe that little, fragile Shaq action figure is growing
up into a bona fide superhero, the self-proclaimed Man of Steel he
always wanted to be. Maybe O'Neal is less sensitive about criticism
and more secure about his game and his goals?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you're reaching a little bit,'' he said, laughing.
``You just make that stuff up or they tell you to write that?
Honestly, I'm healthy. That is a big thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Of playing for Jackson, he added: ``Obviously, he's a great
coach. He never gives me any room to slack off. He expects a lot
out of me; I expect a lot out of myself. We don't have a problem
and I'm sure we'll never have a problem. I don't have a problem
with respecting authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he's the general and I know I'm the lieutenant.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Jackson ever signed on with the Lakers, O'Neal had enough
motivation to kill perception about his lack of commitment. Swept
out of the playoffs in consecutive seasons by the more-disciplined
Utah Jazz and San Antonio Spurs, a fringe candidate in the MVP
balloting and relegated to second-team All-NBA, O'Neal has been
force-fed the idea that Duncan and Garnett were the only ones
genuinely dueling for the league's top player award.
</P>
<P>
   They have been proclaimed more complete franchise players and
much more capable of leading than O'Neal, the Lakers' center.
</P>
<P>
   Knee injuries robbed him of 31 games in 1996-97, his first
season with the Lakers. A strained abdominal muscle, small but
intensely painful, knocked him out of another 22 games in the
1997-98 season. He missed just one game last year in the
lockout-shortened season, but that abdominal strain never healed
completely.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's because I'm injury-free,'' O'Neal said recently.
``Injury-free is big. When I pulled my stomach muscle, I couldn't
reach to block shots. I could only muster up enough energy to do
what I was asked to do on offense.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past O'Neal wasn't committed to protecting the paint and
providing a safety net for teammates. He wasn't rebounding
aggressively enough. He often forced shots way out of his range.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, there's no stopping him,'' his teammate Rick Fox said.
``None whatsoever. The Diesel is just too big, strong and
skilled.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
