<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4964 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-CAR-RICKY-RUDD-NYT &LR;      02-12 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-RICKY-RUDD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUDD MAKING A NEW START AS A DRIVER FOR THE YATES TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's like something from a Hollywood script. Before last season
the veteran NASCAR driver Ricky Rudd tells his main sponsor, Tide,
that it needs to double its financial commitment in order to
compete with the sport's heavyweights. After a study, the detergent
company decides to do so, but in the process severs ties with Rudd
at season's end. For the next month, Rudd scrambles to find a major
sponsor, a time of soul-searching and uncertainty for the
43-year-old. Suddenly, though, comes an offer that figures to
change his life dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   The prestigious Robert Yates Racing Team, the defending Winston
Cup champion Dale Jarrett's team and one with an envious long-term
commitment from big-bucks sponsors, offers Rudd the team's second
car in a three-year deal straight from heaven.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably couldn't have been smart enough to plan that,''
chuckled Rudd, who will make his Winston Cup debut for Yates in
next Sunday's Daytona 500. ``I was so busy trying to get my own
team up and built that I almost didn't see that opportunity when it
knocked on my door. I finally realized that this is everything I
want, and without the headaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudd, so accustomed to making do with less than $5 million for a
season's racing when the top teams were spending $8 million to $10
million, now has all the support to challenge for his new
teammate's title. And he arrives with a reputation for being able
to find the winner's circle in less optimum circumstances. He holds
the Winston Cup record for having won at least one race a year for
16 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're up against the best in the world at what they do,'' he
said. ``They're very competitive. They don't sleep a lot. They lay
awake thinking of new ways to make their cars run better.''
</P>
<P>
   The winning streak ended last year, along with his six-year
struggle to be competitive on a relative shoestring budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to lay blame, but as a team we weren't prepared
aerodynamically when the season began,'' Rudd said. ``We had
switched engine companies for the first time, and the motors just
weren't getting the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   His team eventually switched engine companies again and finished
the season strong, but, as he said: ``Three-fourths of the year was
gone before that happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Yates understood. Even before the Yates team knew Rudd
might be available, Rudd drew nearly 70 percent of the votes as the
replacement for Kenny Irwin in a poll conducted by Yates' son Doug
among the team's personnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a few guys I wouldn't have been afraid to do business
with, but this took a lot of variables out of the equation,''
Robert Yates said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Yates has respected Rudd since they worked together
for a year when Rudd was 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are successful as you want to be in this business,
sometimes you end up creating a monster _ somebody you can't handle
or maybe who doesn't deserve it,'' Yates said. ``I knew right off
it'd be a great situation with Ricky.''
</P>
<P>
   As a testament to his return to a more simplified, focused life,
Rudd is about a month into a physical fitness program. In the
late-1980s, Rudd set a workout standard among drivers that few
could match and he said it gave him more confidence on the race
track. Then in 1994 he became an owner-driver, juggling the sundry
responsibilities of fund-raising, sponsor relations and overseeing
the business while driving the car.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that got sacrificed was my workout
schedule,'' Rudd said.
</P>
<P>
   The added responsibility of running his team did not stop him
from winning. The son of a Chesapeake, Va., salvage yard owner
still notched six of his 20 career victories and finished in the
top five 31 times.
</P>
<P>
   If he had not accepted Yates' offer, he could have driven for at
least several other teams. And never mind that he has reached an
age where he would be viewed as a dinosaur in most other sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't sit here and tell you I'm more physically fit than a
guy that's 21 years old,'' he said. ``But in this sport it comes
back to sort of brainpower and experience. Every driver has his own
peak. But it seems like in the Winston Cup, it's in the mid-40s.
I'm taking it year by year, but I feel great.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody questioned Rudd's determination even before he put on a
display of courage in the 1998 race at Martinsville, Va., that
still resounds in Winston Cup circles. His cooling system failed on
one of the hottest days of the year, and the thin aluminum seat on
which he sat became a hot coal. This happened about 30 laps into a
500-lap race. By race's end, Rudd had severe blisters on his back,
lower thighs and buttocks.
</P>
<P>
   He had something else, too: the winner's trophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was everything I could do to block the pain,'' he said.
``The car was going so well _ that's probably the main reason I
stuck with it. You just dig down deep.''
</P>
<P>
   So, if Jarrett and his new partner happen to be battling for
victory in the last laps of Daytona next Sunday, Yates' sentiment
is simple: let the best man win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never liked monopolies,'' Yates said. ``I'm more of a person
who likes to rob from the rich and give to the poor. Sitting in the
grandstand, I wouldn't want to say, `That guy only won because he
had a teammate helping him.' I look at it like this: they're both
capable of winning. Let's see what happens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
