<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4965 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-MOUNTAIN-OUTDOORS-ART     02-12 1210
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOUNTAIN-OUTDOORS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTDOORS: CLIMBER FOR THE AGES HAS NEXT PEAK IN VIEW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., Ill.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT6 has been sent to NYT photo clients. A graphic
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By PETE BODO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ed Viesturs, clad in a charcoal sweater and jeans, stood
chatting with acquaintances last Monday evening in a corner of the
chapelesque auditorium of the Society for Ethical Culture on West
64th Street in New York, shortly before he would present a slide
show to a standing-room crowd on his exploits as a mountaineer. A
beefy, 20-something man dressed for success in a smart wool topcoat
shouldered his way through the growing throng and inserted himself
in front of Viesturs. ``Hey, dude, sorry to interrupt,'' he
interrupted. ``But you are, like, the man, you are, like, totally
.'' The young man jerked his head toward a smaller fellow,
hunched over and talking to a cell phone. ``Me and my bud, here,
are doing our first climb this summer. We're stoked, and wondering
if....''
</P>
<P>
   Viesturs, 40, imperceptibly drew back. He could be forgiven for
not high-fiving this arriviste to the largely conservative
fraternity of Alpine climbers, but then Viesturs has learned that
you can no longer tell just what _ or who _ will pop out of the
avalanche of public interest in outdoor adventures. The attention
has been caused by, among other things, the climber Jon Krakauer's
1997 best seller (``Into Thin Air''), a book about disaster and
death on the shoulders of Mount Everest.
</P>
<P>
   Viesturs welcomes the interest, partly because it makes it
easier for him to find sponsors for his expeditions. But, Gore-Tex
notwithstanding, he is strictly an old-school mountaineer. He
climbs mountains the old-fashioned way, without the help of bottled
oxygen. As he puts it: ``Using oxygen feels like cheating. I want
to climb the mountain as it is, for what it is, not reduce it to my
abilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite this self-imposed handicap, Viesturs plans by the summer
of 2001 to become the first American to scale each of the world's
14 8,000-meter-plus summits. Only eight climbers have achieved that
feat. Viesturs has already accounted for 12 of those peaks,
including the one deemed most formidable (K-2, on which Viesturs
and his former climbing partner, Scott Fisher, performed the
high-altitude rescue of another climber and were also caught in an
avalanche before their own successful vault to the summit), and, of
course, the highest peak in the world, Everest, at 29,030 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Viesturs has reached the summit of Everest five times, twice
without the aid of oxygen. And the last time he stood at the base
of that mountain and gazed upon its threatening, mist-shrouded
flanks, he experienced a unique reaction. He shrugged, and thought:
``Been there, done that. It's time to move on, Ed.'' Earlier on
Monday, Viesturs sat beneath a pastel, vaguely cubist mural in a
boutique coffee beanery near Gramercy Park. Clear-eyed,
square-jawed and fond of java fuel (Viesturs may like his air thin,
but he ordered a double latte grande coffee), he could have been
mistaken for any of the countless software engineers lounging about
in similar haunts in his adopted hometown of Seattle. Despite years
of exposure to the powerful ultraviolet rays of the Alpine sun,
Viesturs doesn't even look weathered. The only clue to his status
as a mountaineer for the ages can be found in the way he walks,
with the rolling, bow-legged gait of a beat-up athlete.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing about Viesturs' background carries even a faint whiff of
predestination. He grew up in pancake-flat Rockford, Ill., about 90
miles from Chicago, the son of a design engineer. A good student
and a competitive swimmer, he recalls being highly motivated and
goal-oriented. He did not know then that he had the extraordinary
constitution usually found only in people like Sherpas, who are
born and raised at high elevation.
</P>
<P>
   Viesturs has a lung capacity of seven litres, two more than the
average for similar males. He also has a very high anaerobic
threshold, which enhances his ability to function effectively at
times when his body demands and uses oxygen at a higher rate than
it can take it in. Viesturs has a rather ordinary explanation for
all of this: ``My father, Elmars, is of good, strong, Latvian
stock.''
</P>
<P>
   At age 15, Viesturs came upon the book that changed his life,
``Annapurna,'' by Maurice Herzog. After reading it, he took up rock
climbing and vowed one day to make an expedition to the Himalayas.
He attended the University of Washington, where he studied
veterinary medicine and spent all his free time climbing in the
nearby Cascade range. Soon, he was guiding for Rainer
Mountaineering Inc., but he insisted on finishing vet school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a hard worker and I pay great attention to details,'' he
said. ``So, I hate leaving things unfinished.''
</P>
<P>
   Viesturs finished vet school three months early, in order to
make his first expedition to Everest, where he came within 300 feet
of the summit before turning back because of bad weather. The
subsequent, nagging sense of failure felt by this natural-born
i-dotter and t-crosser ensured that Viesturs would not spend much
more time ministering to overweight tabby cats. He soon cobbled
together enough money to continue climbing through guiding, and
worked in construction and carpentry in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   Although he loves animals, his favorite places are among the
most barren and hostile to living organisms on earth. ``Up there,''
he said, ``there is nothing. Just ice, snow and rock. We go up to
visit and that's it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the allure is that it demands utter self-reliance.
Anywhere else on earth, in the desert, in the middle of the ocean,
you can now get on the cell phone, call someone, and have a plane
come and rescue you. You can't do that on the high peaks. If you
drop a glove, in 30 minutes your hand is frozen, then you drop your
ice axe because you can't hold it and then, well, that's about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Viesturs robustly denies that he has any romance with death,
describing his urge to climb as a ``life wish,'' and points out
that his wife, Paula (a frequent companion on trips, but not as a
serious climber), and his 2-year-old son, Gil, have increased his
well-documented caution. ``The main reason I take a cell phone on
my climbs now is so that I can be in touch with my family,'' he
said. ``I want them to know I'm safe.''
</P>
<P>
   But the cell phone has also become an indispensable tool in one
of the toughest climbs contemporary mountaineers face, the
relentless struggle to secure and service sponsors in an age when a
typical Himalayan expedition, regardless of the outcome, can carry
a six-figure price tag. Viesturs will use his cell phone on coming
climbs to post daily progress reports for one of his principal
sponsors, Mountainzone.com.
</P>
<P>
   His sober message will undoubtedly disappoint some of the
erstwhile climbers and dot-com cowboys who already have the phone,
but not much else in the way of climbing gear: ``Getting to the
summit is optional. Getting down is mandatory. It only counts if
you make it back down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
