u s BC-GLF-BUICK-NYT     02-12 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BUICK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE STREAK AND WOODS ARE THE TALK OF THE TOUR
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LA JOLLA, Calif. _ After his thrilling victory Monday at Pebble
Beach, Tiger Woods received a phone call from his close friend Mark
O'Meara.
</P>
<P>
   Woods and O'Meara love to compete. They also love to needle each
other. By winning at Pebble Beach, Woods reached 17 career
victories on the PGA Tour, one more than O'Meara.
</P>
<P>
   That gave Woods ammunition that he didn't waste.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call to congratulate him, and Tiger says, `I just passed you
in all-time wins,''' said O'Meara, smiling and shaking his head.
``I said, `Tiger, I don't need this from you.'''
</P>
<P>
   It has been like that for months, Woods having his way, at the
rest of the tour's expense. Consider this: Woods has won 10 times
since Davis Love III's last victory on tour. Woods has won 10 times
since Phil Mickelson's last victory. Woods has won nine times since
David Duval's last victory. Heading into Saturday's third round of
the Buick Invitational, Woods was threatening to win again.
</P>
<P>
   Woods began Saturday six strokes off the lead at five under par,
trailing Mickelson, Kirk Triplett and Shigeki Maruyama of Japan,
who were tied for first at 11 under. Yet everyone in the field knew
that Woods could devour a six-stroke lead like a lion devouring its
prey.
</P>
<P>
   So with two rounds to play, on a Torrey Pines course that he has
played on since he was a kid, everyone else on the leader board
would be keeping a close eye on Woods, who continued to chase
history. Woods has won his last six starts on tour to tie Ben
Hogan, who won six consecutive starts in 1948, for the
second-longest streak in tour history.
</P>
<P>
   Byron Nelson has the record with 11 victories in 1945, a mark
that looked unreachable until Woods went on his current winning
binge. The tournament expected record-breaking crowds this week,
the largest gallery would be tracking Woods and a worldwide news
media contingent would follow his every shot.
</P>
<P>
   Even other players were having a hard time avoiding streak talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great to see, all this interest,'' Triplett said.
``It's right there on the front page, not the sports page, but the
front page. This is fantastic. Everybody thinks golf is a really
great game, and they're excited about it. A lot of it is because of
Tiger.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara, a neighbor of Woods in Windermere, Fla., has seen him
handle the spotlight since he came on tour, and nothing he does
surprises O'Meara. When Woods won just once on tour in 1998, some
believed that he had been overrated, that he would not become the
tour's most dominant player. Instead, Woods has raised the bar of
excellence in his sport at age 24, and for the past six months,
everyone else has failed to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has lived up to everyone's expectations, even gone beyond
them,'' O'Meara said. ``Tiger has a gift. I said this before the
streak, he's got the most talent of any player I've been able to
play with in the 20 years I've played on tour. Jack Nicklaus may
not tell you this, but he thinks Tiger has the most talent of any
player he's ever seen, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The record that Woods most covets is Nicklaus' 18 major
championships. Woods has won two majors, the 1997 Masters and last
year's PGA Championship. To win 16 or 17 more majors, Woods will
have to remain one of the game's best for the next 15 or 20 years,
something he fully intends to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greatest record of all is 18 professional majors,'' Woods
said before this weekend's tournament began. ``That's a testament
to how good Jack played for a number of years, to win the big
events, year in and year out, for a long period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   But this weekend, Woods will focus on winning the Buick, where
he hopes to author another comeback victory. Woods will also play
next week at the Nissan Open, and he will play the following week
at the Andersen Consulting Match Play Championship, the year's
first event in the World Golf Championships series.
</P>
<P>
   Woods does not often play four consecutive weeks, which will
make keeping the streak alive even more difficult. However, O'Meara
has learned to never say never with Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be hard for him to keep winning every week,''
O'Meara said. ``But with him, nothing is impossible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
