<DOCNO> NYT20000212.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4977 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-TALEOFTWOCHEFS0213-CO     02-12 1823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TALEOFTWOCHEFS0213-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Two cooks in the kitchen
 &HT;    By John Kessler
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Every relationship begins with a meal to remember. For
Clifford Harrison and Anne Quatrano, it was a hamburger.
</P>
<P>
   The co-chefs met at the California Culinary Academy but didn't
really care for each other at first. Harrison thought Quatrano was
``some snotty East Coast chick.'' He was a self-professed surf and
ski bum from Hawaii _ a guy whose yearbook quotes were ``Surf 'til
it hurts!'' and ``I'm flying in the face of fashion so I give you
the BIG ALOHA.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet in their last semester of school, they found themselves side
by side in pastry class. Quatrano was having trouble making creme
patisserie, the heavy vanilla goo that cements strawberries to
sweet crust in a classic fruit tart.
</P>
<P>
   So she asked Harrison for help. He lent her a hand.
</P>
<P>
   She offered him a ride after school. He invited himself up for
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   And she made him a hamburger, served rare on focaccia with
Gorgonzola, pickled onions and a bottle of Pommard to wash it down.
Harrison, dazzled, never left.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since this big aloha some 13 years ago, Harrison and
Quatrano have been a personal and professional team. They now share
life on a 60-acre farm passed down through her mother's family.
Though they haven't gotten around to children (or a marriage
certificate for that matter), they count among their charges five
horses, two potbellied pigs, seven squat-legged Jersey cows, a
vague number of cats and dogs, chickens galore, 55 employees at the
highly regarded Atlanta restaurants Bacchanalia and Floataway Cafe,
and a newly minted gourmet food market.
</P>
<P>
   It is the market, Star Provisions, with its idealistic agenda
and thorough integration with the relocated Bacchanalia, that may
be their great contribution to American food arts. Nothing quite
like it has ever been attempted.
</P>
<P>
   Set alongside the railroad tracks near the Atlanta Water Works,
Bacchanalia and Star Provisions occupy one side of a rehabbed
factory that will eventually contain home furnishing stores at the
other end. It is in a seedily picturesque part of town where the
abandoned shell of industry has been appropriated by the hermit
crab of home design.
</P>
<P>
   The complex opened this month after lengthy construction delays.
Harrison and Quatrano moved their immensely popular Bacchanalia
from a snug cottage and threw in Star Provisions as an added
attraction. The market is a corridor of small shops leading up to
the restaurant entrance and selling the same gourmet provender the
chefs use. There is fish, meat, bread baked in a wood-fired oven,
pastry, fine wines, hand-rolled pasta, locally grown organic
produce, artisanal cheeses aged on the premises and estate-bottled
olive oils from the world's top regions. New York state foie gras,
Perigord black truffles and Caspian Sea caviar are available near
cost. There are also classic cookbooks for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Star Provisions isn't just a market, it's an epicurean
laboratory. Bacchanalia in a box.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, high-end markets and restaurants have explored a
different kind of synergy. Draeger's in San Mateo, Calif., a
gourmet supermarket that sells everything from toilet paper to
$200-a-vial aged balsamico, opened an ambitious restaurant called
Viognier within its massive square footage. In London,
super-restaurateur Terence Conran has set a serious cafe, Bluebird,
above a top-tier gourmet market.
</P>
<P>
   But with these examples the markets are the focal points, and
the restaurants are the icing on the cake. Star Provisions, on the
other hand, has grown out of a destination restaurant. It's as if
Quatrano and Harrison threw open their walk-in cooler and invited
you in. The new Bacchanalia is an avant-garde theater of fine
dining with an exhibition kitchen and an exhibition larder.
</P>
<P>
   What kind of chefs would attempt such a high-stepping concept in
such a lowbrow area? Only ones who are confident of their customer
base, embraced by their community and fully committed to nonstop
work would even have the nerve to try. But is the city ready?
</P>
<P>
   ``The city is never ready for what you do if you try something
unconventional,'' says chef Guenter Seeger of Seeger's restaurant
in Atlanta. ``So you need to make them ready. Annie and Cliff can
make it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen people who work harder than they do,'' adds
local chef Scott Peacock.
</P>
<P>
   Peacock took immediate notice of Bacchanalia when it opened in
late 1992. ``I liked the simplicity of the food. It wasn't gussied
up. It was so straightforward and pure, with nothing intimidating
about it. It had that elusive `easy' quality.''
</P>
<P>
   Many people thought so. Within its first year Bacchanalia became
Atlanta's hottest table. By its second, it was gaining a national
reputation, and Harrison and Quatrano were selected for the list of
``America's Best New Chefs'' by Food &AMP; Wine magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant's signature cuisine was actually a collaboration
of two distinctive _ sometimes polarized _ cooking styles. Harrison
says he is ``more of a logical and technical cook grounded in
standardized French cooking.'' Adds Quatrano, ``Clifford is a
consummate researcher, and I'm not. I'm more of a palate.''
</P>
<P>
   His building blocks are classic stocks, hers are locally grown
vegetables. He loves France for its starred restaurants, she loves
Italy for its peasant dishes. He is known as a loud, autocratic
chef, while she is a fan of quiet teamwork. They have two bottles
of truffle oil next to their stove at home _ black for him, white
for her.
</P>
<P>
   They are different people in every way, and their match is a
mystery. Says their in-house buyer and cheese expert, Raymond Hook,
``The secret to Annie and Cliff is what makes them tick.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrison is 39 but wired like a 12-year-old _ a bundle of
testosterone-fueled squirm. He jumps up out of his seat, giggles
mischievously and tries to get her goat. He also collects firearms
and hangs a cheesy girlie calendar in his cookbook-strewn office.
The big aloha lives on.
</P>
<P>
   His cooking interests lean toward the macho as well. With
old-growth oak trees littering the farm with acorns each fall, he
briefly considered raising acorn-fed pigs for prosciutto. That is,
until one of their dogs attacked the potbellied pigs they keep as
pets, killing one and nearly offing another. ``It was so hard on
Annie,'' says Harrison. ``She really loves animals. The pig was on
the operating table, and I told the vet, `Save this pig!''' Two
hundred stitches later, potbellied Patrick shows his scarred back
and sweet face as he delights in an organic salad for lunch.
Patrick's haunches are safe.
</P>
<P>
   Quatrano, 41, is an old soul _ warm, gentle and centered.
Responsibility edges her voice, and she seems the kind of person
who wakes up with a list of things to do each morning. She keeps
her sandy hair short, doesn't use makeup and wears loose linen
clothes in plain but stunningly resonant blacks and browns.
</P>
<P>
   ``She just has this natural style,'' says Peacock. ``It's in
everything she touches.'' Even though she didn't want Harrison to
get a motorcycle, she persuaded him to exchange a boss black BMW
for the classic but now rare beige.
</P>
<P>
   Quatrano's sense of style pushed them beyond the cramped
confines of the original Bacchanalia. In 1997 she and Harrison
opened their casual second venture, Floataway Cafe, in a cluster of
rehabbed industrial buildings. But it was very much her vision and
her project, with peasant-style European country dishes cooked in a
wood-fired oven and a focus on organic local produce. She became
chef there while Harrison stayed at Bacchanalia and continued to
refine and simplify his cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   Floataway Cafe, an immediate sensation, was largely inspired by
Zuni Cafe in San Francisco, the restaurant where Quatrano first
worked as a waiter in cooking school and whose owner, Judy Rodgers,
she considers a mentor.
</P>
<P>
   Recalls Rodgers, ``Annie was worth her weight in gold whatever
she was doing. She was a server who asked to help out in the
kitchen because she was so zealous, and in about 15 minutes she was
better than anybody. She was a sponge for learning.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed it was the famous Zuni burger that Quatrano first served
to Harrison. And dishes from that restaurant, including kumamoto
oysters with mignonette sauce and a chocolate cake called gateau
Victoire, have shown up in homage on her menu at Floataway.
</P>
<P>
   Yet now that Bacchanalia has moved into a larger and more
luxurious space better suited to fine dining, Quatrano has given
the helm at Floataway to a capable sous-chef and rejoined Harrison
at Bacchanalia. The team is reunited.
</P>
<P>
   The new restaurant has an open floor plan and a romantic view of
the Midtown skyline. It also features a long glass wall that
separates the kitchen in full view of from the dining room. For
Quatrano and Harrison, their cooking is an open book.
</P>
<P>
   And their plate is fuller than ever. Quatrano sat at the rolling
utility cart that serves as her kitchen table at home early one
morning and admitted, ``There's not a day I wake up in the morning
that I don't have to work.'' After five hours of sleep, she leaves
by 7:30 a.m., makes the hour-plus drive to work and stays in town
until midnight, first taking care of the books and payroll for both
restaurants, then cooking dinner. ``But I'll go on the record,''
she says over a cup of custom-roasted coffee, ``I don't do anything
here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Here'' is the funky farmhouse they built from their own
design, one that is clearly echoed at Floataway Cafe. The front
door opens to the middle of a dream kitchen, and visitors
immediately find themselves in a setting of clean architectural
lines, beautiful furnishings and the promise of fine cooking. A
12-foot ``library table'' runs nearly the length of the kitchen in
front of a tall cinder-block hearth. It is a homey and
unpretentious but aesthetically exacting environment.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison tends to the house, the animals, the gardens, the fruit
groves and the honeybees. He orders deliveries for both restaurants
from home, then drives into Atlanta around noon, sometimes on his
motorbike.
</P>
<P>
   After the old Bacchanalia closed but before the new one opened,
he worked as the chef at Floataway for a couple of weeks. ``I
couldn't believe it,'' he recalls. ``There was no veal stock!''
</P>
<P>
   ``And,'' he notes with a wink in her direction, ``Annie's
walk-in (refrigerator) is not as neat as mine.''
</P>
<P>
   She puts her arm around him. Her goat wasn't gotten. Quatrano
and Harrison have a complex, interlocking relationship that defies
casual understanding.
</P>
<P>
   But they clearly fit together like two halves of a
three-dimensional puzzle, balancing each other even in their
personal contradictions and seeming cross purposes. Bacchanalia and
Star Provisions promise the same.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
