<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    1ST LEDE
 &HT;    EDs: Corrects number of capital investments in 14th graf;
hometown of Arthur Ravenel in 24nd graf; dollar figure in 30th
graf.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    S.C. to again play a major role for GOP politics
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ Watching television in the 1960s, Columbia
native Mark Carman was shocked by the black-and-white footage of
state police and their snarling dogs attacking civil rights
marchers in Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   Now he says the unflattering national spotlight has turned on
South Carolina, its image tattered by the prolonged, angry fight
over the Confederate flag, as Republicans descend for Saturday's
pivotal presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are seeing how ugly we are, and it is tough,'' said Carman,
39, manager of Capital Newstand on Main Street, less than a block
from America's last state capitol to fly the Confederate flag.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina is shaping up to be the real loser in the
bruising, neck-and-neck primary between front runners George W.
Bush and John McCain. With Steve Forbes dropping out of the race
last week, Alan Keyes is expected to finish a distant third _ but
with a public image well ahead of the Palmetto State, still
fighting 135 years after the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are in a controversy where we are tearing each other apart
in this state,'' state Sen. Ernie Passailaigue (D-Charleston) said
last week, urging warring colleagues to compromise.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, says Walter Edgar, a history professor at the
University of South Carolina, the unfavorable national covarage
could spark some needed changes by showing ``people in South
Carolina that the outside world is watching.''
</P>
<P>
   The state legislature raised the Confederate flag in 1962 as
part of a Civil War centennial. Recently, Gov. Jim Hodges, several
former governors, the NAACP, the state chamber of commerce and
numerous other groups have called for the flag's removal. But the
legislature has failed to act, torn by the flag's clashing
symbolism _ heritage to Confederate ancestors and slavery to civil
rights groups.
</P>
<P>
   Expressing the growing frustration over the political stalemate,
University of South Carolina economist Doug Woodward joked that
U.S. Army soldiers from nearby Fort Jackson ought to march over and
take down the banner.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward said bad publicity from the flag could cost the state
more than the estimated few million dollars going into Republican
primary ads and accommodations for campaign staffs and reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is unfortunate that we are having this primary now while
this flag debate goes on,'' Woodward said. ''It does not reflect
well on the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither did last month's Republican candidates' debate in
Columbia, staged in an old home improvement store where the
national broadcast picked up catcalls by apparently drunken people
in the audience. A second televised debate is planned for Tuesday.
Alcohol will not be available to the general audience this time,
said Dana Mishoe, spokeswoman for debate sponsor, the Business and
Industry Political Education Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The fierce Republican campaigning has brought excitement to
South Carolina, not to mention unexpected advertising revenue to
radio and television stations. Through Friday, Bush and McCain had
purchased $380,000 worth of air time on NBC affiliate WIS-TV in
Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are expecting more dollars,'' said WIS-TV sales manager
Debbie Johnson, explaining that the close race is forcing Bush and
McCain to spend heavily.
</P>
<P>
   But judging by stinging comments last week on national programs
such as ''Larry King Live,'' C-Span's ''Washington Journal'' and
National Public Radio, the flag fight has overshadowed South
Carolina's achievements, such as attracting last year more than $6
billion in capital investments, a record.
</P>
<P>
   ''The sooner the flag issue is resolved, the better,''
Charleston Mayor Joseph Riley said. ''It has the potential to
incorrectly and unfairly portray our state.''
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina peacefully integrated its public colleges, said
Riley, also noting that retiring state Supreme Court chief justice,
Ernest Finney, is black.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the rancor over the flag has dredged up ugliness from the
past, some of which, fortunately for South Carolina's reputation,
hasn't yet drawn national attention.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina is the only state without a permanent, paid
holiday to honor the Rev. Martin Luther King' Jr.'s birthday. A
state House committee last week endorsed such a holiday, but not
before a Charleston Republican attacked the slain civil rights
leader's character.
</P>
<P>
   King was ''an enthusiastic serial adulterer who wandered through
life in adulterous relationships,'' state Rep. John Graham Altman
told the House Judiciary Committee. ''Perception has overtaken the
reality of the life he led.''
</P>
<P>
   A day later, state Democratic Party Chairman Dick Harpootlian
said he regretted Altman's slap, though it made Republicans look
bad.
</P>
<P>
   ''It makes (South Carolinians) look like a bunch of ignorant
rednecks who can't deal with one another with any degree of common
civility,'' Harpootlian said.
</P>
<P>
   For certain, the flag fight has unleashed hostilities, including
a racist handwritten death threat last week against one of the
flag's most vocal opponents, state Sen. Darrell Jackson
(D-Columbia).
</P>
<P>
   The letter, being investigated by state police, told Jackson he
didn't have ''the right or the class to shine Arthur Ravenel's
shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   Ravenel is a Republican senator from Mount Pleasant who refused
to apologize to the NAACP after telling a Confederate heritage
rally last month that the group stands for ''National Association
for the Mentally Retarded.''
</P>
<P>
   From South Carolina's rancor, the Confederate flag has suddenly
emerged as a lightning rod in America's uneasy debate over race. It
has dogged the Republican presidential candidates since last
month's debate in Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and McCain said South Carolinians ought to decide the
flag's fate, a position that Democratic presidential contender Bill
Bradley last week, during a Columbia stop, denounced as ignoring
''a hateful and shameful past.''
</P>
<P>
   The fierce campaigning has dredged up another skirmish. Visiting
Columbia last week, Democratic presidential contender Bill Bradley
criticized Bush for kicking off his South Carolina campaign with a
speech at Bob Jones University. In 1984, the fundamental Christian
college in Greenville lost its federal tax exempt status for
banning interracial dating and marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am afraid the primary is getting a little more press than we
would like,'' said Tom Sponseller, president of the Hospitality
Association of South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The trade group represents 1,500 hotels, restaurants and other
tourism businesses, increasingly worried about the NAACP's economic
boycott of South Carolina until the flag is removed.
</P>
<P>
   At least 96 groups have canceled plans for conventions and
meetings in South Carolina in response to the boycott, Sponseller
said. Those cancelations total more than $40 million in lost
revenue to businesses, according to the NAACP.
</P>
<P>
   In downtown Columbia, the flag fight has hurt Capital Newstand's
business.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Mark Carman said sales of magazines such as ''Ebony''
and ''Jet'' and of books by black authors have fallen by a third
since the NAACP announced its tourism boycott.
</P>
<P>
   Black people, he said, ''are not going to support a white-owned
store.''
</P>
<P>
   Carman is even more fearful of the possibility that the
Confederate flag would be relocated from atop the Statehouse to the
Confederate soldiers' monument, a short distance from the newstand.
</P>
<P>
   ''If it were at eye level, I'd hear about it five times as
much,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
