<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ULSTER-PEACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY IN NORTHERN IRELAND SEE ONLY WAR OF WORDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST _ Most people woke up here Saturday as passive observers
of the latest political crisis to hit Northern Ireland _ the
suspension of their power-sharing government just 72 days after its
birth.
</P>
<P>
   But if anyone is panicking, they aren't showing it.
</P>
<P>
   While some politicians have issued dire warnings that the peace
process is at its lowest point ever, many ordinary people seem more
relaxed. They seem disappointed but not depressed that the
power-sharing government, intended to transform Northern Ireland
into a modern, stable democracy, was put on ice only 10 weeks after
it was created.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, those boys are always fighting, but at least they're
fighting with their words now,'' said 66-year-old Frank Maguire,
pausing near the euphemistically named ``peace line'' that
separates Catholics and Protestants in West Belfast.
</P>
<P>
   Maguire, a retired pipe fitter, has seen it all _ burned out of
his home in 1969, running gun battles on his street, nephews jailed
for Irish Republican Army activity _ and he knows the difference
between what a crisis here means now and what it meant only a few
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The relatively muted reaction of many people in Northern Ireland
to the latest crisis is testimony to how much the place has changed
in the last decade as the peace process has made the force of
argument, rather than the argument of force, the preferred currency
here.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is the argument over how best to get rid of the
instruments of force, namely the IRA's hidden arsenal, that has led
to the suspension of the power-sharing assembly and the
cross-border institutions that were meant to forge unbreakable
bonds between Protestant unionists and Catholic nationalists in
Northern Ireland, and the people of the whole island.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, when the last power-sharing government collapsed after
five months in the face of a general strike organized by
pro-British loyalist paramilitary groups, there was no hope of
reinstituting it.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA and its loyalist enemies quickly filled the political
vacuum with some of the worst violence of The Troubles.
</P>
<P>
   But many people today seem to accept at face value pledges by
the IRA and the two main loyalist groups, the Ulster Volunteer
Force and the Ulster Freedom Fighters, that their cease-fires are
in no imminent danger of ending. While paramilitary groups continue
to dole out punishment beatings, ``kneecappings'' and the
occasional murder, there is no sense that the latest crisis will
see a sudden return to widespread violence.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, the power-sharing government was the exclusive domain
of moderates, who were pushed aside by extremists determined to use
violence to sort out the age-old dispute over whether Northern
Ireland should remain part of the United Kingdom or become part of
the Irish Republic. This time around, the power-sharing government
was more inclusive, containing political representatives of the
same paramilitary groups that wrecked the 1974 arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   And even though the most recent power-sharing executive lasted
less than half as long as the ill-fated 1974 incarnation, there is
a palpable sense here among many that it is only a matter of time
before the weapons stalemate can be worked out and the local
government can get back up and running. No such optimism existed
five years ago, let alone in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot has changed for the better since 1974,'' said Mae
Frazier, as she did her weekly shopping on Shankill Road, in the
Protestant working-class heartland of West Belfast.
</P>
<P>
   But Frazier's eyes wandered across the street to the storefront
that used to be Frizzell's fish shop, which the IRA blew up in
1993, killing nine Protestant men, women and children. On Shankill,
people do not include the IRA bomber who died in the blast in the
fatality count.
</P>
<P>
   While there remain those capable of violence, many people here
either believe or hope that politics can isolate those few. Most
people here, Protestant and Catholic, unionist and nationalist, see
no alternative to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Many people were impressed by how seriously the 12 members of
the power-sharing Cabinet took their duties. It was evidence that
even politicians here could set a positive example for a more civil
society.
</P>
<P>
   George Quigley, chairman of Ulster Bank and a tireless advocate
for building a more equitable, stable Northern Ireland, said the
creation of the power-sharing government, and the sight of locally
elected people responding to local problems, gave people heart. The
suspension, he said, leaves them craving more local government.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an asset that needs to be unfrozen fast,'' said Quigley.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA's last-minute pledge Friday to eventually put its
weapons ``beyond use'' was not enough to prevent the British
government from suspending the local assembly and restoring direct
rule from London. But the decision by British Secretary of State
Peter Mandelson was seen mainly as a way to save Ulster Union
leader David Trimble, under pressure from his own backers to win a
gesture from the IRA, from resigning and allowing the assembly to
collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Mandelson's decision infuriated republicans _ who see it as
evidence of Britain's refusal to stand up to unionist intransigence
_ and frustrated the Irish government, which was hoping the IRA's
belated flexibility could save the political institutions created
under the Good Friday Agreement of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   While the IRA's critics quickly pointed out that its pledge was
vague, others say the fact that the pledge was made at all is
remarkable proof that the peace process remains viable and capable
of producing compromise, in a society where compromise was once
viewed as treason.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IRA is saying the war is over, but they can't bring
themselves to say the war is over,'' said Michael Sheehan, 55, a
taxi driver originally from Kerry, a republican stronghold of the
Irish Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Many people here, meanwhile, seem to believe the war is over,
too, but can't bring themselves to say it either. The fact that
they are thinking it, though, means there could, finally, be light
at the end of the tunnel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
