<HEADER>
A4981 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-NEWJOBS-STRATEGY0213-     02-12 1320
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWJOBS-STRATEGY0213-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New job? Here's the plan
 &HT;    By Maria Mallory
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Congratulations. You landed the job.
</P>
<P>
   Now what?
</P>
<P>
   Career counselors and experts have some advice about starting a
new job _ strategies, observations and some of their own
experiences to encourage the newly hired and newly promoted.
</P>
<P>
   Keema Small is a recruiter and a member of the Resume Referral
Committee of the Atlanta Chapter of the Society of Human Resource
Management. Through her work at SHRM, Small advises workers looking
for internships and entry-level jobs in human resources.
</P>
<P>
   For a great start, she advises, network. Establish a mentor,
someone who can tell you the ins and outs of your company or just
someone who's willing to help you learn the ropes of your business.
</P>
<P>
   Get a company directory. You can look at a person's title and
get an idea of what he or she does. Maybe the person is in the area
you want or where you eventually want to be. Just tell them who you
are. ``I'm an intern,'' or ``I'm just starting here, and I want to
know more about the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Always get a lot of feedback from your manager. Always ask,
``How am I progressing?'' A lot of people assume they're doing
well. Even if the manager doesn't take the initiative to interact
with you, you should interact with your manager.
</P>
<P>
   Common mistakes: Getting complacent. Thinking you're not
replaceable. Maybe you have done the job before but with a
different company. You need to find out all you can about the
company you're working for. Maybe this company has a certain way
they want you to do things.
</P>
<P>
   Small's experience: ``I started out in health care recruiting.
That's the one thing that allowed me to move into technical
recruiting. Initially, when I started, some interviewers would give
me a hard time because they'd say, `You recruited health care.' In
my opinion, a recruiter is a recruiter. I'd go to meetings and pass
out business cards. I'm not afraid to walk up to someone, introduce
myself, tell them who I am and what my business is. I always tell
them, `If you hear of something, please give me a call.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Phil Van Horn, co-founder of the career Web site
SUCCESSisFUN.com based in Pasadena, Calif., offers these insights:
</P>
<P>
   For a great start: Focus more on listening than talking, arrive
a half hour early and leave an hour late while adjusting, be
patient with others the first few months as relationships (and
office politics) unfold. This is stuff our moms told us a long time
ago, but common courtesy never goes out of style.
</P>
<P>
   Common mistakes: Too often we are given part of the equation in
the interview process and then must assume what type of effort,
communication or result is needed. That can lead to
misunderstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Ask directly the first day or week to have expectations defined.
Look at it as a 30-day initiative. What must be accomplished by you
or your team in the first week or month you are on the job? And
then formally or informally review at the end of the month with
your boss how reality compared with expectation. From that, find
out how misunderstandings should be cleared up and productivity
improved. Approach this in a polite, positive manner and the result
can be surprising.
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn's experience: ``My partner and I literally started
SUCCESSisFUN with just two guys, two computers and a pool table ...
and total chaos in our lives from the long hours. Then we stopped,
assessed the damage, created a strategic site and marketing plan,
and started behaving like the executives and companies we make fun
of (except we wear shorts and sandals all the time). We've been
blessed with positive results. It's easy to be an `expert' on other
people's careers.''
</P>
<P>
   Nick Corcodilos, author and career guru at Ask the Headhunter.
Based in New Jersey, his Web site is www
</P>
<P>
   .asktheheadhunter.com.
</P>
<P>
   For a great start: Get adopted by someone on your new team so
you can learn the ins and outs of how the work is done. No matter
how good you are at the job, what matters most in the first few
months is how well you are accepted. And having a mentor is
critical. This gives you someone to bounce ideas off, someone to
ask for guidance, and someone who can introduce you to others in
the company. The whole key to initial success is other people: Get
close to them.
</P>
<P>
   Then jump in and start doing the job. ``Doing the job in the
interview is critical to actually winning an offer. You must carry
this approach into the job itself. Don't wait to be given work.
Find work, do it, then go to your manager and ask him or her to
grade you.
</P>
<P>
   If you keep your focus on the work rather than on the
formalities of interviewing or the politics of your department, you
will establish the necessary foundation for success in your work.
</P>
<P>
   Common mistakes: Many new hires expect that new ideas they bring
with them are just what the company needs, and they often go
overboard in acting or sounding like a breath of fresh air. While
it's good to jump right in and participate, it's important to
respect the culture and social structure of the team. You have to
earn your way in, by helping, not by taking over.
</P>
<P>
   Corcodilos' experience: ``The first time I worked for a company
other than my own, I devoted the first couple of weeks to getting
to know everyone. I was head of a sales team for a company that had
several locations, and our customers were spread all over. I'd
spend half of each work day getting to know the people in my
location and half locked in my office calling everyone else,
including our customers. I wanted to learn from them and give them
a chance to complain. The reaction was very positive. I was able to
solve most of their problems, and each customer immediately got to
know me as the guy who fixed things. It got us off on the right
foot.''
</P>
<P>
   Michelle A. Olson, regional manger, Employers Group, Orange
County, Calif.:
</P>
<P>
   For a great start: Be sure the job is right for you. The
employer typically uses the interview, reference checks, testing
and sometimes tools to measure a candidate's personality and
potential. However, it is as critical for the candidate to analyze
his or her fit with the company. There is nothing worse than
wearing a shoe that is one size too small. It is equally confining
to take a job that is not suited to the individual. Be sure that
your expectations for challenge and advancement are in sync with
the opportunities offered by the employer.
</P>
<P>
   Be honest with yourself. Don't settle for a job that is below
your capability. You'll find that your days are mundane. Challenge
is what motivates us to be better.
</P>
<P>
   Olson's experience: ``I wanted to be sure I went to work for a
company with a solid reputation and a positive focus. To me,
integrity is as important for the company as it is for the
individual.'' Man Jit Singh, president of Futurestep
(www.futurestep.com), the online recruiting arm of Korn Ferry
International:
</P>
<P>
   For a great start: Two things are essential. First, understand
and clearly define the performance expectation, and second,
understand the culture of the department in which you will work and
the style expectations the culture will place on you.
</P>
<P>
   Common mistakes: ``We see people jumping at opportunities
without assessing whether the new opportunity will leverage their
strengths, the culture of the organization is one with which they
feel an affinity, and the job content is something they would
enjoy.''
</P>
<P>
   Singh's experience: ``I moved from being a partner in a
consulting firm to the CEO of a temporary staffing firm. I think
the most important element in succeeding was adopting a
participatory management style and soliciting input from all levels
of the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Knight Ridder Newspapers contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
