<HEADER>
A4982 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-YARD-DISPLAY0213-COX     02-12 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YARD-DISPLAY0213-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Black history yard display creates controversy
 &HT;    By Bill Osinski and Christy Oglesby
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ No pink flamingoes for Josie Dean.
</P>
<P>
   In her front yard on a thoroughfare, she has created a tableau
of historical hate, complete with a lynched black baby doll and
signs with racial slurs.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, the homemade tourist attraction has created a traffic
problem and more than a little discontent in the racially mixed
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Dean, who is black, has lived on the corner for 11 years, and
she has routinely decorated her yard during holiday seasons and
political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   To mark this year's Black History Month, she created a display
which she calls ``Real Black History.'' The stark depictions of
racial atrocities are mixed with shreds of the Confederate flag and
a white sheet arranged to suggest a Ku Klux Klan night rider.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been this drastic before,'' Dean said.
</P>
<P>
   Dean said she received a divine inspiration to create a display
that would evoke some of the most dire images of this country's
racial history. A spirit voice asked her, ``Why was I lying to his
people?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   So she set out to feature events that she thinks many people are
too quick to forget.
</P>
<P>
   In the week or so it has been on display, there has been a
steady and sometimes heavy stream of visitors.
</P>
<P>
   One mother made a 90-minute bus trip, taking two buses and a
train to bring her three sons to see the display. ``I want them to
know the truth about black history,'' said Tameca Tyson, 26.
</P>
<P>
   Her 8- and 4-year-olds roamed through the display and stared at
the lynching scene while her 1-year-old sat quietly in his
stroller.
</P>
<P>
   ``They always talk about the good of black history and try to
leave out the bad,'' Tyson said. ``They should talk about it all
and this is what happened to us. Sometimes people forget about the
past.''
</P>
<P>
   Phrrya Rivers was there, too, with her three daughters.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is their history,'' said the elementary school teacher.
``I thought this was a very bold and courageous thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   However, some of Dean's neighbors said they fail to see any
historical or artistic merit in the display. All they see is
traffic congestion and racial divisiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's upset with her for turning our neighborhood into a
three-ring circus,'' said David Weathers. ``I think it's offensive
for people of both races all I see is hate.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the dozen or so, black and white, said they were
personally offended by the display, though a few added that they
thought Dean was within her rights.
</P>
<P>
   Some said black residents had called white residents to
apologize for the offensive display and to disassociate themselves
from it.
</P>
<P>
   Harriet Murray, a black neighbor of Dean's, said the display has
generated tension in what had been a quiet, caring neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm offended by it,'' Murray said, adding that she would not
take her young son to see the display because of its hostile
message.
</P>
<P>
   Also, she said, she and others have been disrupted by the stream
of strangers in the neighborhood. ``When I come home, I just want
to be home and left alone,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Pam Klingel, a white resident, said the traffic problem has been
a serious one. ``When I come home, I can't even get into my own
driveway.''
</P>
<P>
   She added that she can't understand why local authorities don't
do more to restrict and control the traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got cited for having an old truck in my yard, and yet she's
allowed to display something like that,'' Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   Dean dismissed her neighbors' complaints, saying, ``They're
jealous because they didn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   And to those who might question the taste of what she calls her
``free museum,'' Dean said, ``If a white woman had done this and
put it in a museum, it would be art.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
