<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4983 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-ZIMBABWE-VOTE-BOS &LR;      02-12 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-VOTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUGABE PUSHES CONSTITUTION, BUT FEW IN ZIMBABWE VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BULAWAYO, Zimbabwe _ John Gazi has a knack for opposing things.
</P>
<P>
   He fought against the whites of former colonial Rhodesia, and
then against the new black leaders of renamed Zimbabwe. He can't
stand the local music. He voted ``no'' in this weekend's referendum
on a new constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``People aren't interested in this thing,'' said Gazi, a builder
of low-cost housing. ``Why do we need a quick vote for an
unacceptable constitution? Even if we all vote no, the result will
come out yes. It's meaningless.''
</P>
<P>
   He may be right. Observers said that after weeks of pitched
campaigning by the government and its critics, poor turnout on the
first day of voting Saturday in Zimbabwe's first-ever referendum
probably ensures that President Robert Mugabe will get his way: a
new constitution that swells his already considerable power.
</P>
<P>
   A pyrrhic victory, Gazi said. Until Gazi and people like him get
what they are looking for, the president _ and Zimbabwe _ rests on
a throne of sand.
</P>
<P>
   Gazi is a veteran of the bush rebellion against white-ruled
Rhodesia. By the time he was 19, he commanded a platoon. His
targets were the large, fertile farms owned by the sons and
daughters of British settlers. He fought for seven years, and when
rebels won independence in 1980, Gazi and his comrades thought they
had finally get back the lands taken under colonialism.
</P>
<P>
   That did not happen. Instead of confiscating farms for black
resettlement, Mugabe left the whites on their land. Zimbabwe's new
ruler understood that agriculture was the backbone of his country's
economy, and that disrupting production would be disastrous.
</P>
<P>
   Within two years, Gazi was back at war. His target was again the
white farmers, but his enemy had changed. ``Land is what we fought
for,'' he said, ``but our government sold out. I'm not disgruntled.
I'm angry.'' He spent six years in solitary confinement in Mugabe's
prisons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Land is a life-and-death issue for Mugabe in the literal
sense, and not just in the sense of his tenure in office,'' said
John Makumbe, a political scientist at the University of Zimbabwe
in Harare, the capital. ``War veterans are very bitter about the
economy. They feel . . . destitute and landless in the country they
liberated. Mugabe knows they could remove him.''
</P>
<P>
   War veterans make up 60 percent of the military and 40 percent
of the police force, Makumbe said, and wield considerable
influence. In December 1997, amid a sudden and sharp economic
plunge, they took to the streets demanding payoffs and pensions.
When Mugabe could not impose a tax increase, he paid the veterans
off-budget.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinary Zimbabweans are running thin on patience for the
veterans. Everyone suffered during the liberation struggle, Makumbe
said, and everyone expected land after independence. A new
opposition movement growing out of the trade unions would cut
veteran pensions.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe, however, seems beholden to his former comrades in arms.
But he is in no position to deliver what they want, economists
said.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all of the most arable lands lie behind the fences of a
few white and black owners, while the majority of blacks live in
crowded urban townships or on stony, government-owned communal
plots. To solve that problem, the draft constitution states that
``the people of Zimbabwe must be enabled to reassert their rights
and regain ownership of their land; accordingly . . . the
government of Zimbabwe has no obligation to pay compensation for
agricultural land compulsorily acquired for resettlement.''
</P>
<P>
   Since November 1997, however, the government has repeatedly
threatened to take white-owned farms, with neither a plan nor the
money to resettle blacks on the land. Many of those already
acquired have fallen into the hands of Mugabe's cronies. Others lie
fallow. With the economy grinding to a halt amid critical shortages
of foreign currency, the government still has no money for land
reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ruling party safeguards the hoarding of land by commercial
farmers,'' Gazi said. ``None of the land that has been acquired has
been given out. Most veterans don't even have houses. Mugabe must
remember that war veterans are the only armed and trained group
that can oppose government. They can rise up anytime.''
</P>
</TEXT>
