Stevenson Ranch, which borders the Newhall Ranch - the largest
housing development ever approved by Los Angeles County. To its
backers, Newhall Ranch is a sensitively planned community. But
critics point out that much of the demand for housing in the region
is among the growing Hispanic and immigrant populations of urban
Los Angeles, where families are doubled up in apartments and cannot
yet afford suburban houses. (Monica Almeida/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) SANTA CLARITA, CA -- Feb. 12, 2000 -- CALIF-SPRAWL-1 --
The Newhall Ranch development site will border Stevenson Ranch,
Southern California's least populated area. Newhall Ranch is the
largest housing development ever approved by Los Angeles County,
with 21,600 units for 70,000 people to be built over the next 20
years. In that time the local population is expected to double.
(Monica Almeida/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- Feb. 12, 2000 -- TOY-FAIR-3 -- A display
shows Action Man, right, kicking a likely evil opponent with a
Mohawk haircut in the Hasbro showroom in Manhattan. Ready or not,
the curtain goes up Sunday on the American International Toy Fair,
the toy industry's most prestigious annual trade show. (Ruth
Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- Feb. 12, 2000 -- TOY-FAIR-2 -- Some 700 New
York actors and actresses have been hired as toy presenters during
the weeklong extravaganza, which is by far their greatest seasonal
employment opportunity outside the city's theater, film and
television industries. One actor, Philip Buch, channels the Action
Man toy figure before an encounter with the evil Dr. X in the
Hasbro showroom in Manhattan. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- Feb. 12, 2000 -- TOY-FAIR-1 -- Befitting New
York, demonstrations at the American International Toy Fair - the
toy industry's most prestigious annual trade show - have many of
the trappings of theater, including serious actors. Jewel Turner
rehearses lines for the Pokemon display in the Hasbro showroom in
Manhattan. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) MILLSTONE, N.J. -- Feb. 12, 2000 -- FAKE-FISH-TROPHIES-3
-- A model of a freshwater fish, left, getting its last touch from
Robert Kennedy at his business, the Great American FishHead Co., in
Millstone. The centuries-old art of skinning, stuffing and
varnishing a fish so it can be stuck on the wall and bragged about
is still alive and well. But taxidermists now make trophies out of
resin and plastic, too. (Dith Pran/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) MILLSTONE, N.J. -- Feb. 12, 2000 -- FAKE-FISH-TROPHIES-2
-- Robert Kennedy, with a rack of plastic blanks he turns into
display fish at his business, the Great American FishHead Co. in
Millstone. The shift toward fake-fish trophies, which has
accelerated over the last few years, has to do with their
durability, as well as with a new environmental sensitivity that
enables anglers to claim that no animals were harmed in the making
of this trophy. (Dith Pran/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) STUART, Fla. -- Feb. 12, 2000 -- FAKE-FISH-TROPHIES-1 --
Mike Kirkhart, who specializes in models of large saltwater fish,
finishing up a marlin head at New Wave Taxidermy in Stuart. A few
saltwater species have long been reproduced synthetically because
their oily skin deteriorates quickly. But taxidermists now make
replicas of everything from arctic char to piranha to spoonbill
catfish. (Cindy Karp/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- Feb. 12, 2000 -- CHILE-DECLASSIFY-3 -- Joyce
Horman with her late husband Charles' mother, Elizabeth Horman, 95.
Recently released documents make clear for the first time that the
State Department concluded from almost the beginning that the
Pinochet government had killed both Horman, 31, and Frank Teruggi,
24. Mrs. Horman is hoping she can finally learn what really
happened to her husband and is asking for Washington's help. ``I
want to know who gave the order,'' she says. (Marilynn K. Yee/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) UNDATED -- Feb. 12, 2000 -- CHILE-DECLASSIFY-2 -- Joyce
and Charles Horman just before they left for Chile, where he was
killed after a 1973 coup. Recently released documents make clear
for the first time that the State Department concluded from almost
the beginning that the Pinochet government had killed both, Horman,
31, and Frank Teruggi, 24. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) UNDATED -- Feb. 12, 2000 -- CHILE-DECLASSIFY-1 -- The
thick black lines imposed by a censor in 1980 have been stripped
away from a government report to reveal more about the deaths of
Charles Horman, left, and Frank Teruggi, center, in Chile in 1973.
American officials categorically denied any role in the young men's
deaths, which were dramatized in the 1982 movie ``Missing.'' (The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) DRODRO, Congo -- Feb. 12, 2000 -- CONGO-ETHNIC-WARS-2 --
A nurse in the town of Drodro with a box of barbed arrowheads that
were removed from patients at a hospital there. The fighting,
although primitive, has killed at least 2,000 people and as many as
7,000. The worst attack occurred about 40 miles north of Bunia, in
the village of Blukwa. (Ian Fisher/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) DRODRO, Congo -- Feb. 12, 2000 -- CONGO-ETHNIC-WARS-1 --
Mandesi Bussi, a Hema who lost three of her five children in a
massacre by the Lendu, found one son, Singo Losukpa, alive among
the dead. The attack in January was reported to have killed 416
Hema. (Ian Fisher/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) TAMPA, Fla. -- Feb. 12, 2000 -- BBA-YANKS-POSADA --
Yankees cathcer Jorge Posada is a talented and hard-working
switch-hitter with power. Now that Joe Girardi is gone, having
signed with the Chicago Cubs, there is only Posada, coming off a
year in which he batted .245 and accumulated more passed balls (17)
than that of 26 teams. To be more effective, the 28-year-old
catcher must forge a better working relationship with the majority
of the Yankees' pitching staff. (Jon Adams/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Feb. 12, 2000 -- BBN-METS-PIAZZA -- After a
rough-and-tumble 1999 season and postseason, Mets catcher Mike
Piazza, who will turn 32 on Sept.4, is ready to go again in 2000.
There are six springs left on Piazza's Mets contract, six more
years to produce as expected for a player with a seven-year,
$91million contract. (Barton Silverman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) CHEYENNE, Wyo. -- Feb. 12, 2000 -- WEST-POLITICS-2 --
Gov. Jim Geringer, R-Wyo., says his region is overlooked. One
reflection of the region's scant influence is that, for the fifth
straight election cycle, not one of the presidential or vice
presidential debates is to be held in any of the eight states.
(Kevin Moloney/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) CHEYENNE, Wyo. -- Feb. 12, 2000 -- WEST-POLITICS-1 --
Gov. Jim Geringer, R-Wyo., says his region is overlooked. ``Any
kind of public debate would focus on policies of the West,'' he
says. Like protection of national forest lands. Who wouldn't be for
that? But if you don't talk about areas for grazing and areas for
logging, then you've not taken everybody into consideration. And
without debates, that part of it gets lost.'' (Kevin Moloney/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- Feb. 12, 2000 -- MOUNTAIN-OUTDOORS -- Ed
Viesturs navigating a slope in the Himalayas. He has reached the
summit of Everest five times and is no longer awed by the
achievement. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Feb. 12, 2000 -- REVIEW-FASHION-2 -- From
Hussein Chalayan for Tse, a boldly geometric-print wool A-line
skirt, far right, with map print shirt. Companion pieces include,
from left, a suit, a dress and a coat. (G. Paul Burnett/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Feb. 12, 2000 -- REVIEW-FASHION-1 -- From
left: Trigere-inspired trousers in exaggerated houndstooth and
high-neck matching blouse, by John Bartlett (G. Paul Burnett/The
New York Times); From Tuleh, matelasse gold trousers with fur
jacket, by Josh Patner and Bryan Bradley; Cynthia Rowley's
slit-front alligator skirt with brass clasp and cowl-neck sweater.
(Corina Lecca/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) UNDATED -- Feb. 12, 2000 -- MCCAIN-FCC -- Sen. John
McCain's behavior as chairman of the Commerce Committee has come
under scrutiny because of his intervention, which came to light
last month, on behalf of a political donor, Lowell Paxson. The
senator wrote the communications commission last year, urging
action on Paxson's application for a television license in
Pittsburgh. Although McCain did not suggest how the commissioners
should vote, Paxson's application was approved. (Monica Almeida/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) UNDATED -- Feb. 12, 2000 -- OBIT-PAASCHE-B&AMP;W -- Maria
Paasche, who helped Jews escape from Nazi Germany on the back of
her motorcycle and whose father and brothers conspired to kill
Hitler, died Jan. 21 in a San Francisco nursing home. She was 90.
(The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Feb. 12, 2000 -- OBIT-TRIPP-B&AMP;W -- Peter
Tripp, a popular disc jockey in New York in the late 1950s whose
career peaked when he stayed awake for more than eight days as a
stunt but later plunged when he was found guilty of accepting
thousands of dollars in payola, died Jan. 31 in a hospital in
Northridge, Calif. He was 73. The cause of death was a stroke, said
Richard W. Fatherley of Kansas City, Kan., a friend. (The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
