<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4995 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NJ-COMMERCIAL-REAL-10     02-12 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-COMMERCIAL-REAL-1060(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: ONE-TIME GRISTMILL BECOMES OFFICES AND SHOWROOM 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOHN HOLUSHA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERONA, N.J. _ The first thing noticed by a visitor to the
Behrle Group's offices is wood _ lots of unpainted, exposed wood.
There are tan horizontal timbers bolted to the darker wooden
columns that support the interior of the building. The roof is
supported by more massive wooden beams, all visible from the second
floor.
</P>
<P>
   Today the building houses modern offices and is a showroom for
the office furniture that Behrle sells, much as an auto dealership
displays different makes of cars. But the structure has roots
extending back to the United States' earliest years. According to
local historians, a least part of the building dates back to 1790,
when it housed a gristmill, powered by the flow of water in the
nearby Peckman River.
</P>
<P>
   This is an example of the successful reuse of a building whose
interior wooden columns and roof supports _ some as much as 15
inches wide on each squared-off side _ are made from the trunks of
single trees and would be almost impossible to duplicate today.
Indeed, much of the new structure is composed of smaller pieces of
wood glued together to match the dimensions of the older, and still
sound, columns and beams.
</P>
<P>
   This is a story of a tenant who could see the possibilities in a
gloomy, one room building that had stood vacant for more than 10
years. It is also about a developer who prefers to preserve the
past rather than bulldoze it and an architect who helped make it
happen.
</P>
<P>
   The Behrle Group consists of 10 companies involved in office
design and furnishing, residential furnishing and country-club
remodeling, eight of which are located here. Since the company is
in the design business, Peter Behrle, the chief executive, said he
was unusually sensitive to the appearance of his own headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted something that was fun and unique,'' he said. ``It
would not be acceptable for us to be in traditional space.''
</P>
<P>
   The main building at the old mill complex is at 271 Grove Ave.
in the northeastern part of this Essex County town. From the late
1800s through the 1940s, it housed a bronze powder mill, where
large hammers pounded sheets of bronze into powder that was used in
inks, labels, flocked wallpaper and other decorations. After
operations moved elsewhere, the place remained a working factory
until 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Although a relatively new owner had started replacing the old
windows with modern insulated models, the building still had a
grim, abandoned look and all the wood that is so gloriously exposed
today was covered with layers of green industrial paint. Even
though it had stood empty for 10 years, the roof had been
maintained, so the wood inside had not been damaged by rain, which
is often the undoing of old buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The building consists of several parts, evidently built at
different times, although no one is completely sure, because many
of the records of the bronze powder mill were discarded by a
subsequent owner. At one end of the building the roof is supported
by a conventional wood truss structure.
</P>
<P>
   But in the main space, the roofline is higher and supported by
the massive timbers with no truss structure. This greater height
and volume of space, presumably built to accommodate the brass
powder machinery, was the key to the project, because it allowed
the installation of a second floor with a dramatic two story
entryway.
</P>
<P>
   Behrle said he had been looking at space in northern New Jersey
for about a year before looking at the building in Verona and
deciding it could work as an office and a showcase. ``I like
putting traditional furniture close to the old beams,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that he had some experience in adapting old industrial
buildings to a new use as a result of a related company's
conversion of an old clothing mill in Bethlehem, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it took a good bit of imagination to see the dreary old
mill as the lively office and design center it has become. ``It was
not a happy place,'' said Charles O. Logan Jr, the president of
Aztec Corp., the architect for the project. ``The floors were
chopped up and everything was covered with paint.''
</P>
<P>
   Once arrangements had been made to lease the building, the
architect and his workers started scraping away the layers of paint
and found that the walls were made of brick piers that supported
roof timbers with concrete block between the piers. The brick was
sandblasted down to its natural finish along with the wooden
columns and beams. The concrete block was painted over again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We covered up the things that were not attractive enough to
enhance,'' Logan said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the big questions was whether the old wooden columns were
strong enough to hold the weight of a second floor. It turned out
the old timbers were, for the most part, up to the job, but the
concrete they stood on was suspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a structural engineer do borings into the footings, and
we had to add support there,'' Logan said. Two steel columns were
also added to ensure the integrity of the second floor, but they
were hidden so as to not detract from the historic wood.
</P>
<P>
   Adding modern utilities such as electrical and
telecommunications wiring, and plumbing, without destroying the
character of the building was a challenge as well, since all the
design and business functions of the Behrle Group are done on
computers. The solution for most of the infrastructure was to cut
trenches in the floor to take the wires and pipes to where they
were needed.
</P>
<P>
   What couldn't be hidden is blatantly displayed. The sheet-metal
heating and air-conditioning ducts contrast sharply with the dark
fir timbers to which they are attached. To provide adequate
headroom on the second floor, angled wooden braces between the
vertical columns and roof beams had to be removed from their
original placements and moved upward.
</P>
<P>
   The work was painstaking and time-consuming. Behrle said he
signed a lease in January 1998, but was not able to move in until
last June. ``It was a complicated project,'' he said. ``So we
didn't rush. We wanted it to be done right.''
</P>
<P>
   The mill complex, which contains some other, smaller buildings
that have also been restored, is owned by J. Webster Realty, one of
the corporate vehicles operated by Steven Plofker, a lawyer and
developer based in Montclair. Plofker said that, where possible, he
tries to preserve old buildings.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He said he was particularly drawn to the massive fir columns and
beams in the building now occupied by the Behrle Group when he
first saw them about four years ago. ``I have never seen new lumber
like that,'' he said. ``It would be painful to demolish something
of that sort.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, to leave the beams completely visible, he put insulation
on top of the roof rather than the usual placement underneath.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he said some changes had to be made to improve the
marketability of the complex. He said he took down some smaller
mill buildings, that he said were beyond repair. ``The columns were
too close, the ceiling were too low,'' he said. An old house on the
property was demolished as well, because it had been remodeled so
many times and in so many different styles that it had little
historical significance.
</P>
<P>
   The site needed modification as well. ``There was a hill behind
the Behrle building, so there was no flat land for parking,''
Plofker said. ``We had to move a lot of dirt to make it suitable.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the demolition, there is a vacant site available
where Plofker said he plans to put up a building to house doctors'
offices. He said he plans to be sensitive to the history of the
mill complex and not plunk a modern glass and steel building
nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I build new, I try to make it look old,'' he said. ``The
nicest compliment I can get in those cases is when someone looks at
a building and says, `Nice restoration.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
