<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-CALIF _ Coverage of Bill Bradley's and Al Gore's
back-to-back speeches at the California Democratic Convention on
Saturday morning. (Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-STRETCH _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush, his
big-budget and big-buddies presidential campaign hanging in the
balance, is entering nine days that could go a long way toward
determining whether he will become a president or a poster boy for
political underachievers. In what could be the most important
stretch of his political career, Bush is battling toward crucial
showdowns with Sen. John McCain in South Carolina, Michigan and
Arizona, his foe's home state. (Herman, Austin American-Statesman)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   SC-GOP _ Once again, the South Carolina primary will play a
pivotal role in Republican presidential politics, and politicos and
media have descended on the state. Why do the natives make of all
this? How much revenue does the election bring in? And is the
national attention necessarily a good thing, considering the
Confederate flag controversy, the high-profile of Bob Jones
University and the fact that much of the audience was drunk during
the first debate. (Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 30.
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   GINGRICH _ Newt Gingrich was a fund-raising powerhouse the first
half of 1999, pulling in more than a $1 million from people all
over the country for his political action committee. That was
before he left his wife. Since July, when Gingrich filed for
divorce from his wife of 18 years, the Friends of Newt Gingrich PAC
has brought in a quarter as much, about $288,000. Gingrich's folks
say they have purposely slowed their fund-raising as they looked to
close down the FONG PAC. Last month, Gingrich started a new kind of
fund-raising machine, one from which he won't be required to file
disclosures and donate money to candidates. (Stanford, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20. MOVED FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CAMPS _ NESTEROVSKOE, Russia _ At first glance, scenery
along the well-paved country road running across the Russian
republic of Ingushetia resembles many American back roads. But the
resemblance ends at the driveways, where instead of mail boxes or
house numbers stand hand-painted signs with the words ``Refugees
Live Here.'' An estimated 200,000 people, or a third of Chechnya's
population, have fled fighting between the Russian army and rebels
and moved to neighboring Ingushetia, nearly doubling this
republic's population. (Coker, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Thursday, Feb. 10.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-VOTEBUYING _ MEXICO CITY _ Somebody obviously didn't like
the idea of a special commission to prevent vote buying during the
campaign to select Mexico's next president on July 2. Elodia
Gutierrez, the commission president, received threatening anonymous
letters and phone calls that only stopped after she went public in
January. Buying or coercing votes by using public social programs
for the poor as bait is considered one of the biggest obstacles to
holding truly clean elections in Mexico. Despite claims they've
changed their ways, the country's ruling Revolutionary
Institutional Party, the PRI, takes ``the grand prize'' when it
comes to this illegal practice, according to groups monitoring
elections. (Ferriss, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTO (of Elodia
Gutierrez).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Thurs., Feb. 10.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS _ JERUSALEM _ The deadline for the framework
agreement toward a final pact on peace between Israel and
Palestinians is expected to come and go. That's a lot less
pessimistic outlook for the oft-turbulent Middle East peace process
than when Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak took over. What now?
(Kaplow, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Thursday in (i) International and (k) Commentary
categories.
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRIA-EU _ VIENNA, Austria _ Austria's new government took
office this week amid cries of outrage from around the world and
threats of isolation from its European neighbors and the United
States. Each night, thousands of raucous demonstrators marched down
this staid and elegant city's boulevards. The cause of it all is
the government's inclusion of the Freedom Party, which is described
as somewhere between neo-Nazi and American Republican. So far, the
greatest affect of the domestic and international indignation is to
greatly enhance Joerg Haider's popularity in Austria and perhaps to
encourage other right wing parties seeking power across Europe.
(Roughton, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Thursday in (i) International (k) Commentary
categories.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: With a box on other right wing parties in Switzerland,
France, Italy, Belgium, Denmark, Germany and Britain.
</P>
<P>
   US-AFRICA _ WASHINGTON _ Despite their obvious close historical
ties, Africans and African Americans have an estranged relationship
that many believe exists because of ignorance on both sides.
(Turay, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Previously budgeted info box will not move.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Wednesday, Feb. 9, in (i) International and (k)
Commentary categories.
</P>
<P>
   DATELINE-INDIA _ President Clinton is coming next month. But, at
the moment, the biggest story in India is about a movie.
Controversial filmmaker Deepa Mehta was set to tackle her latest
sensitive topic here, Hindu widows. She was set to start shooting
her film, which takes place in the 1930s, last week _ until the set
was razed by Hindu nationalists. Now, cultural organizations are
lining up behind Mehta, but the government so far is taking no
steps to protect her. And everyone has an opinion. (Basu, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   UNIVERSE _ WASHINGTON _ New telescopes on the ground and in
orbit are creating a revolution in astronomy. The discovery of 33
planets orbiting other suns in our galaxy, as well as new black
holes, quasars, supernovae and other strange heavenly objects, are
expanding our understanding of the universe and our own solar
system. (Nesmith, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS and SIG.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: This is the first installment of ``Windows on the
Universe,'' an occasional series on astronomical discoveries that
Jeff Nesmith will be writing this year.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   UNIVERSE-TOOLS _ WASHINGTON _ Of several technological
breakthroughs that helped revolutionize modern astronomy, two
events in the 1990s stand out. The first was the launching of
NASA's Hubble Space Telescope in April 1990. The second was a
spin-off of former President Reagan's ``Star Wars'' dream, the
Strategic Defense Initiative (SDI). (Nesmith, Cox News Service)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   ROBERTS _ BETHESDA, Md. _ On Valentine's Day, ABC-TV
correspondent Cokie Roberts and her journalist husband, Steven
Roberts, publish ``From This Day Forward,'' a book about their life
together and the institution of American marriage. (Dart, Cox News
Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Monday in (w) Washington and (e) entertainment
categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA-SLAYINGS _ News of the day following the grand jury
indictment of Baltimore Ravens star Ray Lewis and two of his
friends Friday on murder charges in the stabbing deaths of two men
the morning after the Super Bowl. News reports and Oakley's
attorney said that Oakley, was allegedly on his way to Atlanta to
turn himself in. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   REBEL-FLAG _ The uproar over flying the Confederate battle flag
in South Carolina is playing out in Texas as well. The NAACP wants
the state to ban the flag from public places, particularly public
schools that still use it with their rebel mascot and the Supreme
Court building, with its Confederate plaque. So far, Gov. George W.
Bush and other state leaders have not shown any sign they plan to
follow the group's lead. (Harmon, Austin American-Statesman). 25.
WITH PHOTO. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   YARD-DISPLAY _ ATLANTA _ Josie Dean has put up a yard scene in
honor of black history month that has generated quite a buzz. One
woman Friday traveled an hour and a half by bus to see it; but some
neighbors are turning away. Black visitors say Dean is courageous
to depict a lynching scene, but some white neighbors say it only
stirs up pain from a bygone era. (Oglesby, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
