<SLUG> BC-SKATE-U.S.-CHAMPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 SKATERS, 2 DIFFERENT PATHS TO THE SAME PATCH OF ICE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Minn.)  (mk) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ In the through-the-looking-glass world of figure
skating, 17-year-old Heidi Pakkala and 14-year-old Sarah Hughes are
on career paths that, like railroad tracks, will run parallel but
will never intersect.
</P>
<P>
   It was Hughes who was being celebrated as a potential champion
at the national championships, a veteran of tough international
competition, while Pakkala was making her first appearance at any
level. She had no visibility as a novice, or as a junior, and when
she read a recent newspaper article about her competitors in the
senior women's division, she became nervous and lightheaded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost had to go to the school nurse,'' Pakkala said.
</P>
<P>
   They trained together during the week, preparing for Friday's
short program. Hughes, of Great Neck, N.Y., finished second, while
Pakkala, of Bloomington, Minn., was 13th. Yet each had worked
equally hard and each could claim her own successes. Hughes planned
an unprecedented set of combination jumps for Saturday night's long
program, while Pakkala hoped for the happy anonymity of the lower
reaches of the top 10.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes earned two marks of 5.9 for presentation in the short
program and positioned herself to upset Michelle Kwan. Pakkala
landed an exquisite triple lutz-double toe combination, but she
managed only a single rotation on a mandatory double axel, and the
judges were unforgiving. One gave her a 4.0 for technical merit.
But she recovered with a couple of 5.1s for presentation and the
crowd loved her, booing when her low marks were flashed on the
scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   That was worth the trip. She had arrived here as a nobody, and
she had stirred an audience to support her by voicing disapproval
with the judges. Pakkala had been so nervous before the
performance, said her coach, Kathleen Schmetz Gazich, ``I thought
she would totally bomb.'' After her combination jump, she looked up
at the scoreboard, saw herself skating and felt an odd moment of
disconnection.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was overwhelming,'' said Pakkala, a 5-foot-5-inch high
school senior with cropped blond hair and a soft voice. ``But it
was fun, at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   If she had not won any kind of championship, she had at least
won a victory of perseverance. It is exceedingly rare for a skater
who has made no imprint at the novice or junior level to qualify
for the senior championships. As a 6-year-old, Pakkala had skated
an exhibition before the king and queen of Sweden in Minneapolis.
She had portrayed Sonja Henie, and she even had her own dressing
room.
</P>
<P>
   But, as recently as a year ago, she was discouraged, not
believing in herself or her coach. So she made a switch, her
confidence inflated like a balloon and she earned her way to the
nationals by finishing second at the Midwestern sectionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pessimistic about skating,'' Pakkala said. ``I knew it
was my last chance. So I decided to work as hard as I could.
Everything is a lot better now. I'm glad I didn't peak when I was
14. I think I have a lot more appreciation now. I'd like to keep
doing this for a few years.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, at 12, Hughes won the national junior
championship, which is seldom a sign of future success at the
senior level. The last junior national champion to win a senior
national title was Jill Trenary, a decade ago. Bodies change,
interests change, injury hobbles promising careers. But Hughes has
made an ascendant transition so far. She has not experienced
problems with jumping as her body has matured and her center of
gravity has migrated. In fact, reliability has become her
trademark.
</P>
<P>
   The evolution in her skating occurred quickly last year. At the
nationals, she skated deliberately, with a paint-by-the-numbers
caution, which could be expected of a 13-year-old, and she finished
fourth. A month later she delivered a relaxed, fluid, grown-up
performance and finished seventh at the world championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's long-legged and tall and she's still able to do her
triple jumps while being an elegant skater,'' said Dick Button, the
two-time Olympic champion. ``I think she's in a perfect place at
the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   This season Hughes has worked diligently on the artistic side of
her skating, attempting to draw the audience into her performance,
to feel the music, to show more expressiveness in her face, to
extract what she is feeling inside and to portray it on the
outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel more seasoned,'' Hughes said. ``It feels weird. I'm
only 14. But it feels different from last year.''
</P>
<P>
   She is a freshman at Great Neck North High School, determined to
continue living at home and maintaining some connection to a
regular life. Each morning she takes classes in honors biology and
world history from 8 to 9:30, then travels an hour to a rink in
Hackensack, N.J., and trains until about 3 p.m. Two of her teachers
visit her house to tutor her in English and math. She also plays
the violin in the school orchestra and intends to become a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can go to school, why not be around other kids my age and
not spend all my time around a rink?'' Hughes said. ``When you go
to school, a lot of people don't know anything about a triple lutz.
It brings you back into reality. I think I get the best of both
worlds.''
</P>
<P>
   She is known in the hallways as Sarah the Skater. On Saturday
night she planned to become the first American woman to land triple
salchow-triple loop and triple toe-triple loop combination jumps.
It would be Hughes' best chance to pull off the grand upset, to
skate a more difficult program and hope that her technical ability
could overcome Kwan's artistic superiority.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what sports is all about,'' said Robin Wagner, who
coaches Hughes. ``It's about getting faster, driving faster,
swimming faster. I told Sarah, `Isn't it nice being the first one
doing it instead of having to be the chaser?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
