<SLUG> BC-BKC-VILLANOVA-STJOHN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ST. JOHN'S BEATS VILLANOVA WITH A RUSTY BARKLEY
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There was the no-look bounce pass to complete a
3-on-1 break. There were the windmill hands that knocked the ball
loose, followed by the natural reflex of banging it off Villanova
center Malik Allen's knee. Then, Erick Barkley lofted an alley-oop
pass to Lavor Postell. In just four minutes of basketball, Barkley,
the St. John's guard, rediscovered a smile that had been missing
for a week.
</P>
<P>
   He shot a finger toward the roof of Madison Square Garden. He
hopped on his toes. He was free of the NCAA and back on the court.
If only Villanova would have acted as overjoyed as the 15,208 fans
who showered Barkley with applause during warm-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Wildcats harassed him and took advantage of the
rust that accumulated while he missed two games and practiced with
other matters on his mind. He was an awful 6 of 16 from the field,
missed four 3-pointers and, uncharacteristically, missed four free
throws down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, Barkley finished with 16 points and St. John's
prevailed, 78-75, in a game that neither team looked eager to win
for the entire second half.
</P>
<P>
   For seven minutes, Villanova and St. John's traded baskets and
were deadlocked at 57-57. When Chudney Gray sank two free throws
and Bootsy Thornton followed his own 15-footer with a tip-in
basket, the Red Storm took a 61-57 lead with 7 minutes 40 seconds
left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   But Allen, who finished with 25 points, muscled inside twice to
tie it again, at 61-61. It took a while, but Barkley finally found
his 3-point range, hitting a pair, to put the Red Storm up by 69-65
with just over three minutes left to play. After Thornton posted up
in the lane for a turnaround jumper, it looked as if the Red Storm
had beaten the Wildcats.
</P>
<P>
   No. Jermaine Medley stepped behind the professional 3-point arc
to launch a line drive that ripped through the nets to bring the
Wildcats within 71-69. When Barkley missed a free throw and Allen
hit his 25th point of the afternoon, the Wildcats were still
hanging in at 72-71.
</P>
<P>
   After St. John's Anthony Glover and Villanova's Gary Buchanan
exchanged nifty drives, it was up to Postell to give the Red Storm
the edge. With 21.4 seconds left, the senior co-captain hit a pair
of free throws. It was 76-73 when Buchanan dribbled the ball off
his leg and into Barkley's hands. Barkley was fouled but made only
one of two free throws.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Wildcats did not fade. With 16.9 seconds left, Medley
dribbled the length of the floor and banked in a runner from the
middle of the lane to cut it to 77-75. Villanova fouled Postell on
the inbounds pass and, with 10.5 seconds left, he made one of two.
Allen dribbled past midcourt but had the ball knocked away from
behind. So with 3.3 seconds left, the Wildcats had an inbounds pass
under their bucket and a chance to tie the score.
</P>
<P>
   The ball went to Buchanan in the left corner. He leaped to
attempt a tying 3-pointer, but Glover pinned the ball and it rolled
out of bounds. With eight-tenths of a second left, Villanova
couldn't get another pass to Allen in time for a shot. It was over
_ the third straight victory for the Red Storm (16-6, 8-3).
</P>
<P>
   Early in the first half, Barkley's burst of three assists and
two steals powered the Red Storm to an 18-7 lead, and it appeared
that St. John's was on its way to an easy victory. But Villanova
bombed its way back to a 33-33 halftime tie as Medley hit his third
3-pointer as the buzzer sounded.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats made their 3-pointers count, hitting 6 of 10, while
the Red Storm, one of the Big East's worst 3-point-shooting teams,
hit only 4 of 15.
</P>
<P>
   Between the poor shot selection and sloppy ball-handling _ 12
first-half turnovers that led to 16 Wildcats points _ St. John's
blew a seven-point lead by not scoring for the last 6:22 of the
first half.
</P>
<P>
   It was apparent early that Barkley intended to hustle away the
blues that shrouded him throughout a difficult week in which he
missed victories against Boston College and Providence because of
an NCAA suspension. But on Thursday, an NCAA appeals committee
sliced one game off the three-game penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA ruled that Barkley had received an extra benefit when
he traded a 1996 Jeep Cherokee for a 1995 Chevrolet Suburban owned
by a Rucker League coach who has known Barkley since he was 14.
Although the borrowed Suburban was a year older than the Cherokee,
the NCAA determined it had a higher book value. On Tuesday, it
suspended Barkley for three games.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the appeal, St. John's documented that the Suburban'swindshield wipers and odometer did not work, that it got worse gas
mileage and that it couldn't possibly be worth more than the
Cherokee, according to an associate of Barkley's.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half, Barkley's six assists and five steals gave
the Red Storm energy _ just as his 2-of-9 shooting took it away.
His first four shots were misses from beyond the 3-point arc; he
finally got on the board with a layup with 8:56 left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I served my punishment even though I felt I didn't break any
rules,'' Barkley said in a statement released through St. John's on
Friday. ``Now things can get back to normal with school and playing
basketball again.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Red Storm will have Barkley back for six more regular-season
games _ a treacherous stretch that will decide whether the team
makes the NCAA tournament. St. John's meets No. 3-ranked Duke and
the Big East rival Miami on the road, and will play host to No. 4
Syracuse , No. 13 Connecticut and surging Seton Hall at the Garden.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Storm needs to win at least three of its remaining games
to make the NCAA field of 64. If St. John's regroups and finishes
strong with five victories, its tournament seeding will improve
because of the strength of those opponents.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
