<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-UCONN-RUTGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCONN WOMEN CAN'T BE SLOWED DOWN BY RUTGERS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PISCATAWAY, N.J. _ On one end of the floor, Rutgers was
desperately trying to stick to its game plan, slowly working the
shot clock as it passed the ball around the perimeter until the
final tick of almost every possession. And on the other end,
prodded by the stomping feet of its head coach, Connecticut tried
desperately to break the slow-ball shackles and run. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As if the pressure of facing the No. 1-ranked team in the nation
was not enough, the Scarlet Knights were trying to convince
themselves that there was nothing to fear.
</P>
<P>
   And Rutgers fought it from the opening tip until the final
minute. But when Connecticut's Sue Bird went barreling into press
row, calling a timeout as she was about to crash, with 6.2 seconds
left, the Scarlet Knights finally lowered their heads and accepted
the harsh reality that they could not stop the Huskies.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut squeezed out a 49-45 victory at the Rutgers Athletic
Center, staying out of the Lady Knights' grasp long enough to score
enough to escape with the victory. And for the ninth time in 10
tries, Rutgers found itself on the short end of the score against
Connecticut (21-1).
</P>
<P>
   While the point total for the Huskies was a season low, the
Knights found themselves unable to score when they needed to most.
Rutgers (15-5) scored 19 points in the second half and eight points
in the final 9 minutes 5 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The Knights had started the season at the top of some polls, but
tumbled after a season-opening loss to North Carolina State and
then unexpected defeats to George Washington University and
Villanova. Entering this game as the nation's No. 10-ranked team,
and enduring the familiar position of looking up at Connecticut,
which has held the No. 1 spot for 14 weeks, Rutgers saw it as a
chance for revenge and redemption.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout a first half in which his Huskies could not find the
basket, UConn coach Geno Auriemma sat passively. He walked slowly
and deliberately to the locker room at halftime. When Auriemma
emerged for the second half, he would not sit for a second, and
neither would his team. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies came and pressed Rutgers, with the huge contingent
of Connecticut fans who filled the upper half of the RAC screeching
their team on. With 13:38 to play, the Huskies pulled even, 34-34.
UConn had trailed by as many as 11 points in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers pushed ahead again, 37-36, on a free throw by Tammy
Sutton-Brown. But the Huskies continued to apply the pressure,
taking their first lead since 3-2, on a jumper by Kennitra Johnson
that made it 38-37 with 8:50 to play. When Swin Cash followed with
a layup, it gave Connecticut a 40-37 advantage, its biggest lead of
the game to that point.
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers tied the score on a 3-pointer by Tasha Pointer, but the
Knights' efforts to slow the pace were taking a toll. With Auriemma
shuttling in fresh bodies and Rutgers countering by milking the
30-second clock to its end almost every possession, the foul
trouble and pressure continued to mount against Rutgers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After Pointer tied the score, 40-40, Rutgers did not score again
for 3:20 as the deficit grew to 48-40 before Usha Gilmore somehow
banked in a 3-pointer from the deep right corner.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut's only defeat this season had come three games
earlier, a 72-71 loss to Tennessee. But UConn had followed that
setback with a 52-point decision over Seton Hall and a 47-point
mastery of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Just as they had in the first meeting between the teams this
season, a 65-50 Connecticut victory, the Lady Knights raced to an
early lead Saturday. In the first meeting, Rutgers led by 21-12
before seeing it all disappear under the weight of a 17-0 run by
the Huskies. In that game, Rutgers had held the Huskies to 29
points in the first half, a season low for Connecticut. Saturday,
whether it was the Rutgers defense or miserable shooting by
Connecticut, the Scarlet Knights built a 26-20 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   The only semblance of offense by either team came from Rutgers'
Shawnetta Stewart, who hit 4 of 5 shots, including three
3-pointers, for 11 points in the opening 12 minutes, as Rutgers
built a 17-10 lead. But she left the game at that point, spending
the rest of the first half on the bench with an ice pack strapped
to the back of her neck after colliding with UConn's Svetlana
Abrosimova.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Stewart out, and its offense stalled with four
shot-clock violations, Rutgers was able to extend the lead to 21-10
before the Huskies began to inch back. An 10-2 run, capped by an
Asjha Jones layup with 9 seconds left, closed the gap to three
points. But Rutgers answered with a 3-pointer by Pointer at the
buzzer to gain its halftime advantage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
