<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASS-BIOTECH-REAL-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: SPACE FOR RESEARCH IS EXPANDING IN CAMBRIDGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SUSAN DIESENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Developers and life-science companies are
planning to invest about $1 billion to build over 3 million square
feet of new research labs in Cambridge, more than doubling the
amount of research and development space in this six-square-mile
city.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the buildings will go up within a few blocks of Kendall
Square, where the region's biotechnology industry first put down
roots in the early 1980s. Five new buildings with 1.2 million
square feet of space are in construction or were recently completed
in the area. Four other projects in the neighborhood with a total
of 2.1 million square feet of research space have received city
approvals.
</P>
<P>
   Biotechnology and pharmaceutical companies that are not building
themselves have agreed to lease most of what is in construction,
some at annual rents approaching $50 a square foot. The buildings
themselves are among the most costly commercial structures, costing
about $350 a square foot to build, from conception to fit-out.
</P>
<P>
   The lure for this new construction is the intellectual firepower
of the Cambridge work force, forged at some of the world's top
colleges, research institutes, medical schools and teaching
hospitals here and across the Charles River in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   On the Boston side of the Charles, where the medical schools of
Harvard, Tufts and Boston universities conduct training programs,
1.3 million more square feet of biomedical and pharmaceutical labs
are being developed, according to E. Owen Donnelly, deputy director
of the Boston Redevelopment Authority.
</P>
<P>
   The biotechnology, biomedical and pharmaceutical companies of
the life-science industry put a premium on locating in areas with
plentiful academic links because new products usually spring from
lab discoveries.
</P>
<P>
   ``To keep our pipeline full, we want to be in the Cambridge
market,'' said Peter J. McCawley, development manager for Amgen
Inc., which with 1999 revenues of $2.4 billion is the United
States' largest biotechnology company. ``It's no secret that
Cambridge has the largest and best pool of scientific research
talent in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Amgen sells products based on genetic information unearthed by
biotech research, such as Procrit and Epogen to enhance red blood
cells.
</P>
<P>
   Amgen, which is based in Thousand Oaks, Calif., started work
last year on a $100 million, 285,000-square-foot lab on a
71,000-square-foot site that it bought for $1.4 million in the slow
market of 1994. Instead of building then, it developed a research
center near Boulder, Colo. But in 1998 it converted that lab into a
manufacturing plant and started to plan its Cambridge project.
</P>
<P>
   Amgen's sliver of a site here, once part of a sprawling plant
that made fire hose, will be wedged in front of the research lab
for Genzyme Inc. and across the street from a new lab being built
for Biogen Inc. by Boston Properties Inc. Once its building is
completed, Biogen will occupy 740,000 square feet in the
neighborhood where it first leased space in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the three biotechnology companies make five of the
industry's 10 best-selling products, according to a 1999 report by
Ernst &AMP; Young.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Amgen shimmied into this little site because, like most
life-science companies, it wanted to be near industry colleagues
and researchers to share knowledge and insights. ``We can't
convince these companies to take cheaper space in the suburbs,''
said Steve Buckley, regional director of the life-sciences practice
for Ernst &AMP; Young.
</P>
<P>
   The presence here of an industry giant like Amgen, therefore,
creates a new critical mass for the life-science industry that will
attract even more companies, according to John A. Southard Sr., an
economist for Tordo Wheaton Research, which is a unit of the
international real estate firm CB Richard Ellis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, it signals that the region's real-estate market is
finally moving to the next level of growth after one of the
nation's worst downturns,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Cambridge has about 11 million square feet of offices, 8 million
square feet of which is in the East Cambridge neighborhood bordered
by Kendall Square on the west and the Charles River on the east. It
also has 2 million square feet of research labs for bench
scientists who work in controlled environments, known as wet labs.
</P>
<P>
   By late 1999 the labs had a vacancy rate of less than 1 percent,
vs. 24 percent in 1995. Since then, rents have risen as much as 150
percent to reach $50 a square foot annually for some new space,
said Gregory W. Hoffmeister, a broker for Spaulding Slye Colliers
International.
</P>
<P>
   Star attractions for these companies are Harvard and the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, which together own about
half of the city's land, said Jean E. Strain, Cambridge's director
of economic development.
</P>
<P>
   Another magnet is the Whitehead Institute/M.I.T. Center for
Genome Research in Kendall Square, which is about halfway between
the two colleges. Scientists there are mapping the human genetic
material. Such research could revolutionize health care with the
ability to grow new organs and design drug therapies for a person's
genetic profile.
</P>
<P>
   With wet lab space set to jump from 2 million to about 5.3
million square feet, the city will adopt new zoning rules to
prevent overbuilding.
</P>
<P>
   With the real-estate boom of the 1980s, new zoning rules and
special permit requirements appeared. Last month Cambridge passed
an 18-month moratorium on new permits for projects larger than
20,000 square feet around Kendall Square, and in April it is
expected to adopt a new zoning code to control future growth
citywide, said City Councilor Henrietta Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago, property owners worried that it would become
more difficult to build and they could lose value,'' said
Hoffmeister, the broker.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the city may reduce the ratio of usable building space
to site size, from a floor area ratio of 4 to 2.5, said Lester W.
Barber, Cambridge's director of zoning. For Amgen, that could have
meant a building of 200,000 square feet rather than 285,000 square
feet, for a loss in value of $30 million. Amgen's new eight-story
building, designed by Stubbins Associates, is to be completed in
June.
</P>
<P>
   The current strong demand increases existing property values,
said Thomas Ragno, a vice president of Beacon Capital Partners Inc.
Beacon owns Technology Square, a five-building complex with a
million square feet of space in Kendall Square. The complex,
completed in 1975, is currently being renovated and expanded. Ragno
projects $50-a-square-foot rents for the new research and
development space, designed by Sasaki Associates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
