<HEADLINE>
MORRIS SOSNOW, 93, REAL ESTATE DEVELOPER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Calif.)  (lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Morris Sosnow, a residential real estate developer on
Long Island, particularly during the post-World War II suburban
boom, died Jan. 15 in Manhasset. He was 93.
</P>
<P>
   In 1946, Sosnow and a partner, Leonard Schwartz, founded
Birchwood Park Homes in Mineola, in response to new
government-backed home mortgages, a wave of returning war veterans
and a spate of private financing available for construction.
</P>
<P>
   Birchwood Park built thousands of Cape Cods, split-levels and
ranches, mostly for middle-income buyers, in Long Island towns.
</P>
<P>
   Sosnow, who lived in Kings Point and in Miami Beach, was born on
May 6, 1906, in Kolno, Poland.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Kate; three daughters, Bernice
Lieberman of Palm Beach, Fla., Lorraine Aaron of Kings Point and
Sheila Nagler of Piedmont, Calif.; a sister, Henya Joskowitz of
Rehovot, Israel; seven grandchildren and five great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
