<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5014 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-HOUSTON-82     02-12 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-HOUSTON-820(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON, A STAR AT LAST, TAKES IT IN STRIDE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   On occasion, Allan Houston and his wife will pull into the
parking lot of a movie theater. And as Houston unbuckles his seat
belt and gathers his things in the slow, smooth motions of a scuba
diver, Tammy Houston has already hustled to the line, has a ticket
in her hand and is heading for the concession stand.
</P>
<P>
   There is the unhurried Houston, left behind to arrive at the
pace of a happy-go-lucky whistler.
</P>
<P>
   On some nights, Houston and Latrell Sprewell will hit the
Madison Square Garden stage together like the Odd Couple. And as
Houston lofts up jumpers with a cashmere touch, the kinetic
Sprewell will plunge a dunk through the hoop and begin flexing like
Popeye.
</P>
<P>
   There stands the amused Houston, the content wallflower during
his teammate's dunk party.
</P>
<P>
   On television, the faces of Eddie Jones and Ray Allen are
illuminated against a dark background as handpicked commercial
stars for Michael Jordan's shoe line. As Houston, the uncelebrated
Nike endorser, takes note of the national ad, he is at peace with
the perception of his personality, game and lifestyle as more
suburban than street, more poetry than pomp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't _ and I'm glad I'm not the type to do it _ but I don't
look at a Nike commercial to decide where I rank among players in
the league,'' Houston said. ``I think when Jordan and his people
decide who to highlight, I think it has to do with the charisma you
bring to the game. It's not that I don't have it, but Jordan and
his staff are looking at that, looking for something exciting, I
guess.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, this weekend, Houston finds himself in the middle of
the hip and at center stage in the hype. But as much as anyone
worth his crossover move, Houston belongs as an All-Star. Maybe
Madison Avenue hasn't caught on to the guard's understated
elegance, but the coaches who voted for the All-Star team reserves
did.
</P>
<P>
   The coaches are the ones who have sent their defenders out to
bump him, harass him, even whack his shooting hand. Still, Houston
scores. And in this way, this most benevolent of players can
inflict unspeakable cruelty on an opponent, as Heat coach Pat Riley
has witnessed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's become a superstar, not just an All-Star,'' said Riley,
who watched Houston's deft runner eliminate his team in the first
round of the playoffs last May. ``Anybody can be an All-Star. There
aren't many who can do what he can do. He's just developed and
worked and he's become what he is. He's right there with ... I
can't think of anybody else at the two spot in this game now. The
other guy left.''
</P>
<P>
   That guy was Jordan. But how did this happen? How did the
unassuming shooting guard who was picked No. 11 in the 1993 draft _
behind players like Calbert Cheaney, Bobby Hurley, Rodney Rogers
and Lindsey Hunter _ make such a leap?
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the 10 to 15 pounds of muscle he has added, and the
diligence he has shown in his summertime workouts, a lot of his
rise can be attributed to that passive temperament of his. If
Houston had been packing a large ego when he arrived in New York
four years ago, he could not have withstood the isolation behind
John Starks and tough-love approach used by Jeff Van Gundy. If he
had been self-absorbed or insecure about his position on the team,
he would have never accepted the arrival of Sprewell last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If one of us would have been selfish, it wouldn't have worked
out,'' Houston said. ``Neither one of us had an ego about it. Last
year, there came a point when we were trying to get each other
going. We wanted each other to do well. There could have been a lot
of things that could have ruined it. In New York, you can let a lot
of bad stuff get in your head to make it bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston could have prejudged Sprewell. His wholesome
sensibilities could have been offended by Sprewell's past. After
all, Houston's father was a coach. Despite their fundamental
differences _ Houston slips into chapel after his pregame warm-ups
while Sprewell is just slipping into the arena parking lot to make
tipoff _ they are much more similar than the surface indicates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people look at me as the good guy who doesn't make
mistakes, but I really do,'' Houston said. ``I'm not perfect. And
then I think people don't see the other side of Spree. I see a guy
who is very giving and cares about other people. I see that all the
time. He's not what you might think.''
</P>
<P>
   When Houston was called by a team official on the morning of
Feb. 1 and told he had made the All-Star team, his first thought
was not of himself. The team official said the first words out of
Houston's mouth were: ``What about Latrell, did he make it?''
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell didn't make it, but Houston did. Houston was
disappointed. He wanted to go to Oakland as a group, with his
teammate and his coach. Instead, Van Gundy will be there, and so
will Houston's father, Wade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all just a blessing,'' Houston said. ``This past year has
been a blessing.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   It began with his runner in Miami and his spectacular Game 6
against Indiana in the Eastern Conference finals. A day later, on
June 12, Houston became the father of a baby girl.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's changed the way I go out and treat the game,'' Houston
said. ``I treat it more like it's fun. I still work as hard but I
don't take it home anymore. In the past, I would. I'd get really
quiet. A bad game would just really put me in that pensive state.
Tammy would try to pull me out of it. I still do my preparation,
but I don't take it home like I used to.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he just wants to be Daddy when he walks through the front
door. He just wants to plop down on the floor with his 7-month-old
daughter and pull out her PlaySchool piano.
</P>
<P>
   ``We taught her how to bang on it, and she starts making these
sounds with her voice,'' Houston said. ``It's amazing, at seven
months, she's putting it together. Tammy, she's humble about it,
but she can sing. And I've been telling Tammy that our little girl
is going to be musically inclined. I said, `Tammy, we've got a
little gospel singer or the next Whitney Houston or something.'''
</P>
<P>
   Houston is at peace, on the court and off it. And yet some
mischief lurks inside him. A week ago, Houston spotted a clear path
to the basket against the Portland Trail Blazers. But as his eyes
opened wide, and his body floated through the paint, he whacked a
sure one-handed dunk off the back of the rim as hard as ax splits a
log.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do want to make it fun sometimes,'' Houston said. ``But I
know what I am. I know who I am. And I know what I do best. It's
not about making the highlight with a spectacular play. The way I
look at it, it'll all be made up for when and if I have a ring. In
the finals, where there are only two teams playing, that's when
I'll worry about public perceptions. I want to be looked at as a
champion.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
