<HEADER>
A5017 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-NBAFEAT0213-COX     02-12 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBAFEAT0213-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Former NBA player talks of life after drug addiction
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ He was a tragic case. An all-star talent with a
self-destructing drug habit. ``The ship be sinking,'' was Micheal
Ray Richardson's most famous quote. He was talking about his team,
the New Jersey Nets. He could have been talking about his life.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson is a few weeks from turning 45 now, which is an
accomplishment in itself when considering the path he travelled
during his NBA days in the 1980s. Cocaine addiction cut short his
career in the league, as he was banned for life because of repeated
violations of the drug policy.
</P>
<P>
   More than one concluded that viewing the nightly news would one
day reveal Richardson was found somewhere in a drugged stupor - or
worse. ``I don't even know if I would be living,'' Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, he saved his own life by abandoning the States
and playing professionally in Europe. Eleven years later,
Richardson professes to be healthy, wealthy and looking forward to
retirement. Getting to this place, however, was an odyessy that
merits your attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever Happened to Micheal Ray?'' is a piercing and
emotional account of the life and wild times of Richardson, a
former New York Knick and New Jersey Net, that airs Wednesday night
at 10 on TNT.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's honest,'' Richardson said of the account of his life.
``It's real.''
</P>
<P>
   Think Isaiah Rider is a handful? Richardson's behavior makes
Rider look like the guy next door who cuts your grass for you just
because it's the neighborly thing to do. Drugs had a firm hold over
Richardson. There was the time in 1985, after remarrying and
signing a multi-million dollar contract that Richardson vanished
for three days following a team Christmas party.
</P>
<P>
   Then-coach Dave Wohl found him in a New Jersey hotel room wiped
out, with drug paraphernalia strewn all over the place. There were
many times like that for Richardson, a sad fact that stunted a
career that could have been special. Finally, on Feb. 26, 1986,
Richardson was permanently banned from the NBA after failing
another drug test.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drugs and life just don't mix,'' Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
   Moving to Europe saved his life, he contends. After a year
playing there, he said the Philadelphia 76ers offered him a
one-year contract to return to the NBA. But he wanted two years,
and decided to return to Europe. That was his last NBA opportunity,
which fazes him in the least. He now makes his home in the south of
France. And he claims to have been drug-free for 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even think about (drugs) anymore,'' he said. ``That's
over. I experienced that when I was young. I'm at a different phase
in my life now.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Richardson said he plans to enjoy life while every so often
looking back at how far he's come. He and Ray Williams formed one
of the most dynamic backcourts in the league in the early `80s with
the Knicks. But their reckless behavior cut short their glory.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson found it again playing professionally overseas. ``It
helped me a lot, getting out of the environment here,'' he said.
``Out of sight out of mind.''
</P>
<P>
   He's not out of sight now. ``Whatever Happened to Micheal Ray?''
puts him firmly back in the public's mind. Ultimately, it's a
feel-good story because Richardson is alive and healthy and able to
tell his story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted people to hear from Micheal Ray,'' he said. ``A lot
of things have been said about me, but I didn't say it. . . I could
have probably played 12 or 13 years in the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   He played only six before being barred. ``But when I was
there,'' he said, ``I know I was good.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Richardson was outstanding. A torrid defender and cunny
playmaker, the 6-4 guard puzzled teams with his ability to slash to
the basket to score or set up teammate or to pull up from long
range.
</P>
<P>
   And he was brash. One night, with the Nets down by three with
three seconds left, Wohl designed a play for Richardson to take a
trey to tie the game and force overtime. After the timeout,
Richardson came over to the press table and sought out a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to hit this (expletive) shot,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He did. That was Richardson; confident and good. Of course, a
month later, he was AWOL from the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a good career,'' he said. ``There were bumps and bruises
on the way. But I'm still here.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
