<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBAITEMS0213-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ADVICE CORNER
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Miami coach Pat Riley coached nine NBA All-Star games,
so many that the league came up with the rule that the same coach
could not participate in consecutive years. Like everything else he
does regarding the game, Riley now says he took it too seriously,
and told his former assistant, Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy, to not
make the same mistake as he heads the East squad tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he should wear some earrings and try to relate to the
players,'' Riley joked. ``Maybe some tattoos and baggy pants and
shorts and stuff, and get with it. That's what I was going to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was too serious,'' he said. ``I did nine of them. In every
single one of them the players looked at me like, `What's this
about plays and strategy and curfew and all this stuff?' ''
</P>
<P>
   PHILLS SAVED FATHER
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bobby Phills Sr., the father of Charlotte guard Bobby
Phills, who died in a car accident last month, said his son saved
his life on Christmas eve.
</P>
<P>
   The men and the player's daughter went fishing on Lake Norman.
``There was about 3 feet between the dock and the boat,'' the elder
Phills said. ``As I went back on the boat to get (his
granddaughter's) hat, my left foot gave way. I suddenly knew I was
underwater _ completely submerged in 20 feet of very cold water.''
</P>
<P>
   Phills Sr. can't swim, and he said he was certain he would die
in the freezing water. Suddenly, his son pulled him to safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a miracle,'' Phills Sr. said. ``If it had happened
two minutes earlier, he would have been at the front of the boat
and I would have drowned.''
</P>
<P>
   THUMBS UP
</P>
<P>
   To Detroit's Jerry Stackhouse. Instead of playing the cool role,
as virtually all NBA players do, Stackhouse has been outwardly
joyous about making the All-Star team. It's refreshing.
</P>
<P>
   THUMBS DOWN
</P>
<P>
   To Utah's Karl Malone. Malone hedged all week about whether he'd
play in today's classic because of a sore back. You'll recall
Malone said he'd never play in another All-Star Game in 1998 after
Kobe Bryant refused a screen he wanted to set. He should have just
stuck to that.
</P>
<P>
