u s BC-CAR-DAYTONA-POLE0213-     02-12 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-DAYTONA-POLE0213-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Back-of-the-pack starters winning in Winston Cup
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ When the Winston Cup drivers last fired up
their engines for a race, Bobby Labonte and others made a mockery
of the NASCAR qualifying rounds.
</P>
<P>
   It happened last November during the circuit's season finale at
Atlanta Motor Speedway. Labonte, who claimed he had mechanical
problems, was so slow in qualifying that he had to take a
provisional to earn a spot in the 43-car field.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 18 Pontiac started No. 37 in the NAPA 500, but being at
the back of the pack had no effect on Labonte. Over the next
several hours, Labonte carefully weaved his way to the front of the
pack and won the event. It was one of the lowest starting positions
for a race winner in Winston Cup history.
</P>
<P>
   But Labonte's efforts were just the beginning of a trend for
that race. Tony Stewart, who started at No. 23 and also was held up
41 seconds during an infamous pit stop, took third place. Three
other drivers who started 35th or worse rounded out the top 10.
</P>
<P>
   The wacky differences between the starting and finishing
positions, which occured at numerous races last year, appeared to
render qualifying meaningless. To some race teams, it was a
flat-out waste of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is making the race,'' said No. 55
Chevy driver Kenny Wallace. ``As long as you can make it into the
race, it doesn't really matter where you start.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason is because these races are so long. We're going 500
miles here at Daytona. We've started from the back in long races
like this and made it all the way to the front, as long as you have
a good car. And we've done the same things at short tracks, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Other impressive winners were Jeff Burton, starting 38th at the
Jiffy Lube 300 at New Hampshire and Dale Earnhardt at The Winston
500 (27th starting position) at Talladega and the Goody's 500 in
Bristol (26th).
</P>
<P>
   ``What (Labonte) did in Atlanta was remarkable; it hardly ever
happens like that, where drivers pass just about the entire field
to win,'' claimed Rusty Wallace. ``If you don't qualify well, you
need a long race to make up some of the lost ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, Dale Jarrett consistently qualified in the top 10
last year, but never won a pole position. It was a rare
non-achievement a Winston Cup champion. However, Jarrett's
perspective on the importance of qualifying may speak for many in
the garage area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody tries to go out and get a pole (or good qualifying
run), but sometimes that just don't not happen,'' said Jarrett, who
won the circuit's 1999 title.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning the pole wasn't something on our minds a lot
throughout last season. Now you go through the week and try to get
your car in the best condition for qualifying. If it happens, it
does. But it is not something we feel is a huge part of what you
have to do to win the Winston Cup championship. Race day is the
most important day.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Jarrett's crew is more concerned with setting up
the No. 88 Ford Taurus for the race day rather than qualifying.
It's the procedure for many of the top drivers: Mark Martin
finished third in the final standings despite capturing only one
pole; Jeff Burton, who established a notorious reputation for his
erractic qualifying efforts, posted the second-best number of race
wins (6).
</P>
<P>
   ``We're worried about qualifying, but not to the point where we
are going to make a big deal out of it if we don't do so good,''
Labonte said. ``You know, if we don't sit in the first or second
row on race day, we're not going to be miserable because there is a
lot more to look forward to in the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Johnny Benson, ``You spend a lot of time setting up for
qualifying, then have to spend the entire next day preparing the
car for the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Wallace is a prime performer in qualifying. He had the
fastest times at qualifying for four races. Wallace ended up having
only one win to show _ the spring race at Bristol _ for the four
pole positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Qualifyng is not meaningless, but it is a pain,'' Wallace
said. ``It gives your race team a lot of exposure for your race
team when you qualify good. But I think ... it's just another
(NASCAR) procedure we go through that I am not sure why we have to
do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace said he has heard garage talk of NASCAR requiring
drivers to use the same engines in the race as they do for
qualifying. There may be better ways of doing the qualifying
competition, but it will alway be needed in some form. For example,
58 cars are trying to earn a spot in the Daytona 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are an awful lot of good race cars with good team and
good sponsors,'' Dale Earnhardt said. ``It's really a shame someone
has to go home this weekend. It would be just too hard for NASCAR
to start 60 cars in a race.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifteen cars are leaving here early,'' Mike Wallace said.
``That is the worrisome part of this qualifying deal. You've got a
big sponsor and driver that will have their heart and soul in it,
then be disappointed and have to go home.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
