<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-CALIF0213-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore attacks Bradley in California convention speech
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ Riding a wave of support from Democratic
activists here, Vice President Al Gore on Saturday went for the
jugular in his nomination battle with former New Jersey senator
Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to 3,000 Democrats at the state party convention,
Gore assailed Bradley as a disloyal Democrat who abandoned the
party when he left the Senate in 1997. He also accused Bradley of
launching attacks that were based on ``talking points from the
Republican National Committee.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Real Democrats don't aid and abet the Republicans,'' Gore
said. ``Standing together we stay and fight the Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also spoke to convention delegates, delivering a
40-minute speech that asked voters to choose between a more timid
leader and one who was committed to the Democratic Party's history
of ``big ideas and big ideals.''
</P>
<P>
   The two candidates presented starkly different campaign styles
to delegates, and their respective entrances into the convention
hall reflected the degree to which Gore is the strong favorite of
the party establishment.
</P>
<P>
   While Bradley was surrounded by a handful of local elected
leaders and a lone member of Congress, Gore was joined on stage by
almost every major office holder in the state, including Gov. Gray
Davis, who gave Gore a glowing endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   Gore stood on stage for a full five minutes before he began
speaking, allowing the cameras to capture him arm in arm with Davis
and Sens. Barbara Boxer and Dianne Feinstein.
</P>
<P>
   Still somewhat unknown in California, Bradley devoted a portion
of his remarks to his small-town upbringing in Crystal City, Mo.,
and his conversion to the Democratic Party as a Senate intern
witnessing passage of the 1964 Civil Rights Act.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley told several jokes, and seemed to stumble over some of
his remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, meanwhile, delivered a focused, fiery speech, using some
version of the word ``fight'' dozens of times, and even in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will fight for you,'' said Gore in a refrain he repeated
over and over. ``I will never give in.''
</P>
<P>
   He pledged to make polluters pay for pollution, raise the
minimum wage $1 an hour and ``defeat the gun lobby.''
</P>
<P>
   He bragged about the economic success of the 1990s and ridiculed
Bradley for ``running down the Democratic achievements of the past
seven years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just the other night senator Bradley attacked the Democratic
Party, demeaning the Democratic Party as in his words, a job
placement bureau,'' Gore said. ``Well, I guess with 20 million new
jobs ... that's pretty good job placement.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also responded to Bradley's recent criticisms of Gore for
his involvement in the 1996 fund raising scandals, which Bradley
has said will hurt Democratic chances against the Republicans in
the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator Bradley claims he's doing us a service because he
doesn't want to see Democrats bashed in the fall,'' Gore said.
``His proposed solution is to bash Democrats in the spring.''
</P>
<P>
   In his speech to delegates, Bradley mention Gore by name only
once, referring to him simply as ``Al.'' Bradley outlined three
differences with Gore on policy.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said Gore's health care proposal would insure only seven
million new people, while his would reach 30 million. He said his
proposal for gun control would require the licensing of all of the
nation's 65 million handguns, while Gore proposed to license only
the 2 million new handguns sold every year.
</P>
<P>
   On education, Bradley said his new proposal to require schools
receiving federal money to ensure their teachers are properly
qualified would affect more teachers than what Gore has proposed.
</P>
<P>
   Tellingly, perhaps, Bradley mentioned Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz.)
before he even got around to discussing his differences with Gore.
For the first time, Bradley acknowledged that McCain was attracting
some support from Democrats, a trend that analysts say could be
coming at Bradley's expense.
</P>
<P>
   ``John McCain is moving in the polls, getting some democratic
support,'' Bradley said. ``He's moving because he's standing up for
reform. And if we don't stand up for reform, we have a special
vulnerability.''
</P>
<P>
   Without mentioning Gore by name, Bradley said that Democratic
fund-raising scandals had created a ``crisis of identity'' within
the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans are expected to be in the pockets of special
interests,'' he said. ``We are not. ... That's why the fundamental
objective here is campaign finance reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Before his remarks to delegates, Bradley spoke to about 300
supporters in a conference room adjacent to the San Jose Convention
center complex. Bradley acknowledged that he trailed Gore in the
Golden state, which sends 10 percent of the delegates to the
Democratic convention. The California primary is March 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we are going to make it up,'' said Bradley, before turning
to a basketball metaphor to describe his predicament. ``I remember
one game we were down by about 19 points with five minutes to go
and we won the game, so we've got plenty of time here in
California.''
</P>
<P>
   But some of his California supporters were less certain. Asked
if Bradley could stage a comeback, Joyce Theios, a convention
delegate and supporter from Sutter Creek, Calif., said, ``I don't
think so. The party is so entrenched.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
