<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5023 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-S.C.-STRATEGY-1S     02-12 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-S.C.-STRATEGY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH TREATING SOUTH CAROLINA AS A MUST WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to rewrite throughout. Deletes reference to $45,000 as the
value of the advertising time abandoned by Forbes.)  
(mk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ In a determined all-out drive to stop Sen.
John McCain from winning the primary here on Saturday, Gov. George
W. Bush's campaign has scrapped its original travel schedule,
bought virtually every extra dollar of broadcast advertising time
still available and expanded its mail and telephone appeals to
300,000 more homes of voters who might be leaning toward McCain.
</P>
<P>
   The contest in South Carolina has become so consequential that
Bush campaign officials said they added tens of thousands of
dollars to their state advertising budget in the last several days.
In the end, they will have pumped close to $3 million into
advertising in the state, they said, roughly the same amount they
spent in the hard-fought New Hampshire race over a longer stretch.
</P>
<P>
   But the most unusual new move is an appeal to independents and
Democrats, which had not been planned until McCain jolted the Bush
campaign with his landslide in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advisers said that their biggest fear was that those
voters would flock to McCain. The objective of the telephone and
mail program _ on top of an already planned outreach to homes of
300,000 reliable Republican voters _ is to persuade them to back
Bush or, at the very least, discourage them from turning out for
McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the overtures to moderates, the campaign is pressing its
cause with conservatives. Beginning on Monday, a recorded message
from Rep. Henry J. Hyde, R-Ill., chairman of the House Judiciary
Committee and a revered figure among anti-abortion groups, will be
telephoned to homes of 100,000 conservative voters.
</P>
<P>
   These efforts, coupled with a stepped-up drive on Capitol Hill
to keep Bush's congressional supporters on board, reflect a
consensus among the governor's aides that unless he prevails in
South Carolina, his prospects to capture the Republican nomination
will be far more perilous. Several of Bush's advisers said they
were uneasy about their prospects _ yet buoyed by surveys late last
week suggesting that McCain's momentum is waning.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we'd have won New Hampshire,'' said Warren Tompkins, Bush's
chief strategist in this state, ``McCain would have been gone, so
there wouldn't have been a heck of a lot going on down here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our immediate challenge,'' Tompkins said, ``was to settle
everybody down and overcome the aftershock after New Hampshire.''
Now, he said, ``I don't know what else we can do. We've got people
working in every county. We've got people out doing everything.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the overt changes, like Bush's new emphasis on
depicting himself as the genuine reformer, and his more energetic
style on the stump, the Bush campaign has taken several steps
behind the scenes.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's emergence as a threat has forced the Bush operation to
tear up its earlier game plans for winning the nomination. In the
same way that former Sen. Bob Dole mistakenly focused on the
challenge from Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, four years ago, Bush
advisers were preoccupied for more than a year with Steve Forbes
and his hefty war chest, and never seemed particularly worried
about McCain.
</P>
<P>
   One senior Bush official said the campaign may have been slow to
react to McCain because ``when the budgeting was done, the doomsday
scenario was Steve Forbes unleashing a huge negative attack that we
had to respond to.''
</P>
<P>
   While much of the broadcast time for television commercials in
South Carolina had to be bought in advance, Bush officials said
they grabbed up the leftover advertising time made available by
Forbes' departure from the race last week, bringing to nearly $3
million the sum the campaign is pumping into television and radio
advertising in the state, according to Bush campaign aides.
</P>
<P>
   McCain officials said they were spending closer to $2.5 million
on advertising.
</P>
<P>
   In a demonstration of the importance of this state, Bush shelved
his original post-New Hampshire schedule, which called for campaign
trips to California and Arizona, and is campaigning virtually
exclusively in South Carolina. Arizona and Michigan hold their
primaries three days after the voting here. But given the time
constraints, Bush's advisers concluded that the best way for them
to assure success in those states was to emerge triumphant from
South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Several Bush advisers said they should have reacted more nimbly
to McCain after New Hampshire, and that it was a mistake for Bush
to have appeared here with former Vice President Dan Quayle after
that defeat. The advisers said it undermined the governor's message
that he, not McCain, was the anti-Washington outsider.
</P>
<P>
   Mistake or not, Bush is increasingly campaigning with public
figures from South Carolina. And his aides have spurned requests
from several of Bush's supporters in Congress to campaign in this
state.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some trepidation about bringing in too many people
from the outside,'' Tompkins said. ``We're trying to use as many
home-grown surrogates as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Bush's most prominent supporters here, like Tompkins
and former Govs. Carroll Campbell and David Beasley, are keeping
some distance at public events.
</P>
<P>
   The drive to stop McCain and help Bush is not limited to South
Carolina. Late last week, Joe Allbaugh, Bush's campaign manager,
held a conference call with many Bush backers in Washington _
including people close to former President Bush _ to explain how
the governor would win South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Other Bush lieutenants in Washington, including Haley Barbour,
the lobbyist who headed the Republican Party, and Rep. Rob Portman,
R-Ohio, have reassured the governor's supporters on Capitol Hill
about the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just encourage them to take a deep breath and look at the
results in Delaware,'' Portman said of Bush's triumph last week in
the primary there.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., a Bush supporter, said that he,
for one, was worried that Bush ``took for granted that he was going
to win this thing.'' He said of McCain: ``There is some
appreciation that this guy is a war hero and has a clean record.
There are people that are concerned, and logically so, that this is
a big election in South Carolina. If McCain wins, it's going to be
a marathon to the end.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Part of the strategy of the Bush team is to tamp down any
perception in the press and among political professionals that
Bush's eventual emergence as the inevitable nominee is in doubt. As
part of that, the campaign is portraying the governor's victory in
the Delaware primary as a monumental triumph.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Rove, Bush's chief national strategist, went as far as to
cite Bush's victory in the caucuses in Alaska on Jan. 24, which
campaign officials had barely mentioned in the past. ``Bush has won
three and lost one,'' Rove said. ``You should be asking the McCain
campaign if it could sustain a fourth loss out of five.''
</P>
<P>
   Another senior Bush official said that while the governor could
endure a defeat here next Saturday, it would be a crippling setback
with the potential to lead major supporters to defect to McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to be nervous,'' the official said. ``There's not a
soul in this sort of high-pressure contest who doesn't think of all
the scenarios that are possible. The good ones make you feel warm
and fuzzy. The bad ones make you nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   In seeking to undercut McCain, the Bush campaign has had some
help from independent groups that are running commercials attacking
McCain: the National Right to Life Committee and the National
Smokers Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   While Tompkins insisted that the campaign did not work in tandem
with the outside groups _ which would be illegal _ he said their
advertisements were useful for the cause. ``There are instances
when people run independent expenditures that are not helpful,'' he
said. ``Some of these groups are not very sophisticated.''
</P>
<P>
   All week long, the McCain campaign has accused the Bush
operation of a major effort at ``push polling,'' in which voters
are told they are being contacted for polls but actually are given
negative information about a candidate. Bush officials insist they
are not making such calls.
</P>
<P>
   But campaign officials said they had stepped up efforts to call
likely voters in this state _ they are now reaching out to as many
as 600,000 households _ to urge them to back Bush, and in some
cases raise questions about McCain.
</P>
<P>
   In calls on Friday, people expected to vote were reminded of
Bush's ``strong victory'' in Delaware and told, ``Don't be misled
by McCain's negative campaign tactics.''
</P>
<P>
   While such calls are often effective, the efforts to criticize
an opponent do not always work. One respondent chastised a Bush
caller, telling her: ``I saw an ad yesterday that Bush had on. I
didn't like him saying something back about McCain. To do one
negative against another. To me they both look bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Another respondent told a Bush caller, ``I like Bush, but I
don't like running people down like that.'' The respondent also
groused that there were no Bush signs in her part of the state. ``I
just don't understand why we haven't got any signs,'' she said. ``I
see McCain's!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-12-00 1853EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
