</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TAXCUT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A BLOATED TAX CUT FOR MARRIAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Sunday, Feb. 13:
</P>
<P>
   The House passed a Republican-sponsored bill last week that
would give a big tax cut to all married couples _ even those who
are benefiting from the existing tax code and not suffering at all
from the so-called ``marriage penalty.'' The GOP points to married
couples who, under the current code, pay more in tax than they
would as two unrelated individuals. That penalty, say the
Republicans, amounts to an unconscionable attack on marriage.
</P>
<P>
   But what the Republicans gloss over is the fact that the tax
code also provides a bonus to many other married couples. Indeed,
over 40 percent of married couples pay less tax than they would as
separate individuals. Yet the GOP bill hands them an additional tax
cut anyway. About half of the total tax reduction would go to
families already enjoying a tax bonus.
</P>
<P>
   This scattershot approach would eventually cost about $30
billion a year _ more than President Clinton proposes to spend on a
drug benefit for Medicare and nearly half as much as Bill Bradley
wants to spend on health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Eliminating the marriage penalty might seem like an elementary
issue of fairness. But ``marriage neutrality'' is only one
principle at stake. The income tax code also aims to be
progressive, taxing high-income taxpayers at a higher rate than
low-income taxpayers. The code is also designed to achieve
``horizontal equity'' _ imposing the same tax on married couples
with the same total income no matter how the earnings are split
between spouses.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that these three principles of fairness are at
war. As a matter of mathematical logic, no code can achieve all
three. The principles have to be balanced.
</P>
<P>
   The current code, which provides bonuses to almost half of all
married couples, can hardly be labeled anti-marriage. Yet some
families are hurt in undesirable ways that can be remedied without
much damage to the other principles of fair taxation.
</P>
<P>
   The code penalizes families with two earners, especially if the
two spouses earn approximately the same amount. Worse, the code
hits hard at low-income families receiving housing benefits, food
stamps and tax credits. Marriage can push such couples into income
brackets for which the benefits are substantially reduced if not
eliminated. That can discourage single mothers from marrying.
</P>
<P>
   So tax relief for some married couples is warranted. But the
House bill lacks any such focus. It would raise the income at which
all married couples jump from the 15 percent tax bracket to the 28
percent bracket, a move that has the perverse effect of benefiting
the richest third of all families.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would also increase the standard deduction for all
married couples. Both provisions would apply to families whether
they now pay a marriage penalty or receive a marriage bonus. The
one provision that does focus on needy families would increase tax
credits for low-income married couples with children. But this tax
cut accounts for a very small part of the total tax reduction under
the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's plan, by contrast, would focus on raising the standard
deduction for two-earner families, those who suffer most from the
marriage penalty. Gov. George W. Bush's tax plan provides a
deduction for the earnings, up to a ceiling, of the second spouse.
This too is focused on eliminating a penalty on low- and
moderate-income spouses who work.
</P>
<P>
   None of the proposals takes care of the problem of individuals
who receive housing benefits and food stamps and decide to marry.
But the Clinton and Bush plans rightly focus on the plight of
two-earner families. The House would scatter about $180 billion
over 10 years across all married couples, needy or not. That money
would be far better spent on Medicare, education and even smartly
targeted tax cuts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
