<HEADER>
A5031 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-RANGERS-LEETCH-NY     02-12 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-LEETCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEETCH HAS RETURNED TO FIND A TEAM TRANSFORMED
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After missing 11 weeks and 32 games with a broken
right forearm, Brian Leetch returned to the New York Rangers'
lineup last week. After a 5-2 thrashing of the Boston Bruins at
Madison Square Garden on Friday night, Leetch was asked if it felt
as if he had returned to the same team he had left.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said, ``it really doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   And not just because the Rangers would qualify for the
postseason for the first time in three years if the season ended
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are four guys here now that I haven't really played
with,'' Leetch said, citing Valery Kamensky, Alexandre Daigle,
Radek Dvorak and Rich Pilon. Kamensky was a free-agent signing, but
he missed 23 of the Rangers' first 32 games with a stress fracture
in his right forearm. Daigle, Dvorak and Pilon were all added this
season by Neil Smith, the Rangers' president and general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Daigle was obtained from Tampa Bay on Oct. 3 for future
considerations (in other words, basically for nothing), but he was
not recalled from the minor league Hartford affiliate until Nov.
19. Pilon was claimed off waivers from the Islanders on Dec. 1.
Dvorak was obtained from Florida in a three-way deal on Dec. 30
that sent Todd Harvey to San Jose and Mike Vernon to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The insertions of Dvorak, Kamensky and Daigle into the lineup
have helped transform the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now have a lot of speed,'' said Leetch, the team captain.
And that speed has helped the Rangers turn their season around.
</P>
<P>
   When Leetch went down, the Rangers were six games under .500.
The night they claimed Pilon, the Rangers fell to seven games under
.500. And many felt that both Smith and coach John Muckler were in
danger of losing their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   After a brief spurt in December pulled the Rangers to within
three games of .500, a streak of seven games without a victory
dropped them back to seven games under .500, tying their season
worst. On the morning of Jan. 4, the Rangers were 12-19-7 with
three regulation ties and going nowhere fast.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, however, the Rangers are 12-5-1, the streak not
coincidentally beginning when Muckler formed the Czech Connection
line of Petr Nedved centering Jan Hlavac and Dvorak. For the
season, the Rangers are now 24-24-8 with three regulation ties.
With 59 points, the Rangers were seventh in the Eastern Conference
after Friday night's game. In other words, with 26 games left in
their season, a playoff spot was the Rangers' to lose.
</P>
<P>
   Late Friday night, Smith was asked if his current roster was the
best lineup the Rangers have dressed since they last qualified for
the playoffs in the 1996-97 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our fastest lineup,'' Smith said, after some thought.
``It's our most skilled lineup.'' Those responses came after Smith
had asked a question of his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it our youngest lineup?'' Smith asked rhetorically.
</P>
<P>
   The answer, according to the Elias Sports Bureau, is no. This
season's Rangers (who had an average age of 29.4 years for Friday's
game) have on average been older than last season's, but younger
than the team Smith assembled two seasons ago.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is that the team's better players this season
have been younger, so the team seems younger. Dvorak is 22; Hlavac
is 23; Nedved is 28. Since Muckler formed the Czech line, Nedved
has had two hat tricks, Dvorak one and Hlavac one _ the first hat
trick of his fledgling NHL career, Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all great skaters,'' Muckler said. ``They could be as
good as they want to be. I hope it continues. It's something we're
going to need to get into the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Smith, Muckler did not hesitate when he was asked if the
Rangers' current lineup is the best Muckler has had to work with
since he became the Rangers' head coach on Feb. 19, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question,'' Muckler said. ``With Val in the lineup, with
Devo in the lineup, with Leetchie coming back, that's three pretty
good additions. That gives us an abundance of speed. And it's
changed our options, it's changed the things we can do. In the
first period'' _ Friday night _ ``we moved the puck as well as
we've moved it all year long.''
</P>
<P>
   Goaltender Mike Richter agreed. ``The big thing we have going
for us now is we have more speed,'' Richter said. ``That alone
really opens up everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Richter and Leetch have the most tenure on the Rangers. They
know better than anyone else how difficult the last two seasons
have been. But you could sense some optimism exuding from Leetch
late Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team definitely has the most offense,'' the
offensive-minded Leetch said when asked to compare and contrast the
last three seasons. ``It creates the most scoring chances. And
that's been our biggest problem. We've had to grind it out the last
two seasons. We've had to rely on Mike and on our special teams to
win close games.''
</P>
<P>
   Not Friday, when the Rangers overcame a lackluster second period
to blow out the Bruins on skill alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to get some goals,'' Leetch said.
</P>
<P>
   He could have added: for a change. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
