u s BC-BKN-NBA-BEST0213-COX     02-12 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-BEST0213-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Who's the NBA's best?
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For so long, the consensus was unanimous: Michael
Jordan reigned, without challenge, as the NBA's best player. It's
also been pretty well established that Jordan is irreplaceable, as
a talent, gate attraction and winner. But as the league moves
forward in the two seasons since his retirement, a new debate
rages: Who's the best player in the NBA?
</P>
<P>
   The candidates are many, and so the answers vary depending on
who is speaking. And when.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be anybody on a particular week,'' Milwaukee's Glenn
Robinson said. ``One week it could be Allen Iverson. Another week
Ray Allen. Another week Shaquille (O'Neal). It's just not that
clear.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider, too, Kevin Garnett and Tim Duncan, Gary Payton and
Jason Kidd, Grant Hill and Chris Webber. Getting the picture?
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you put a finger on it?'' Charlotte all-star guard Eddie
Jones said. ``I can't.''
</P>
<P>
   A canvassing of several participants in today's 39th NBA
All-Star Game at the Arena in Oakland did not reveal a ``best
player.'' But it did reveal a ``most dominant,'' which comes in the
form of 7-foot-1, 315-pound O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every team needs a Shaquille O'Neal, a big man,'' Robinson
said, ``and he's the best. You can only foul him. Otherwise, it's
his game.''
</P>
<P>
   Kidd, the Suns' brilliant point guard, faced O'Neal last week
and came away thoroughly impressed. Again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played against Shaq the other night, and, gosh,'' Kidd
said. ``He's incredible. He can dominate any night. We're men, but
he makes it like men against boys. He's just so much stronger than
anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Indiana power forward Dale Davis: ``I don't know about a
best player in the league. But I know the most dominant is Shaq,''
Davis said. ``He really has come out this year. He's stronger,
that's for sure, and playing in a forceful way that no one can
really handle. Not one-on-one.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal's size and strength are not the only elements that make
him virtually unstoppable. His agility, remarkable ability to get
up the court for a man his size and the development of an array of
inside post maneuvers have elevated him to a plateau many believe
is slightly above his peers.
</P>
<P>
   However, he will not pin the ``best player'' tag on his massive
chest.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he's the best player in the NBA, O'Neal said: ``No. The
way the system is set up, I don't get to show all my skills. Am I
the most dominant? Yes. The way the system is, Tim Duncan can show
all he's got, Jason Williams can show all he's got because the
system allows it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I can't (because of where he plays on the floor). That's a
shame, but it's OK. I'm the most dominant player and I'd rather be
that then the best.''
</P>
<P>
   And while O'Neal generally is regarded as the player who is most
valuable to his team _ ``If I played with that guy,'' Iverson said,
``there's no way we'd lose a seven-game series to anybody'' _
different people rank others on that level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Gary Payton,'' former Boston Celtic great K.C. Jones
said. ``He's a phenom. He'll defend with the best of them. He'll
get nine rebounds and 13 assists and still get 25 points. Most
great offensive players are not that committed on the defensive
end. But Gary Payton will play both ends great. Michael Jordan was
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan and Magic Johnson revolutionized the game. They were
solid ballhandlers whose strengths were as much mental as it was
physical. It will be some time before others are compared with
those multiple-championship winners. But Garnett and Duncan already
possess the physical attributes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys like me and Tim Duncan transcend what traditional
7-footers do,'' Garnett said. ``We've shown that you don't have to
be just a post-up player. You can be a perimeter player, be mobile,
get out on the break, take guys off the dribble. We can do it
all.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if there's any one answer to the question,'' the
Hawks' Dikembe Mutombo said. ``There are so many best players in
the league right now. In the East, you have Alonzo Mourning and
Allen Iverson. In the West, you have Shaquille O'Neal and Kevin
Garnett. But if I had to choose one, I would say this year it's
Alonzo Mourning. I'm very proud of what he's doing on a daily
basis. He's scoring, rebounding, blocking shots. And his team is
winning. I think when all is said and done, you have to look at the
great player and what his team is doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Iverson was ripped by many former players who
said his game was selfish and out of control. Tonight, he starts in
his first All-Star Game. ``I never looked at it like others did,''
Utah great John Stockton said. ``I make my own judgments. And all I
know is this: From playing against him, Allen Iverson is a good
competitor and a heck of a player. People can say what they want,
but you cannot take that away from him. He deserves his due. He's
one of the best players in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   There are many in that category, which makes labeling the best
that much harder. ``So many guys bring so much,'' Kidd said.
``Iverson plays with speed, Vince Carter plays above the rim, Gary
Payton does it with defense. Shaq has power. Kobe (Bryant) slashes.
Garnett and Duncan can post you up and go outside. (There's) just
so much talent out there right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
