<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BUICK-3RD0213-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Woods hoping for his seventh consecutive win at the Buick
Invitational
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LA JOLLA, Calif. _ OK, maybe it's a little early to beef up the
security for Riviera Country Club, site of next week's Nissan Open.
Maybe it's a bit premature to sweep out all of the celebrities from
the clubhouse or add a few truckloads of extra sushi.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   The Tiger Woods Streakmobile still could be pulling into the Los
Angeles area Monday, all fueled up and on the move. While Woods
didn't storm to the absolute top of the Buick Invitational
leaderboard Saturday at Torrey Pines Golf Course, after a 5-under
par 67, he's within striking range for today's final round, tied
for fourth and six shots behind leader Phil Mickelson, in his quest
for a seventh straight PGA Tour win.
</P>
<P>
   What's that? Six shots back and still in range? Hey, you tell
the guy he can't do it.
</P>
<P>
   In normal times, the tendency would be to expect a successful
close from Mickelson, a San Diego native and the 1993 champion,
despite a 1999 Sunday scoring average (72.5) that ranked 134th on
tour. But these aren't normal times. It's a time when Woods, who is
trying to match Byron Nelson's 11 straight wins, can come from
behind with one foot in the parking lot. After erasing a seven-shot
deficit in seven holes at Pebble Beach last Monday, truly anything
is possible.
</P>
<P>
   Do you expect to win (Sunday), Tiger?
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh-huh,'' he said. ``I'm going to try. We'll see what
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Will you be more disappointed than ever if you don't win?
</P>
<P>
   ``Huh-uh, huh-uh,'' Woods said. ``That's just the way it is
sometimes. You give it everything you have, and there's no regrets.
If I went out there tomorrow without the determination or the fire
and lost, yeah, I would be disappointed in myself and kicking
myself, but that's not the way I play . .I play for the thrill of
it, the chance. You play for three and a half days to give yourself
a chance on Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson, who shared the lead after 36 holes, broke out
Saturday with a 67 to move to 16-under 200 and set up a splendid
final-round scenario. Without a victory in 1999, he'd enjoy nothing
better than to end Woods' streak in his own backyard. Also winless
last year was Sea Island's Davis Love III, who had a 69 and is at
11-under one ahead of Woods and five behind Mickelson.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's Shigeki Maryuma is at 14-under, two shots behind
Mickelson. Jeff Sluman and Fred Couples are at 10-under, tied with
Woods.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging Woods' comeback miracle at Pebble Beach,
Mickelson suggested, ``I think he's going to have to do something
pretty extraordinary. Obviously, you don't want to rule anything
out, but if I go out and play a solid round, I'm going to be in a
position to force him to shoot a ridiculously low round, like 10 or
11 under.''
</P>
<P>
   With any amount of putting success Saturday, Woods could have
been four or five shots better on the board. He power-lipped an
eagle try at the par-5 13th. He rammed a 10-footer for birdie by
the hole at the 18th. But that's the way things can go on Southern
California's spongy, poa annua greens, where the ball doesn't roll
as smoothly as on bentgrass.
</P>
<P>
   Highly ``disappointed'' with his performance on the greens,
though pleased with his technique, Woods frequently muttered
unprintables to himself and slammed down his putter.
</P>
<P>
   ``God almighty,'' he said, ``it was just one of those days when
I didn't make any putts.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the leaderboard changed a bit from when Woods finished
_ he was only two back at the time _ he said, ``I'm right in the
ballgame....There's not too many guys to pass, anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   With all the hoopla connected with The Streak, Woods is the most
cool and collected of anyone. Asked if he's more nervous than
normally, he said, ``To tell you the truth, I'm actually more calm
now....I think it's just because I've dealt with it before. This
doesn't compare to the way it was in `97.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Love had Mickelson far more prominently on his
mind than Woods, recent history notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to be a little closer to Phil,'' Love said. ``He's
going to be hard to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
