<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFORM-PARTY-MEET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEROT SUPPORTERS TAKE BACK REFORM PARTY IN CHAOTIC MEETING  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE _ The Ross Perot faction of the Reform Party retook
control of its ruling machinery on Saturday during a meeting here
of party leaders that was so rowdy and divisive that the police
threatened at several points to intervene.
</P>
<P>
   The takeover by the partisans of the party's founder, on a
series of 3-to-1 votes, came just one day after Gov. Jesse Ventura
of Minnesota, the party's highest-ranking elected official, bolted
party ranks, charging that it had become a ``hopelessly
dysfunctional'' political entity at one of the most crucial
junctures in its history, the eve of the 2000 presidential
election.
</P>
<P>
   Before his departure, Ventura had been mentioned as a possible
Reform Party candidate for president. The party has a hefty $12
million in federal funding to give its nominee this year, and
Donald Trump, the real estate developer, is exploring the
possibility of a Reform candidacy while Pat Buchanan, the
conservative commentator, already is seeking the party's
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Perot, who has thus far run twice for president, taking more
votes from the Republican than the Democratic nominees, has given
no indication one way or the other as to what he might do. But
whether he or Trump or Buchanan or someone else ends up on the
Reform ticket, many of the party leaders here Saturday lamented
that the angry division left in the party after a morning and
afternoon of bitter infighting would likely prove to be a serious
political detriment.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura's followers took control of the party last year
following his show of surprising political strength in his state's
1998 governor's election. But as was made clear in Saturday's
voting here, at a gathering of the party's governing national
committee, Ventura never had the iron grip on the party that Perot
had for so many years, and now presumably has once again.
</P>
<P>
   The change in control came amid angry shouts of ``fraud'' and
``thievery'' and ``revenge'' by Ventura partisans, but to no avail.
And at the end of the day, a day that saw more than one screaming,
red-faced party member dragged from a floor microphone and more
than one Nashville police officer call out ``calm down, calm
down,'' the party chairman that the Ventura followers had installed
early this year, Jack Gargan of Florida, had been removed from
office on charges that he had grossly mismanaged the party's
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been a disaster from the start, ruled by fiat rather than
rules,'' said Pat Muth, a fellow party member from Florida and a
longtime Perot supporter.
</P>
<P>
   Gargan denied the charges and called his removal a fraud
perpetrated during a meeting of the national committee that was
scheduled illegally, on too short a notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not the Reform Party I know,'' he told the committee
members after the vote, ``not the party of honesty and integrity.
This was a sham.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he vowed to fight for reinstallation as chairman, saying he
would call a party convention to be held in mid-March in Las Vegas.
That vow brought hoots of derision from many committee members, a
number of them already making their way out of the meeting room at
a suburban hotel here.
</P>
<P>
   Gargan also raised the possibility of taking his fight to court.
</P>
<P>
   The committee chose Pat Choate, Perot's running mate in the 1996
presidential contest, to succeed Gargan as interim chairman, until
the party can hold a convention. Choate, one of Buchanan's campaign
managers this year, immediately resigned that job, saying that his
``first loyalty'' was to the party.
</P>
<P>
   Russ Verney, the party chairman ousted earlier by the Ventura
forces and one of Perot's closest political aides, said that Gargan
was ``absolutely, totally wrong'' in charging that Saturday's
meeting had been called illegally.
</P>
<P>
   ``The party's rules,'' he said, ``hold that one-fourth of the
members of the national committee can call a meeting and, in fact,
more than 40 percent of them did. How else could you have vote
after vote here in which more than two-thirds of the committee vote
against what Gargan is trying to do?''
</P>
<P>
   The infighting was at its worst early on on Saturday when
committee members could not agree on whether the meeting had been
called according to party rules. So many speakers tried to reach
the floor mikes to have their say that floor managers lost control.
Sometimes three and four people were shouting at once, while other
committee members were jostling _ and sometimes engaging in shoving
battles _ in an effort to speak.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
