<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: IT'S ALL MADNESS BEFORE THE MARCH MADNESS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is a good thing for college basketball that March
is on the way and a sport that is creatively defined by hypocrisy
will emerge from the madness it descends into the other 11 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get these kids involved in changing the system,''
Mike Jarvis said Saturday after his St. John's team hung on to
defeat Villanova, 78-75, at Madison Square Garden. ``The way it is,
it's not for them.''
</P>
<P>
   The way it is in college basketball, the coaches rake in
hundreds of thousands of dollars and practically wear sandwich
signs for sneaker companies and open their programs to flesh
peddlers from the street and honor signed contracts at the rate
most players make 3-pointers. Good for Jarvis if he believes there
is something wrong with this picture (sure he does), along with
those arbitrary and superficial punishments meted out by the N CAA.
</P>
<P>
   There was, nonetheless, old-fashioned activism in the air at the
Garden Saturday. Jarvis called on players to rise up against ``the
system,'' and point guard Erik Barkley began by scribbling ``Only
God can judge me'' and ``Free at Last'' on his sneakers and the St.
John's cheerleaders joined in by fastening the Barkley Band-Aid of
honor across their cheekbones.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere, Tom Wolfe was taking notes for a novel.
</P>
<P>
   The Band-Aid sure was the appropriate symbolic prop for how a
sport that is choking on ethics polices itself. As ridiculous as
the NCAA can be, Jarvis responded to the suspension of Barkley by
comparing it to the Gestapo and by saying that he felt raped. He
apologized the next day but _ you know what? _ he sounded just as
hopelessly self-righteous Sunday, albeit with less inflammatory
rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did a better job of educating my kids about their rights,''
Jarvis said. ``Everything happens for a reason. Hopefully, I'll be
able to say I made a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Not if he continues targeting the NCAA for college basketball's
major ills, which is akin to blaming clowns for the foolishness of
the circus. If he wants to make a difference, he could encourage
David Stern and Isiah Thomas to hurry up with that professional
developmental league that will make college basketball less of the
sad meat market it has become.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley said Saturday that someone from the home office in
Kansas City had interrogated him on Feb. 2 into admitting that he
had swapped his 1996 Jeep Cherokee for a 1995 Chevrolet Suburban
owned by a Rucker League coach he has known since he was 14. The
NCAA interpreted this as a violation of its bylaw against receiving
preferential treatment and extra benefits. Barkley was suspended
for three games, but that was reduced to two when St. John's
appealed on the basis that, among other things, the Chevy's
windshield wipers did not work.
</P>
<P>
   Hypothetical question for the new, improved standardized tests
that will be given to basketball recruits once they take Jarvis'
advice and overthrow ``the system:''
</P>
<P>
   Player X is driving along, in his Jeep Cherokee, which he
legitimately purchased with the money he made cutting the athletic
director's grass once during the month of December. A hurricane
suddenly begins _ the windshield wipers will not kick on. What
should Player X do?
</P>
<P>
   A) Call the coach's mechanic and accept free maintenance of the
wipers.
</P>
<P>
   B) Swap his Jeep for a newer car offered by a friend of the
program who just happened to be passing by.
</P>
<P>
   C) Drive the wiper-less vehicle home in the blinding downpour.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the NCAA bureaucrats could have recognized the
Barkley car swap for what it was, a violation only in the most
punitive interpretation of vaguely written rules. If Barkley had
admitted to borrowing a friend's Playstation along with the latest
in sports game software, would that be ``preferential treatment and
extra benefits'' too?
</P>
<P>
   But the bottom line here is that the NCAA looks for smoke
because it usually has reason to suspect there is fire. It has to
start somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis used to rail against the influence of Amateur Athletic
Union coaches in the college game, but one of his first moves at
St. John's was the hiring of Dermon Player, formerly of the
Riverside Church AAU program. Why wouldn't the NCAA or anyone else
at least be suspicious?
</P>
<P>
   The kids are always the ones, not the coaches or the athletic
directors or the school presidents, who get punished. In that
sense, Jarvis is right about the inequities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was more worried about my reputation,'' Barkley said. ``I
thought I was going to be labeled as the bad kid from New York.''
</P>
<P>
   The ovation he received upon introduction alleviated that fear.
His magnetic dribble and penetrating eyes helped St. John's build
an early lead, and his two 3-pointers down the stretch helped hold
off Villanova. St. John's took another step toward the big
tournament next month, the road to the Final Four, which is the
only drive worth taking in a sport whose wipers too often don't
work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-12-00 2008EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
