<SLUG> BC-STATES-watch-NAT </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  New York Times Votechart
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   CORRECTED WASHINGTON WATCH VOTE CHARTCORRECTED Questions
regarding this transmission should be directed to 202-628-3100,
ext. 224. PLEASE NOTE: THIS IS THE CORRECTED VERSION OF THE VOTE
CHART THAT MOVED FRIDAY NIGHT. IN THE EARLIER CHART, THE
DECRIPTIONS FOR THE HOUSE VOTES WERE REVERSED. PLEASE MAKE THE
CORRECTION. WASHINGTON, Feb. 12 -- The following chart shows how
senators and representatives voted on key bills and amendments
within the last week. A ``Y'' means the member voted for the
measure; an ``N'' means the member voted against the measure; a
``?'' means the member did not vote; and a ``P'' means the member
voted ``present.''
</P>
<P>
   SENATE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: WASTE
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Thursday approved, 64 to 34, a bill that would
require nuclear waste to be shipped to a disposal site in Nevada
from power plants around the country, once a burial site in Nevada
is licensed. Supporters say a plan to remove waste from temporary
storage sites is long overdue. Opponents, including President
Clinton, say the plan does not give the Environmental Protection
Agency sufficient oversight in monitoring the storage radiation
levels. A ``yes'' vote supports the bill.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: TAXES-DEM
</P>
<P>
   The House on Thursday rejected, 192 to 233, an $89 billion,
Democratic-backed measure that seeks to reduce the so-called
marriage tax, but prioritizes saving Social Security and Medicare
ahead of the tax cut. The bill increases the standard deduction for
married couples, but at a smaller rate than the Republican proposal
that was passed. The Democratic measure would also increase the
earned-income tax credit for lower-income couples. Supporters said
the bill addressses the need to eliminate the marriage tax without
jeopardizing Social Security and Medicare. Opponents said the bill
does not go far enough to help married couples. A ``yes'' vote
favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: TAXES-GOP
</P>
<P>
   The House on Thursday approved, 269 to 158, a $182 billion
measure that seeks to reduce the so-called marriage tax. The bill
attempts to remedy an aspect of the tax code that leaves some
married couples paying more in taxes than two single filers
reporting the same income. The measure raises the standard
deduction for married couples and also increases the earned-income
tax credit for lower-income couples. Supporters said couples should
not be penalized just because they are married. Opponents said the
Republican-sponsored plan is too costly, provides too much tax
relief to higher-income couples and further risks the future of
Social Security and Medicare. A ``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2
</P>
<P>
   --- ---
</P>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The attendance record is not part of the
current vote chart because the company that supplied us with the
information is no longer in service. We are looking for a new
source.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
