<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5156 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-ATLANTA-SLAYINGS13-CO     02-12 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATLANTA-SLAYINGS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    One suspect in Atlanta slayings may surrender
 &HT;    By Alfred Charles and Joshua B. Good
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Reginald ``A.J.'' Oakley plans to surrender to Atlanta
police, a lawyer who knows the Baltimore man _ one of two suspects
still at large in last week's stabbing deaths _ said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, law enforcement officials in South Florida continued
searching for the other suspect, Joseph L. Sweeting of Miami. And
the third man charged in the case, Baltimore Ravens star Ray Lewis,
was moved from the Atlanta Detention Center to the Fulton County
Jail, where his supporters plan to stage a rally today.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, Oakley and Sweeting were indicted Friday by the Fulton
County grand jury for the killings of Richard Lollar, 24, and
Jacinth Baker, 21, early Jan. 31 after a night of post-Super Bowl
partying at an Atlanta nightclub, Cobalt.
</P>
<P>
   Oakley, 31, intended to turn himself in to police Saturday, said
Jesse Ingram, a suburban Baltimore sports and entertainment lawyer
whose son, also a lawyer, has previously represented Oakley.
</P>
<P>
   He said Oakley, to whom he spoke several days ago, had traveled
to Atlanta to surrender, but that he did not know the name of
Oakley's Atlanta attorney. He said the source of his information
was Oakley's brother, Brian, with whom he has been in close
contact.
</P>
<P>
   Oakley had not surrendered as of Saturday evening, and his
brother could not be reached. Ingram said Oakley told him he did
not know the two men in Atlanta had died until Oakley returned to
Baltimore from Atlanta and saw the story on the TV news. Ingram
said Oakley, a barber, met Lewis through a mutual friend, Garfield
C. Yuille, 36. Ingram said Yuille and Lewis used to hang out at
basketball games and nightclubs.
</P>
<P>
   Ingram, who is also a professor of psychology at Bowie State
University, said Oakley did not go to police immediately because he
was afraid for himself and afraid that if he were arrested, his
6-month-old son, Reginald Oakley Jr., might grow up without a
father at home.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta on Saturday, Lewis was transferred from the Atlanta
Detention Center, where he had been held since shortly after the
killings, to the Fulton County jail in northwest Atlanta, where a
prayer vigil in his honor is planned today.
</P>
<P>
   Mountain Movers Ministries, which works with professional
athletes, is staging the 4 p.m. vigil.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. J. Richard Harris, who said he has known Lewis since he
was in high school, believes that the linebacker is innocent and is
``the third victim'' of the crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want this to be a spiritual gathering,'' said Harris, whose
news release on the vigil claims some NFL players will attend. ``We
don't want curiosity seekers. We are praying for this young man's
spirit.'' The Baltimore Sun reported Saturday that Baltimore
Ravens' owner Art Modell plans to appear at Lewis' Monday bond
hearing as a character witness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to see him out of jail,'' Modell told the newspaper.
``I've had a relationship
</P>
<P>
   with him for four years. I know him as a devoted, extremely
devoted son and father. I've got some good anecdotes and stories
about him in his involvement with the Police Athletic League. He is
a good citizen with some flaws we'll address later.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile in South Florida, the search continued for Sweeting.
</P>
<P>
   A police officer who arrested Sweeting several times when
Sweeting was younger said he was not surprised by news of his
alleged involvement in the murders of Lollar and Baker.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was part of a violent, drug dealing gang involved in
burglary and robbery in the early 1980s,'' Deputy Carl Baaske said.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 20 years, Baaske walked the beat in the
neighborhood where Sweeting grew up. He later left the Miami-Dade
Police Department to take a job with the Walton County Sheriff's
Office in the Florida Panhandle. He said Sweeting was ``one of the
worst.''
</P>
<P>
   Family members offered a vastly different view of the former
high school wrestling star.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's never been involved in anything like this,'' his brother,
Arthur, told The Miami Herald on Friday. ``Joe is part of a good
family. He grew up in the Baptist Church.''
</P>
<P>
   Family members said Sweeting, 34, no longer resides at their
home in Goulds, a poor area in unincorporated south Dade County.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeting attended Southridge High and, although he was shorter
than many other wrestlers, the Herald singled him out in 1983 for
his athletic prowess.
</P>
<P>
   But the promise Sweeting showed in high school evaporated when
he hooked up with a neighborhood gang.
</P>
<P>
   Dade County police said Sweeting's arrest record began in the
1980s, when he was booked on two charges of possession of a firearm
by a felon, carrying a concealed firearm, robbery, altering the ID
on a firearm, grand theft, burglary, resisting arrest without
violence and violation of probation.
</P>
<P>
   The Herald reported Saturday that the FBI tracked Sweeting in
1993 as a possible subject involved in a group that specialized in
jewelry heists and cocaine shipments in three states. Although 18
members of the group were indicted, Sweeting was not.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how or when Sweeting met Lewis, although the
relationship likely started during Lewis' days as a football star
for the University of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Said brother Arthur Sweeting: ``We know Ray Lewis. But we know a
lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution staff writers Ernie Suggs and Janet
Frankston contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
