<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5199 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-CAR-AUTONOTES-JARRETT     02-12 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-AUTONOTES-JARRETT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JARRETT WON'T MIND REPEATING HIMSELF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ And so it begins for Dale Jarrett. The
driver of the No. 88 Ford Taurus starts a new chapter in his racing
career when he attempts to repeat as NASCAR Winston Cup champion.
So, after he delivered car owner Robert Yates their first
championship last season, what will Jarrett do for an encore? What
will serve as his motivation this time around?
</P>
<P>
   ``Just the thrill of victory,'' said Jarrett, who will sport not
only a new mount in the Y2K Taurus but also a new look _ sans
moustache. ``It's got nothing to do with money; it's got to do with
accumulating victories, major victories, and trying to add to our
championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett has proven capable at winning NASCAR's ``majors,'' with
victories in the Daytona 500 (1993, '96), the Coca-Cola 600 at
Charlotte (1996), the Winston 500 at Talladega (1998), and the
Brickyard 400 at Indianapolis (1996, '99). And last year, he proved
capable of winning championships. He collected four of them, while
recording 24 top-five finishes, 29 top-10s, and just one DNF, when
he crashed between Turns 3 and 4 at the Daytona 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly I feel with more experience that I've become a
better race driver,'' Jarrett said. ``But, along with that, with my
equipment it's amazing how much better a driver I became. You have
to have equipment and the people around you, and Todd Parrott is a
big reason for the success. He, Robert Yates, and (engine builder)
Doug Yates give me equipment, week in and week out, to go out and
get the job done.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as the Daytona 500, patience is what it's about. The
first 400 miles are for show, to get yourself in position, to see
what everybody else has and to see what you have _ where your car
is the best and what you can do.
</P>
<P>
   ``You use those last 100 miles to position yourself and try to
get in the right spot so you can make the moves. If that means that
your car works better out front, you've got to get yourself in the
lead to try and make them pass you. If you feel like you've got a
car capable of making a pass late in the race, you get yourself in
a position to set someone up.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen drivers will get a glimpse of their cars' ability to
circumnavigate the 2.5-mile trioval at Daytona International
Speedway when they dice it up Sunday in the 2000 Bud Shootout, a
25-lap race for the 14 Bud Pole Award winners from last season and
the winner of a 25-lap qualifier. As a non-pole-winner in 1999
(amazingly), Jarrett will be in that qualifying field.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that he won no poles last year in no way diminished
Jarrett's season, in which he joined his father, Ned, as a NASCAR
champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very special,'' he said. ``This was something that I
could kind of pay my dad back. Obviously, I couldn't pay him back
with money or anything else, but a championship was something we
could enjoy as father and son, especially knowing that there's only
one other father-son team (Lee and Richard Petty) to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   And after hiring five members of Jeff Gordon's Rainbow Warriors
pit crew, he appears to have bolstered his chances for a repeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming in as the championship team, we realize that people are
going to be watching what we do and paying attention to what
contributed to our success, and I think it's nice,'' Jarrett said.
``Hopefully, we'll be able to withstand their challenges and maybe
have another championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt driving on
</P>
<P>
   Though he took a month off at the end of the year to have back
surgery, Dale Earnhardt signed a contract extension with car owner
Richard Childress that will keep him behind the wheel of the No. 3
Goodwrench Chevrolet for the next three years. ``It's good through
the year 2003 with options for more, so there's no retirement
clause in there or anything,'' said Earnhardt. ``So we're in good
shape.'' Earnhardt returned to the driver's seat Jan. 31 for a test
at Las Vegas Motor Speedway, where he eased into it with a fast lap
of 161.162 miles per hour. ``I feel great,'' Earnhardt said . . .
Northern Light Technology Inc., an Internet firm based in
Cambridge, has made two significant ventures in racing. It has
agreed to a five-year, $50 million title sponsorship of the Indy
Racing League. ``Northern Light's commitment increases the forward
momentum of our series, and is a genuine marketing and media forum
for both of our groups,'' said Tony George, IRL founder and
president of Indianapolis Motor Speedway. Then last week, Northern
Light announced it was joining forces with Roush Racing as primary
sponsor of Jeff Burton's No. 9 Busch Grand National Series car . .
. Robbie Buhl won the IRL season opener at Walt Disney World
Speedway Jan. 29. It was the second career victory for Buhl, a
graduate of New England College in Henniker, N.H., who won his
first IRL race at New Hampshire International Speedway . . . Dario
Franchitti, who finished runner-up to Juan Montoya for the FedEx
CART championship last season, will likely be out six weeks after
suffering a fractured pelvis and multiple small contusions of the
brain in a single-car accident during a CART Spring Training
practice session last Wednesday at Homestead-Miami Speedway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
