<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5201 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-LEWIS-BO     02-12 1583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-LEWIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWIS MUST GUARD AGAINTS BIG MISTAKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Michael Grant was peeved, which is not his usual
state of mind.
</P>
<P>
   It was Tuesday morning in Manhattan and Grant was standing next
to the source of his peevishness and within a few feet of that
man's associates, all of whom had irked him no end. Hot emotion
roiled through Grant's 6-foot-7-inch body, boiling up like steam
before he let it drift away.
</P>
<P>
   Grant intends to vent those feelings soon, at the expense of the
undisputed heavyweight champion of the world. Grant intends to
coldcock Lennox Lewis for what he has done, or at least for what
Grant thinks he has done.
</P>
<P>
   But this was not the day for that.
</P>
<P>
   This was a day for business suits and TV lights, a day for hype,
not hypertension at the Theater at Madison Square Garden. The more
kinetic moment will come April 29, in the same building where Grant
was standing back-to-back with Lewis. That will be a night of heat.
This was an afternoon for cool.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the jump, I've felt disrespected,'' the undefeated No. 2
contender said when asked about the days that led up to the making
of this fight. The world had little reason to anticipate this
matchup until Lewis's forces made the offer to an opponent they
clearly believe is ill-suited to face down their more experienced
champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We signed this fight and those guys were already looking over
my head to see who Lennox Lewis would fight next,'' said Grant.
``That really offended me. I have to say they've really got some
hell to pay for that. They gave me no respect in this whole
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant is not prone to speak that way. He understands better than
most that prizefighting is a business. He accepts that with a
patience rarely seen.
</P>
<P>
   So Grant has pounded out 31 straight victories, 22 by knockout.
Because he is a stablemate of Evander Holyfield, Grant would not
fight him even if offered the opportunity. He would wait for
another chance to become a world champion.
</P>
<P>
   Now that chance has come earlier than expected because Holyfield
was unable to conquer Lewis. The opportunity arrived only after
Grant battled his way to a win over Andrew Golota and took a
beating doing it. Twice Grant was knocked to the floor in the first
round, and his features were badly rearranged. Wise beyond his
years, Grant knows it was the sight of him face-down on the canvas
that convinced Lewis and his people to give him this chance.
</P>
<P>
   That, in fact, is the business Lewis is in. Champions are in the
as-little-chance-as-possible business when it comes to picking
opponents. So when he saw Grant on the floor, Lewis knew he had
found his next opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had just walked through Golota, I'd be fighting (No. 1
contender) John Ruiz (in a boxoff to pick a mandatory challenger to
Lewis),'' Grant said. ``What happened to me against Golota was fuel
for them, and I'm glad they took it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted the fight and I wanted the fight. It's a good
situation for myself, even if a lot of people are underestimating
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant, though a large and powerful man, showed inexperience
against Golota, who battered Grant before he rallied and made
Golota quit on his feet.
</P>
<P>
   Grant showed great heart and formidable punching power,
withstanding the early beating to come back to destroy Golota. When
Lewis faced Golota, he stopped him in the first round, so his
thinking is obvious.
</P>
<P>
   To Lewis's advisers, this is a chance to mix without risk.
</P>
<P>
   Grant understands why they should be confident; Lewis has more
experience in big fights and holds all the title belts worth
holding after beating Holyfield last November. What Grant finds
off-putting is that Lewis's camp already announced a July title
defense in England, where Lewis sometimes lives.
</P>
<P>
   To Grant, that is not confidence, it is disrespect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know what he thinks of me,'' Grant said, ``but
I'll be honest with you. He isn't thinking highly, and I think he
should. I always think highly of my opponents. I've never gone into
a fight mad until now.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got some hell coming to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Short jabs
</P>
<P>
   There are two ways to look at what happened last week to Tiger
and Rock Allen. Either it was a failed attempt at brotherly love,
costing the identical twins their shots at making the US Olympic
boxing team, or it was proof they've learned early about the
sport's chicanery. Tiger, a featherweight, was 4 1/2 pounds over
the limit and was disqualified. Then he allegedly weighed in for
his brother, Rock, a 132-pound lightweight also struggling with the
scales, and signed paperwork on Rock's behalf at that weigh-in.
While a grievance was being filed, Rock was allowed to compete and
defeated the top-ranked lightweight, Mahlon Kerwick, 16-9. Later,
there was a disqualification, and Kerwick was moved to the
championship bracket of the double-elimination tournament. The
Allens' father and coach, Naazim Richardson, refused to allow
either to appear at the grievance hearing and declined to discuss
the issue. Once USA Boxing officials declared the signature on Rock
Allen's paperwork to be that of his brother's, what else was there
to say? That it was a case of mistaken handwriting? . . . One
interesting scenario at the US trials in Tampa, Fla., would have
been brothers Nonito and Glen Donaire fighting each other in the
semifinals of the 106-pound division, but Glen was beaten in a
controversial decision . . . One thing worries Lewis about Mike
Tyson. He's worried somebody is going to destroy Tyson before he
gets the chance to. ``I'm definitely worried about that,'' said
Lewis. ``I want to fight Tyson because he's the only man of my era
I didn't fight. He paid me not to fight him (which is one way to
look at step-aside money). Tyson has a lot of fans who believe in
him. At this point, he is the only person of consequence for me to
fight. I don't need to be fighting these new heavyweights like
Grant. They're not of my era. Tyson is the mark for me to think
about retiring. There would be a very good possibility of that
after beating him. I've still got a goal to reach. Once I reach it,
I can retire. That's to box Mike Tyson and retire undefeated.''
Although the public still believes in Tyson, Lewis does not.
Frankly, some people think Tyson knows it, too, which is why he
puts himself in the ring with guys like Julius Francis, the stiff
he knocked down five times in two rounds in his last fight. ``The
public still thinks Tyson is Tyson,'' Lewis said. ``He's not. He
said himself (before the Francis fight) that he's not ready to
fight me. I would agree with him.'' . . . Here's Lewis's view on
World Boxing Organization champion Vitali Klitschko. ``Who is he?''
Lewis said of the towering Russian who fights out of Germany. ``Who
has he fought?'' Good questions . . . Lewis did agree that the
Klitschko brothers, who stand 6-8 and 6-6, are the spectre of the
heavyweights of the future, as is the 6-7 Grant, who is 2 inches
taller than Lewis. ``The days of the small heavyweights are over,''
said Lewis. ``No more 215- to 220-pound champions. They're coming
around now at 245-250.'' . . . Holyfield, a small heavyweight who
still carries some clout, will be back in action in May or June,
most likely in Las Vegas, although no date or opponent is in place.
What is sure is that he will not retire, as some have speculated
(or suggested). Holyfield still believes his destiny is to retire
as champion. He just doesn't want to start the final quest until
his divorce proceedings are over . . . Laila Ali's opinion of the
opening performance of 38-year-old Jacqueline Frazier-Lyde,
daughter of Joe Frazier: ``She stinks!'' Frazier-Lyde apparently is
on a course to take the same kind of whipping from Muhammad Ali's
daughter as Ali twice put on her father . . . Ali has fights in
Canada and China this spring while Frazier-Lyde seeks other
pushovers, like her debut, to build up enough of a ``record'' to
square off with young Ali. Meanwhile, lurking in the wings against
the wishes of her father is 23-year-old Freeda Foreman, daughter of
George, who turns pro April 1 in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Around and around
</P>
<P>
   Talk of a Roy Jones Jr.-Joe Calzaghe fight has begun. The deal
at present is for Jones to receive the US television money,
Calzaghe the British television money, and they split the gate for
what would likely be a London fight. The way Calzaghe looked in his
last outing vs. David Starie, it won't be an easy sell, but HBO
will buy it. What other choice does it have for Jones? The hard
part comes when his promoter, Murad Muhammad, tells Jones what
he'll be getting paid. TV rights fees for overseas fights are
usually halved in the US . . . Former WBO heavyweight champion
Herbie Hide has yet to be paid for losing his title to Vitali
Klitschko. He is in a battle with promoter Frank Warren and the
British Board of Boxing Control . . . The night Ms. Foreman fights,
she'll be on the undercard of a show featuring ex-Olympians Chris
Byrd vs. Lawrence Clay-Bey. This is a real test for Clay-Bey, who
has struggled with several injuries, slowing his development since
he was captain of the 1996 US Olympic team. The fight led John
Hornewer, an adviser to Byrd, to comment, ``Clay-Bey must have a
bonus clause in his contract if he goes 12-0. Why else would
America Presents put him in with Chris? He can't beat him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
