<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-DAYTONA-YATES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YATES HAS TWO SEATS IN DAYTONA FRONT ROW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Robert Yates had the winning quinella in
Saturday's Bud Pole qualifications for the 42d Daytona 500.
</P>
<P>
   His winning combination? The No. 88 and 28 cars.
</P>
<P>
   After Dale Jarrett delivered Yates his first Winston Cup
championship last season, the NASCAR owner presided over a sizzling
start to the 2000 season when his two-car stable swept the front
row for next Sunday's Daytona 500. Jarrett put his No. 88 Ford
Quality Care Taurus on the pole position with a fast lap of 191.091
miles per hour while teammate Ricky Rudd put his No. 28 Havoline
Ford Taurus alongside on the outside pole with a lap of 190.384
m.p.h.
</P>
<P>
   ``You only have two spots that are given out today and we got to
capture both of those,'' said Yates. ``There's nothing like this.
It's awesome. Now we can really focus and concentrate on our cars
and our chassis, we don't have to worry about the other races.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Jarrett's second career pole at Daytona since 1995, which
also happened to be the last time a Ford started at the front of
the 43-car field, thus snapping a General Motors streak of four
consecutive Daytona 500 poles. The next 28 spots will be determined
in Thursday's Twin 125-mile qualifiers, with the next six
determined by qualifying speeds and the final seven going to
provisional starters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ricky and I are fortunate to be the ones sitting in these
cars,'' said Jarrett, who captured his first championship title
despite going without a pole last season. ``It shows the effort
that's put forth at Robert Yates Racing the last couple of years
when we've come here and we haven't been as strong as Robert and
the team are used to at this race track, especially in qualifying.
We've run good in the races, but it's been because of a huge effort
in getting the cars driving really good. Now we have two fast race
cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of effort put forth, a lot of talking back and
forth between the two teams,'' Jarrett added, ``and it's paid
off.''
</P>
<P>
   It proved especially beneficial for Rudd.
</P>
<P>
   Last July, a crestfallen Rudd held a press conference in the
Benny Kahn infield press room at Daytona to announce that Tide had
severed its ties as sponsor of his struggling racing team. It dealt
a mortal blow to Rudd Performance Motorsports.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, it seemed like it was the end of the world,''
Rudd recalled. ``I mean, you didn't understand. You had such tunnel
vision, you were focusing on one thing trying to build that race
team into something that amounted to something and something that
would be here for a while. All the hours you're awake, because you
don't sleep a whole lot thinking of what it takes to make the team
competitive, all I saw at the time was sort of the gloom and doom
if we didn't come up with a sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was almost stupid to the fact that I didn't realize the
opportunity I had in front of me,'' he added, ``because I was still
trying to put together a sponsorship deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudd was forced to liquidate his team at an auction when Yates
came calling with an opportunity to replace Kenny Irwin as driver
of the No. 28 car. ``I'm just really fortunate that the opportunity
was there for me,'' Rudd said. ``There's no way I could have been
smart enough to plan this scenario out, the way the events
unfolded, it just fell in my lap. I was just glad I was able to
capitalize.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's effort went a long way in rejuvenating Rudd.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just nice to sit in a car that goes fast,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   GM drivers were hard-pressed to say the same after they
struggled to keep up the blistering pace set by Ford drivers, who
occupied six of the Top 10 qualifying spots. Mike Skinner was the
fastest GM qualifier in his Chevrolet Monte Carlo with a lap of
189.781 m.p.h.
</P>
<P>
   Former open-wheel driver Scott Pruett, whose last race resulted
in a pole at CART's season-ending event at Fontana with a lap of
235 miles per hour, was the fastest rookie after he qualified ninth
in 189.470. He, too, drove a Ford.
</P>
</TEXT>
