u s BC-OLY-BOXING-TRIALS-BOS     02-12 0265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BOXING-TRIALS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIAL RUN WILL CONTINUE IN CONNECTICUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA _ For the 12 American boxers who emerge from this week's
Olympic Trials, the road to Sydney does not end at the Tampa
Convention Center with the nationally televised finals.
</P>
<P>
   The winners must fight again in two weeks at Foxwoods in
Connecticut against the winners of the losers' brackets, or someone
else judged the most worthy contender. If the trials champion wins
one bout, the challenge is over, but if the challenger wins two, he
takes the team slot and the trials winner becomes the alternate.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, no American boxer is assured of a spot on the Olympic
team because in 1997, the Association of International Amateur
Boxing voted to limit the number of boxers from the Americas in the
Games. Now only certain countries like Cuba get byes into each of
the 12 Olympic weight classes. The rest, including the United
States, must qualify fighters in one of three regional qualifying
tournaments. Only 22 boxers will earn Olympic spots at both the
North American and Central American qualifiers, and 10 will be
selected from the South American qualifier.
</P>
<P>
   The first qualifier will be in Tampa March 27-April 1. The
second will be April 17-22 in Mexico and the final shot comes May
23-28 in Argentina, where only gold medalists will qualify for the
Games. If the American fighters survive those qualifiers, they will
make the journey to Sydney for the Olympic Games, which run Sept.
16-Oct. 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-12-00 2125EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000212.0237 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5209 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-NFLNOTE-VETERANS-     02-12 2602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTE-VETERANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADITIONS LEAK AWAY AS VETERANS ARE LET GO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Et tu, NFL?
</P>
<P>
   It used to be we could point to baseball, basketball, and hockey
and say how the money destroyed so many of the things we loved
about those sports. There was a time when a Ted Williams or a Carl
Yastrzemski would play his entire career with the Red Sox, when a
Bill Russell or a Larry Bird would play for no one but the Celtics.
You will never see it again.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL was once a league in which players would see their
careers through with one team. John Elway, one team. Walter Payton,
one team. John Hannah, one team. Bruce Armstrong . . . Ben Coates .
. .
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots almost preserved that era in these crazy times when
money has destroyed all things warm and cozy about the sports we
grew up with.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong and Coates should have retired Patriots, on their own
terms. They shouldn't have been asked to take pay cuts. They
shouldn't have been told to do it or hit the highway.
</P>
<P>
   The Ice Age is here.
</P>
<P>
   Shame on the NFL. Shame on the Buffalo Bills. Imagine, telling
Bruce Smith he makes too much money. Imagine, telling Thurman
Thomas his services are no longer needed.
</P>
<P>
   How did it get to the point where Dan Marino has to ask for his
contract to be voided by the Dolphins and he's actually asking to
play in Tampa Bay _ Miami's Florida rival?
</P>
<P>
   Shame on the Vikings. Randall McDaniel, an 11-time Pro Bowler,
returned from Honolulu and is told he has been waived. See ya,
Randall; 11 Pro Bowls are OK, but we have to pay somebody else.
</P>
<P>
   Couldn't the owners, in the process of lining their pockets with
millions of dollars in television and luxury-box revenue, at least
keep alive some semblance of tradition? Couldn't we have one
player, maybe two, go from rookie season to retirement with the
same team? If you're a sports fan, this is how you remember it
being in your childhood.
</P>
<P>
   What is bothersome about the Armstrong case (and others like it)
is that he already had done them a favor. The Patriots signed him
in 1998 to a four-year, $16.5 million contract. Armstrong then
agreed to restructure the deal last year to help the team's bottom
line. This year Armstrong was asked, ``Can you take a pay cut?''
Actually, it wasn't even that polite. It was more like, ``Take a
pay cut or be gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Wait a second. It was the Patriots who came to Armstrong last
year and asked if they could redo his deal. He did them a favor. If
they're going to ask him to play for $2 million, why did they sign
him to such a big contract in the first place?
</P>
<P>
   Let's be real. The Patriots, like all NFL teams, are restricted
by the salary cap. As the money has grown following the $17.6
billion TV deal signed two years ago, capologists around the league
have attempted to keep their young core players with megadeals. As
a result, the older players have suffered, taking pay cuts or being
discarded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teams have to be very careful they don't do what the Dallas
Cowboys have done and made six or seven players the biggest part of
their payroll,'' said agent Jack Mills, whose clients include Ted
Johnson. ``Then you have depleted talent on the rest of your team.
Unfortunately, this is what's happening around the league now.''
</P>
<P>
   The capologists don't mean to be unfeeling; they are simply
bottom-line folks who have to stretch a penny in ways that can be
cruel.
</P>
<P>
   We understand the Patriots' stance on Armstrong and Coates;
restructuring contracts for two older players who your organization
feels don't have much left doesn't make fiscal sense.
</P>
<P>
   That's fine for older players who have been picked up by teams
later in their careers, but there are some players that teams
simply have to bite the bullet on and keep for the sake of
tradition. Coates and Armstrong are two such players.
</P>
<P>
   Down the road, Drew Bledsoe is going to find himself in the same
situation. A generation of kids has followed him faithfully since
he came into the league in 1993. How cruel will the Patriots be
with Bledsoe?
</P>
<P>
   As for the players, while they're in the process of breaking the
bank, couldn't they make sure they don't break their team's back?
</P>
<P>
   Lawyer Milloy and Ty Law shouldn't feel entirely guilty that
because they've been signed to enormous contracts, Willie Clay,
Dave Wohlabaugh, Todd Collins, Armstrong, and Coates had to be
sacrificed. To hear Ray Anderson, Milloy's agent, tell it, Milloy
was very conscious of the consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the beginning, Lawyer was exposed to the other side of
this issue,'' said Anderson. ``I also represent Denny Green, Brian
Billick, Tony Dungy, Gunther Cunningham, and other coaches so I
know firsthand the problems they're facing with salary cap issues,
and Denny in particular has had to cut veteran players like Randall
McDaniel who were very dear to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Lawyer that while you're getting your deal, one of your
fellow players in our agency, Darnell Walker from the 49ers, is
getting cut as a $600,000-$700,000 player because the 49ers didn't
work the cap properly.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we are very aware of what the Patriots needed to
do. We knew they didn't have a lot of money to work with, so we
structured a deal that Lawyer could be happy with and at the same
time make sure the Patriots could keep their cap number under $2
million the first year. I guess I'm very sensitive to criticism
that Lawyer or I were responsible, because of the contract, for the
team letting Bruce Armstrong or Ben Coates go.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Shawn Jefferson, who accepted a five-year, $18 million deal
with Atlanta Friday, wondered, ``I don't know if this salary cap is
good for the game. I think it screws a lot of players. There are so
many guys who get cut because there's a big contract given to one
player. That doesn't make sense. If you sign one guy to one big
contract, what good does it do if you have to let four or five good
players go? That's what happened to the Patriots. It's great to say
you have a good core of six or seven great players, but they can't
win all the games for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Milloy once said that he looked around the stadium and saw fans
wearing the jerseys of the ``big money'' players, but it wasn't
necessarily those players who win football games. Now he's wearing
one of those popular jerseys, and some of the less-popular ones
belong to players no longer with the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lawyer wants to win,'' said Anderson, ``but I told him that,
`You and six other guys can't go out there and carry the team.' ''
</P>
<P>
   We're not advocating that players like Milloy, Law, Johnson,
Willie McGinest, Bledsoe, etc. say, ``Wait, don't give me all that
money; give some of it to somebody else.'' But it's up to owners
and players to realize that the money isn't being distributed
fairly. They should tweak the system so it doesn't go haywire.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time in the big-money era that I can remember
so many great players and future Hall of Famers being cut. It means
the system isn't working. Those older players _ many still
productive, some still Pro Bowlers _ should be finishing their
careers with their original teams.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots owner Robert Kraft has proposed the best idea so far _
that the league make more contracts incentive-laced. Players should
perform for the big money. Otherwise, the lopsided pay scale will
only worsen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those of us in the business have seen it coming,'' said Jim
Gould, agent for Terry Glenn. ``The players are going to be paid
big dollars earlier in their careers and then they're going to have
to scramble to make a medium-range salary and stay on a roster.
It's unfortunate it's come to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Some teams had to scramble to get under the $62.2 million cap
last week _ and that was after it went up $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers had to strip $24 million by restructuring the
contracts of Terrell Owens, Garrison Hearst, Charlie Garner,
Derrick Deese, Winfred Tubbs, Steve Young, Bryant Young, and Gabe
Wilkins, and cutting safety Tim McDonald and linebacker Lee
Woodall, while Charles Haley retired.
</P>
<P>
   All of the restructuring will create more problems down the road
for the 49ers, even though they got $3 million under the cap for
next season. The 49ers should have their signing privileges
revoked.
</P>
<P>
   In this fiscal mayhem, teams must remember their tradition and
the players who helped mold that tradition. Coates and Armstrong
signed contracts that should have been ironclad, for what they did
in the past and for what they were projected to do in the future.
</P>
<P>
   A bond between players and teams has been broken and may never
return. Not in the Ice Age.
</P>
<P>
   Ham-handed action
</P>
<P>
   Ray Hamilton left the Patriots with class and dignity, throwing
no stones. In yet another situation that should have been handled
differently, Hamilton, a longtime Patriot player and coach, is
leaving to become the Jets' defensive line coach. ``The Patriots
were good to me,'' said Hamilton. ``They treated me fairly and gave
me the ability to work at something I love.'' In New York, Hamilton
will coach a three-man line. Even though that's not what the
Patriots were using, said Hamilton, ``I played in a 3-4 my first
nine years in the league and I coached it my first five years as a
coach.'' . . . Coates already has gotten calls from 12 teams, with
the most serious suitors being Tampa Bay, Baltimore, Washington,
and New Orleans . . . Bobby Grier has remained silent during the
Patriots' transition to Bill Belichick, but Tom Donahoe, the man
who almost replaced Grier, said, ``It's a very difficult and uneasy
feeling when you're in Bobby's position. I feel for him, I really
do. It's a difficult job. You're always under scrutiny. But I know
Bobby has worked very, very hard for the Patriots organization and
hopefully things can work out for him.'' Belichick brought in Scott
Pioli from the Jets to be assistant director of player personnel,
which must make that anxiety even greater. But word out of New York
is that Belichick, Pioli, Charlie Weis, and Eric Mangini work very
nicely together . . . Patriots unrestricted free agent defensive
end Ferric Collons could wind up with the 49ers, according to agent
Angelo Wright. Collons would like to remain in New England, but San
Francisco is his home . . . Ohio State's Dave Kennedy, one of the
top strength and conditioning coaches in the country, will stay
put, and continue to train Glenn in the offseason . . . Starting
left guard Heath Irwin will not be re-signed by the Patriots.
Mills, his agent, said the team has shown no interest in him. The
Dolphins are the early bidders for Irwin, who would be reunited in
Miami with former Patriots line coach Paul Boudreau. Irwin will
visit Miami Tuesday . . . The Patriots appear tied to Todd Rucci at
guard, with the possibility that Max Lane will move to left or
right tackle . . . Thinking about McDaniel for the Patriots? Think
not. McDaniel wants to stay in the Midwest, not far from his
Minnesota home . . . Bettors, here's a tip: Whatever the odds are
on Cleveland winning the division, take them. Forget about their
record last season. The Browns have great cap space, and if they
can get the right people around a maturing Tim Couch, they might be
in business quicker than you think. Coach Chris Palmer has already
talked to Armstrong and Coates, he may go after Troy Brown, and he
may try to trade the No. 1 pick to the Saints for Ricky Williams.
The Browns feel it might be better to bring in veteran receivers
around sophomore Kevin Johnson rather than drafting Peter Warrick
No. 1 . . . Belichick phoned Clay Friday to talk about the
possibility of returning to the Patriots. ``I'd love to be back
there,'' said Clay. ``I think Lawyer and Ty and myself really feed
off each other. I think we work so good together that it would be
good to have us playing together again. I know Lawyer and Ty are
rooting for me and put in a word for me all the time. We'll see how
it goes. I think my agent will be speaking to them next week.'' It
appears that Belichick doesn't think Chris Carter can be a starter,
and he still doesn't know much about Tony George. Belichick may
convert Tebucky Jones to safety, but he won't know until he watches
Jones in mini-camp in April . . . Word is that Zefross Moss has
thought about retiring. That would be about a $1.6 million savings
on the cap . . . Robert Edwards continues to make a great effort to
come back to football, but it's still early to start thinking about
that. Edwards has been working out at the University of Georgia and
has been very dedicated to his grueling routine.
</P>
<P>
   A job for Jumbo?
</P>
<P>
   Don't rule out Jumbo Elliott coming to New England for a year or
two. Elliott is having back surgery to repair a bulging disk but
should be as good as new after rehabilitation. Elliott had a subpar
season battling his back problems . . . Which offensive lineman do
you think the Patriots would be looking at? Jon Runyan? As of
Friday, they had had no contact with Runyan's agent, Ben Dogra.
Runyan has visited Philadelphia, and three other teams have called.
The Titans' right tackle could still re-sign with Tennessee . . .
Patriots defensive lineman Chris Sullivan may not have to take the
hometown discount after all. He has four teams interested in him,
one of which is the 49ers . . . Damien Woody is honeymooning in
Hawaii. If he keeps up his workout routine _ which he'd better
under Belichick _ he'll be one of the best centers in the league in
a short time . . . Jeff Blake could be huge in New Orleans. The
former Bengal, who got a four-year deal worth $17.2 million Friday,
is out from under the shadow of Akili Smith in Cincinnati. The
Saints have strugged the past couple of years with Billy Joe this
and Billy Joe that. Now they have a quarterback they can build with
. . . The Patriots shouldn't look any farther than Boston
University for a strength and conditioning coach. Mike Boyle is one
of the best in the country, though most of his work has been with
hockey players . . . Kraft was very close to Armstrong, which made
the team's decision to cut him a painful one. Kraft tried to
contact Armstrong Friday, but he had already left for Boston to
have his right knee examined . . . Don't be shocked if Barry
Sanders returns to football soon and gets traded to Miami. The
Dolphins would love a high-profile running back, especially with
Marino gone. Boudreau was offensive line coach in Detroit with
Sanders and certainly knows how to create blocking schemes for him
. . . Steve Israel is drawing interest from the Bengals, who are in
the market for a corner who won't break the bank . . . The Falcons
wanted a strong veteran presence in their receiving corps and got
one in Jefferson. He seriously considered going to Cleveland, and
at one point Thursday even thought he would stay in New England. In
fact, Weis phoned Jefferson that day and asked what it would take
to get him signed. Jefferson wanted a $4 million-$5 million signing
bonus and a $2.5 million average salary. The Patriots didn't act
and Jefferson was gone. ``I wanted to come back to New England
after I talked to Charlie (Weis) because I've always enjoyed
playing for Charlie,'' said Jefferson. ``I was comfortable with
things in New England and working for Coach Belichick. But I told
them things were going to move quickly. I didn't want it to prolong
into the free agent period. But they didn't act quickly enough.''
Jefferson owns a catering business in Atlanta and will not be far
from his home near Jacksonville.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
