<DOCNO> NYT20000212.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5211 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKC-UVM-HAZING-BOS &LR;      02-12 3382
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKC-UVM-HAZING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAZING: RITE OR WRONG? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hazing? No way. Not this.
</P>
<P>
   Not the shaving of the pubic regions or the donning of togas and
women's thongs that were de rigueur for admission to a University
of Vermont team hockey party the night of Oct. 2 at a house rented
by captain Kevin Karlander, during which nine freshmen went through
their final initiation rites, under the auspices of the
upperclassmen.
</P>
<P>
   Not the array of party games in which the freshmen, among other
things, were the targets of beer poured and spat upon them by their
elders; participated in a pie-eating contest in which the entree
was seafood quiche with ketchup topped by barbecue sauce _ with a
community bucket at their disposal when several of them vomited;
passed a communal chunk of bread chewed in descending order from
the pie-eating champion to the last-place finisher; consumed 32
warm beers in a dark basement room; performed pushups while naked
over glasses of warm beer into which they dipped their private
parts, the number of pushups determining whether they could drink
their own glass or someone else's afterward; and did the so-called
elephant walk, parading naked around the house while holding the
genitals of the person ahead of them in line.
</P>
<P>
   At least four freshmen who experienced some or all of these
alleged activities consider the ritual harmless, a unifying
vehicle, strictly voluntary, a source of brotherhood that made them
feel like genuine team members.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still don't think I was hazed,'' said goalie Shawn
Conschafter, 18. ``We were all given the option beforehand to opt
out, and nobody did. We didn't know anything about what was going
to be going on, but we all looked forward to it and had a good
time.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, said forward J.F. Gamelin, 20, when the Catamounts
reconvened for practice the following Monday, ``I felt I knew
everyone on the team much better.''
</P>
<P>
   So they cannot comprehend the volcanic fallout from the
nocturnal gathering: the actions of classmate Corey LaTulippe, a
fourth-string walk-on goalie who has left school and is playing on
a junior team in Rochester, N.Y., after filing a suit against the
university and seven players in which he alleges that his civil
rights were violated, his privacy invaded, and he was the victim of
assault and battery; the scathing report by the Vermont attorney
general, who called for the enactment of an antihazing law and
blasted the school for lax early procedures before it complied with
a state investigation; the outrage among observers and especially
administrators around the nation who denounced the supposed bonding
rituals as acts of depravity and vowed to be more vigilant in
policing their own athletes; and, worst of all, the decision by the
university to cancel the final 15 games of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the whole thing has been blown out of proportion,''
said left wing Ian Morse, 19. ``People haven't seen something like
this for a while. The general public doesn't understand the
(dynamic) within a hockey team.''
</P>
<P>
   On the contrary, say experts and college administrators, the
problem is that student-athletes often don't understand the
dynamite that comprises repulsive behavior, as opposed to uplifting
_ or at least innocent _ rites of passage into the team framework.
The UVM case has dramatically revived the issue nationwide. And
while almost all of the NCAA's more than 1,000 member schools have
explicit policies against hazing both printed in handbooks and
emphasized verbally to and by coaches before each season, that
message is now being reinforced with a vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   At Alfred (N.Y.) University, which last year compiled a landmark
report on college athletic hazing, requests for information and
advice have increased drastically since the UVM case. While she
couldn't quantify the UVM factor, school spokeswoman Sue Goetschius
said, ``It definitely has piqued interest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue of hazing has everyone's attention on campus right
now,'' said Northeastern athletic director Ian McCaw. ``We've tried
to be proactive since that incident. We've had a mandatory
department meeting, brought in all the coaches and staff, and
brought in university counsel to discuss the state law on hazing,
what signs to look for. Later this month, I'll meet with all of the
student-athletes, 500 of them, to discuss hazing, what students
should do if they feel hazed, and the university counsel will be
there to discuss state law.''
</P>
<P>
   UVM is particularly sensitive to the issue and adopting a
hardcore crackdown. According to assistant AD Jeff Schulman, the
school has assembled a presidential committee that includes experts
in adolescent behavior and met with the student advisory committee
last week. In addition, it is implementing a more intensive
educational system and will require all its athletes to sign a
contract regarding hazing practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``They must understand that there is no place for degrading,
humiliating behavior,'' said Schulman.
</P>
<P>
   Other schools that have been the sites of hazing have taken
action against a recurrence.
</P>
<P>
   At the University of Texas almost five years ago, a freshman
drowned during a party among the school's spirit group, the Texas
Cowboys, at which recruits were driven out to a lake and forced to
drink as much beer as they could. Since then, in each sport, a
Longhorn senior has been designated as a big brother or big sister
to an underclassman, functioning as both confidant and de facto
guardian.
</P>
<P>
   At the University of North Carolina two years ago, the men's
soccer team held a party that involved freshman hazing. When news
of the incident surfaced, the team captains were stripped of their
titles and the coach banned the Tar Heels from attending a
tournament in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Zero tolerance
</P>
<P>
   Boston University hockey coach Jack Parker, like his peers, has
never tolerated hazing during his 27-year tenure. But it seems
that, unlike the case with some of his peers, his players have
taken him literally.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a beginning-of-the-year party to get to know the
players,'' said Jacques Joubert, captain of the Terriers' 1995 NCAA
champions. ``It was a welcome-aboard party. We didn't even like to
call it an initiation because we felt if the coaches thought enough
of you to recruit you, that was initiation enough. We didn't have
to put them through anything. The idea was to make them comfortable
instead of saying, `You have to prove yourself.' We'd stress that,
`You're part of the team. We don't want to intimidate you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Joubert's account was independently echoed by Chris McCann
(Class of '91) and the Bruins' Shawn Bates (Class of '97). But
Parker recalls that it took a while to transmit the message about
just how pristine he wanted the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the early years, we'd put out a nice spread for the
players,'' said Parker. ``There wouldn't be any trouble at the
party, but after the party, maybe some of the guys would go out to
a bar and maybe someone would have trouble in their dorm because of
alcohol. About the third or fourth year, I told my captains, `No
alcohol. I don't want any of that stuff.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Being watchdogs is a burden shared by all athletic mentors; the
UVM situation merely redirected the spotlight on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is innocent and nobody is guilty,'' said Jack
MacDonald, the former Boston College track coach who now is AD at
Quinnipiac College in Hamden, Conn. ``We're all responsible. I've
told the kids at our school, `The biggest fear of any college
athletic director, coach, or administrator is that we'll come back
to work Monday morning and find one of you not here.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, supervisors can go only so far in monitoring activities.
</P>
<P>
   UVM sophomore defenseman Joe Flammia, 21, of Woburn, fears that
coach Mike Gilligan, who preached against hazing before the season,
might become a scapegoat.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's like a parent,'' Flammia said. ``They can't watch you
all the time. Once we leave the rink, we're on our own. We just
absolutely disregarded what he had to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Former University of Maine and BC football coach Jack Bicknell
took a hands-on approach to outlawing hazing, even in the bread
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hated everything about it,'' Bicknell said. ``By hazing, I
mean seniors coming in late from lifting weights and moving to the
front of the dinner line and making the freshmen move back. I said,
`The heck with this. We're not going to treat people this way.' A
lot of it had to do with the fact that (the upperclassmen) had been
hazed as freshmen and were waiting their turn to make someone else
miserable. And some of the kids doing the hazing wouldn't hit a
fly. They were probably the ones who had been mistreated as kids.
The great players wouldn't be involved. The ones on the fringe
would say, `Well, gee, you should've seen what happened to me.' I'd
say, `Well, I wasn't here when it happened to you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Defining the term
</P>
<P>
   There is understandable confusion about what constitutes hazing.
The NCAA addresses the issue only as one of its principles of
student-athlete welfare: ``It is the responsibility of each member
institution to protect the health of and provide a safe environment
for each of its participating student-athletes.''
</P>
<P>
   And that is a matter of interpretation. Forty-one states have
antihazing laws _ including Massachusetts since 1984 _ so what is
permitted in one place may be prohibited in another. The NCAA
leaves antihazing enforcement to the discretion of each member
school. The waters can be so murky that some administrators prefer
to err on the side of caution. Hockey East commissioner Joe
Bertagna says University of New Hampshire coach Dick Umile, who did
not return a call from the Globe, takes a rigid approach to
preclude any hassles: He won't even allow freshmen to be assigned
to pick up pucks after practice, a longstanding hockey tradition.
</P>
<P>
   The Alfred study is increasingly becoming the point of reference
for the NCAA, which has wholeheartedly embraced, supported, and
promulgated the findings.
</P>
<P>
   Alfred defines hazing as ``any activity expected of someone
joining a group that humiliates, degrades, abuses or endangers,
regardless of a person's willingness to participate. This does not
include rookies carrying the balls, team parties with community
games, or going out with your teammates, unless an atmosphere of
humiliation, degradation, abuse or danger arises.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the UVM indoctrination would be a clear
violation of Alfred's standards, qualifying as the most severe of
the four categories of behavior listed: acceptable, questionable,
alcohol-related, and unacceptable (potentially dangerous or
criminal).
</P>
<P>
   But athletes who have participated in what they assumed to be
innocuous rites of passage would be surprised that technically,
they, too, were involved in a transgression.
</P>
<P>
   When Bruins forward Anson Carter played at Michigan State, there
was an annual rookie indoctrination party.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd do stupid things like Rollerblade down the street with a
dress on, or dress up in goofy clothes, '70s clothes,'' said
Carter, who wore vintage disco attire as a freshman, while the
following two incoming classes skated in drag. ``Nobody had to do
it if they didn't want to. Nobody gets hurt by it. Nobody's in the
hospital. It's just a way of promoting chemistry.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also questionable behavior under the Alfred guidelines. And
Dr. Norm Pollard, who directs Alfred's counseling center and served
on the committee that undertook the national survey, said, ``We
found that on campuses, if people were involved in questionable
behavior, they were far more likely to be involved in dangerous
behavior. If they're willing to do this in public, they're likelier
to do far worse in private.''
</P>
<P>
   Alfred's coup was uncovering some of the behavior for the
public, because there is a code of silence that exists among many
athletic teams.
</P>
<P>
   Bruins defenseman Hal Gill, who attended Providence College,
said, ``There's a fine line between hazing and being part of the
team. I'm not going to lie _ there's things you do _ but every guy
I've ever talked to said the best part is being part of the team.
We'd go out drinking, sing songs as a team. We used to have a
rookie party. It never became a thing where anyone became alienated
or intimidated. You didn't have to do it. If you wanted to do it,
fine. If not, you could go home.''
</P>
<P>
   Being a voluntary participant does not exclude hazing because
it's impossible to gauge the effect of implicit peer pressure. And
like fraternities _ of which these athletic activities often are an
outgrowth _ teams can function as secret societies of a sort.
</P>
<P>
   Survey breaks the secrecy
</P>
<P>
   The Vermont problems _ and penalties _ were compounded by the
fact that the upperclassmen conspired to cover up the situation
when they were initially questioned by the university, thereby
employing a cherished, if misguided, sense of honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's in the locker room should stay in the locker room,''
said Gill. ``What's in the team should stay in the team. The CIA
doesn't tell secrets.''
</P>
<P>
   The Alfred study _ prompted by a football hazing at the school
in 1998 when freshmen were lashed together and forced to drink
until they vomited, resulting in two being hospitalized because of
alcohol poisoning _ exposed secrets the respondents didn't even
think were necessarily worth revealing.
</P>
<P>
   The committee canvassed a random sampling of 10,000 athletes
from 224 NCAA schools who submitted names and addresses of their
athletes to Alfred. The response rate _ 2,027 completed surveys _
was approximately 20 percent and about equally represented each
region and the three NCAA divisions. From that, Alfred extrapolated
that among the more than 325,000 NCAA athletes, 255,637 _ 79
percent _ were subject to some sort of hazing. Yet of the group
that acknowledged participating in activities that would qualify as
hazing, only 12 percent felt they had been hazed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It indicates that a lot were involved in hazing they weren't
aware of,'' Pollard said.
</P>
<P>
   The survey's principal investigator, Nadine Hoover, mentioned
other forms of harassment were revealed that may not have been as
obvious:
</P>
<P>
   ``Skinny-dipping; streaking, stealing each other's clothes . . .
immersion (in water); going from house to house asking for milk;
putting a pig's head in a football helmet; urinating in lockers;
one kid said an administrator forced him to get into a box-sized
locker; lots of alcohol consumption stuff; exposure to extreme
cold; forced use of steroids, ephedrine; being forced to exercise
until they pass out; being forced to inflict pain until they pass
out; being cruel to animals.''
</P>
<P>
   Or acting like them.
</P>
<P>
   Mixed reaction at UVM
</P>
<P>
   Among the Vermont players who agreed to be interviewed by the
Globe, the reaction was startling, at least on the surface.
</P>
<P>
   The freshmen seemed almost defiant, blaming their predicament on
a player they perceived as a malcontent _ LaTulippe, whose
attorneys declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He eagerly participated,'' said Conschafter, who, when asked
if he thought the Catamounts had been robbed of their season,
replied, ``Most definitely.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To say he was abused is ridiculous,'' said defenseman David
Noble, 19, of Cohasset. ``Everybody was excited about being part of
the UVM team. It was one of the many things we did that made us as
close a team as we are. If I thought it went too far, I'd be
jumping on the bandwagon and suing everybody. You don't see anybody
else here doing that, do you? (LaTulippe) was a bad goalie. If he
hadn't been cut, you wouldn't have heard anything about this.''
</P>
<P>
   The upperclassmen who commented seemed contrite, or at least
regretful.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely was a mistake,'' said sophomore center Ryan Cox,
20, of Norwell. ``We've paid the consequences. I just want it to
get over with, but it just keeps dragging on. We suffered the
biggest consequences _ a lost season. I wake up with an empty
feeling in my stomach knowing there's no hockey. It wasn't as if
anybody held a gun to their heads or said, `We're going to beat you
up on the ice (if you don't attend the party).' Maybe peer pressure
got to them.''
</P>
<P>
   And exposure got the Catamounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at how things turned out, it's because of that _
yeah, it was a mistake,'' said junior defenseman Martin Wilde, 22.
</P>
<P>
   Flammia indicated that the entire matter might have been caused
by a sense of reluctant obligation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I didn't regret everything that happened, I'd have to be
crazy,'' he said. ``We lost our season. I wish we didn't do it, but
by the same token, I went through it, other guys went through it,
and nothing happened. Nobody likes doing it _ I didn't enjoy it (as
a freshman). But we all went through it. There was a sense of
pressure that we had to do it. (As freshmen), we were told, `Guys,
we don't want to do it but we have to. You'll have to do it, too.
It brings us together.' Do I think it brings us together? Not now.
But I did then.''
</P>
<P>
   Such seeming role reversal in fact is not as bizarre as it might
sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe it or not, that's not an unusual reaction,'' said
Eileen Stevens of Sayville, N.Y., an antihazing crusader who has
spoken at some 700 colleges in the 22 years since her son, Chuck
Stenzel, died of acute alcohol poisoning and exposure resulting
from a fraternity hazing at Alfred. ``There's such a strong sense
of acceptance among these young men or women that they feel it's
OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a team situation, coaches and upperclassmen have bought
into it and are on such a pedestal. They went through it, then
they'll have their turn. It perpetuates it. Emotionally, (freshmen)
may not be secure enough to realize their rights are being
violated. Even if there's a flicker of discomfort, they feel there
must be something wrong with them. They don't want to be the
whistleblower or the rat. They don't realize that would be
courageous.''
</P>
<P>
   The key, UVM coach Gilligan believes, is to keep driving home
the message until it is observed without supervision or sanctions
being necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest challenge we have as educators is to try to get
these young adults to understand what is hazing,'' said the
embattled coach. ``A lot of them and their classmates don't feel it
was hazing because it was voluntary. They don't understand there's
a condition in the air that (makes them) feel they should
participate.''
</P>
<P>
   The stigma does not belong to UVM alone. The Catamounts'
greatest misfortune might have been detection.
</P>
<P>
   The Vermont players also claim to have empirical evidence that
theirs is not an isolated case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know for a fact that things like this happen all over the
country,'' Conschafter said. ``It's no different. I've got friends
around the country who play Division 3 hockey and football. They've
gone through the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the revelations, Flammia found himself a magnet
for correspondence from strangers with a common theme: concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gotten e-mails from players as far away as Alaska,'' he
said. ``People I don't even know asking me for details of what we
did because they've done the same things and don't want to get in
trouble. I think what we did was excessive, but I've heard from
other players saying they've done a lot worse.''
</P>
<P>
   The Catamounts believe the notoriety they've received will end
the practice, and administrators hope they're correct. But college
officials also believe that the cessation will be merely temporary
if they practice benign neglect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Real change is going to have to happen campus to campus,''
Pollard said. ``Each state is going to have to have an antihazing
law.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Alfred AD Jim Moretti, whose school seems to have
established a model for hazing awareness, takes nothing for
granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not immune to having it happen again,'' he said.
``Nobody is.''
</P>
<P>
   The imperative is to strike while the issue is prominent, and
Gilligan, who may be a casualty of the shrapnel up in Burlington,
offers a rueful perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure it will (have a national impact),'' he said. ``My
next job might be on the lecture circuit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
