<HEADER>
A5212 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-SKATE-USMEN-GOEBELWEI     02-12 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKATE-USMEN-GOEBELWEISS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOEBEL DOES QUADS, BUT WEISS GETS TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Figure skating purists have been debating the
sport-or-art question ever since Mr. Paulsen did his single axel in
1882. After Saturday afternoon, when Tim Goebel jumped out of Gund
Arena and still couldn't take the US men's title from Michael
Weiss, they'll be arguing for another century and more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a judge,'' said the 19-year-old Goebel with a shrug,
after he'd nailed a historic three quadruple jumps in the long
program and still lost to Weiss, who couldn't manage even one. ``I
just went out and did my job and I was pleased with what I did.
Michael skated a very solid program and he was the reigning
national champion.''
</P>
<P>
   No men's titleholder had been dethroned since hometowner Rudy
Galindo upset Todd Eldredge in San Jose in 1996. But the
23-year-old Weiss had been nursing an ankle stress fracture all
season and hadn't competed since November. And Goebel, who'd landed
three quads at Skate America at the beginning of the season, had a
much more demanding long program and was skating in front of his
home crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time you go to a competition, you have to attack,'' said
Goebel, a freshman at Case Western Reserve in Cleveland who trains
in nearby Lakewood. ``Being cautious, being defensive is costly.
Whenever you go out there, you have to be aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Goebel, who skated first in the final group, did three quads in
a row _ a quad salchow-triple toe combination, a quad toe loop, and
another quad salchow. He also did a triple axel-triple toe combo
and four other triples. His only mistake _ and it probably cost him
the title _ was stepping out of the axel in the combination. Had he
nailed it, Goebel likely would have earned a string of 6.0
technical marks instead of eight 5.9s and a 5.8.
</P>
<P>
   When the music stopped, Goebel knelt and covered his face in his
hands, just as Bob Beamon did when he jumped 29 feet at the 1968
Olympics and created his own airspace. No man ever had landed even
one quad in a US championships.
</P>
<P>
   But his skywalking, and the imbalance it created in his program,
cost Goebel on the artistic side, where he was given mostly 5.7s
and a 5.6. ``You gotta have both,'' mused Audrey Weisiger, Weiss's
coach. ``It's an athletic-artistic combination that succeeds.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiss, derided as a graceless leaper when Eldredge used to beat
him, had worked hard on polishing his programs. Though he never got
around on his planned quad toe Saturday night, settling for a
triple, Weiss hit everything else, including a triple axel-triple
toe, a second combination, and another triple axel, nine triples in
all.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't sure what Goebel had done, but from the marks and the
cheering, Weiss had a good clue. ``I assumed he'd hit at least one
quad and possibly three,'' he said. ``I knew I'd have to put it all
out there to pull out a win.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Weiss's technical marks were only 5.8s and 5.7s, he
outpointed Goebel on artistry, with a 6.0 (from Joan Burns), three
5.9s, and five 5.8s. When the math was done, Weiss had prevailed
6-3, with the artistic tiebreaker winning him four judges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even put into words how amazing this is,'' said Weiss.
``As everyone says, it's always tougher to defend a title than to
win it. I was really psyched to pull this one off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
