</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BUICK-MICKELSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICKELSON IN DRIVER'S SEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ In another time, he was the brightest star whose
talent made the golf world stop and take notice. But even though
Phil Mickelson could hit a flop shot into a thimble from 25 paces,
he couldn't do anything about the arrival of Tiger Woods's fire and
magic.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson, so used to the spotlight, perhaps has done a low
simmer as he has been pushed to the background by Woods, but he has
the opportunity Sunday to alter that landscape. He birdied four of
the last seven holes Saturday to shoot 5-under-par 67 and complete
three rounds of the Buick Invitational at 16-under 200, good for a
two-shot lead over Shigeki Maruyama. Davis Love shot 69 and is
alone in third at 205.
</P>
<P>
   Though he played near-flawless golf in front of a home crowd at
a course he has known since boyhood (Torrey Pines's South Course),
Mickelson knew what would face him afterward, so he volunteered
almost curtly this assessment of the situation: ``All I know is he
played a very good round today, but started six back and he's still
six back,'' said Mickelson about Woods, who settled for what had to
be a disappointing 67 and is tied for fourth in his quest to win a
seventh straight tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Disappointing not because he played poorly _ to the contrary,
Woods climbed past 18 players _ but because it fell short of his
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sixty-five,'' said Woods, when asked what his goal was for the
third round. ``I gave myself a lot of opportunities. I can't tell
you how many good putts I hit that just didn't go in.''
</P>
<P>
   Fresh on his mind as he said that was his finish _ birdie
attempts from inside of 10 feet on the final three holes, none of
which fell.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson, on the other hand, delivered on his chances down the
stretch to break away from Maruyama (they had been tied at 13-under
through 14) and push Woods even further down the board.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (Woods) is going to have to do something extraordinary
to make up ground,'' said Mickelson, who is still haunted by his
one-shot loss to Woods at the NEC Invitational last August, a
tournament that started this winning streak. ``Obviously he is
capable of doing that. I expect he's going to get out to a quick
start and go low, but if I play a solid round I'm going to be in a
position to force him to shoot a ridiculously low round.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods came from five shots back after three rounds to win last
week's AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach National Pro-Am, a fact Mickelson is well
aware of. But Mickelson has never been confused with Matt Gogel,
the PGA Tour rookie who squandered last week's lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to try and play intelligent, aggressive golf,'' said
Mickelson, who will be paired with Maruyama and Love in the final
group. Woods will be with two of the others at 10 under, Jeff
Sluman (66) and Fred Couples (67), just in front of Mickelson, a
fact that doesn't faze him.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson seems determined to get back a piece of the spotlight
that Woods has dominated. Since the end of 1996 when Woods stormed
out of the gates, Mickelson has won just four times, compared with
17 for Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``My focus has changed. I'm excited not only about this
tournament, but the entire year,'' said Mickelson.
</P>
<P>
   He showed it, too. Starting the day tied with Maruyama and Kirk
Triplett (73), Mickelson began slowly and was in danger of getting
swallowed up by the roars filtering back from Woods's gallery.
That's because Woods, thanks to a knock-down wedge to 2 feet at the
par-4 third and a two-putt birdie at the par-5 sixth, was at 7
under, just four behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt confident,'' said Woods, who elicited more roars when
he reached the par-5 ninth hole with a 2-iron from 245 yards. Two
putts, another birdie, and the charge seemed on. Particularly since
Mickelson had gone out in five consecutive pars and Maruyama had
fallen to 10 under with a bogey at the par-4 fourth.
</P>
<P>
   When Woods knocked a 5-iron to 15 feet at the par-3 11th and
made the putt, he was 9 under with two par 5s to play. Mickelson
had gotten to 13 under by making birdie at each of the par 5s on
the front, but the momentum seemed to be all Woods's.
</P>
<P>
   Momentum that a cool putter took away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is just a little disconcerting, knowing you are hitting
good putts and they're not going in,'' said Woods, whose biggest
heartache came at the par-5 13th. He had drilled a 2-iron from 244
yards, his ball coming to rest 18 feet from the pin. The eagle putt
was on line all the way, but ``it made a flat line on me, instead
of continuing to break.''
</P>
<P>
   It hit the left lip, spun out, and left him a most frustrating
birdie tap-in. He was 10 under, but wouldn't make another birdie,
not even at the 498-yard par-5 18th, a hole he usually can reach
with an 8-iron. But Woods drove it into the rough, could only get
it to the front of the green, then missed a 6-footer after a good
chip.
</P>
<P>
   Woods had failed to apply even more pressure, which seemed to
relieve Mickelson. The lefthander, after a sloppy three-putt bogey
at the par-4 10th, went on a birdie binge _ the 12th, 15th, 16th,
and 18th. On the closing hole, he laid back with a 3-wood off the
tee, then drilled another 3-wood from 240 yards to set up a
two-putt birdie, a sequence of shots that seemed to put an
exclamation point to his statement that he is still a threat to be
considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can I win six straight?'' Mickelson said, repeating a question
that had been asked of him. He shook his head. ``I'm just trying to
win one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
