u s BC-OLY-BOXINGTRIALS-BENN     02-12 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BOXINGTRIALS-BENNETT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BENNETT CAME OUT OF PRISON WITH FIGHTING CHANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA _ The Toy Store Bandit would like to steal a place on the
Olympic team before the month is out. That's not much time, but
Michael Bennett knows all about time.
</P>
<P>
   He knows about hard time and fast time and how time can
disappear. He also knows that he's running out of time.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Bennett was a 19-year-old small-college football player
from Chicago who earned money loading trucks for UPS when he wasn't
attending North Park College. He was a product of the hardest place
in the city, the Cabrini-Green housing project, a place so full of
small-time criminals and hate that the federal government finally
gave up on it and shut the place down. When that happened, people
cheered. Unfortunately, the cheer didn't rise up before Bennett
went down.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, Bennett had no Olympic dreams or any other kind of
dreams. What he had was a nightmare that began the day he walked
into a Toys ``R'' Us with a friend and a sawed-off shotgun with
mayhem and money on his mind. Not even a month after they left that
store, they were leaving Chicago as guests of the Illinois penal
system.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bennett insists that it was his friend who carried the
gun, he was the one who got the 26 years of hard time because his
friend cut a deal in exchange for fingering Bennett. Such is the
way dreams die in fetid places like Cabrini-Green. They die before
they're born.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was stupid what I did,'' Bennett said. ``I couldn't even
tell you what I was thinking that day.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not, but he can tell you exactly what he was thinking a
few months later, when a Chicago judge told him he owed the state
of Illinois 26 years for his mistake. He was thinking about math.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I remember was the judge said, `26 years,' and I heard
some woman in the back say, `Damn, that's a long time,' '' Bennett
recalled. ``I went to my cell and tried to figure out how long that
was. I tried to even figure in for the leap years. When I got done
I thought, `Oh my God.' ''
</P>
<P>
   That's because 26 years times 365 days is 9,490 days, and times
24 hours a day is 227,760 hours. There's no reason to multiply
after that because you know what you just lost.
</P>
<P>
   At age 19, you've lost your youth and perhaps your life. That's
an expensive trip to the toy store.
</P>
<P>
   But Bennett says he accepted it. Of course, what choice did he
have? He was ``accepting'' what he could not avoid. He was
accepting watching the best years of his life dissolve into dark
nights and dank days in a penitentiary called ``The Pit,'' a cold
place built into an old rock quarry in Menard, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Maximum security. Maximum pain. Maximum time. Minimum future.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett would go to jail a teenager and come out with more than
half his life gone.
</P>
<P>
   So how long is 26 years? A long time to think about a toy store
and a shotgun and a bad idea. But that's what Bennett got. Time to
think.
</P>
<P>
   And, just maybe in the end, he got something else. Maybe he also
got what prison can sometimes bring a man. Maybe he got redemption.
</P>
<P>
   While at the Menard Correctional Institute, Bennett discovered
the boxing ring and three guys named Papa-San, Mongoose, and
Pharoah. How much they knew about boxing is hard to tell, but they
knew enough to pass on what they had to give to Bennett a couple of
years after he got to prison. He took those lessons and to his
first victory in a long time, a prison win over a tough guy with a
big mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where I started to learn the jab, the hook, and the old
1-2,'' Bennett said. ``I never intended to be a boxer. I just did
it to try it.''
</P>
<P>
   He tried boxing and the Bible, and both worked for him. Seven
years later, he was paroled for good behavior. When he came out, he
carried his boxing gloves and the good book. His two sisters were
waiting with the honey buns that he forgot he used to love. He
showed them the Bible and the boxing gloves and told them the two
might save him yet.
</P>
<P>
   Now here he is, barely 18 months later, captain of the United
States national boxing team and fighting to win a spot on the 2000
Olympic team at 201 pounds. Saturday he won the trials at the Tampa
Convention Center by dominating a man who had twice beaten him,
Colorado's DaVarryl Williamson, and now Bennett must win only one
more fight, in two weeks at the Olympic boxoffs at Foxwoods.
</P>
<P>
   If he makes it, Bennett will not be the first ex-con to fight
his way to freedom, but that doesn't make his story less
compelling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not ashamed of my past,'' Bennett said last week. ``It's
something I can't erase. I made a bad choice and paid heavily for
it. Some people have to pay more for their mistakes than others,
but if I hadn't gone to prison I wouldn't have found boxing.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a high price to pay for finding a sport that fits your
talents; Bennett would not recommend this road. But it is his road
and his story and he is on it now, further than he ever expected to
be after winning a silver medal at the US Championships last
February after only nine amateur fights. He won the US Challenge
and then the World Championship in Houston last September.
</P>
<P>
   The World Championship victory was tainted because Bennett never
got to fight the reigning Olympic and World Amateur champion, Felix
Savon, in the final. The Cuban team walked out of the tournament in
protest of earlier decisions. But Bennett still has the medal and
he'll accept the break without complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Once Savon refused to get into the ring, all Bennett had to do
to become world champion was walk into an empty ring, hear the
first bell ring, and have his hand raised.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with hearing a judge say, ``26 years, son,'' it was a
blessing.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, though, Bennett's trials are not over. Even if he
survives the road to Sydney, he still must face his past. Bennett
needs permission from Australian immigration officials to be
admitted into the country because he is a felon convicted of a
violent crime.
</P>
<P>
   USA Boxing officials have already applied for permission in case
Bennett qualifies, which is a strong possibility now that he is
past his nemesis, Williamson. But a strong chance is no guarantee,
just as a fast start at Cabrini-Green was no guarantee Bennett
wouldn't be standing in a toy store with a shotgun, and a friend
who was anything but.
</P>
<P>
   Still, US Olympic officials are hopeful Bennett will be allowed
into Australia in September and his Illinois parole officers let
him travel to box because they realize what boxing is to him.
</P>
<P>
   It is his chance.
</P>
<P>
   It is a fighter's chance, and that isn't always much of one. But
it's a chance, and he'll take it as far as he can. As far away as
it can take him from a toy store and a shotgun and a place where
the doors clang shut at night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I've learned my lesson,'' Bennett said. ``All I want is
a chance and I think I'll get it.''
</P>
<P>
   If he does, it will have come the hard way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
