<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5218 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-NBAALLSTAR-VANGUN     02-12 1330
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBAALLSTAR-VANGUNDY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAN GUNDY IS A KNICK WITH A KNACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Of all the factual tidbits that have shaken
loose from the 49th NBA All-Star Game, here is the leader in the
clubhouse: Jeff Van Gundy is a partial Yalie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went there one year,'' reported the coach of the East
All-Stars. ``I was recruited by Ray Carazzo and he cut me on the
first day of practice! I mean, recruited and cut in one day. I
wanted to play, so I decided to leave. My mother still can't
believe I left an Ivy League school to play basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that he was the second coming of Gary Payton.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a player, I was just good enough to get my father fired,''
he said with a laugh. ``You know how they say every white suburban
kid can shoot free throws? The problem is, you've got to be able to
get to the line. I could only penetrate with the pass, so I never
got there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yale experience is an improbable story, but just about
everything concerning Van Gundy's presence in the All-Star Game is
improbable. Like, who is this guy, and how did he survive four
Knick coaching regimes to become the head man at age 33? How did
this modestly gifted Division 3 point guard (Nazareth in Rochester,
N.Y.) position himself to be able to say, ``Reggie, go in for
Allen'' in the NBA's great showcase game?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he's the son of a coach, but is that such an exclusive
club? Coaches, and there are thousands of them, breed just like
everyone else. Why is Bill Van Gundy's kid the chosen one?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a tremendous amount of luck involved,'' said Van
Gundy. ``Players filter up according to their abilities, but it
doesn't necessarily work that way with coaches. There are plenty of
guys in Division 3 who can do as good or better a job at this as I
can.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy's big break came because he had a player. He was
coaching at McQuaid Jesuit High School in Rochester, N.Y., and the
best player on his team was a lefthanded marksman named Greg
Woodard. College folk started to come around, and one of them was
Providence assistant Stu Jackson. The two hit it off, and when a
vacancy cropped up (Herb Sendek was heading off to bigger and
better things) Van Gundy was offered the position of grad assistant
on Rick Pitino's staff. When Jackson succeeded Pitino as coach of
the Knicks, he invited Van Gundy aboard. Eternal moral of the
story: It's not what you know; it's who you know.
</P>
<P>
   (The P.S. on this one is that Woodard went to Villanova.)
</P>
<P>
   Once ensconced, Van Gundy bit into the job in pit bull fashion,
going the extra mile, and then 10 more extra miles. It turns out
that this really was where he belonged, that having absorbed
basketball knowledge on all those car rides to and from practice
with his dad and having gone to all those practices and having
learned to diagram plays when he was 10 years old, that basketball
is basketball, and there's no reason why he couldn't impart a bit
of his knowledge to highly skilled professional players.
</P>
<P>
   Some people don't get it. They assume players will only listen
to ring-laden men such as Western All-Star counterpart Phil Jackson
or a hoop demigod such as Larry Bird, but Van Gundy says he is
proof to the contrary. You can be a short, balding former Division
3 point guard and you can still get their attention if you've got
what they perceive to be the ``Right Stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Players don't care about anything other than you be
competitive, reliable, sincere, and responsible,'' he said. ``They
don't care if you're big or small, black or white. All they want is
someone who can help them become better.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, Van Gundy is a phenomenon. You know he's smart,
because in the normal swirl of professional sports little-known
assistant coaches don't survive when Jackson is replaced by John
MacLeod and John MacLeod is replaced by Pat Riley and Pat Riley is
succeeded by Don Nelson. He must have extraordinary political
skills to go along with his basketball acumen.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he just knows where the corpses are stashed. But there
must be more. He quite obviously has something going for him that
the players respect, although he is quick to say that he owes
certain people more than he ever could repay. ``Guys like Patrick
Ewing, Mark Jackson, and Charles Oakley gave me respect before I
earned it,'' he acknowledged. ``What happened as time went on was
that I then made my way in the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   So here he is, back where it all began. His father was coaching
in nearby Martinez, Calif. (birthplace of Joe DiMaggio), and this
was home until the end of his freshman year when Bill Van Gundy
took a job in upstate New York. The Bay Area scribes couldn't get
enough of Van Gundy's local references, about the trips he would
take with his dad to local schools, and how his dad would have him
read the box scores aloud or ask him to diagram so-and-so's
out-of-bounds plays. ``I now know he already knew what was in the
box scores, and that he probably threw the diagrams into the waste
basket,'' Van Gundy said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy says he always will take what he calls his father's
``Division 3 values'' wherever he goes. Bill Van Gundy, who spent
15 years coaching at Genesee Community College in Batavia, N.Y., is
from the old school, as you might suspect, and that means you honor
your commitments. That's why he will not be in attendance Sunday.
Though officially retired, Bill Van Gundy is an unpaid volunteer
assistant at St. John Fisher College in Rochester, and there is a
game Sunday. Mom Cindy will represent his interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's him,'' said Van Gundy with a shrug, before quickly
pointing out that his dad was present for his career pinnacle as
Knicks coach in the 1999 NBA Finals. ``He was at both games in San
Antonio,'' Van Gundy said. ``Here's a guy who coached all his life,
and he's much better than I'll ever be. To see the pride in his
face over what I was doing was very satisfying.''
</P>
<P>
   No one in the game better understands the capriciousness of it
all than Van Gundy, who with three weeks to go in the regular
season last year was much closer to being an unemployed coach than
an All-Star coach. The Knicks won a few games, got on a roll, and
got past Miami when Allan Houston's last-second shot hit the rim,
bounced off the glass, and fell in at the buzzer. That shot lifted
New York into a weird Indiana series (remember Larry Johnson's
controversial 4-point shot?) and into the Finals against San
Antonio. And what did this say about Jeff Van Gundy?
</P>
<P>
   ``The NBA is a results-oriented business,'' he said. ``At the
end of the year we got a few lucky bounces. But what happened in
the final 15 games of the season and the playoffs didn't mean I was
coaching any better than I was earlier in the season.''
</P>
<P>
   The immediate task is figuring out how to coach in an All-Star
Game. ``I can say we just want to have them go out there and have
fun,'' he said. ``I'd love to see the league have a showcase game,
and the only way I know to do that is for them to play hard and
play together.''
</P>
<P>
   He hopes his team can exploit its quickness edge. ``We've only
got three guys over 6-9, and their starting front line is all over
7-feet,'' he said with a sigh.
</P>
<P>
   It's certainly been a memorable 12 months for Van Gundy. He saw
his name splashed all over the back pages of the New York tabloids
(``Unfortunately, my name lends itself to headlines . . . `Van
Gone,' `Pack Up The Van,' stuff like that''), he went to the
Finals, and now he is coach at the All-Star Game. Not bad for a
Yale dropout. No Skull and Bones for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friends and I kept trying to break in there,'' he said with
a laugh. ``That was my life's work that whole freshman year.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth is he has found his life's work, and you can argue
that it culminates Sunday when a 38-year-old Division 3 point guard
gives orders to the world's greatest basketball players.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
