<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5219 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-SKATE-SPEED-SHORTTRAC     02-12 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKATE-SPEED-SHORTTRACK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEINSTEIN SPRINTS TO WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALPOLE _ He is from Brookline, a freshman at Harvard, and when
the starter's gun for the 500-meter men's final exploded Saturday,
Daniel Weinstein exploded with it, grabbing an immediate lead that
set off the home fans in explosions of noise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great feeling hearing all the noise,'' said the
19-year-old Weinstein. ``In 500 meters, you just go.''
</P>
<P>
   But as the bell lap began, Apolo Anton Ohno, the top-ranked
American ``and a skater who's been skating so well recently, maybe
the best in the world,'' said Weinstein, was at his heels looming
on his inside. ``I had a couple of chances to pass Dan,'' said
Ohno.
</P>
<P>
   And as the skaters entered the final turn of the final lap in
the US Short-Track Championships at Iorio Arena, ``I didn't see
Apolo but I could feel him and hear him,'' said Weinstein. ``He's
such a good skater you just know he's going to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Entering that final turn, Ohno, 17, of Colorado Springs, had to
decide whether to try to pass Weinstein on the inside. ``I had a
couple of chances to go inside,'' said Ohno, ``but Dan would
probably have shut me down.''
</P>
<P>
   And by the narrowest of margins, Weinstein edged Ohno in the
race, their times indicative of the closeness of the event.
Weinstein finished in 43.459 seconds to Ohno's 43.543 seconds.
Rusty Smith was third in 43.616 and Tom O'Hare fourth in 43.760.
</P>
<P>
   In the women's 500 meters, old reliable and four-time Olympian
Amy Peterson of Ballston Springs, N.Y., blew away the field. She
took the lead right after the gun and was never threatened by any
of her competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson, 27, continues to rule as the top American woman. The
reason for her excellence, she said, is ``the pure joy of
speedskating, which I love. I love the sport, I love the lifestyle,
and I've had a strong family that's been behind me.''
</P>
<P>
   Peterson won in a time of 46.924 seconds. Julie Goskowicz, 19,
of Colorado Springs, finished second in 46.990 and surprising
Caroline Hallisey, 19, of Natick, finished third in 47.057,
continuing her good day.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, in the 1,500-meter finals, Ohno won a race that was
just as exciting as the 500-meter event, edging Weinstein and
Smith. Ohno confidently stayed back in the early laps and took the
lead with about two laps to go and lived up to his top-ranked
billing.
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein played it safe, trying to avoid mishaps with
second-tier skaters. Several times he went to the lead to avoid
trouble. But going to the lead early reduces the energy left for
the final laps, and Weinstein finished second with a time of
2:23.589, just behind Ohno's 2:23.369. Smith's time for third was
2:23.746.
</P>
<P>
   In the women's 1,500-meter finals, Peterson, as usual, dominated
the field, winning with a time of 2:32.934, ahead of second-place
finisher Goskowicz (2:33.040) and Hallisey (2:33.441).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy,'' said Hallisey, who had been the fifth-ranked
American woman going into the competition. ``I was able to finish
third behind the two (Peterson and Goskowicz) who everybody
expected to be 1-2. My goal is still to finish in the top two.''
</P>
<P>
   This competition is important for the skaters because it
determines the makeup of the US team that will go to the world team
championships in The Hague, Netherlands, and the world individual
championships in Sheffield, England, both next month.
</P>
<P>
   The top five finishers in both the men's and women's
championships will go to the team championships while only the top
three men and top two women are eligible for the individual
championships. The makeup of the US team is decided by results in
the 500, 1,000, and 1,500 meters, combined with the rankings in the
time trials, which were held Friday. The final race to determine
the makeup of the team is the 1,000 meters Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
