<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5220 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-SAIL-AMERICASCUP-NEWZ     02-12 1496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAIL-AMERICASCUP-NEWZEALAND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH WATER MARK FOR NEW ZEALAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ You expect, perhaps, royalty. Or
something close.
</P>
<P>
   After all, a visit to the home of Sir Peter Blake begins with a
ferry ride across to Auckland's North Shore, then a short walk up
Sir Peter Blake Boulevard to the house on terraced gardens that
opens majestically on the skyline of the city shimmering in the
late afternoon sun.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, much of the modern look of the City of Sails _ with
the 1,000-foot Sky Needle and America's Cup Village of waterfront
businesses, restaurants, and condos, its basin full of mega-yachts
in for The Cup _ is attributable to the accomplishments of Sir
Peter Blake.
</P>
<P>
   But royalty? It makes him laugh.
</P>
<P>
   The tall, tousled-hair fellow wearing a rugby shirt, shorts, and
bright red socks looks more like an ageless kid than a ``Knight
Commander of the Civil Division of the Most Excellent Order of the
British Empire,'' an honor bestowed on him by the Queen Elizabeth
II five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   That was the year when, as leader of the Black Magic sailing
team, Blake fulfilled a 10-year-old dream of his nation to win the
America's Cup.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard for Americans, living in a country of 260 million with
the breadth and complexity of the US sports economy, to understand
the importance of the America's Cup to this tiny island nation of 3
million.
</P>
<P>
   But to see the effect now of seven national teams in Auckland
competing all year for the Cup _ and the half-billion-dollar impact
on the economy _ is to understand Blake's assessment five years ago
when his country won in San Diego: ``It's the most important thing
that ever happened to New Zealand.''
</P>
<P>
   Blake was 47 then, and the achievement of his team culminated an
effort that began in 1985 when a banker named Michael Fay first
fired the America's Cup passion by backing a New Zealand entry in
the 12-meter World Championships in Fremantle, Australia, a
preliminary to the 1986-87 America's Cup there.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Fay pointed out that New Zealand had the strongest
economy in the Southern Hemisphere coming out of World War II but
had been on a slide ever since. The America's Cup, with its huge
international prestige, could focus the eyes of the world on New
Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   New Zealand came close on that first try, finishing second in
the Louis Vuitton challenger finals to Dennis Conner, whose Stars &AMP;
Stripes took the Cup to San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, Blake, an Auckland native, was becoming a growing
presence in New Zealand's sailing world, with victories in the
Sydney-Hobart Race, Admiral's Cup, and the Whitbread
Round-the-World Race on the crew of Steinlager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pretty well stuck into it,'' says Blake of his sailing
exploits, of which the long-term offshore adventures are closer to
his heart than round-the-buoys racing. ``I've been sailing my whole
life. I wouldn't know what else to do.''
</P>
<P>
   But he viewed the America's Cup as a job to be finished, and in
1992 he became part of the famous New Zealand team that, on the eve
of victory in the challenger series, unraveled and lost to Paul
Cayard skippering Il Moro de Venezia for Italy.
</P>
<P>
   But Blake's reputation for team management made him a natural to
lead New Zealand into the 1995 Cup in San Diego. In the meantime,
the year before that Cup, just to ``get a splash of sea water on my
face,'' Blake shattered the Jules Verne Record as skipper of ENZA
(``Eat New Zealand Apples''), a 60-foot catamaran that made a
nonstop round-the-world voyage in 74 days, 22 hours, 17 minutes,
and 22 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner was he back from that adventure than his team was off
to San Diego with two boats named Black Magic. This time, neither
internal team politics nor the tremendous pressure from
psychological warfare _ two elements that doomed the '92 effort _
would touch Team New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   Blake's personality _ jocular, folksy, good-natured _ was a
contrast to the sharp focus of his mission. He stood as a firewall
between Team New Zealand and the intense off-the-water pressures of
Cup competition. On the water, blessed with the two quickest boats
in San Diego, designed by Doug Peterson, New Zealand sailed to a
victory that was so decisive as to be almost anticlimactic. Blake
rode the boat as mainsheet trimmer. He is credited with being a
calming influence on the team.
</P>
<P>
   Blake also was credited with being one of the most persuasive
voices in getting sponsor dollars behind Team New Zealand: $40
million for this year's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reckon it was just our time,'' says Blake, always with a
modest tone, always trying to minimize his own part in these
sailing glories. ``We had quick boats, and our sailors did their
part.''
</P>
<P>
   In many speeches and appearances around San Diego in the wake of
the triumph, Blake emphasized that New Zealand's reign as defender
of the Cup would bring rules to ``level the playing field,'' a
much-debated topic.
</P>
<P>
   With the New York Yacht Club installed as Challenger of Record _
despite a short-circuit attempt by Bill Koch _ Blake announced that
the next defense would come in 2000, five long years away. There
were groans. Critics said that such a long time between defenses
would ruin the event, that it would be forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   But Blake's resolve was clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed the time to rebuild our waterfront,'' he said at the
time. ``There's nothing there for an event like the America's Cup
and what it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Few critics can be found from those years. Wherever the Cup goes
next time, the Auckland waterfront, with Viaduct Basin holding all
the racing compounds and America's Cup Village surrounding it, is
stunning. This seaport sets a new standard by which all future Cups
will be measured _ all part of the Blake vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without Blake's vision or his presence,'' says Alan Sephton, a
syndicate spokesman, ``there would have been no one to pick up from
where Michael Fay left off. It took some convincing to get him into
it, but no one else could have handled the figurehead role. He
really inspired the imagination of the entire country.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Blake wants to see Team New Zealand make at least one
successful defense of the Cup (the new black boats take on Italy's
Prada in just over a week). But, he concedes, his head is really
not in the game anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Though he is titular head of the defense syndicate, there is a
been-there-done-that feel. He rarely sails on the racing boats, and
the sailing team does not need him as it once did. Blake is a man
who craves change and new challenges.
</P>
<P>
   It might seem that Sir Peter, now in his 50s, having
accomplished so much for himself and his country, might just sit
back a bit and take life easy. Hosting barbecues on his patio, or
attending wife Pippa's art show opening, or involving himself in
the lives of his children (Jane, 16, and James, 13), Blake gives
every appearance of contentment in life.
</P>
<P>
   But appearances couldn't be further from the truth. As soon as
the Cup ends, Blake will begin his duties as new head of the
Jacques Cousteau Society and begin testing the systems of the
conservation group's latest acquisition: Antarctic Explorer, an
aluminum-plated, 117-foot-long, 30-foot-wide sailing vessel
equipped to handle ice closures in the Arctic winters.
</P>
<P>
   Since Cousteau died in 1997, the society he gave his name to has
floundered. Blake hopes to rebuild it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we've got about 100,000 members,'' he says. ``We
want to build it up to a membership of 1-5 million. What we have to
do is get it back in front of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea is for Antarctic Explorer, and perhaps similar teams on
other oceans, to undertake a number of high-profile adventures and
air them on world television.
</P>
<P>
   ``For people to care about the ocean, you have to make them
passionate about the beauty first,'' says Blake. ``The earth
depends on the ocean, and people have to care and develop a love
before they think about saving it.''
</P>
<P>
   The issues of massive pollution, overharvesting of fisheries,
and even recreational pollution of the coast are all focuses for
the revitalized Cousteau Society.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not like Greenpeace,'' says Blake. ``We'll make
suggestions of how things could be done differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Antarctic Explorer is built like a huge wedge so that as ice
solidifies under it, the hull actually gets pushed up and becomes a
winter dwelling. The big diesel generators convert from water- to
air-cooled, and until the ice melts again, the ship becomes a
building.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just imagine the beauty of it,'' Blake muses, with a faraway
look. ``Think of the seals and sea lions and polar bears
everywhere. It'll be just beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   As his mind wanders to the Northwest Passage, the first
adventure on Antarctic Explorer, it is clear that Sir Peter Blake
has already moved 10,000 miles or so beyond the America's Cup.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
