u s BC-BKN-NBANOTES-CELTICS-     02-12 1791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTES-CELTICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRIVOLOUS CONTRACTS HURT CELTICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I never thought I'd see the day the Celtics would have to trade
two pretty good players in the space of six months because they
felt they could not afford to re-sign them. And now that one of
them is back, does that change anything? No. He'll be traded again,
soon, for the same reason.
</P>
<P>
   When, precisely, did this team become the Minnesota Twins? Or,
to bring the analogy closer to home: Don't Paul Gaston's comments
about fielding a ``competitive team'' while running it like a
business sound eerily similar to Jeremy Jacobs's?
</P>
<P>
   Rick Pitino has been sounding like a member of the Poor Boys
Club. He noted more than once last week that his team could not
compete with the likes of Orlando, Miami, Portland, or New York
because of budgetary limits. Those limits are the reason, we are
led to believe, that Ron Mercer is no longer here and the man who
replaced him, Danny Fortson, once was no longer here, is back, but,
we can be sure, not for long.
</P>
<P>
   Sure it's true. It's true because the budget is bloated with
salaries Pitino unhesitatingly handed to players of lesser ability.
He's not restricted by a budget; he's restricted by his own
largesse.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven months ago, Pitino emerged from the lockout wearing a
here-to-there grin. The new deal, he said, was a godsend for the
Celtics. It enabled teams to build through the draft, as he was
doing, while retaining their young talent, as he planned on doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``In pure economic terms, we were in trouble,'' he said that
January day, referring to the old ways. ``It would have been
difficult for the Boston Celtics to survive and for probably half
the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, he didn't think a nanosecond about handing out $71 million
to Antoine Walker. While he could possibly defend that one _
although the evidence is pretty skimpy _ why on earth did he shell
out $8 million to Walter McCarty, a player who has zero market
value?
</P>
<P>
   Why did he pay $30-something million for Vitaly Potapenko before
Potapenko had spent 72 hours with the team? Because, like Mercer
and Fortson, Potapenko was headed for free agency. (And, like
McCarty, he was represented by David Falk, to whom Pitino steered
most of his Kentucky guys.) Why did he shell out $24 million for
Tony Battie, who plays about once every fifth game? Because, he,
too, was headed for free agency.
</P>
<P>
   It's like going to the store for provisions and coming home
without milk, eggs, and bread because you spent the money on Pop
Tarts.
</P>
<P>
   None of these deals is a budget killer. But totaled, they blow
it apart. Next year, Potapenko, Battie, and McCarty will collect a
combined $10.28 million. Take one of those players out of the
equation _ McCarty is the logical one _ and you've got an extra
$2.8 million to keep Mercer. Instead we've now seen Mercer traded
and McCarty playing about 10 minutes a game.
</P>
<P>
   More disturbing is the team's quick decision to move the players
without anything close to give-and-take, toss-numbers-around
negotiations. Fortson's agent, Raymond Brothers, called the
Celtics' move ```ridiculous.'' Was there ever a serious bargaining
session? ``No,'' he said. ``None.'' Maybe they don't think Fortson
is worth what he thinks he's worth. That's what negotiations are
all about. (Fortson would hardly be the first player to overvalue
himself.) Mercer got the same treatment. One meeting. Bye-bye.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino understood the situation going in; yet it's mind-boggling
to think Gaston could break the bank for a coach and close the bank
on the players. But the bank is closed because the money isn't
there. As the overseer of the basketball treasury, Pitino has, as
Gaston likes to say, breached his ``fiduciary responsibility.'' His
team, and its fans, are now paying for it.
</P>
<P>
   First-half awards
</P>
<P>
   As Bill Fitch liked to say, why judge a movie halfway through?
But we do it anyway; so, here we go:
</P>
<P>
   --MVP: Shaquille O'Neal, LA Lakers. Not even a doubt here. When
the Lakers went through their recent slide, it was due to Shaq
playing like the old Shaq, concerned about scoring. When he's
rebounding, running, and blocking shots the way he's been doing
most of this year, he's unstoppable, and so is his team. He was
transcendent against the Timberwolves last Wednesday, at one point
scoring 18 straight LA points.
</P>
<P>
   --Coach of the Year: Phil Jackson, LA Lakers. They said he
couldn't win without No. 23. Well, he doesn't need No. 23 because
No. 23 is gonzo. He now has the next-best thing, No. 34, and he has
gotten No. 34 to do what no other coach could do before. Why is
that, Shaq? ``He's a white version of my father,'' O'Neal said.
``He's always on me. I like that. I respect that.''
</P>
<P>
   --Rookie of the Year: Elton Brand, Chicago. You can say he's
getting points for a bad team, which he is, but the Bulls aren't
that much worse than the Clippers or Rockets. Here's what GM Jerry
Krause had to say about Brand last week: ``Wait until two years
from now. We have him working with Al Vermiel, who is the best
strength coach in the business. He will be the strongest man in the
league. He never touched a weight at Duke. Mike (Krzyzewski)
doesn't believe in it.''
</P>
<P>
   --Sixth Man: Brian Grant, Portland. Yes, he plays only 20
minutes a game, but so what? He represents what the Trail Blazers
are all about and 28 other teams would lust for him. The guy is
your prototypical warrior.
</P>
<P>
   --Most Improved Player: Dirk Nowitzki, Dallas. More than a few
candidates here, but Nowitzki has gone from being buried to burying
treys and showing what the fuss was all about in the first place.
Even Nellie hasn't messed him up.
</P>
<P>
   --Defensive Player of the Year: Eddie Jones, Charlotte. He's the
leader in steals, and it's frightening to see what happened to
Charlotte when he was out of the lineup. The Hornets not only were
2-8 when he wasn't playing, but also allowed 8 more points a game
in those 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   --Executive of the Year: John Gabriel, Orlando. He is doing the
unthinkable, rebuilding while remaining competitive thanks to his
hiring of Doc Rivers. And then wait until this summer. Boom.
Hooterville Chic. Waffle Houses are in again.
</P>
<P>
   Balancing act
</P>
<P>
   If the Trail Blazers keep playing the way they're playing and
win the NBA championship, they will have a leading scorer with the
lowest average on an NBA champion since the shot clock was
implemented. Only eight champions since 1955 have had a leading
scorer average fewer than 20 points a game, including three Boston
titlists (1976, 1964, and 1963). The champions with the
least-productive leading scorers were the Pistons, who were led by
Isiah Thomas and Adrian Dantley in their two title years, each
averaging 18.4 points a game. Portland goes into the All-Star
break, incredibly, without a player averaging even 16 points. Steve
Smith is at 15.9. That's not all. Every NBA champ since 1955 has
had at least one player average 35 minutes a game. Portland has
none; two players are at 34.8. That's a testament to their balance
and depth . . . After yet another tough loss, this one to Philly on
a buzzer-beating tip-in by Larry Hughes, the Nets staggered home
for the All-Star break. Then team president Michael Rowe held a
conference call with beat reporters and basically ripped apart
everyone. Rowe called the Nets' performance ``absolutely
unacceptable'' and said that things would change. One thing that's
going to change: his travel plans. Rowe said he would start
accompanying the team on trips and making his presence known
pertaining to hoop matters. As he put it, he will ``interface''
with the basketball operations. But one thing that won't change, he
said, is the status of coach Don Casey. ```I would like to work
with what we have, and I'd like to get through the season,'' Rowe
said. How, exactly, does that square with: ``When I look at how we
play, I hear a lot of explanations and excuses. I have not heard
solutions.'' . . . Hughes, of course, is one of several players
being shopped. Everywhere. ``I think the Sixers are committed to
trading Larry Hughes,'' said Orlando coach Rivers. ``They are
committed to moving him. They're going to contact everyone.'' . . .
This just in from the Staples Center, where the Celtics will
conclude their Western swing against the Lakers Feb. 25. One
seasoned NBA observer reports that the ``game presentation'' is
decidedly understated. And this is from the team that ushered in
the Laker Girls (who are still there). According to the source, the
grating cacophony so prevalent around the league isn't nearly as
bad as one might think in the entertainment capital of the world .
. . By the way, the Lakers are asking fans, in conjunction with the
History Channel, to pick the top moment in the franchise's history.
There are 10 choices, the most obvious to me being the 33-game
winning streak in 1971-72. Other selections include the drafting of
Jerry West and Magic Johnson, the 1980 title, the 1985 title (Pat
Riley's favorite), the 1972 title (the first in LA), the
acquisition of Kareem Abdul-Jabbar, West's 60-foot shot against the
Knicks in the playoffs (a game LA lost), Kareem setting the scoring
record, and the 1988 title. The Lakers arrived in Los Angeles for
the 1960-61 season with no real home court and played in whatever
building could accommodate them (high school gyms, a shrine
auditorium). They also had no radio coverage that year.
</P>
<P>
   Frequent fliers
</P>
<P>
   Here's a comforting but on-the-mark comment from Dana Barros as
the trading deadline approaches. ``Everyone is expendable,'' he
said. ``Very few players in this league are not going to be traded,
or are untradeable. If you don't understand that, then you don't
understand the business of the league. There's always that
possibility that anyone can go at any time. I go through it every
year. I'm sure everyone else does.'' . . . No sooner had the
All-Star selections been announced then jilted Jalen Rose scored 20
or more points in four straight games. The Celtics were the last of
his victims last Wednesday . . . Lakers GM Mitch Kupchak said there
was a 60 percent chance the team won't make a deal in the next 11
days. The Lakers are in the market for a backup center/power
forward. Wonder what they'd give for Fortson? . . . And finally
this: Since Pitino has arrived, here is the staggering personnel
count: He has traded for 19 players, signed 16 free agents
(remember William Cunningham?), and drafted five players (let's not
forget Ben Pepper and Kris Clack). Those numbers do not count the
players he released upon arriving (the nine who were renounced to
sign Travis Knight).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
