<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5222 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-SANGLEE-BO     02-12 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-SANGLEE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LANGUAGE ONE CHALLENGE FACED BY SANG LEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ Yes, he is different by design. The orange
hair, now trimmed to shoulder length to satisfy his new boss, Dan
Duquette, was no accident of birth.
</P>
<P>
   But Sang Lee is not simply some knockoff cartoon character
imported from South Korea to pitch for the Red Sox. An early
arrival at spring training, the 28-year-old Lee is thousands of
miles from home, separated from his wife and two young daughters,
trying to adjust to a place where he can't speak the language,
sharing a hotel room with a UMass student hired to be his
translator, his guitar his only familiar companion.
</P>
<P>
   Sang Lee isn't afraid to admit he's lonely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine if you were in South Korea by yourself,'' he says to a
visitor. ``Then you would understand. Total alienation. The
language barrier is huge.''
</P>
<P>
   Park Seung-Hyun is studying sports management at UMass-Amherst.
He has finished all of his required classwork, but in an
independent study project approved by his professor, Dr. Mark
McDonald, he has been enlisted by the Red Sox to make Lee's
transition easier.
</P>
<P>
   Parky, as he came to be called last summer in Pawtucket, where
he did some work for the Sox, is from Seoul, the South Korean
capital that is also home to Lee.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a superstar in Korea,'' Park says. ``I saw him in the
stadium and on TV, but this is the first time we met face to face.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is very unique, the way he dyes his hair. But when you talk
to him, he's kind of an ordinary person. I've known him only for a
week, but he's a very good person.''
</P>
<P>
   Park has a laptop computer with him, and he has called up some
Korean Web sites for Lee. The pitcher doesn't play video games.
``He says they're bad for his eyes,'' Park says.
</P>
<P>
   The two have visited a Korean restaurant in town, but just once.
</P>
<P>
   ``American food,'' Lee says. ``Outback Steak House.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He eats everything,'' Park says, ``but he has given up beer.
He knows how important this is for him.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time Lee has left home to pitch. Before
being signed by the Red Sox, he spent two years pitching in Japan.
The second year was easier. He'd learned some Japanese by then.
</P>
<P>
   Lee understands some English, too, though his preferred modes of
communication are either through Park or by the use of some often
funny pantomimes. Asked if he knows of Fernando Valenzuela, the
Mexican-born pitcher who knew no English when he arrived to play
with the Dodgers, Lee does a dead-on impression of Valenzuela's
pitching motion, complete with an eye-rolling look heavenward at
the top of his delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Mention Sox reliever Rod Beck, and Lee tugs at his long locks,
then sketches an imaginary Fu Manchu moustache above his lip.
</P>
<P>
   ``He jokes with me,'' Park said, ``about playing guitar with Rod
Beck as his drummer.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he plans to do with a weekend off, Lee rests his
cheek on folded hands. ``Sleep,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   For the last week, Lee has been working out with a group of
mostly minor leaguers at the Sox training complex here. Signed to a
two-year, $3.35 million deal, Lee is projected to join Rheal
Cormier as a lefthanded setup man in the Sox bullpen, though he
could also begin the season in Pawtucket. He won 20 games as a
starter in Korea in 1995, but he says he was forced to become a
reliever because of a herniated disk in his back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's destiny, whether it will be Boston or Pawtucket,'' Lee
says through Park. ``Baseball is so unpredictable. It's obvious
that I'm going to be nervous on the mound when I begin.''
</P>
<P>
   But he has a clear understanding of the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's assume that I can speak very good English but can't
pitch,'' he says. ``People will ignore me. But if I can't speak
English and pitch very well, people will have some respect.''
</P>
<P>
   The language barrier does not mask Lee's playful personality. He
is affable and approachable, looking his questioner in the eye even
as he awaits the translation. When he is told that he seems very
natural, he quickly answers, ``Thank you,'' in English, then adds,
also in English: ``Myself, freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   He elaborates, with the help of Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pursue freedom,'' he says, ``but I don't break the clubhouse
rules. I don't care about my image. I just want to be myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to be an ordinary person. That's why I pursue
freedom. Fans see players on the field and think we are all
traditional because we are all wearing the same uniform. Then
people look at your outside life and seem surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee has already begun long-tossing. A week from Sunday, he will
participate in his first official workout with the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not thinking about the hitters,'' he says. ``I have to
focus on myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``But major league baseball is the best in the world. That's why
I want to be here. Playing major league baseball is my dream.''
</P>
<P>
   It was either that or playing guitar in a rock band. Lee smiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm addicted,'' he says, ``to my guitar.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
