</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARRIED AWAY WITH PROSPECT OF WINTER'S END 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The truck leaves Tuesday. Not a day too soon.
</P>
<P>
   This is flatline time for New England sports. The ground is a
depressing mix of ice, mud, and slush and there's so little to
entertain the local sports fan. That's why in Wednesday's editions
of the Globe, we'll cheer you up with the cornball picture of the
Red Sox truck getting packed for Fort Myers.
</P>
<P>
   The Truck Day photo has become one of those odd rituals that are
so indigenous to New England. On Jan. 2 we show you the L Street
Brownies swimming at Carson Beach. In July we bring you pictures of
the Fourth fireworks fans homesteading on the Esplanade. Labor Day
weekend annually brings photos of the student U-Hauls on Bay State
Road.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Truck Day, signifying six more weeks of winter
wasteland.
</P>
<P>
   And what a waste this winter has been.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics officially stink again. It's 15 years and counting,
and there's no indication that the happy days are coming back.
Alleged savior Rick Pitino is the latest victim of a league that
makes it almost impossible to recover once you have fallen. Pitino
is making Dave Gavitt look good. Like Gavitt, Pitino was great in
every job he had before coming to the Celtics, but he's been
strangled by the salary cap and the initial draft lottery that took
him out of the Tim Duncan sweeps.
</P>
<P>
   Little Ricky has been downright Gormanesque. He trades Ron
Mercer for Danny ``We Hardly Knew Ye'' Fortson and now he can't
even give Fortson away for the immortal Alvin Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics are free-falling in the Atlantic Division, bound to
catch New Jersey before they return from their six-game
post-All-Star Western trip. They have no player you'd pay $50 to
see. And Antoine Walker is playing like Elvin Hayes (one shot per
minute, one technical per game) without the talent.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins could still make the playoffs, but do we really want
to see another one-and-out at the hands of the New Jersey Devils?
Tracking the future of Pat Burns and Ray Bourque will provide
Boston's only April hockey drama. Burns is on the hot seat, ducking
media bombs and long-range missiles fired from Jeremy ``Neutral
Zone Trap'' Jacobs in Buffalo. The humble, heroic Bourque has
eschewed any Yazlike farewell tour and will probably announce his
retirement by mailing 18,000 thank you notes to citizens of Bruins
Nation.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have managed to stay in the news, hiring a new
coach, paying $35 million to another defensive back, and releasing
Bruce Armstrong and Ben Coates. Could we not have any tears for
Messrs. Armstrong and Coates? It's pretty simple. The free agency
agreement the players signed means that older players will be
dumped to make room for young stars coming into their prime.
Armstrong and Coates benefitted when they were the young players,
now they are gone because they won't play for (relatively) short
money. It's cold, but it's business. The Patriots really had no
choice in the matter.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just the performances of the local teams that make this
such a depressing winter. We've also said goodbye to a couple of
opponents who made regular trips to Fenway and Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   For 18 years, Patriot season ticket-holders knew that they'd
have at least one opportunity to watch the most prolific passer in
football history. Now there's no guarantee we'll see Dan Marino
again.
</P>
<P>
   The Ken Griffey situation is worse. Baseball's best player, who
was good for six games a year at Fenway for the last decade, may
never be back on Yawkey Way. Griff has joined the National League
Central, and there are no plans for the Red Sox to play the
Cincinnati Reds unless we reenact the 1975 World Series. It is a
huge loss for Sox season ticket-holders and all those who bought
Seattle game tickets to see Griffey. Junior is going to chase Hank
Aaron's home run record and he's going to do it without hitting in
Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and now that the Ryder Cup has come and gone, we know that
Tiger Woods won't be coming here for at least three years, possibly
longer.
</P>
<P>
   This is why we look forward to the Truck Day photo. A week from
Sunday, we'll be reading about Juan Pena's arm, Rich Garces's
waistline, and Jin Ho Cho's visa problems, and all will be right
with the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-12-00 2140EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
