</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-CRENSHAW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STILL A CUP OF CHEER TO CRENSHAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ When the rounds of golf don't go well _ as they did
not these past few days _ Ben Crenshaw still manages a smile. It is
genuine, too. He is a man content, perhaps not with his golf, but
certainly with his life, and much of that comfort stems from the
roars he can still hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Countless numbers of people called,'' said Crenshaw. ``So many
wonderful letters and correspondence.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a little more than four months ago that Crenshaw was in
the middle of something that still gives him chills: the dramatic
rally by the United States to win the Ryder Cup at The Country Club
in Brookline. For two years, Crenshaw had poured his heart and soul
into the job of captain, and for it to have ended happily as one of
the sport's most memorable days is more than he could have dreamed
of.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were desperate for a win, we really were,'' said Crenshaw,
who made his playing debut in 2000 at this week's Buick
Invitational. The US had lost the two previous matches and
Crenshaw, perhaps more than he should have, took it as a personal
crusade to win back the Cup. He put his stamp of approval on nearly
every aspect of the proceedings _ from course condition, team
hotel, dinners, transportation, uniforms, to the all-important
captain's picks.
</P>
<P>
   As he stood on the putting green following his first round at
Torrey Pines Thursday, Crenshaw looked far different from the man
who nearly broke down in front of the national media a month before
the Ryder Cup matches. The money controversy had exploded, Crenshaw
ripped into four particular players, and the event seemed headed
for disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, Crenshaw, the PGA of America, and the players got
through the turbulence, and months later the captain's demeanor is
far different.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been home with my three girls,'' he said. ``I've been
very quiet, and that's what I wanted. It's what I needed.''
</P>
<P>
   He recently turned 48, and most certainly he is in the twilight
of a distinguished playing career. Consumed by his captaincy,
Crenshaw devoted little time to practice, which shows in his
performance. He missed the cut in all 13 starts last year, and
since 1997 he has made just seven cuts in 45 tournaments. He shot
76-74 missed the cut here.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. Crenshaw's passion these days is course design (his
Sand Dunes in Nebraska has won great praise and is one of the
country's finest) and his resume remains impressive: 19 Tour
victories, including two Masters. Besides, as a passionate golf
historian, he feels honored to be witness to a new chapter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in the middle of something that is phenomenal,'' said
Crenshaw when asked about Tiger Woods. ``We never thought the game
could be dominated because there was too much talent. But he has
such a great flair for the dramatics, he is intent on getting
himself better, takes care of himself, and prioritizes his time
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``And his mind. Despite all those great aspects, I think his
mind is his greatest asset.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods's quest to keep a winning streak alive has been the
central story to this Buick Invitational, but Crenshaw was asked
about something that would be even more incredible. The grand slam?
</P>
<P>
   Crenshaw didn't hesitate. ``It's possible with Tiger.''
</P>
<P>
   Pebble for your thoughts
</P>
<P>
   Leftovers from the AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach National Pro-Am: Before
Woods hit that wedge into the 15th at Pebble Beach for the eagle
that ignited his dramatic comeback, he backed off the shot. The
hole runs parallel to 17 Mile Drive and it seems a driver going by
yelled something unpleasant. ``I just kind of waited, let things
settle down, and regrouped,'' said Woods . . . One of Woods's shots
that was less dramatic but perhaps more skillful came in the third
round after an approach to the brutal eighth hole got caught in the
wind and landed short, in thick hay beside a greenside bunker.
Woods could only guess that the ball he was hitting was his, for it
was buried about 6 inches on the side of a steep slope (since he
was in a hazard, he would not have been penalized if it turned out
not to be his), and he had to do all he could to keep from falling
over backward as he swung. ``I could not have moved that ball a
foot,'' said CBS's David Feherty. Woods safely negotiated the shot
to the green, about 15-20 yards, then two-putted for his only bogey
of the final 36 holes . . . Talk about misfortune, how about the
two amateurs who drew Joe Ozaki and John Maginnes? They were in the
same group, and neither pro made a birdie in two rounds . . . Matt
Gogel not only missed the birdie attempt at 18 that could have tied
Woods, he missed the 2-foot comebacker. That careless stroke cost
him $80,000, the different between being solo second and having to
share second-place money . . . Tom Lehman had longtime caddie Andy
Martinez back on the bag after he took off the Phoenix Open with
leg cramps. While Martinez was recuperating, Lehman broke a winless
stretch that dated back to the end of 1996 . . . At the end of
Round 3, the odds were 2-1 that Woods would skip the 2001 AT&AMP;T, but
now that he's defending champ, all bets are off . . . Sergio Garcia
may be charismatic but he also seems a perfect candidate for
burnout. He missed the cut in Phoenix, barely made it at Pebble
Beach, then packed his bags for an event in Australia. He will
return to the United States for the World Match Play (Feb. 23-27),
and plans to play Bay Hill, TPC, the Masters, and perhaps the MCI
Heritage. Then comes extensive competition in Europe, with emphasis
on the majors. While he gets in trouble on the course, he is
charming off of it. Asked if it were OK to call him El Nino, a
nickname he reportedly did not like, Garcia said, ``Watever you
want to call me. I know my name is Sergio.'' Told that El Nino is a
bad expression in these parts, because of the horrific weather
associated with it, Garcia blushed and said, ``I'm the one who is
playing, I'm not the one who is up there in the cloud. This Nino is
OK, is not going to give you any problems.'' . . . CBS opted to
show the final round of Pebble Beach on tape delay to viewers in
San Francisco and Los Angeles, which backfired when word leaked out
that Woods had stormed to victory . . . Paul Azinger and Chip Beck
were anything but consistent at Pebble Beach. Azinger opened with a
76 at Pebble, then went out in 40 at Poppy Hills. He scorched the
back side in 29 _ eagle, four birdies, nothing worse than a 4 on
his card _ but shot 72 the next day at Spyglass and missed the cut.
Beck bounced back from an opening 80 at Pebble to shoot 66 at Poppy
Hills, but missed the cut after a 73 at Pebble . . . When Woods's
partner for the AT&AMP;T pro-am was announced, most folks said, ``Jerry
Who?'' But Sue Curtin, director of member services with the
Massachusetts Golf Association, knew exactly who Jerry Chang was.
Curtin and Chang were teammates on the Westlake High School golf
team in Ventura County, Calif. Chang went on to Stanford, where he
was teammates with Woods, another product of the Southern
California golf scene. ``Even in junior golf, all you ever heard
was Tiger Woods,'' said Curtin, who once won the girls' division of
a tournament in which the boys' champ was Phil Mickelson, ``so it's
no different now.'' Two other high school teammates of Curtin _
Chris Zambri and Charlie Wi _ are members of the BUY.com Tour.
</P>
<P>
   The mighty Quinn
</P>
<P>
   It was a wonderful start to the season for Fran Quinn, who won
the BUY.com Florida Classic. ``My whole goal was to go out and get
myself in position with nine holes to go,'' said Quinn, who had
closed 1999 with a couple of victories on the Asian PGA Tour after
just missing out on his US PGA Tour card. Three shots behind to
start the final 18 last Sunday, Quinn closed with a 66 to overtake
Mark Hensby. Kevin Johnson of Pembroke was third with a final-round
67_274. Geoff Sisk and Pat Bates, like Quinn and Johnson former
Mass. Open champions, finished at 4-over 288, well down the list.
Bates is back after missing nearly all of 1999 with an injury . . .
At the Florida Classic, Lance Ten Broeck took advantage of his
boss's week off to return to golf battles. Alas, he missed the cut
at 74-77. Ten Broeck caddies for Jesper Parnevik on the PGA Tour .
. . The MGA and New England PGA have joined forces with the Boston
Parks and Recreation Department for a four-week indoor golf camp
this winter. Sponsored by Fleet Boston Financial and Pepsi-Cola,
the program is for children who took part in MGA Inner City Camps
at Franklin Park and George Wright last summer . . . With a
contribution of $251,057 following last summer's tournament, the
PGA Senior Tour event at Nashawtuc CC in Concord has given more
than $2 million to local charities. The event will celebrate its
20th anniversary this year (Aug. 25-27), and a verbal commitment
has been secured from 50-year-old rookie Tom Kite.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
