<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5225 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-MURPHY-B     02-12 1660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-MURPHY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURPHY'S FLAW WAS AUDIBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Joe Murphy chapter in the Bruins' history book officially
closed Thursday when the hottest team in the NHL _ the Washington
Capitals _ claimed him off waivers.
</P>
<P>
   Unofficially, the 32-year-old right wing became an asterisk in
Bruins lore a week earlier when he was essentially fired for
insubordination.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy arrived with a reputation as an oddball, which wasn't
necessarily bad. Al Iafrate marched to his own drummer, too, and
had Iafrate been healthy _ as he was when he dominated the
Boston-Montreal playoff series in 1994 _ his idiosyncrasies would
have been ignored or at least tolerated. But the difference with
Murphy was that he wasn't a team guy _ on a team that desperately
needed cohesion. The Bruins struggled to find chemistry, struggled
to find their identity, and according to sources within the team,
Murphy's diatribes about ice time, his nasty swipes at coaches past
and present, and his inappropriate fits of temper all contributed
to his demise.
</P>
<P>
   Players have beefs with coaches over assorted things. It's not
that rare. But it is rare when it manifests itself the way it did
with Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Fee, Murphy's Boston-based attorney, said Murphy wasn't
planning on telling his side of the story unless a grievance is
filed to recoup back pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe decided, and I kind of recommended, he not get into a `he
said, she said' relative to the episode with the press,'' said Fee.
``I didn't think it was going to be productive and I think it might
have been counterproductive in attempting to get him to another
team, which was our first priority. If and when a grievance is
filed, then Joe's side will certainly be made known.''
</P>
<P>
   Fee said the Bruins were wrong to suspend Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still would contend that the fact they suspended him over
this particular incident was an excessive position to take,'' said
Fee. ``I think every player in the NHL ought to be concerned about
this case because if an angry word is exchanged or it's perceived
there's an angry word exchanged between a player and a coach, then
does the club have a right to terminate their contract or suspend
them for three weeks? I think that's the most important question
that came out of this whole thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are other remedies a club has. There are fines, you can
put him on waivers and designate him for assignment to the minors,
there are a number of things they can do. They took a position of
suspending the player and I don't agree with the suspension.''
</P>
<P>
   Fee bristled at suggestions that Murphy might benefit from
counseling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a doctor,'' said Fee. ``He's a hockey player as far as
I'm concerned. I'm not a psychiatrist and I think it's a dangerous
suggestion because it's unfounded and based on innuendo and
opinions that aren't medically sound. If Joe needs anything, I'm
sure he'll find a way to obtain what it is he needs if he needs
anything at all.''
</P>
<P>
   What Fee thinks Murphy needs is a fresh start, which he has with
the Capitals. It could be an ideal situation for Murphy, since
Michael Jordan owns the sports headlines in Washington these days.
Whether Murphy will blend in better with the Capitals remains to be
seen. Coach Ron Wilson seems no more inclined to put up with
insubordination any more than Pat Burns was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope people leave him alone,'' said Fee, ``and let him play
hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   Close calls
</P>
<P>
   Games should be called more closely down the stretch, as
referees will abide by a league edict to monitor obstruction and
goalie interference, among other things. ``There's too much
slashing going on right now,'' said Colin Campbell, the NHL's dean
of discipline. ``What does a team do when you slash a guy once and
nothing happens, then a guy does the same thing with the same force
and he breaks somebody's arm? You get one side saying, `Look, our
guy never does anything like that. It was just a single, not a home
run.' The other team says, `Yeah, well, he's gone for eight weeks.'
The guys who have the puck all the time and take the routes where
they're going to the net like Doug Weight get hit more. It's not
right.'' Campbell acknowledged that the tighter crease has altered
how players operate around the goalies. ``For about six years, the
defensemen could hack and whack and shove players out of the way
and guys were doing their best to stay out of the crease,'' he
said. ``Now players fall the right way (on the goalies) and they've
got it figured out.'' . . . The Canucks received some bad news when
top scoring defenseman Adrian Aucoin was lost for five weeks with a
sliced tendon on the middle finger of his right hand. Aucoin was
hurt against Calgary last Wednesday when the skate of a Flames
player cut through his glove . . . The Capitals continued their
roll Thursday night, shutting out the Canadiens in Montreal, 1-0.
Beating the Habs is hardly a feat these days, but the victory
boosted the Capitals' unbeaten streak at the Molson Centre to eight
games (7-0-1), and the shutout by Olaf Kolzig was his 15th,
surpassing Jim Carey as the team's career leader. ``It feels nice
but he probably did it in only a couple of years,'' said Kolzig.
``I did it in 10.'' . . . Cross-promotion on the Super Bowl and the
blockbuster hit ``Who Wants to be a Millionaire'' appeared to pay
off for ABC. The network's telecast of the NHL All-Star Game last
Sunday received a 23 percent jump in ratings compared with last
year's game, broadcast by Fox. Wonder how many people would watch
if the game was actually any good?
</P>
<P>
   Broadway bullies
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to good matchups, nothing would be better than
watching the Devils and Rangers go at it in the playoffs. Consider
that the Devils are unbeaten in 19 straight regular-season games
against the Rangers _ but the Rangers have never lost a playoff
series to New Jersey. ``Nineteen games is a lot,'' said Devils
goalie Martin Brodeur. ``You should get confidence from that, and
the other team should get discouraged. But for us, all that will go
right out the window if we play them in the playoffs. Everyone is
going to be telling us that we've never won against these guys in
the playoffs and the next thing you know, we're thinking about
that. That's because the playoffs are a different season.'' As good
as the hockey is, the sideshows are almost as entertaining with
these teams. Last Wednesday, Devils pest Claude Lemieux got into it
with Rangers coach John Muckler after Lemieux slashed Rangers
defenseman Brian Leetch. Lemieux gave the officials enough grief
that they ejected him. On his way off the ice, Lemieux and the
65-year-old Muckler yelled at each other, and it spilled over after
the game. ``He couldn't hit his way out of a paper bag,'' said
Muckler. ``I've seen him fight, he fights like a girl.'' When told
of those comments, Lemieux said, ``I want to see that paper bag so
I can put it over his head and make him better-looking. But I can't
fight him. I'd be embarrassed to fight a senior citizen.'' . . . No
announcement has been made, but it appears that Buffalo goalie
Dominik Hasek may not retire at the end of the year. Hasek had said
this would be his last season because he wants to move his family
back to the Czech Republic, but he is rethinking his position after
a groin injury sidelined him for half the year. ``I like to be on
the ice,'' said Hasek. ``I like to stop the puck and feel this
winning feeling. The situation is completely different than in the
beginning of the season. I was out for a long time.'' . . . The
Flyers, much maligned the last few years because of goaltending,
have denied rumors about acquiring Hasek. ``Bleeping ridiculous,''
was how general manager Bobby Clarke put it. ``He's scheduled to
make $9 million. We've got to do new contracts with (Eric) Lindros
and (John) LeClair. How many guys like that can you have?''
</P>
<P>
   All choked up
</P>
<P>
   Montreal forward Shayne Corson has dealt with colitis for 18
years. A few weeks ago, Corson thought he had cancer of the
esophagus, which killed his father at age 45. Corson found out that
he actually had a hiatal hernia, which causes acid buildup and
trouble swallowing. It can be treated with medication or surgery.
``There have been days where I felt like I was going through
hell,'' said Corson. ``I read up on so many things, went through so
many medical books trying to find out what was wrong. It drove me
crazy.'' Now the 33-year-old is finally relieved to know he'll be
all right. ``It felt so good,'' he said. ``You can fix that
problem.'' . . . When Jacques Lemaire left New Jersey to take over
as Montreal's senior hockey consultant, it was assumed that he
would eventually take over as general manager from Rejean Houle.
But Lemaire said he has no interest in the GM job. ``Why would I
want to do something that isn't fun?'' said Lemaire. ``If I was
ever going to coach (or be a GM) again, I'd probably go somewhere I
would enjoy the work. Not here. Montreal is different. The media
here is so competitive. Look at all the guys who've coached here
before, like Pat Burns. They don't want to come back, either.''
Lemaire acknowledged the change in Montreal, with the team having
such titanic struggles. ``Something is heavy _ and I know the
players feel it,'' said Lemaire. ``It's difficult because sometimes
we see a player we want, someone who could help us, and we hear he
won't come to Montreal. He'd rather play in Phoenix or somewhere
else.'' . . . Speaking of the Habs, defenseman Vladimir Malakhov is
in big trouble. He hasn't been able to play because of a knee
injury but apparently he's well enough to go skiing, which is a
violation of his contract. He has been suspended without pay . . .
Thirty days to the trading deadline. Let's hope the Bruins will
make a move that doesn't involve the coach.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
