<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-12 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5442 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     02-12 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: TOM LANDRY'S CONTROL OF THE COWBOYS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   He was known as Ol' Stone Face, and on the sideline it was easy
to see why. However well or poorly the Dallas Cowboys were playing,
Coach Tom Landry's expression under his snap-brim fedora never
changed. But that's the way he wanted it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leadership is a matter of having people look at you and gain
confidence, seeing how you react,'' he once said, alluding to his
Cowboys players. ``If you're in control, they're in control.''
</P>
<P>
   At age 70, six years after Tom Landry stopped coaching and four
decades after he had flown 30 missions as a B-17 pilot based in
England during World War II, that control was still there. When the
single-engine Cessna he was piloting in 1995 started sputtering
over Ennis, Texas, he calmly landed it in a dirt field next to a
high school. He, his wife, Alicia, and two other family members
walked away.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no apparent injuries or damage to the plane,''
federal authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   As a coach, Landry's control never wavered. He was considered a
defensive guru for having invented the 4-3 alignment as a defensive
back and player-coach for the Giants. With the Cowboys, he
developed what is known as the flex defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as complicated as it sounds,'' defensive end Harvey
Martin once said. ``We just plug all the gaps.''
</P>
<P>
   On offense, Landry sent in every play to the Cowboys quarterback
(Don Meredith, Roger Staubach or Danny White) so that he would know
what to look for as the play developed. On a running play, he
checked the blocking at the point of attack. On a pass play, he
scanned the opposing team's pass defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were to see me as a cheerleader,'' he once said, ``that
would mean I was only watching, instead of thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Landry, who died Saturday night, was always thinking _ about
football. After a game in Texas Stadium heat that hovered above 100
degrees, he was asked why he had not taken off his sports coat, now
soaked through with perspiration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I forgot,'' he said with a sheepish grin.
</P>
<P>
   More than anyone else, Landry built the Cowboys into America's
Team as one of the National Football League's flagship franchises.
For the first 29 years of the Cowboys' existence, he not only
coached the team, he also constructed it. He educated the assistant
coaches, notably Mike Ditka and Dan Reeves, who would be head
coaches elsewhere. He picked and polished the players.
</P>
<P>
   Not just the obvious draft choices, but obscure free agents like
wide receiver Drew Pearson and safety Cliff Harris, who developed
into All-Pro players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Landry's not a yell-type leader; he's almost like a
father, someone you really want to please,'' Pearson has said. ``He
can give you this subtle look at the right time, and it's worth a
thousand words. There's nothing phony about him. Just being around
him, I learned so much about football _ and life.''
</P>
<P>
   Danny White once remembered a Cowboys meeting when illegal drugs
were beginning to infest pro football.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Landry told us he didn't care if we didn't win a game,
but that we were going to get rid of any drug problems we might
have,'' White said. ``That told me how he feels about people. He
would rather change a person's life for the good than win football
games.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the president of the Fellowship of Christian Athletes,
Landry had a philosophy beyond X's and O's.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game is played with the heart,'' he said. ``You don't
have to drink or swear or hit people in the face when they're not
looking, but you do have to be tough to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Landry's teams won. When the Cowboys' current owner, Jerry
Jones, unceremoniously fired him in 1989 after purchasing the
franchise for a reported $140 million, his 250 victories were third
among career NFL coaches, behind George Halas and Don Shula. His
Cowboys had won 2 Super Bowls, 5 conference championships and 13
division titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the worst scenario,'' Landry said of his abrupt
dismissal, ``but I'm not bitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Landry had too much dignity to be bitter, but the day after he
was fired, he broke down during a farewell speech to his players.
</P>
<P>
   ``It must have lasted only five minutes,'' Danny White said,
``but time stood still.''
</P>
<P>
   Time stood still then for the Cowboys' alumni, too, especially
Bob Lilly, the Hall of Fame defensive tackle on their Super Bowl VI
champions. When Lilly learned of Landry's firing, he said, ``A lot
of old Cowboys are crying tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   And now those old Cowboys are crying again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-12-00 2313EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
