<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-BRUTALITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONGTIME CRITICS AND MANY POLICE OFFICIALS AGREE: END ABUSES  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Striking an uncharacteristically harmonious and
conciliatory tone, longtime critics of the police like the Rev. Al
Sharpton joined law enforcement officials from across New York
state in a gathering Saturday to examine what could be done to
combat police brutality.
</P>
<P>
   Police chiefs, lawyers, legislators, civil libertarians, clergy
members and police union officials from Long Island to Buffalo
answered the call of Norman Siegel, the executive director of the
New York Civil Liberties Union, to hold a summit meeting at the
Center for Worker Education in Lower Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   While the summit meeting highlighted many of the participants'
differences on the solutions, it was clear that those who attended
agreed there was a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to be open-minded,'' Police Chief John C. Nielsen of
Albany said in an interview Saturday. He acknowledged that he was a
bit nervous about attending the conference. The attraction, he
said, was the chance to listen to other ideas about how to improve
his department's relationship with its community.
</P>
<P>
   The keynote speakers _ Siegel, Sharpton and former Mayor David
Dinkins _ avoided attacking the New York City police and made only
fleeting references to the way Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has handled
the police.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an issue I think that has gone so long ignored that we
have begun to reap the impact of ignoring it,'' Sharpton told an
audience of about 200. ``It should have the attention of everyone,
including police, because this is not an anti-police movement, but
it is anti-police brutality.''
</P>
<P>
   Participants spoke about police brutality in their communities,
asked questions, took notes and compared statistics and programs.
Many of the participants hammered home civil rights themes,
comparing the struggle to fight police brutality to the civil
rights movement and the struggle for sexual equality.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the law enforcement officials who attended the event
said they supported many of the suggested ideas, including
increasing diversity in their departments and requiring officers to
live within the municipalities that they police or providing
incentives for them to do so.
</P>
<P>
   There were also differences of opinion, on subjects like
civilian complaint boards. While many community leaders wanted more
civilian oversight, police officials generally said discipline
should come from within the department.
</P>
<P>
   The summit meeting came at a time when police agencies across
the state are coming under increasing scrutiny because of highly
publicized allegations of brutality.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's event highlighted a rift within the New York
department itself, as the city's main police union did not
participate, while the leading minority organizations for officers
jumped at the opportunity. Patrick J. Lynch, the president of the
city's Patrolmen's Benevolent Association, the largest police
union, was invited to be a keynote speaker but declined because of
scheduling conflicts, the event's organizers said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the suggestions of additional oversight, Eloise
Dowdell-Curry, the president of the Syracuse Urban League, said,
``I don't care how many layers of bureaucracy and special
prosecutors you put on top of things, there will be nothing that
you can do until you eliminate the `blue wall of silence,''' a
reference to a belief that officers tend to protect one another to
avoid prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. James Shepard of the Rochester police acknowledged the need
for change to eliminate brutality. ``But you must return to what
Martin Luther King said: `Do not judge me by the color of my skin,
judge me by the content of my character,''' ant Shepard said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't judge me by the color of my uniform, but by the content
of my character.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-12-00 2333EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
